ng Address1,Shipping Address2,Shipping Company,Shipping City,Shipping Zip,Shipping Province,Shipping Country,Shipping Phone,Notes,Note Attributes,Cancelled at,Payment Method,Payment Reference,Refunded Amount,Vendor,Id,Tags,Risk Level,Source,Lineitem discount,Tax 1 Name,Tax 1 Value,Tax 2 Name,Tax 2 Value,Tax 3 Name,Tax 3 Value,Tax 4 Name,Tax 4 Value,Tax 5 Name,Tax 5 Value\n#1001,testing@test.com,paid,2015-09-04 12:54:26 -0400,unfulfilled,,yes,USD,6.25,7.00,1.18,14.43,FREEBOWLS,8.00,Tier 1,2015-09-04 12:54:26 -0400,3,Peanut Butter Cacao - Regular,3.50,,4,true,true,pending,TEst Test,\"300, Madison Ave\",300,Madison Ave,\"\",New York,'10017,NY,US,\"\",TEst Test,\"300, Madison Ave\",300,Madison Ave,\"\",New York,'10017,NY,US,\"\",,\"\",,Shopify Payments,c3208003652.1,0.00,Farmivore Shop,1345455556,\"\",Low,web,0.00,NY State Tax 4%,0.53,New York County Tax 4.875%,0.65,,,,,,\n#1001,testing@test.com,,,,,,,,,,,,,,2015-09-04 12:54:26 -0400,1,Apple Pie - Gluten-Free,3.75,\"\",\"\",true,true,pending,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,Farmivore Shop,,,,,0.00,,,,,,,,,,\n","markerStore":{"nextMarkerId":5,"markersById":{"0":{"range":{"start":{"row":0,"column":0},"end":{"row":0,"column":0}},"properties":{"type":"selection","editorId":536,"preserveFolds":true,"goalScreenRange":null},"reversed":false,"tailed":false,"valid":true,"invalidate":"never","maintainHistory":true}},"version":2},"history":{"version":3,"nextCheckpointId":0,"undoStack":[],"redoStack":[]},"encoding":"utf8","filePath":"/Users/joegesualdo/Downloads/orders_export.csv","digestWhenLastPersisted":"da39a3ee5e6b4b0d3255bfef95601890afd80709","preferredLineEnding":null,"deserializer":"TextBuffer","version":2},{"load":false,"text":"1\r\n00:00:07,279 --> 00:00:13,820\r\nHarper Audio Presents the Alchemist By Paulo\nCoelho , Read By Jeromey Irons\r\n\r\n2\r\n00:00:13,082 --> 00:00:20,082\r\n\"The alchemist picked up a book that someone\nin the caravan had brought. Leafing through\r\n\r\n3\r\n00:00:24,619 --> 00:00:28,683\r\nthe pages, he found a story about Narcissus.\r\n\r\n4\r\n00:00:29,259 --> 00:00:34,330\r\nThe alchemist knew the legend of Narcissus,\na youth who knelt daily beside a lake to contemplate\r\n\r\n5\r\n00:00:34,969 --> 00:00:41,690\r\nhis own beauty. He was so fascinated by himself\nthat, one morning, he fell into the lake and\r\n\r\n6\r\n00:00:41,069 --> 00:00:48,069\r\ndrowned. At the spot where he fell, a flower\nwas born, which was called the narcissus.\r\n\r\n7\r\n00:00:51,289 --> 00:00:55,480\r\nBut this was not how the author of the book\nended the story.\r\n\r\n8\r\n00:00:55,048 --> 00:01:00,877\r\nHe said that when Narcissus died, the goddesses\nof the forest appeared and found the lake,\r\n\r\n9\r\n00:01:01,309 --> 00:01:05,550\r\nwhich had been fresh water, transformed into\na lake of salty tears.\r\n\r\n10\r\n00:01:05,055 --> 00:01:09,068\r\n'Why do you weep?' the goddesses asked.\r\n\r\n11\r\n00:01:09,068 --> 00:01:13,110\r\n'I weep for Narcissus,\" the lake replied.\r\n\r\n12\r\n00:01:14,001 --> 00:01:19,008\r\n'Ah, it is no surprise that you weep for Narcissus,'\nthey said, 'for though we always pursued him\r\n\r\n13\r\n00:01:19,017 --> 00:01:23,106\r\nin the forest, you alone could contemplate\nhis beauty close at hand.'\r\n\r\n14\r\n00:01:24,006 --> 00:01:28,605\r\n'But... was Narcissus beautiful?' the lake\nasked.\r\n\r\n15\r\n00:01:28,659 --> 00:01:35,100\r\n'Who better than you to know that?' the goddesses\nasked in wonder. 'After all, it was by your\r\n\r\n16\r\n00:01:35,001 --> 00:01:39,023\r\nbanks that he knelt each day to contemplate\nhimself!'\r\n\r\n17\r\n00:01:39,032 --> 00:01:45,081\r\nThe lake was silent for some time. Finally,\nit said:\r\n\r\n18\r\n00:01:45,369 --> 00:01:51,468\r\n'I weep for Narcissus, but I never noticed\nthat Narcissus was beautiful. I weep because,\r\n\r\n19\r\n00:01:52,359 --> 00:01:58,378\r\neach time he knelt beside my banks, I could\nsee, in the depths of his eyes, my own beauty\r\n\r\n20\r\n00:01:58,549 --> 00:01:59,380\r\nreflected.'\r\n\r\n21\r\n00:01:59,038 --> 00:02:03,132\r\n'What a lovely story,' the alchemist thought.\"\r\n\r\n22\r\n00:02:04,032 --> 00:02:10,391\r\nThe boy's name was Santiago. Dusk was falling\nas the boy arrived with his herd\r\n\r\n23\r\n00:02:10,679 --> 00:02:15,650\r\nat an abandoned church. The roof had fallen\nin long ago, and an enormous\r\n\r\n24\r\n00:02:15,065 --> 00:02:19,162\r\nsycamore had grown on the spot where the sacristy\nhad once stood.\r\n\r\n25\r\n00:02:20,062 --> 00:02:24,065\r\nHe decided to spend the night there. He saw\nto it that all the sheep entered\r\n\r\n26\r\n00:02:24,065 --> 00:02:28,068\r\nthrough the ruined gate, and then laid some\nplanks across it to prevent the flock\r\n\r\n27\r\n00:02:28,095 --> 00:02:32,994\r\nfrom wandering away during the night. There\nwere no wolves in the region, but\r\n\r\n28\r\n00:02:33,849 --> 00:02:36,896\r\nonce an animal had strayed during the night,\nand the boy had had to spend the\r\n\r\n29\r\n00:02:37,319 --> 00:02:43,230\r\nentire next day searching for it.\nHe swept the floor with his jacket and lay\r\n\r\n30\r\n00:02:43,023 --> 00:02:49,034\r\ndown, using the book he had just\nfinished reading as a pillow. He told himself\r\n\r\n31\r\n00:02:49,034 --> 00:02:53,047\r\nthat he would have to start reading\nthicker books: they lasted longer, and made\r\n\r\n32\r\n00:02:53,047 --> 00:02:58,106\r\nmore comfortable pillows.\nIt was still dark when he awoke, and, looking\r\n\r\n33\r\n00:02:59,006 --> 00:03:04,185\r\nup, he could see the stars through\nthe half-destroyed roof.\r\n\r\n34\r\n00:03:04,239 --> 00:03:08,292\r\nI wanted to sleep a little longer, he thought.\nHe had had the same dream that\r\n\r\n35\r\n00:03:08,769 --> 00:03:14,890\r\nnight as a week ago, and once again he had\nawakened before it ended.\r\n\r\n36\r\n00:03:14,089 --> 00:03:19,358\r\nHe arose and, taking up his crook, began to\nawaken the sheep that still slept.\r\n\r\n37\r\n00:03:20,159 --> 00:03:23,810\r\nHe had noticed that, as soon as he awoke,\nmost of his animals also began to\r\n\r\n38\r\n00:03:23,081 --> 00:03:28,165\r\nstir. It was as if some mysterious energy\nbound his life to that of the sheep,\r\n\r\n39\r\n00:03:29,065 --> 00:03:32,264\r\nwith whom he had spent the past two years,\nleading them through the\r\n\r\n40\r\n00:03:32,849 --> 00:03:36,921\r\ncountryside in search of food and water. \"They\nare so used to me that they\r\n\r\n41\r\n00:03:37,569 --> 00:03:42,170\r\nknow my schedule,\" he muttered. Thinking about\nthat for a moment, he realized\r\n\r\n42\r\n00:03:42,017 --> 00:03:45,646\r\nthat it could be the other way around: that\nit was he who had become\r\n\r\n43\r\n00:03:45,799 --> 00:03:49,807\r\naccustomed to their schedule.\nBut there were certain of them who took a\r\n\r\n44\r\n00:03:50,599 --> 00:03:55,602\r\nbit longer to awaken. The boy\nprodded them, one by one, with his crook,\r\n\r\n45\r\n00:03:55,629 --> 00:04:00,646\r\ncalling each by name. He had always\nbelieved that the sheep were able to understand\r\n\r\n46\r\n00:04:00,799 --> 00:04:03,865\r\nwhat he said. So there were\ntimes when he read them parts of his books\r\n\r\n47\r\n00:04:04,459 --> 00:04:08,890\r\nthat had made an impression on\nhim, or when he would tell them of the loneliness\r\n\r\n48\r\n00:04:08,089 --> 00:04:12,158\r\nor the happiness of a\nshepherd in the fields. Sometimes he would\r\n\r\n49\r\n00:04:12,959 --> 00:04:17,820\r\ncomment to them on the things he\nhad seen in the villages they passed.\r\n\r\n50\r\n00:04:17,082 --> 00:04:23,241\r\nBut for the past few days he had spoken to\nthem about only one thing: the girl,\r\n\r\n51\r\n00:04:23,979 --> 00:04:27,100\r\nthe daughter of a merchant who lived in the\nvillage they would reach in about\r\n\r\n52\r\n00:04:27,001 --> 00:04:33,087\r\nfour days. He had been to the village only\nonce, the year before. The merchant\r\n\r\n53\r\n00:04:33,096 --> 00:04:37,124\r\nwas the proprietor of a dry goods shop, and\nhe always demanded that the sheep\r\n\r\n54\r\n00:04:38,024 --> 00:04:42,099\r\nbe sheared in his presence, so that he would\nnot be cheated. A friend had told\r\n\r\n55\r\n00:04:42,099 --> 00:04:45,151\r\nthe boy about the shop, and he had taken his\nsheep there.\r\n\r\n56\r\n00:04:46,051 --> 00:04:49,119\r\n*\n\"I need to sell some wool,\" the boy told the\r\n\r\n57\r\n00:04:50,019 --> 00:04:52,102\r\nmerchant.\nThe shop was busy, and the man asked the shepherd\r\n\r\n58\r\n00:04:53,002 --> 00:04:57,019\r\nto wait until the afternoon.\nSo the boy sat on the steps of the shop and\r\n\r\n59\r\n00:04:57,019 --> 00:05:01,074\r\ntook a book from his bag.\n\"I didn't know shepherds knew how to read,\"\r\n\r\n60\r\n00:05:01,074 --> 00:05:07,116\r\nsaid a girl's voice behind him.\nThe girl was typical of the region of Andalusia,\r\n\r\n61\r\n00:05:08,016 --> 00:05:13,555\r\nwith flowing black hair, and eyes\nthat vaguely recalled the Moorish conquerors.\r\n\r\n62\r\n00:05:13,699 --> 00:05:19,650\r\n\"Well, usually I learn more from my sheep\nthan from books,\" he answered.\r\n\r\n63\r\n00:05:19,065 --> 00:05:22,088\r\nDuring the two hours that they talked, she\ntold him she was the merchant's\r\n\r\n64\r\n00:05:22,088 --> 00:05:25,747\r\ndaughter, and spoke of life in the village,\nwhere each day was like all the\r\n\r\n65\r\n00:05:26,539 --> 00:05:32,440\r\nothers. The shepherd told her of the Andalusian\ncountryside, and related the\r\n\r\n66\r\n00:05:32,044 --> 00:05:36,069\r\nnews from the other towns where he had stopped.\nIt was a pleasant change\r\n\r\n67\r\n00:05:36,069 --> 00:05:40,165\r\nfrom talking to his sheep.\n\"How did you learn to read?\" the girl asked\r\n\r\n68\r\n00:05:41,065 --> 00:05:44,087\r\nat one point.\n\"Like everybody learns,\" he said. \"In school.\"\r\n\r\n69\r\n00:05:44,087 --> 00:05:49,286\r\n\"Well, if you know how to read, why are you\njust a shepherd?\"\r\n\r\n70\r\n00:05:50,069 --> 00:05:53,870\r\nThe boy mumbled an answer that allowed him\nto avoid responding to her\r\n\r\n71\r\n00:05:53,087 --> 00:05:58,130\r\nquestion. He was sure the girl would never\nunderstand. He went on telling\r\n\r\n72\r\n00:05:59,003 --> 00:06:04,016\r\nstories about his travels, and her bright,\nMoorish eyes went wide with fear and\r\n\r\n73\r\n00:06:04,043 --> 00:06:09,105\r\nsurprise. As the time passed, the boy found\nhimself wishing that the day would\r\n\r\n74\r\n00:06:10,005 --> 00:06:16,033\r\nnever end, that her father would stay busy\nand keep him waiting for three days.\r\n\r\n75\r\n00:06:16,033 --> 00:06:19,992\r\nHe recognized that he was feeling something\nhe had never experienced before:\r\n\r\n76\r\n00:06:20,289 --> 00:06:25,383\r\nthe desire to live in one place forever. With\nthe girl with the raven hair, his\r\n\r\n77\r\n00:06:26,229 --> 00:06:32,273\r\ndays would never be the same again.\nBut finally the merchant appeared, and asked\r\n\r\n78\r\n00:06:32,669 --> 00:06:37,080\r\nthe boy to shear four sheep. He\npaid for the wool and asked the shepherd to\r\n\r\n79\r\n00:06:37,008 --> 00:06:40,347\r\ncome back the following year.\n*\r\n\r\n80\r\n00:06:40,419 --> 00:06:45,423\r\nAnd now it was only four days before he would\nbe back in that same village. He\r\n\r\n81\r\n00:06:45,819 --> 00:06:50,460\r\nwas excited, and at the same time uneasy:\nmaybe the girl had already\r\n\r\n82\r\n00:06:50,046 --> 00:06:54,108\r\nforgotten him. Lots of shepherds passed through,\nselling their wool.\r\n\r\n83\r\n00:06:55,008 --> 00:07:00,467\r\n\"It doesn't matter,\" he said to his sheep.\n\"I know other girls in other places.\"\r\n\r\n84\r\n00:07:00,539 --> 00:07:06,270\r\nBut in his heart he knew that it did matter.\nAnd he knew that shepherds, like\r\n\r\n85\r\n00:07:06,027 --> 00:07:09,576\r\nseamen and like traveling salesmen, always\nfound a town where there was\r\n\r\n86\r\n00:07:09,819 --> 00:07:13,825\r\nsomeone who could make them forget the joys\nof carefree wandering.\r\n\r\n87\r\n00:07:13,879 --> 00:07:18,520\r\nThe day was dawning, and the shepherd urged\nhis sheep in the direction of the\r\n\r\n88\r\n00:07:18,052 --> 00:07:23,053\r\nsun. They never have to make any decisions,\nhe thought. Maybe that's why they\r\n\r\n89\r\n00:07:23,062 --> 00:07:27,100\r\nalways stay close to me.\nThe only things that concerned the sheep were\r\n\r\n90\r\n00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:32,044\r\nfood and water. As long as the\nboy knew how to find the best pastures in\r\n\r\n91\r\n00:07:32,044 --> 00:07:38,072\r\nAndalusia, they would be his friends.\nYes, their days were all the same, with the\r\n\r\n92\r\n00:07:38,072 --> 00:07:42,119\r\nseemingly endless hours between\nsunrise and dusk; and they had never read\r\n\r\n93\r\n00:07:43,019 --> 00:07:47,958\r\na book in their young lives, and\ndidn't understand when the boy told them about\r\n\r\n94\r\n00:07:48,129 --> 00:07:53,560\r\nthe sights of the cities. They\nwere content with just food and water, and,\r\n\r\n95\r\n00:07:53,056 --> 00:07:56,127\r\nin exchange, they generously gave\nof their wool, their company, and--once in\r\n\r\n96\r\n00:07:57,027 --> 00:08:04,027\r\na while--their meat.\nIf I became a monster today, and decided to\r\n\r\n97\r\n00:08:04,078 --> 00:08:08,143\r\nkill them, one by one, they would\nbecome aware only after most of the flock\r\n\r\n98\r\n00:08:09,043 --> 00:08:13,212\r\nhad been slaughtered, thought the\nboy. They trust me, and they've forgotten\r\n\r\n99\r\n00:08:13,599 --> 00:08:19,470\r\nhow to rely on their own instincts,\nbecause I lead them to nourishment.\r\n\r\n100\r\n00:08:19,047 --> 00:08:23,866\r\nThe boy was surprised at his thoughts. Maybe\nthe church, with the sycamore\r\n\r\n101\r\n00:08:24,289 --> 00:08:29,360\r\ngrowing from within, had been haunted. It\nhad caused him to have the same\r\n\r\n102\r\n00:08:29,036 --> 00:08:33,775\r\ndream for a second time, and it was causing\nhim to feel anger toward his\r\n\r\n103\r\n00:08:34,099 --> 00:08:38,181\r\nfaithful companions. He drank a bit from the\nwine that remained from his dinner\r\n\r\n104\r\n00:08:38,919 --> 00:08:43,700\r\nof the night before, and he gathered his jacket\ncloser to his body. He knew that\r\n\r\n105\r\n00:08:43,007 --> 00:08:47,102\r\na few hours from now, with the sun at its\nzenith, the heat would be so great that\r\n\r\n106\r\n00:08:48,065 --> 00:08:52,121\r\nhe would not be able to lead his flock across\nthe fields. It was the time of day\r\n\r\n107\r\n00:08:53,021 --> 00:08:58,119\r\nwhen all of Spain slept during the summer.\nThe heat lasted until nightfall, and\r\n\r\n108\r\n00:08:59,019 --> 00:09:03,114\r\nall that time he had to carry his jacket.\nBut when he thought to complain about\r\n\r\n109\r\n00:09:04,014 --> 00:09:08,058\r\nthe burden of its weight, he remembered that,\nbecause he had the jacket, he\r\n\r\n110\r\n00:09:08,058 --> 00:09:14,103\r\nhad withstood the cold of the dawn.\nWe have to be prepared for change, he thought,\r\n\r\n111\r\n00:09:15,003 --> 00:09:19,078\r\nand he was grateful for the\njacket's weight and warmth.\r\n\r\n112\r\n00:09:19,078 --> 00:09:24,084\r\nThe jacket had a purpose, and so did the boy.\nHis purpose in life was to travel,\r\n\r\n113\r\n00:09:25,038 --> 00:09:29,039\r\nand, after two years of walking the Andalusian\nterrain, he knew all the cities of\r\n\r\n114\r\n00:09:29,048 --> 00:09:34,089\r\nthe region. He was planning, on this visit,\nto explain to the girl how it was that a\r\n\r\n115\r\n00:09:34,089 --> 00:09:38,115\r\nsimple shepherd knew how to read. That he\nhad attended a seminary until he\r\n\r\n116\r\n00:09:39,015 --> 00:09:43,079\r\nwas sixteen. His parents had wanted him to\nbecome a priest, and thereby a\r\n\r\n117\r\n00:09:43,079 --> 00:09:48,127\r\nsource of pride for a simple farm family.\nThey worked hard just to have food\r\n\r\n118\r\n00:09:49,027 --> 00:09:55,031\r\nand water, like the sheep. He had studied\nLatin, Spanish, and theology. But\r\n\r\n119\r\n00:09:55,031 --> 00:09:59,117\r\never since he had been a child, he had wanted\nto know the world, and this was\r\n\r\n120\r\n00:10:00,017 --> 00:10:06,064\r\nmuch more important to him than knowing God\nand learning about man's sins.\r\n\r\n121\r\n00:10:06,064 --> 00:10:10,102\r\nOne afternoon, on a visit to his family, he\nhad summoned up the courage to tell\r\n\r\n122\r\n00:10:11,002 --> 00:10:16,002\r\nhis father that he didn't want to become a\npriest. That he wanted to travel.\r\n\r\n123\r\n00:10:16,002 --> 00:10:18,077\r\n*\n\"People from all over the world have passed\r\n\r\n124\r\n00:10:18,077 --> 00:10:22,106\r\nthrough this village, son,\" said his\nfather. \"They come in search of new things,\r\n\r\n125\r\n00:10:23,006 --> 00:10:26,039\r\nbut when they leave they are\nbasically the same people they were when they\r\n\r\n126\r\n00:10:26,039 --> 00:10:29,044\r\narrived. They climb the\nmountain to see the castle, and they wind\r\n\r\n127\r\n00:10:29,089 --> 00:10:33,181\r\nup thinking that the past was better\nthan what we have now. They have blond hair,\r\n\r\n128\r\n00:10:34,081 --> 00:10:37,139\r\nor dark skin, but basically\nthey're the same as the people who live right\r\n\r\n129\r\n00:10:38,039 --> 00:10:41,065\r\nhere.\"\n\"But I'd like to see the castles in the towns\r\n\r\n130\r\n00:10:41,065 --> 00:10:46,116\r\nwhere they live,\" the boy explained.\n\"Those people, when they see our land, say\r\n\r\n131\r\n00:10:47,016 --> 00:10:50,041\r\nthat they would like to live here\nforever,\" his father continued.\r\n\r\n132\r\n00:10:50,041 --> 00:10:54,115\r\n\"Well, I'd like to see their land, and see\nhow they live,\" said his son.\r\n\r\n133\r\n00:10:55,015 --> 00:10:58,054\r\n\"The people who come here have a lot of money\nto spend, so they can afford to\r\n\r\n134\r\n00:10:58,054 --> 00:11:01,135\r\ntravel,\" his father said. \"Amongst us, the\nonly ones who travel are the\r\n\r\n135\r\n00:11:02,035 --> 00:11:05,128\r\nshepherds.\"\n\"Well, then I'll be a shepherd!\"\r\n\r\n136\r\n00:11:06,028 --> 00:11:12,033\r\nHis father said no more. The next day, he\ngave his son a pouch that held three\r\n\r\n137\r\n00:11:12,033 --> 00:11:17,102\r\nancient Spanish gold coins.\n\"I found these one day in the fields. I wanted\r\n\r\n138\r\n00:11:18,002 --> 00:11:23,027\r\nthem to be a part of your\ninheritance. But use them to buy your flock.\r\n\r\n139\r\n00:11:23,027 --> 00:11:27,106\r\nTake to the fields, and someday\nyou'll learn that our countryside is the best,\r\n\r\n140\r\n00:11:28,006 --> 00:11:34,010\r\nand our women the most beautiful.\"\nAnd he gave the boy his blessing. The boy\r\n\r\n141\r\n00:11:34,046 --> 00:11:40,077\r\ncould see in his father's gaze a desire\nto be able, himself, to travel the world--a\r\n\r\n142\r\n00:11:40,077 --> 00:11:44,129\r\ndesire that was still alive, despite his\nfather's having had to bury it, over dozens\r\n\r\n143\r\n00:11:45,029 --> 00:11:49,048\r\nof years, under the burden of\nstruggling for water to drink, food to eat,\r\n\r\n144\r\n00:11:49,048 --> 00:11:52,092\r\nand the same place to sleep every\nnight of his life.\r\n\r\n145\r\n00:11:52,092 --> 00:11:56,157\r\n*\nThe horizon was tinged with red, and suddenly\r\n\r\n146\r\n00:11:57,057 --> 00:12:02,057\r\nthe sun appeared. The boy\nthought back to that conversation with his\r\n\r\n147\r\n00:12:02,057 --> 00:12:06,152\r\nfather, and felt happy; he had\nalready seen many castles and met many women\r\n\r\n148\r\n00:12:07,052 --> 00:12:13,070\r\n(but none the equal of the\none who awaited him several days hence). He\r\n\r\n149\r\n00:12:13,007 --> 00:12:17,082\r\nowned a jacket, a book that he\ncould trade for another, and a flock of sheep.\r\n\r\n150\r\n00:12:18,045 --> 00:12:24,079\r\nBut, most important, he was able\nevery day to live out his dream. If he were\r\n\r\n151\r\n00:12:24,079 --> 00:12:29,142\r\nto tire of the Andalusian fields, he\ncould sell his sheep and go to sea. By the\r\n\r\n152\r\n00:12:30,042 --> 00:12:34,057\r\ntime he had had enough of the sea,\nhe would already have known other cities,\r\n\r\n153\r\n00:12:34,057 --> 00:12:38,151\r\nother women, and other chances to\nbe happy. I couldn't have found God in the\r\n\r\n154\r\n00:12:39,051 --> 00:12:44,099\r\nseminary, he thought, as he looked\nat the sunrise.\r\n\r\n155\r\n00:12:44,099 --> 00:12:48,160\r\nWhenever he could, he sought out a new road\nto travel. He had never been to\r\n\r\n156\r\n00:12:49,006 --> 00:12:52,037\r\nthat ruined church before, in spite of having\ntraveled through those parts many\r\n\r\n157\r\n00:12:52,091 --> 00:12:57,174\r\ntimes. The world was huge and inexhaustible;\nhe had only to allow his sheep to\r\n\r\n158\r\n00:12:58,074 --> 00:13:03,163\r\nset the route for a while, and he would discover\nother interesting things. The\r\n\r\n159\r\n00:13:04,063 --> 00:13:07,085\r\nproblem is that they don't even realize that\nthey're walking a new road every\r\n\r\n160\r\n00:13:07,085 --> 00:13:11,167\r\nday. They don't see that the fields are new\nand the seasons change. All they\r\n\r\n161\r\n00:13:12,067 --> 00:13:18,075\r\nthink about is food and water.\nMaybe we're all that way, the boy mused. Even\r\n\r\n162\r\n00:13:18,075 --> 00:13:24,079\r\nme--I haven't thought of other\nwomen since I met the merchant's daughter.\r\n\r\n163\r\n00:13:24,079 --> 00:13:29,087\r\nLooking at the sun, he calculated\nthat he would reach Tarifa before midday.\r\n\r\n164\r\n00:13:29,087 --> 00:13:33,179\r\nThere, he could exchange his book\nfor a thicker one, fill his wine bottle, shave,\r\n\r\n165\r\n00:13:34,079 --> 00:13:38,137\r\nand have a haircut; he had to\nprepare himself for his meeting with the girl,\r\n\r\n166\r\n00:13:39,037 --> 00:13:41,105\r\nand he didn't want to think about\nthe possibility that some other shepherd,\r\n\r\n167\r\n00:13:42,005 --> 00:13:47,036\r\nwith a larger flock of sheep, had\narrived there before him and asked for her\r\n\r\n168\r\n00:13:47,036 --> 00:13:49,091\r\nhand.\nIt's the possibility of having a dream come\r\n\r\n169\r\n00:13:49,091 --> 00:13:53,118\r\ntrue that makes life interesting, he\nthought, as he looked again at the position\r\n\r\n170\r\n00:13:54,018 --> 00:14:00,044\r\nof the sun, and hurried his pace. He\nhad suddenly remembered that, in Tarifa, there\r\n\r\n171\r\n00:14:00,044 --> 00:14:04,068\r\nwas an old woman who\ninterpreted dreams.\r\n\r\n172\r\n00:14:04,068 --> 00:14:06,135\r\n*\nThe old woman led the boy to a room at the\r\n\r\n173\r\n00:14:07,035 --> 00:14:11,090\r\nback of her house; it was\nseparated from her living room by a curtain\r\n\r\n174\r\n00:14:11,009 --> 00:14:16,075\r\nof colored beads. The room's\nfurnishings consisted of a table, an image\r\n\r\n175\r\n00:14:17,056 --> 00:14:21,119\r\nof the Sacred Heart of Jesus, and two\nchairs.\r\n\r\n176\r\n00:14:22,019 --> 00:14:27,117\r\nThe woman sat down, and told him to be seated\nas well. Then she took both of\r\n\r\n177\r\n00:14:28,017 --> 00:14:35,017\r\nhis hands in hers, and began quietly to pray.\nIt sounded like a Gypsy prayer. The boy had\r\n\r\n178\r\n00:14:37,006 --> 00:14:40,098\r\nalready had experience on the\nroad with Gypsies; they also traveled, but\r\n\r\n179\r\n00:14:40,098 --> 00:14:44,189\r\nthey had no flocks of sheep. People\nsaid that Gypsies spent their lives tricking\r\n\r\n180\r\n00:14:45,089 --> 00:14:51,100\r\nothers. It was also said that they had\na pact with the devil, and that they kidnapped\r\n\r\n181\r\n00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:57,043\r\nchildren and, taking them away\nto their mysterious camps, made them their\r\n\r\n182\r\n00:14:57,043 --> 00:15:01,056\r\nslaves. As a child, the boy had\nalways been frightened to death that he would\r\n\r\n183\r\n00:15:01,056 --> 00:15:05,060\r\nbe captured by Gypsies, and this\nchildhood fear returned when the old woman\r\n\r\n184\r\n00:15:05,006 --> 00:15:10,083\r\ntook his hands in hers.\nBut she has the Sacred Heart of Jesus there,\r\n\r\n185\r\n00:15:11,037 --> 00:15:16,065\r\nhe thought, trying to reassure\nhimself. He didn't want his hand to begin\r\n\r\n186\r\n00:15:16,065 --> 00:15:22,067\r\ntrembling, showing the old woman that\nhe was fearful. He recited an Our Father silently.\r\n\r\n187\r\n00:15:22,067 --> 00:15:29,067\r\n\"Very interesting,\" said the woman, never\ntaking her eyes from the boy's hands,\r\n\r\n188\r\n00:15:29,067 --> 00:15:36,067\r\nand then she fell silent.\nThe boy was becoming nervous. His hands began\r\n\r\n189\r\n00:15:36,068 --> 00:15:39,163\r\nto tremble, and the woman\nsensed it. He quickly pulled his hands away.\r\n\r\n190\r\n00:15:40,063 --> 00:15:43,119\r\n\"I didn't come here to have you read my palm,\"\nhe said, already regretting\r\n\r\n191\r\n00:15:44,019 --> 00:15:47,075\r\nhaving come. He thought for a moment that\nit would be better to pay her fee\r\n\r\n192\r\n00:15:47,075 --> 00:15:51,123\r\nand leave without learning a thing, that he\nwas giving too much importance to\r\n\r\n193\r\n00:15:52,023 --> 00:15:56,065\r\nhis recurrent dream.\n\"You came so that you could learn about your\r\n\r\n194\r\n00:15:56,065 --> 00:16:02,087\r\ndreams,\" said the old woman.\n\"And dreams are the language of God. When\r\n\r\n195\r\n00:16:02,087 --> 00:16:05,180\r\nhe speaks in our language, I can\ninterpret what he has said. But if he speaks\r\n\r\n196\r\n00:16:06,008 --> 00:16:12,036\r\nin the language of the soul, it is\nonly you who can understand. But, whichever\r\n\r\n197\r\n00:16:13,008 --> 00:16:16,014\r\nit is, I'm going to charge you for\nthe consultation.\"\r\n\r\n198\r\n00:16:16,068 --> 00:16:22,142\r\nAnother trick, the boy thought. But he decided\nto take a chance. A shepherd\r\n\r\n199\r\n00:16:23,042 --> 00:16:27,048\r\nalways takes his chances with wolves and with\ndrought, and that's what makes a\r\n\r\n200\r\n00:16:27,048 --> 00:16:32,141\r\nshepherd's life exciting.\n\"I have had the same dream twice,\" he said.\r\n\r\n201\r\n00:16:33,041 --> 00:16:39,125\r\n\"I dreamed that I was in a field\nwith my sheep, when a child appeared and began\r\n\r\n202\r\n00:16:40,025 --> 00:16:43,088\r\nto play with the animals. I\ndon't like people to do that, because the\r\n\r\n203\r\n00:16:43,088 --> 00:16:47,143\r\nsheep are afraid of strangers. But\nchildren always seem to be able to play with\r\n\r\n204\r\n00:16:48,043 --> 00:16:52,068\r\nthem without frightening them. I\ndon't know why. I don't know how animals know\r\n\r\n205\r\n00:16:52,068 --> 00:16:56,139\r\nthe age of human beings.\"\n\"Tell me more about your dream,\" said the\r\n\r\n206\r\n00:16:57,039 --> 00:17:00,111\r\nwoman. \"I have to get back to my\ncooking, and, since you don't have much money,\r\n\r\n207\r\n00:17:01,011 --> 00:17:06,039\r\nI can't give you a lot of time.\"\n\"The child went on playing with my sheep for\r\n\r\n208\r\n00:17:06,039 --> 00:17:11,048\r\nquite a while,\" continued the boy,\na bit upset. \"And suddenly, the child took\r\n\r\n209\r\n00:17:11,048 --> 00:17:14,123\r\nme by both hands and transported me\nto the Egyptian pyramids.\"\r\n\r\n210\r\n00:17:15,023 --> 00:17:19,078\r\nHe paused for a moment to see if the woman\nknew what the Egyptian pyramids\r\n\r\n211\r\n00:17:19,078 --> 00:17:25,155\r\nwere. But she said nothing.\n\"Then, at the Egyptian pyramids,\"--he said\r\n\r\n212\r\n00:17:26,055 --> 00:17:30,112\r\nthe last three words slowly, so that\nthe old woman would understand--\"the child\r\n\r\n213\r\n00:17:31,012 --> 00:17:37,047\r\nsaid to me, If you come here, you\nwill find a hidden treasure.' And, just as\r\n\r\n214\r\n00:17:37,047 --> 00:17:42,108\r\nshe was about to show me the exact\nlocation, I woke up. Both times.\"\r\n\r\n215\r\n00:17:43,008 --> 00:17:48,069\r\nThe woman was silent for some time. Then she\nagain took his hands and studied\r\n\r\n216\r\n00:17:48,069 --> 00:17:53,070\r\nthem carefully.\n\"I'm not going to charge you anything now,\"\r\n\r\n217\r\n00:17:53,079 --> 00:17:59,145\r\nshe said. \"But I want one-tenth of\nthe treasure, if you find it.\"\r\n\r\n218\r\n00:18:00,045 --> 00:18:04,066\r\nThe boy laughed--out of happiness. He was\ngoing to be able to save the little\r\n\r\n219\r\n00:18:04,066 --> 00:18:08,073\r\nmoney he had because of a dream about hidden\ntreasure!\r\n\r\n220\r\n00:18:08,073 --> 00:18:14,082\r\n\"Well, interpret the dream,\" he said.\n\"First, swear to me. Swear that you will give\r\n\r\n221\r\n00:18:14,082 --> 00:18:17,166\r\nme one-tenth of your treasure in\nexchange for what I am going to tell you.\"\r\n\r\n222\r\n00:18:18,066 --> 00:18:22,085\r\nThe shepherd swore that he would. The old\nwoman asked him to swear again\r\n\r\n223\r\n00:18:22,085 --> 00:18:25,107\r\nwhile looking at the image of the Sacred Heart\nof Jesus.\r\n\r\n224\r\n00:18:26,007 --> 00:18:32,025\r\n\"It's a dream in the language of the world,\"\nshe said. \"I can interpret it, but the\r\n\r\n225\r\n00:18:32,025 --> 00:18:37,026\r\ninterpretation is very difficult. That's why\nI feel that I deserve a part of what\r\n\r\n226\r\n00:18:37,035 --> 00:18:42,130\r\nyou find.\n\"And this is my interpretation: you must go\r\n\r\n227\r\n00:18:43,003 --> 00:18:49,019\r\nto the Pyramids in Egypt. I have\nnever heard of them, but, if it was a child\r\n\r\n228\r\n00:18:49,046 --> 00:18:55,050\r\nwho showed them to you, they exist.\nThere you will find a treasure that will make\r\n\r\n229\r\n00:18:55,086 --> 00:19:01,087\r\nyou a rich man.\"\nThe boy was surprised, and then irritated.\r\n\r\n230\r\n00:19:01,087 --> 00:19:05,100\r\nHe didn't need to seek out the old\nwoman for this! But then he remembered that\r\n\r\n231\r\n00:19:06,000 --> 00:19:08,000\r\nhe wasn't going to have to pay\nanything.\r\n\r\n232\r\n00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:11,017\r\n\"I didn't need to waste my time just for this,\"\nhe said.\r\n\r\n233\r\n00:19:11,017 --> 00:19:17,051\r\n\"I told you that your dream was a difficult\none. It's the simple things in life that\r\n\r\n234\r\n00:19:17,051 --> 00:19:22,060\r\nare the most extraordinary; only wise men\nare able to understand them. And\r\n\r\n235\r\n00:19:22,006 --> 00:19:27,024\r\nsince I am not wise, I have had to learn other\narts, such as the reading of\r\n\r\n236\r\n00:19:27,078 --> 00:19:30,125\r\npalms.\"\n\"Well, how am I going to get to Egypt?\"\r\n\r\n237\r\n00:19:31,025 --> 00:19:38,025\r\n\"I only interpret dreams. I don't know how\nto turn them into reality. That's why\r\n\r\n238\r\n00:19:38,039 --> 00:19:40,105\r\nI have to live off what my daughters provide\nme with.\"\r\n\r\n239\r\n00:19:41,005 --> 00:19:46,099\r\n\"And what if I never get to Egypt?\"\n\"Then I don't get paid. It wouldn't be the\r\n\r\n240\r\n00:19:46,099 --> 00:19:50,176\r\nfirst time.\"\nAnd the woman told the boy to leave, saying\r\n\r\n241\r\n00:19:51,076 --> 00:19:55,079\r\nshe had already wasted too much\ntime with him.\r\n\r\n242\r\n00:19:55,079 --> 00:19:59,177\r\nSo the boy was disappointed; he decided that\nhe would never again believe in\r\n\r\n243\r\n00:20:00,077 --> 00:20:05,118\r\ndreams. He remembered that he had a number\nof things he had to take care of:\r\n\r\n244\r\n00:20:06,018 --> 00:20:09,084\r\nhe went to the market for something to eat,\nhe traded his book for one that was\r\n\r\n245\r\n00:20:09,084 --> 00:20:13,145\r\nthicker, and he found a bench in the plaza\nwhere he could sample the new wine\r\n\r\n246\r\n00:20:14,045 --> 00:20:20,052\r\nhe had bought. The day was hot, and the wine\nwas refreshing. The sheep were\r\n\r\n247\r\n00:20:21,015 --> 00:20:25,040\r\nat the gates of the city, in a stable that\nbelonged to a friend. The boy knew a lot\r\n\r\n248\r\n00:20:25,004 --> 00:20:29,088\r\nof people in the city. That was what made\ntraveling appeal to him--he always\r\n\r\n249\r\n00:20:30,024 --> 00:20:35,032\r\nmade new friends, and he didn't need to spend\nall of his time with them. When\r\n\r\n250\r\n00:20:35,032 --> 00:20:38,054\r\nsomeone sees the same people every day, as\nhad happened with him at the\r\n\r\n251\r\n00:20:38,054 --> 00:20:42,148\r\nseminary, they wind up becoming a part of\nthat person's life. And then they\r\n\r\n252\r\n00:20:43,048 --> 00:20:48,143\r\nwant the person to change. If someone isn't\nwhat others want them to be, the\r\n\r\n253\r\n00:20:49,043 --> 00:20:54,045\r\nothers become angry. Everyone seems to have\na clear idea of how other people\r\n\r\n254\r\n00:20:54,045 --> 00:20:59,124\r\nshould lead their lives, but none about his\nor her own.\r\n\r\n255\r\n00:21:00,024 --> 00:21:04,025\r\nHe decided to wait until the sun had sunk\na bit lower in the sky before following\r\n\r\n256\r\n00:21:04,025 --> 00:21:11,025\r\nhis flock back through the fields. Three days\nfrom now, he would be with the\r\n\r\n257\r\n00:21:11,039 --> 00:21:16,100\r\nmerchant's daughter.\nHe started to read the book he had bought.\r\n\r\n258\r\n00:21:17,000 --> 00:21:21,052\r\nOn the very first page it described a\nburial ceremony. And the names of the people\r\n\r\n259\r\n00:21:21,052 --> 00:21:25,089\r\ninvolved were very difficult to\npronounce. If he ever wrote a book, he thought,\r\n\r\n260\r\n00:21:25,089 --> 00:21:27,165\r\nhe would present one person at\na time, so that the reader wouldn't have to\r\n\r\n261\r\n00:21:28,065 --> 00:21:31,139\r\nworry about memorizing a lot of\nnames.\r\n\r\n262\r\n00:21:32,039 --> 00:21:35,088\r\nWhen he was finally able to concentrate on\nwhat he was reading, he liked the\r\n\r\n263\r\n00:21:35,088 --> 00:21:40,095\r\nbook better; the burial was on a snowy day,\nand he welcomed the feeling of\r\n\r\n264\r\n00:21:40,095 --> 00:21:46,118\r\nbeing cold. As he read on, an old man sat\ndown at his side and tried to strike up\r\n\r\n265\r\n00:21:47,018 --> 00:21:52,025\r\na conversation.\n\"What are they doing?\" the old man asked,\r\n\r\n266\r\n00:21:52,025 --> 00:21:57,121\r\npointing at the people in the plaza.\n\"Working,\" the boy answered dryly, making\r\n\r\n267\r\n00:21:58,021 --> 00:22:01,024\r\nit look as if he wanted to\nconcentrate on his reading.\r\n\r\n268\r\n00:22:01,051 --> 00:22:04,127\r\nActually, he was thinking about shearing his\nsheep in front of the merchant's\r\n\r\n269\r\n00:22:05,027 --> 00:22:08,032\r\ndaughter, so that she could see that he was\nsomeone who was capable of doing\r\n\r\n270\r\n00:22:08,077 --> 00:22:14,089\r\ndifficult things. He had already imagined\nthe scene many times; every time, the\r\n\r\n271\r\n00:22:14,089 --> 00:22:17,118\r\ngirl became fascinated when he explained that\nthe sheep had to be sheared\r\n\r\n272\r\n00:22:18,018 --> 00:22:23,021\r\nfrom back to front. He also tried to remember\nsome good stories to relate as he\r\n\r\n273\r\n00:22:23,021 --> 00:22:28,074\r\nsheared the sheep. Most of them he had read\nin books, but he would tell them\r\n\r\n274\r\n00:22:28,074 --> 00:22:32,107\r\nas if they were from his personal experience.\nShe would never know the\r\n\r\n275\r\n00:22:33,007 --> 00:22:35,065\r\ndifference, because she didn't know how to\nread.\r\n\r\n276\r\n00:22:35,065 --> 00:22:40,101\r\nMeanwhile, the old man persisted in his attempt\nto strike up a conversation. He\r\n\r\n277\r\n00:22:41,001 --> 00:22:45,010\r\nsaid that he was tired and thirsty, and asked\nif he might have a sip of the boy's\r\n\r\n278\r\n00:22:45,091 --> 00:22:49,149\r\nwine. The boy offered his bottle, hoping that\nthe old man would leave him\r\n\r\n279\r\n00:22:50,049 --> 00:22:55,124\r\nalone.\nBut the old man wanted to talk, and he asked\r\n\r\n280\r\n00:22:56,024 --> 00:23:01,037\r\nthe boy what book he was\nreading. The boy was tempted to be rude, and\r\n\r\n281\r\n00:23:01,037 --> 00:23:04,056\r\nmove to another bench, but his\nfather had taught him to be respectful of\r\n\r\n282\r\n00:23:04,056 --> 00:23:09,118\r\nthe elderly. So he held out the book to\nthe man--for two reasons: first, that he,\r\n\r\n283\r\n00:23:10,018 --> 00:23:15,020\r\nhimself, wasn't sure how to pronounce\nthe title; and second, that if the old man\r\n\r\n284\r\n00:23:15,038 --> 00:23:18,127\r\ndidn't know how to read, he would\nprobably feel ashamed and decide of his own\r\n\r\n285\r\n00:23:19,027 --> 00:23:24,034\r\naccord to change benches.\n\"Hmm...\" said the old man, looking at all\r\n\r\n286\r\n00:23:24,097 --> 00:23:30,139\r\nsides of the book, as if it were some\nstrange object. \"This is an important book,\r\n\r\n287\r\n00:23:31,039 --> 00:23:37,041\r\nbut it's really irritating.\"\nThe boy was shocked. The old man knew how\r\n\r\n288\r\n00:23:37,059 --> 00:23:42,138\r\nto read, and had already read the\nbook. And if the book was irritating, as the\r\n\r\n289\r\n00:23:43,038 --> 00:23:45,109\r\nold man had said, the boy still had\ntime to change it for another.\r\n\r\n290\r\n00:23:46,009 --> 00:23:51,086\r\n\"It's a book that says the same thing almost\nall the other books in the world\r\n\r\n291\r\n00:23:51,086 --> 00:23:57,089\r\nsay,\" continued the old man. \"It describes\npeople's inability to choose their own\r\n\r\n292\r\n00:23:57,089 --> 00:24:04,089\r\ndestinies. And it ends up saying that everyone\nbelieves the world's greatest lie.\"\r\n\r\n293\r\n00:24:05,085 --> 00:24:10,109\r\n\"What's the world's greatest lie?\" the boy\nasked, completely surprised.\r\n\r\n294\r\n00:24:11,009 --> 00:24:17,083\r\n\"It's this: that at a certain point in our\nlives, we lose control of what's happening\r\n\r\n295\r\n00:24:17,083 --> 00:24:24,083\r\nto us, and our lives become controlled by\nfate. That's the world's greatest lie.\"\r\n\r\n296\r\n00:24:25,006 --> 00:24:29,011\r\n\"That's never happened to me,\" the boy said.\n\"They wanted me to be a priest,\r\n\r\n297\r\n00:24:30,001 --> 00:24:35,092\r\nbut I decided to become a shepherd.\"\n\"Much better,\" said the old man. \"Because\r\n\r\n298\r\n00:24:36,001 --> 00:24:40,079\r\nyou really like to travel.\"\n\"He knew what I was thinking,\" the boy said\r\n\r\n299\r\n00:24:40,079 --> 00:24:44,158\r\nto himself. The old man,\nmeanwhile, was leafing through the book, without\r\n\r\n300\r\n00:24:45,058 --> 00:24:48,155\r\nseeming to want to return it\nat all. The boy noticed that the man's clothing\r\n\r\n301\r\n00:24:49,055 --> 00:24:55,097\r\nwas strange. He looked like an\nArab, which was not unusual in those parts.\r\n\r\n302\r\n00:24:55,097 --> 00:24:59,132\r\nAfrica was only a few hours from\nTarifa; one had only to cross the narrow straits\r\n\r\n303\r\n00:25:00,032 --> 00:25:05,051\r\nby boat. Arabs often appeared in\nthe city, shopping and chanting their strange\r\n\r\n304\r\n00:25:05,051 --> 00:25:09,089\r\nprayers several times a day.\n\"Where are you from?\" the boy asked.\r\n\r\n305\r\n00:25:09,089 --> 00:25:13,180\r\n\"From many places.\"\n\"No one can be from many places,\" the boy\r\n\r\n306\r\n00:25:14,008 --> 00:25:18,070\r\nsaid. \"I'm a shepherd, and I have\nbeen to many places, but I come from only\r\n\r\n307\r\n00:25:19,042 --> 00:25:25,098\r\none place--from a city near an\nancient castle. That's where I was born.\"\r\n\r\n308\r\n00:25:25,098 --> 00:25:30,107\r\n\"Well then, we could say that I was born in\nSalem.\"\r\n\r\n309\r\n00:25:31,007 --> 00:25:34,046\r\nThe boy didn't know where Salem was, but he\ndidn't want to ask, fearing that he\r\n\r\n310\r\n00:25:34,046 --> 00:25:39,112\r\nwould appear ignorant. He looked at the people\nin the plaza for a while; they\r\n\r\n311\r\n00:25:40,012 --> 00:25:44,074\r\nwere coming and going, and all of them seemed\nto be very busy.\r\n\r\n312\r\n00:25:44,074 --> 00:25:50,133\r\n\"So, what is Salem like?\" he asked, trying\nto get some sort of clue.\r\n\r\n313\r\n00:25:51,033 --> 00:25:57,108\r\n\"It's like it always has been.\"\nNo clue yet. But he knew that Salem wasn't\r\n\r\n314\r\n00:25:58,008 --> 00:26:03,090\r\nin Andalusia. If it were, he would\nalready have heard of it.\r\n\r\n315\r\n00:26:03,009 --> 00:26:10,009\r\n\"And what do you do in Salem?\" he insisted.\n\"What do I do in Salem?\" The old man laughed.\r\n\r\n316\r\n00:26:11,001 --> 00:26:18,001\r\n\"Well, I'm the king of Salem!\"\nPeople say strange things, the boy thought.\r\n\r\n317\r\n00:26:19,067 --> 00:26:22,126\r\nSometimes it's better to be with the\nsheep, who don't say anything. And better\r\n\r\n318\r\n00:26:23,026 --> 00:26:27,112\r\nstill to be alone with one's books.\nThey tell their incredible stories at the\r\n\r\n319\r\n00:26:28,012 --> 00:26:32,111\r\ntime when you want to hear them. But\nwhen you're talking to people, they say some\r\n\r\n320\r\n00:26:33,011 --> 00:26:37,082\r\nthings that are so strange that\nyou don't know how to continue the conversation.\r\n\r\n321\r\n00:26:37,082 --> 00:26:43,168\r\n\"My name is Melchizedek,\" said the old man.\n\"How many sheep do you have?\"\r\n\r\n322\r\n00:26:44,068 --> 00:26:49,197\r\n\"Enough,\" said the boy. He could see that\nthe old man wanted to know more\r\n\r\n323\r\n00:26:49,809 --> 00:26:55,850\r\nabout his life.\n\"Well, then, we've got a problem. I can't\r\n\r\n324\r\n00:26:55,085 --> 00:26:58,173\r\nhelp you if you feel you've got enough\nsheep.\"\r\n\r\n325\r\n00:26:59,073 --> 00:27:04,094\r\nThe boy was getting irritated. He wasn't asking\nfor help. It was the old man who\r\n\r\n326\r\n00:27:04,094 --> 00:27:07,170\r\nhad asked for a drink of his wine, and had\nstarted the conversation.\r\n\r\n327\r\n00:27:08,007 --> 00:27:12,033\r\n\"Give me my book,\" the boy said. \"I have to\ngo and gather my sheep and get\r\n\r\n328\r\n00:27:12,096 --> 00:27:15,105\r\ngoing.\"\n\"Give me one-tenth of your sheep,\" said the\r\n\r\n329\r\n00:27:16,086 --> 00:27:21,174\r\nold man, \"and I'll tell you how to\nfind the hidden treasure.\"\r\n\r\n330\r\n00:27:22,074 --> 00:27:26,162\r\nThe boy remembered his dream, and suddenly\neverything was clear to him. The\r\n\r\n331\r\n00:27:27,062 --> 00:27:31,128\r\nold woman hadn't charged him anything, but\nthe old man--maybe he was her\r\n\r\n332\r\n00:27:32,028 --> 00:27:35,083\r\nhusband--was going to find a way to get much\nmore money in exchange for\r\n\r\n333\r\n00:27:35,083 --> 00:27:40,091\r\ninformation about something that didn't even\nexist. The old man was probably a\r\n\r\n334\r\n00:27:41,063 --> 00:27:45,102\r\nGypsy, too.\nBut before the boy could say anything, the\r\n\r\n335\r\n00:27:46,002 --> 00:27:52,004\r\nold man leaned over, picked up a\nstick, and began to write in the sand of the\r\n\r\n336\r\n00:27:52,004 --> 00:27:58,015\r\nplaza. Something bright reflected\nfrom his chest with such intensity that the\r\n\r\n337\r\n00:27:58,015 --> 00:28:03,018\r\nboy was momentarily blinded. With a\nmovement that was too quick for someone his\r\n\r\n338\r\n00:28:03,045 --> 00:28:08,083\r\nage, the man covered whatever\nit was with his cape. When his vision returned\r\n\r\n339\r\n00:28:08,083 --> 00:28:14,107\r\nto normal, the boy was able to\nread what the old man had written in the sand.\r\n\r\n340\r\n00:28:15,007 --> 00:28:22,007\r\nThere, in the sand of the plaza of that small\ncity, the boy read the names of his\r\n\r\n341\r\n00:28:22,044 --> 00:28:28,046\r\nfather and his mother and the name of the\nseminary he had attended. He read\r\n\r\n342\r\n00:28:28,064 --> 00:28:33,158\r\nthe name of the merchant's daughter, which\nhe hadn't even known, and he read\r\n\r\n343\r\n00:28:34,058 --> 00:28:37,067\r\nthings he had never told anyone.\n*\r\n\r\n344\r\n00:28:37,067 --> 00:28:44,067\r\n\"I'm the king of Salem,\" the old man had said.\n\"Why would a king be talking with a shepherd?\"\r\n\r\n345\r\n00:28:46,002 --> 00:28:48,085\r\nthe boy asked, awed and\nembarrassed.\r\n\r\n346\r\n00:28:48,085 --> 00:28:52,150\r\n\"For several reasons. But let's say that the\nmost important is that you have\r\n\r\n347\r\n00:28:53,005 --> 00:28:59,087\r\nsucceeded in discovering your Personal Legend.\"\nThe boy didn't know what a person's \"Personal\r\n\r\n348\r\n00:29:00,032 --> 00:29:05,641\r\nLegend\" was.\n\"It's what you have always wanted to accomplish.\r\n\r\n349\r\n00:29:05,929 --> 00:29:10,190\r\nEveryone, when they are\nyoung, knows what their Personal Legend is.\r\n\r\n350\r\n00:29:10,019 --> 00:29:15,098\r\n\"At that point in their lives, everything\nis clear and everything is possible. They\r\n\r\n351\r\n00:29:15,098 --> 00:29:18,192\r\nare not afraid to dream, and to yearn for\neverything they would like to see\r\n\r\n352\r\n00:29:19,092 --> 00:29:24,176\r\nhappen to them in their lives. But, as time\npasses, a mysterious force begins to\r\n\r\n353\r\n00:29:25,076 --> 00:29:32,076\r\nconvince them that it will be impossible for\nthem to realize their Personal Legend.\"\r\n\r\n354\r\n00:29:33,032 --> 00:29:37,063\r\nNone of what the old man was saying made much\nsense to the boy. But he\r\n\r\n355\r\n00:29:37,063 --> 00:29:42,362\r\nwanted to know what the \"mysterious force\"\nwas; the merchant's daughter\r\n\r\n356\r\n00:29:42,929 --> 00:29:45,490\r\nwould be impressed when he told her about\nthat!\r\n\r\n357\r\n00:29:45,049 --> 00:29:52,049\r\n\"It's a force that appears to be negative,\nbut actually shows you how to realize\r\n\r\n358\r\n00:29:52,052 --> 00:29:57,149\r\nyour Personal Legend. It prepares your spirit\nand your will, because there is one great\r\n\r\n359\r\n00:29:58,049 --> 00:30:04,120\r\ntruth on this planet: whoever you are, or\nwhatever it is that you do, when you\r\n\r\n360\r\n00:30:05,002 --> 00:30:12,002\r\nreally want something, it's because that desire\noriginated in the soul of the\r\n\r\n361\r\n00:30:12,022 --> 00:30:19,022\r\nuniverse. It's your mission on earth.\"\n\"Even when all you want to do is travel? Or\r\n\r\n362\r\n00:30:19,088 --> 00:30:21,152\r\nmarry the daughter of a textile\nmerchant?\"\r\n\r\n363\r\n00:30:22,052 --> 00:30:29,052\r\n\"Yes, or even search for treasure. The Soul\nof the World is nourished by\r\n\r\n364\r\n00:30:30,008 --> 00:30:36,101\r\npeople's happiness. And also by unhappiness,\nenvy, and jealousy. To realize\r\n\r\n365\r\n00:30:37,001 --> 00:30:44,001\r\none's Personal Legend is a person's only real\nobligation. All things are one.\r\n\r\n366\r\n00:30:44,025 --> 00:30:50,834\r\n\"And, when you want something, all the universe\nconspires in helping you to\r\n\r\n367\r\n00:30:51,059 --> 00:30:56,980\r\nachieve it.\"\nThey were both silent for a time, observing\r\n\r\n368\r\n00:30:56,098 --> 00:31:01,155\r\nthe plaza and the townspeople. It\nwas the old man who spoke first.\r\n\r\n369\r\n00:31:02,055 --> 00:31:08,104\r\n\"Why do you tend a flock of sheep?\"\n\"Because I like to travel.\"\r\n\r\n370\r\n00:31:09,004 --> 00:31:12,079\r\nThe old man pointed to a baker standing in\nhis shop window at one corner of\r\n\r\n371\r\n00:31:12,079 --> 00:31:19,079\r\nthe plaza. \"When he was a child, that man\nwanted to travel, too. But he decided\r\n\r\n372\r\n00:31:21,041 --> 00:31:27,116\r\nfirst to buy his bakery and put some money\naside. When he's an old man, he's\r\n\r\n373\r\n00:31:28,016 --> 00:31:35,016\r\ngoing to spend a month in Africa. He never\nrealized that people are capable, at\r\n\r\n374\r\n00:31:35,006 --> 00:31:38,087\r\nany time in their lives, of doing what they\ndream of.\"\r\n\r\n375\r\n00:31:39,041 --> 00:31:42,128\r\n\"He should have decided to become a shepherd,\"\nthe boy said.\r\n\r\n376\r\n00:31:43,028 --> 00:31:48,044\r\n\"Well, he thought about that,\" the old man\nsaid. \"But bakers are more important\r\n\r\n377\r\n00:31:48,044 --> 00:31:52,120\r\npeople than shepherds. Bakers have homes,\nwhile shepherds sleep out in the\r\n\r\n378\r\n00:31:53,002 --> 00:31:59,231\r\nopen. Parents would rather see their children\nmarry bakers than shepherds.\"\r\n\r\n379\r\n00:31:59,429 --> 00:32:04,000\r\nThe boy felt a pang in his heart, thinking\nabout the merchant's daughter. There\r\n\r\n380\r\n00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:10,083\r\nwas surely a baker in her town.\nThe old man continued, \"In the long run, what\r\n\r\n381\r\n00:32:10,083 --> 00:32:14,144\r\npeople think about shepherds and\nbakers becomes more important for them than\r\n\r\n382\r\n00:32:15,044 --> 00:32:21,047\r\ntheir own destinies.\"\nThe old man leafed through the book, and fell\r\n\r\n383\r\n00:32:21,047 --> 00:32:26,084\r\nto reading a page he came to.\nThe boy waited, and then interrupted the old\r\n\r\n384\r\n00:32:26,084 --> 00:32:31,053\r\nman just as he himself had been\ninterrupted. \"Why are you telling me all this?\"\r\n\r\n385\r\n00:32:31,809 --> 00:32:37,884\r\n\"Because you are trying to realize your Personal\nLegend. And you are at the point where\r\n\r\n386\r\n00:32:38,559 --> 00:32:44,630\r\nyou're about to give it all up.\"\n\"And that's when you always appear on the\r\n\r\n387\r\n00:32:44,063 --> 00:32:47,145\r\nscene?\"\n\"Not always in this way, but I always appear\r\n\r\n388\r\n00:32:48,045 --> 00:32:54,109\r\nin one form or another. Sometimes\nI appear in the form of a solution, or a good\r\n\r\n389\r\n00:32:55,009 --> 00:33:01,070\r\nidea. At other times, at a crucial\nmoment, I make it easier for things to happen.\r\n\r\n390\r\n00:33:01,007 --> 00:33:06,091\r\nThere are other things I do, too,\nbut most of the time people don't realize\r\n\r\n391\r\n00:33:07,054 --> 00:33:12,070\r\nI've done them.\"\nThe old man related that, the week before,\r\n\r\n392\r\n00:33:12,007 --> 00:33:18,056\r\nhe had been forced to appear before\na miner, and had taken the form of a stone.\r\n\r\n393\r\n00:33:19,019 --> 00:33:23,054\r\nThe miner had abandoned\neverything to go mining for emeralds. For\r\n\r\n394\r\n00:33:23,054 --> 00:33:27,123\r\nfive years he had been working a\ncertain river, and had examined hundreds of\r\n\r\n395\r\n00:33:28,023 --> 00:33:33,040\r\nthousands of stones looking for an\nemerald. The miner was about to give it all\r\n\r\n396\r\n00:33:33,004 --> 00:33:37,533\r\nup, right at the point when, if he\nwere to examine just one more stone--just\r\n\r\n397\r\n00:33:37,929 --> 00:33:44,410\r\none more--he would find his emerald.\nSince the miner had sacrificed everything\r\n\r\n398\r\n00:33:44,041 --> 00:33:46,114\r\nto his Personal Legend, the old man decided\nto\r\n\r\n399\r\n00:33:47,014 --> 00:33:53,053\r\nbecome involved. He transformed himself into\na stone that rolled up to the\r\n\r\n400\r\n00:33:53,053 --> 00:33:58,952\r\nminer's foot. The miner, with all the anger\nand frustration of his five fruitless\r\n\r\n401\r\n00:33:59,429 --> 00:34:04,710\r\nyears, picked up the stone and threw it aside.\nBut he had thrown it with such\r\n\r\n402\r\n00:34:04,071 --> 00:34:09,290\r\nforce that it broke the stone it fell upon,\nand there, embedded in the broken\r\n\r\n403\r\n00:34:09,929 --> 00:34:13,948\r\nstone, was the most beautiful emerald in the\nworld.\r\n\r\n404\r\n00:34:14,119 --> 00:34:20,020\r\n\"People learn, early in their lives, what\nis their reason for being,\" said the old\r\n\r\n405\r\n00:34:20,002 --> 00:34:25,021\r\nman, with a certain bitterness. \"Maybe that's\nwhy they give up on it so early,\r\n\r\n406\r\n00:34:25,021 --> 00:34:30,740\r\ntoo. But that's the way it is.\"\nThe boy reminded the old man that he had said\r\n\r\n407\r\n00:34:30,929 --> 00:34:33,510\r\nsomething about hidden\ntreasure.\r\n\r\n408\r\n00:34:33,051 --> 00:34:39,079\r\n\"Treasure is uncovered by the force of flowing\nwater, and it is buried by the\r\n\r\n409\r\n00:34:39,079 --> 00:34:43,086\r\nsame currents,\" said the old man. \"If you\nwant to learn about your own\r\n\r\n410\r\n00:34:44,049 --> 00:34:47,126\r\ntreasure, you will have to give me one-tenth\nof your flock.\"\r\n\r\n411\r\n00:34:48,026 --> 00:34:55,026\r\n\"What about one-tenth of my treasure?\"\nThe old man looked disappointed. \"If you start\r\n\r\n412\r\n00:34:56,095 --> 00:35:00,116\r\nout by promising what you don't\neven have yet, you'll lose your desire to\r\n\r\n413\r\n00:35:01,016 --> 00:35:05,048\r\nwork toward getting it.\"\nThe boy told him that he had already promised\r\n\r\n414\r\n00:35:05,048 --> 00:35:07,056\r\nto give one-tenth of his treasure\nto the Gypsy.\r\n\r\n415\r\n00:35:07,056 --> 00:35:13,082\r\n\"Gypsies are experts at getting people to\ndo that,\" sighed the old man. \"In any\r\n\r\n416\r\n00:35:13,082 --> 00:35:18,140\r\ncase, it's good that you've learned that everything\nin life has its price. This is\r\n\r\n417\r\n00:35:19,004 --> 00:35:25,022\r\nwhat the Warriors of the Light try to teach.\"\nThe old man returned the book to the boy.\r\n\r\n418\r\n00:35:25,058 --> 00:35:32,058\r\n\"Tomorrow, at this same time, bring me a tenth\nof your flock. And I will tell you\r\n\r\n419\r\n00:35:33,046 --> 00:35:40,046\r\nhow to find the hidden treasure. Good afternoon.\"\nAnd he vanished around the corner of the plaza.\r\n\r\n420\r\n00:35:42,008 --> 00:35:44,025\r\n*\nThe boy began again to read his book, but\r\n\r\n421\r\n00:35:44,097 --> 00:35:48,123\r\nhe was no longer able to\nconcentrate. He was tense and upset, because\r\n\r\n422\r\n00:35:49,023 --> 00:35:52,101\r\nhe knew that the old man was\nright. He went over to the bakery and bought\r\n\r\n423\r\n00:35:53,001 --> 00:35:57,002\r\na loaf of bread, thinking about\nwhether or not he should tell the baker what\r\n\r\n424\r\n00:35:57,002 --> 00:36:01,053\r\nthe old man had said about him.\nSometimes it's better to leave things as they\r\n\r\n425\r\n00:36:01,053 --> 00:36:05,057\r\nare, he thought to himself, and\ndecided to say nothing. If he were to say\r\n\r\n426\r\n00:36:05,093 --> 00:36:08,169\r\nanything, the baker would spend three\ndays thinking about giving it all up, even\r\n\r\n427\r\n00:36:09,069 --> 00:36:13,098\r\nthough he had gotten used to the way\nthings were. The boy could certainly resist\r\n\r\n428\r\n00:36:13,098 --> 00:36:19,122\r\ncausing that kind of anxiety for the\nbaker. So he began to wander through the city,\r\n\r\n429\r\n00:36:20,022 --> 00:36:26,049\r\nand found himself at the gates.\nThere was a small building there, with a window\r\n\r\n430\r\n00:36:26,049 --> 00:36:32,052\r\nat which people bought tickets\nto Africa. And he knew that Egypt was in Africa.\r\n\r\n431\r\n00:36:32,052 --> 00:36:37,066\r\n\"Can I help you?\" asked the man behind the\nwindow.\r\n\r\n432\r\n00:36:37,066 --> 00:36:44,066\r\n\"Maybe tomorrow,\" said the boy, moving away.\nIf he sold just one of his sheep,\r\n\r\n433\r\n00:36:44,078 --> 00:36:48,150\r\nhe'd have enough to get to the other shore\nof the strait. The idea frightened\r\n\r\n434\r\n00:36:49,005 --> 00:36:53,009\r\nhim.\n\"Another dreamer,\" said the ticket seller\r\n\r\n435\r\n00:36:53,054 --> 00:36:58,105\r\nto his assistant, watching the boy walk\naway. \"He doesn't have enough money to travel.\"\r\n\r\n436\r\n00:36:59,005 --> 00:37:03,070\r\nWhile standing at the ticket window, the boy\nhad remembered his flock, and\r\n\r\n437\r\n00:37:03,007 --> 00:37:07,070\r\ndecided he should go back to being a shepherd.\nIn two years he had learned\r\n\r\n438\r\n00:37:08,033 --> 00:37:12,119\r\neverything about shepherding: he knew how\nto shear sheep, how to care for\r\n\r\n439\r\n00:37:13,019 --> 00:37:17,108\r\npregnant ewes, and how to protect the sheep\nfrom wolves. He knew all the\r\n\r\n440\r\n00:37:18,008 --> 00:37:23,059\r\nfields and pastures of Andalusia. And he knew\nwhat was the fair price for every\r\n\r\n441\r\n00:37:23,059 --> 00:37:28,104\r\none of his animals.\nHe decided to return to his friend's stable\r\n\r\n442\r\n00:37:29,004 --> 00:37:35,043\r\nby the longest route possible. As he\nwalked past the city's castle, he interrupted\r\n\r\n443\r\n00:37:35,043 --> 00:37:39,131\r\nhis return, and climbed the stone\nramp that led to the top of the wall. From\r\n\r\n444\r\n00:37:40,031 --> 00:37:46,046\r\nthere, he could see Africa in the\ndistance. Someone had once told him that it\r\n\r\n445\r\n00:37:46,046 --> 00:37:51,124\r\nwas from there that the Moors had\ncome, to occupy all of Spain.\r\n\r\n446\r\n00:37:52,024 --> 00:37:56,095\r\nHe could see almost the entire city from where\nhe sat, including the plaza where\r\n\r\n447\r\n00:37:56,095 --> 00:38:00,122\r\nhe had talked with the old man. Curse the\nmoment I met that old man, he\r\n\r\n448\r\n00:38:01,022 --> 00:38:05,038\r\nthought. He had come to the town only to find\na woman who could interpret his\r\n\r\n449\r\n00:38:05,038 --> 00:38:09,071\r\ndream. Neither the woman nor the old man were\nat all impressed by the fact\r\n\r\n450\r\n00:38:09,071 --> 00:38:13,127\r\nthat he was a shepherd. They were solitary\nindividuals who no longer believed\r\n\r\n451\r\n00:38:14,027 --> 00:38:18,108\r\nin things, and didn't understand that shepherds\nbecome attached to their sheep.\r\n\r\n452\r\n00:38:19,008 --> 00:38:22,049\r\nHe knew everything about each member of his\nflock: he knew which ones were\r\n\r\n453\r\n00:38:22,049 --> 00:38:25,100\r\nlame, which one was to give birth two months\nfrom now, and which were the\r\n\r\n454\r\n00:38:26,000 --> 00:38:30,091\r\nlaziest. He knew how to shear them, and how\nto slaughter them. If he ever\r\n\r\n455\r\n00:38:30,091 --> 00:38:37,091\r\ndecided to leave them, they would suffer.\nThe wind began to pick up. He knew that wind:\r\n\r\n456\r\n00:38:38,058 --> 00:38:42,110\r\npeople called it the levanter,\nbecause on it the Moors had come from the\r\n\r\n457\r\n00:38:43,001 --> 00:38:44,068\r\nLevant at the eastern end of the\nMediterranean.\r\n\r\n458\r\n00:38:44,077 --> 00:38:51,077\r\nThe levanter increased in intensity. Here\nI am, between my flock and my\r\n\r\n459\r\n00:38:51,093 --> 00:38:56,149\r\ntreasure, the boy thought. He had to choose\nbetween something he had become\r\n\r\n460\r\n00:38:57,049 --> 00:39:01,140\r\naccustomed to and something he wanted to have.\nThere was also the merchant's\r\n\r\n461\r\n00:39:02,004 --> 00:39:06,069\r\ndaughter, but she wasn't as important as his\nflock, because she didn't depend on\r\n\r\n462\r\n00:39:07,005 --> 00:39:11,088\r\nhim. Maybe she didn't even remember him. He\nwas sure that it made no\r\n\r\n463\r\n00:39:11,088 --> 00:39:17,116\r\ndifference to her on which day he appeared:\nfor her, every day was the same,\r\n\r\n464\r\n00:39:18,016 --> 00:39:22,050\r\nand when each day is the same as the next,\nit's because people fail to recognize\r\n\r\n465\r\n00:39:22,005 --> 00:39:26,069\r\nthe good things that happen in their lives\nevery day that the sun rises.\r\n\r\n466\r\n00:39:27,014 --> 00:39:32,028\r\nI left my father, my mother, and the town\ncastle behind. They have gotten used\r\n\r\n467\r\n00:39:32,028 --> 00:39:37,119\r\nto my being away, and so have I. The sheep\nwill get used to my not being\r\n\r\n468\r\n00:39:38,019 --> 00:39:44,081\r\nthere, too, the boy thought.\nFrom where he sat, he could observe the plaza.\r\n\r\n469\r\n00:39:44,081 --> 00:39:48,085\r\nPeople continued to come and\ngo from the baker's shop. A young couple sat\r\n\r\n470\r\n00:39:48,085 --> 00:39:51,604\r\non the bench where he had talked\nwith the old man, and they kissed.\r\n\r\n471\r\n00:39:52,369 --> 00:39:58,760\r\n\"That baker...\" he said to himself, without\ncompleting the thought. The levanter\r\n\r\n472\r\n00:39:58,076 --> 00:40:03,142\r\nwas still getting stronger, and he felt its\nforce on his face. That wind had\r\n\r\n473\r\n00:40:04,042 --> 00:40:08,115\r\nbrought the Moors, yes, but it had also brought\nthe smell of the desert and of\r\n\r\n474\r\n00:40:09,015 --> 00:40:14,464\r\nveiled women. It had brought with it the sweat\nand the dreams of men who had\r\n\r\n475\r\n00:40:14,599 --> 00:40:21,150\r\nonce left to search for the unknown, and for\ngold and adventure--and for the\r\n\r\n476\r\n00:40:21,015 --> 00:40:26,079\r\nPyramids. The boy felt jealous of the freedom\nof the wind, and saw that he\r\n\r\n477\r\n00:40:26,079 --> 00:40:30,121\r\ncould have the same freedom. There was nothing\nto hold him back except\r\n\r\n478\r\n00:40:31,021 --> 00:40:36,047\r\nhimself. The sheep, the merchant's daughter,\nand the fields of Andalusia were\r\n\r\n479\r\n00:40:36,047 --> 00:40:43,047\r\nonly steps along the way to his Personal Legend.\nThe next day, the boy met the old man at noon.\r\n\r\n480\r\n00:40:46,000 --> 00:40:51,002\r\nHe brought six sheep with him.\n\"I'm surprised,\" the boy said. \"My friend\r\n\r\n481\r\n00:40:51,002 --> 00:40:54,581\r\nbought all the other sheep\nimmediately. He said that he had always dreamed\r\n\r\n482\r\n00:40:54,599 --> 00:40:57,510\r\nof being a shepherd, and\nthat it was a good omen.\"\r\n\r\n483\r\n00:40:57,051 --> 00:41:04,051\r\n\"That's the way it always is,\" said the old\nman. \"It's called the principle of\r\n\r\n484\r\n00:41:04,599 --> 00:41:11,080\r\nfavorability. When you play cards the first\ntime, you are almost sure to win.\r\n\r\n485\r\n00:41:11,008 --> 00:41:12,101\r\nBeginner's luck.\"\n\"Why is that?\"\r\n\r\n486\r\n00:41:13,001 --> 00:41:19,017\r\n\"Because there is a force that wants you to\nrealize your Personal Legend; it whets your\r\n\r\n487\r\n00:41:19,017 --> 00:41:25,105\r\nappetite with a taste of success.\"\nThen the old man began to inspect the sheep,\r\n\r\n488\r\n00:41:26,005 --> 00:41:30,016\r\nand he saw that one was lame.\nThe boy explained that it wasn't important,\r\n\r\n489\r\n00:41:30,016 --> 00:41:33,079\r\nsince that sheep was the most\nintelligent of the flock, and produced the\r\n\r\n490\r\n00:41:33,079 --> 00:41:36,156\r\nmost wool.\n\"Where is the treasure?\" he asked.\r\n\r\n491\r\n00:41:37,056 --> 00:41:44,056\r\n\"It's in Egypt, near the Pyramids.\"\nThe boy was startled. The old woman had said\r\n\r\n492\r\n00:41:45,003 --> 00:41:48,078\r\nthe same thing. But she hadn't\ncharged him anything.\r\n\r\n493\r\n00:41:49,005 --> 00:41:54,066\r\n\"In order to find the treasure, you will have\nto follow the omens. God has\r\n\r\n494\r\n00:41:54,066 --> 00:42:00,071\r\nprepared a path for everyone to follow. You\njust have to read the omens that he\r\n\r\n495\r\n00:42:01,016 --> 00:42:06,032\r\nleft for you.\"\nBefore the boy could reply, a butterfly appeared\r\n\r\n496\r\n00:42:06,032 --> 00:42:10,091\r\nand fluttered between him and\nthe old man. He remembered something his grandfather\r\n\r\n497\r\n00:42:10,091 --> 00:42:15,150\r\nhad once told him: that\nbutterflies were a good omen. Like crickets,\r\n\r\n498\r\n00:42:16,005 --> 00:42:20,604\r\nand like expectations; like lizards\nand four-leaf clovers.\r\n\r\n499\r\n00:42:21,099 --> 00:42:27,750\r\n\"That's right,\" said the old man, able to\nread the boy's thoughts. \"Just as your\r\n\r\n500\r\n00:42:27,075 --> 00:42:34,075\r\ngrandfather taught you. These are good omens.\"\nThe old man opened his cape, and the boy was\r\n\r\n501\r\n00:42:35,059 --> 00:42:41,094\r\nstruck by what he saw. The old\nman wore a breastplate of heavy gold, covered\r\n\r\n502\r\n00:42:41,094 --> 00:42:45,121\r\nwith precious stones. The boy\nrecalled the brilliance he had noticed on\r\n\r\n503\r\n00:42:46,021 --> 00:42:51,079\r\nthe previous day.\nHe really was a king! He must be disguised\r\n\r\n504\r\n00:42:51,079 --> 00:42:57,105\r\nto avoid encounters with thieves.\n\"Take these,\" said the old man, holding out\r\n\r\n505\r\n00:42:58,005 --> 00:43:03,021\r\na white stone and a black stone that\nhad been embedded at the center of the breastplate.\r\n\r\n506\r\n00:43:03,021 --> 00:43:09,094\r\n\"They are called Urim and\nThummim. The black signifies 'yes,' and the\r\n\r\n507\r\n00:43:09,094 --> 00:43:16,094\r\nwhite 'no.' When you are unable to\nread the omens, they will help you to do so.\r\n\r\n508\r\n00:43:17,004 --> 00:43:24,004\r\nAlways ask an objective question.\n\"But, if you can, try to make your own decisions.\r\n\r\n509\r\n00:43:25,007 --> 00:43:29,082\r\nThe treasure is at the\nPyramids; that you already knew. But I had\r\n\r\n510\r\n00:43:30,045 --> 00:43:36,444\r\nto insist on the payment of six\nsheep because I helped you to make your decision.\"\r\n\r\n511\r\n00:43:36,849 --> 00:43:43,020\r\nThe boy put the stones in his pouch. From\nthen on, he would make his own\r\n\r\n512\r\n00:43:43,002 --> 00:43:47,026\r\ndecisions.\n\"Don't forget that everything you deal with\r\n\r\n513\r\n00:43:47,026 --> 00:43:52,053\r\nis only one thing and nothing else.\nAnd don't forget the language of omens. And,\r\n\r\n514\r\n00:43:52,053 --> 00:43:57,102\r\nabove all, don't forget to follow\nyour Personal Legend through to its conclusion.\r\n\r\n515\r\n00:43:58,002 --> 00:44:03,050\r\n\"But before I go, I want to tell you a little\nstory.\r\n\r\n516\r\n00:44:03,005 --> 00:44:08,013\r\n\"A certain shopkeeper sent his son to learn\nabout the secret of happiness from\r\n\r\n517\r\n00:44:08,058 --> 00:44:13,100\r\nthe wisest man in the world. The lad wandered\nthrough the desert for forty\r\n\r\n518\r\n00:44:14,000 --> 00:44:19,083\r\ndays, and finally came upon a beautiful castle,\nhigh atop a mountain. It was\r\n\r\n519\r\n00:44:19,083 --> 00:44:25,104\r\nthere that the wise man lived.\n\"Rather than finding a saintly man, though,\r\n\r\n520\r\n00:44:26,004 --> 00:44:31,067\r\nour hero, on entering the main room\nof the castle, saw a hive of activity: tradesmen\r\n\r\n521\r\n00:44:31,067 --> 00:44:34,131\r\ncame and went, people were\nconversing in the corners, a small orchestra\r\n\r\n522\r\n00:44:35,031 --> 00:44:39,057\r\nwas playing soft music, and there\nwas a table covered with platters of the most\r\n\r\n523\r\n00:44:39,057 --> 00:44:45,124\r\ndelicious food in that part of the\nworld. The wise man conversed with everyone,\r\n\r\n524\r\n00:44:46,024 --> 00:44:50,383\r\nand the boy had to wait for two\nhours before it was his turn to be given the\r\n\r\n525\r\n00:44:50,599 --> 00:44:55,420\r\nman's attention.\n\"The wise man listened attentively to the\r\n\r\n526\r\n00:44:55,042 --> 00:44:59,139\r\nboy's explanation of why he had\ncome, but told him that he didn't have time\r\n\r\n527\r\n00:45:00,039 --> 00:45:06,044\r\njust then to explain the secret of\nhappiness. He suggested that the boy look\r\n\r\n528\r\n00:45:06,044 --> 00:45:11,047\r\naround the palace and return in two\nhours.\r\n\r\n529\r\n00:45:11,047 --> 00:45:16,072\r\n\" 'Meanwhile, I want to ask you to do something,'\nsaid the wise man, handing\r\n\r\n530\r\n00:45:16,072 --> 00:45:22,077\r\nthe boy a teaspoon that held two drops of\noil. 'As you wander around, carry this\r\n\r\n531\r\n00:45:23,022 --> 00:45:27,671\r\nspoon with you without allowing the oil to\nspill.'\r\n\r\n532\r\n00:45:27,869 --> 00:45:33,290\r\n\"The boy began climbing and descending the\nmany stairways of the palace,\r\n\r\n533\r\n00:45:33,029 --> 00:45:39,050\r\nkeeping his eyes fixed on the spoon. After\ntwo hours, he returned to the room\r\n\r\n534\r\n00:45:39,005 --> 00:45:44,011\r\nwhere the wise man was.\n\" 'Well,' asked the wise man, 'did you see\r\n\r\n535\r\n00:45:44,056 --> 00:45:47,120\r\nthe Persian tapestries that are\nhanging in my dining hall? Did you see the\r\n\r\n536\r\n00:45:48,002 --> 00:45:52,027\r\ngarden that it took the master\ngardener ten years to create? Did you notice\r\n\r\n537\r\n00:45:52,045 --> 00:45:54,127\r\nthe beautiful parchments in my\nlibrary?'\r\n\r\n538\r\n00:45:55,027 --> 00:46:02,027\r\n\"The boy was embarrassed, and confessed that\nhe had observed nothing. His\r\n\r\n539\r\n00:46:02,049 --> 00:46:06,133\r\nonly concern had been not to spill the oil\nthat the wise man had entrusted to\r\n\r\n540\r\n00:46:07,033 --> 00:46:11,822\r\nhim.\n\" 'Then go back and observe the marvels of\r\n\r\n541\r\n00:46:12,119 --> 00:46:18,980\r\nmy world,' said the wise man. 'You\ncannot trust a man if you don't know his house.'\r\n\r\n542\r\n00:46:18,098 --> 00:46:23,165\r\n\"Relieved, the boy picked up the spoon and\nreturned to his exploration of the\r\n\r\n543\r\n00:46:24,065 --> 00:46:30,534\r\npalace, this time observing all of the works\nof art on the ceilings and the walls.\r\n\r\n544\r\n00:46:31,119 --> 00:46:36,143\r\nHe saw the gardens, the mountains all around\nhim, the beauty of the flowers,\r\n\r\n545\r\n00:46:36,359 --> 00:46:42,080\r\nand the taste with which everything had been\nselected. Upon returning to the\r\n\r\n546\r\n00:46:42,008 --> 00:46:47,066\r\nwise man, he related in detail everything\nhe had seen.\r\n\r\n547\r\n00:46:47,066 --> 00:46:51,158\r\n\" 'But where are the drops of oil I entrusted\nto you?' asked the wise man.\r\n\r\n548\r\n00:46:52,058 --> 00:46:58,114\r\n\"Looking down at the spoon he held, the boy\nsaw that the oil was gone.\r\n\r\n549\r\n00:46:59,014 --> 00:47:04,020\r\n\" 'Well, there is only one piece of advice\nI can give you,' said the wisest of wise\r\n\r\n550\r\n00:47:04,074 --> 00:47:11,074\r\nmen. 'The secret of happiness is to see all\nthe marvels of the world, and never\r\n\r\n551\r\n00:47:13,031 --> 00:47:17,082\r\nto forget the drops of oil on the spoon.'\n\"\r\n\r\n552\r\n00:47:17,082 --> 00:47:22,096\r\nThe shepherd said nothing. He had understood\nthe story the old king had told\r\n\r\n553\r\n00:47:22,096 --> 00:47:29,096\r\nhim. A shepherd may like to travel, but he\nshould never forget about his sheep.\r\n\r\n554\r\n00:47:30,022 --> 00:47:35,038\r\nThe old man looked at the boy and, with his\nhands held together, made several\r\n\r\n555\r\n00:47:35,038 --> 00:47:42,038\r\nstrange gestures over the boy's head. Then,\ntaking his sheep, he walked away.\r\n\r\n556\r\n00:47:42,089 --> 00:47:44,188\r\n*\nAt the highest point in Tarifa there is an\r\n\r\n557\r\n00:47:45,088 --> 00:47:51,145\r\nold fort, built by the Moors. From atop\nits walls, one can catch a glimpse of Africa.\r\n\r\n558\r\n00:47:52,045 --> 00:47:58,046\r\nMelchizedek, the king of Salem, sat\non the wall of the fort that afternoon, and\r\n\r\n559\r\n00:47:58,046 --> 00:48:04,051\r\nfelt the levanter blowing in his face.\nThe sheep fidgeted nearby, uneasy with their\r\n\r\n560\r\n00:48:04,051 --> 00:48:09,106\r\nnew owner and excited by so\nmuch change. All they wanted was food and\r\n\r\n561\r\n00:48:10,006 --> 00:48:15,015\r\nwater.\nMelchizedek watched a small ship that was\r\n\r\n562\r\n00:48:15,015 --> 00:48:21,078\r\nplowing its way out of the port. He\nwould never again see the boy, just as he\r\n\r\n563\r\n00:48:21,078 --> 00:48:26,086\r\nhad never seen Abraham again after\nhaving charged him his one-tenth fee. That\r\n\r\n564\r\n00:48:27,058 --> 00:48:31,067\r\nwas his work.\nThe gods should not have desires, because\r\n\r\n565\r\n00:48:32,048 --> 00:48:39,048\r\nthey don't have destinies. But the\nking of Salem hoped desperately that the boy\r\n\r\n566\r\n00:48:39,063 --> 00:48:43,095\r\nwould be successful.\nIt's too bad that he's quickly going to forget\r\n\r\n567\r\n00:48:43,095 --> 00:48:44,144\r\nmy name, he thought. I should\nhave repeated it for him. Then when he spoke\r\n\r\n568\r\n00:48:45,044 --> 00:48:50,193\r\nabout me he would say that I am\nMelchizedek, the king of Salem.\r\n\r\n569\r\n00:48:50,589 --> 00:48:54,900\r\nHe looked to the skies, feeling a bit abashed,\nand said, \"I know it's the vanity of\r\n\r\n570\r\n00:48:54,009 --> 00:48:55,026\r\nvanities, as you said, my Lord. But an old\nking sometimes has to take some\r\n\r\n571\r\n00:48:56,007 --> 00:48:56,043\r\npride in himself.\"\n*\r\n\r\n572\r\n00:48:56,043 --> 00:49:01,128\r\nHow strange Africa is, thought the boy.\nHe was sitting in a bar very much like the\r\n\r\n573\r\n00:49:02,028 --> 00:49:06,037\r\nother bars he had seen along the\nnarrow streets of Tangier. Some men were smoking\r\n\r\n574\r\n00:49:07,018 --> 00:49:11,047\r\nfrom a gigantic pipe that\nthey passed from one to the other. In just\r\n\r\n575\r\n00:49:11,047 --> 00:49:17,122\r\na few hours he had seen men walking\nhand in hand, women with their faces covered,\r\n\r\n576\r\n00:49:18,022 --> 00:49:22,057\r\nand priests that climbed to the\ntops of towers and chanted--as everyone about\r\n\r\n577\r\n00:49:22,057 --> 00:49:25,151\r\nhim went to their knees and\nplaced their foreheads on the ground.\r\n\r\n578\r\n00:49:26,051 --> 00:49:32,098\r\n\"A practice of infidels,\" he said to himself.\nAs a child in church, he had always\r\n\r\n579\r\n00:49:32,098 --> 00:49:37,987\r\nlooked at the image of Saint Santiago Matamoros\non his white horse, his sword\r\n\r\n580\r\n00:49:38,869 --> 00:49:45,630\r\nunsheathed, and figures such as these kneeling\nat his feet. The boy felt ill and\r\n\r\n581\r\n00:49:45,063 --> 00:49:51,069\r\nterribly alone. The infidels had an evil look\nabout them.\r\n\r\n582\r\n00:49:51,069 --> 00:49:57,070\r\nBesides this, in the rush of his travels he\nhad forgotten a detail, just one detail,\r\n\r\n583\r\n00:49:57,007 --> 00:50:01,056\r\nwhich could keep him from his treasure for\na long time: only Arabic was spoken\r\n\r\n584\r\n00:50:02,019 --> 00:50:06,077\r\nin this country.\nThe owner of the bar approached him, and the\r\n\r\n585\r\n00:50:06,077 --> 00:50:11,146\r\nboy pointed to a drink that had\nbeen served at the next table. It turned out\r\n\r\n586\r\n00:50:11,839 --> 00:50:16,060\r\nto be a bitter tea. The boy preferred\nwine.\r\n\r\n587\r\n00:50:16,006 --> 00:50:20,092\r\nBut he didn't need to worry about that right\nnow. What he had to be concerned\r\n\r\n588\r\n00:50:20,092 --> 00:50:25,095\r\nabout was his treasure, and how he was going\nto go about getting it. The sale of\r\n\r\n589\r\n00:50:25,095 --> 00:50:29,118\r\nhis sheep had left him with enough money in\nhis pouch, and the boy knew that\r\n\r\n590\r\n00:50:30,018 --> 00:50:37,018\r\nin money there was magic; whoever has money\nis never really alone. Before\r\n\r\n591\r\n00:50:37,003 --> 00:50:42,071\r\nlong, maybe in just a few days, he would be\nat the Pyramids. An old man, with\r\n\r\n592\r\n00:50:42,098 --> 00:50:47,182\r\na breastplate of gold, wouldn't have lied\njust to acquire six sheep.\r\n\r\n593\r\n00:50:48,082 --> 00:50:52,120\r\nThe old man had spoken about signs and omens,\nand, as the boy was crossing\r\n\r\n594\r\n00:50:53,002 --> 00:50:59,008\r\nthe strait, he had thought about omens. Yes,\nthe old man had known what he\r\n\r\n595\r\n00:50:59,026 --> 00:51:03,101\r\nwas talking about: during the time the boy\nhad spent in the fields of Andalusia,\r\n\r\n596\r\n00:51:04,001 --> 00:51:07,030\r\nhe had become used to learning which path\nhe should take by observing the\r\n\r\n597\r\n00:51:07,003 --> 00:51:11,098\r\nground and the sky. He had discovered that\nthe presence of a certain bird\r\n\r\n598\r\n00:51:12,025 --> 00:51:16,067\r\nmeant that a snake was nearby, and that a\ncertain shrub was a sign that there\r\n\r\n599\r\n00:51:16,067 --> 00:51:21,256\r\nwas water in the area. The sheep had taught\nhim that.\r\n\r\n600\r\n00:51:21,859 --> 00:51:25,960\r\nIf God leads the sheep so well, he will also\nlead a man, he thought, and that\r\n\r\n601\r\n00:51:25,096 --> 00:51:28,165\r\nmade him feel better. The tea seemed less\nbitter.\r\n\r\n602\r\n00:51:29,065 --> 00:51:34,088\r\n\"Who are you?\" he heard a voice ask him in\nSpanish.\r\n\r\n603\r\n00:51:34,088 --> 00:51:38,090\r\nThe boy was relieved. He was thinking about\nomens, and someone had\r\n\r\n604\r\n00:51:38,009 --> 00:51:42,090\r\nappeared.\n\"How come you speak Spanish?\" he asked. The\r\n\r\n605\r\n00:51:43,071 --> 00:51:47,980\r\nnew arrival was a young man in\nWestern dress, but the color of his skin suggested\r\n\r\n606\r\n00:51:48,619 --> 00:51:53,760\r\nhe was from this city. He was\nabout the same age and height as the boy.\r\n\r\n607\r\n00:51:53,076 --> 00:51:56,145\r\n\"Almost everyone here speaks Spanish. We're\nonly two hours from Spain.\"\r\n\r\n608\r\n00:51:57,045 --> 00:52:01,964\r\n\"Sit down, and let me treat you to something,\"\nsaid the boy. \"And ask for a\r\n\r\n609\r\n00:52:02,369 --> 00:52:07,630\r\nglass of wine for me. I hate this tea.\"\n\"There is no wine in this country,\" the young\r\n\r\n610\r\n00:52:07,063 --> 00:52:10,052\r\nman said. \"The religion here\nforbids it.\"\r\n\r\n611\r\n00:52:10,619 --> 00:52:15,130\r\nThe boy told him then that he needed to get\nto the Pyramids. He almost began\r\n\r\n612\r\n00:52:15,013 --> 00:52:20,065\r\nto tell about his treasure, but decided not\nto do so. If he did, it was possible that\r\n\r\n613\r\n00:52:20,065 --> 00:52:23,163\r\nthe Arab would want a part of it as payment\nfor taking him there. He\r\n\r\n614\r\n00:52:24,063 --> 00:52:26,151\r\nremembered what the old man had said about\noffering something you didn't\r\n\r\n615\r\n00:52:27,051 --> 00:52:32,088\r\neven have yet.\n\"I'd like you to take me there if you can.\r\n\r\n616\r\n00:52:32,088 --> 00:52:37,100\r\nI can pay you to serve as my guide.\"\n\"Do you have any idea how to get there?\" the\r\n\r\n617\r\n00:52:38,000 --> 00:52:41,859\r\nnewcomer asked.\nThe boy noticed that the owner of the bar\r\n\r\n618\r\n00:52:41,859 --> 00:52:46,890\r\nstood nearby, listening attentively to\ntheir conversation. He felt uneasy at the\r\n\r\n619\r\n00:52:46,089 --> 00:52:51,140\r\nman's presence. But he had found a\nguide, and didn't want to miss out on an opportunity.\r\n\r\n620\r\n00:52:52,004 --> 00:52:57,020\r\n\"You have to cross the entire Sahara desert,\"\nsaid the young man. \"And to do\r\n\r\n621\r\n00:52:57,056 --> 00:53:01,154\r\nthat, you need money. I need to know whether\nyou have enough.\"\r\n\r\n622\r\n00:53:02,054 --> 00:53:06,093\r\nThe boy thought it a strange question. But\nhe trusted in the old man, who had\r\n\r\n623\r\n00:53:06,093 --> 00:53:09,772\r\nsaid that, when you really want something,\nthe universe always conspires in\r\n\r\n624\r\n00:53:10,609 --> 00:53:14,630\r\nyour favor.\nHe took his money from his pouch and showed\r\n\r\n625\r\n00:53:14,063 --> 00:53:19,067\r\nit to the young man. The owner\nof the bar came over and looked, as well.\r\n\r\n626\r\n00:53:20,003 --> 00:53:25,332\r\nThe two men exchanged some words\nin Arabic, and the bar owner seemed irritated.\r\n\r\n627\r\n00:53:25,359 --> 00:53:30,930\r\n\"Let's get out of here\" said the new arrival.\n\"He wants us to leave.\"\r\n\r\n628\r\n00:53:30,093 --> 00:53:33,188\r\nThe boy was relieved. He got up to pay the\nbill, but the owner grabbed him and\r\n\r\n629\r\n00:53:34,088 --> 00:53:38,094\r\nbegan to speak to him in an angry stream of\nwords. The boy was strong, and\r\n\r\n630\r\n00:53:39,048 --> 00:53:43,687\r\nwanted to retaliate, but he was in a foreign\ncountry. His new friend pushed the\r\n\r\n631\r\n00:53:44,119 --> 00:53:48,143\r\nowner aside, and pulled the boy outside with\nhim. \"He wanted your money,\" he\r\n\r\n632\r\n00:53:48,359 --> 00:53:54,410\r\nsaid. \"Tangier is not like the rest of Africa.\nThis is a port, and every port has its\r\n\r\n633\r\n00:53:54,869 --> 00:53:59,916\r\nthieves.\"\nThe boy trusted his new friend. He had helped\r\n\r\n634\r\n00:54:00,339 --> 00:54:05,430\r\nhim out in a dangerous situation.\nHe took out his money and counted it.\r\n\r\n635\r\n00:54:05,043 --> 00:54:09,222\r\n\"We could get to the Pyramids by tomorrow,\"\nsaid the other, taking the money.\r\n\r\n636\r\n00:54:09,609 --> 00:54:15,130\r\n\"But I have to buy two camels.\"\nThey walked together through the narrow streets\r\n\r\n637\r\n00:54:15,013 --> 00:54:21,028\r\nof Tangier. Everywhere there\nwere stalls with items for sale. They reached\r\n\r\n638\r\n00:54:21,028 --> 00:54:25,107\r\nthe center of a large plaza where\nthe market was held. There were thousands\r\n\r\n639\r\n00:54:25,359 --> 00:54:31,070\r\nof people there, arguing, selling,\nand buying; vegetables for sale amongst daggers,\r\n\r\n640\r\n00:54:31,007 --> 00:54:35,088\r\nand carpets displayed\nalongside tobacco. But the boy never took\r\n\r\n641\r\n00:54:35,088 --> 00:54:40,177\r\nhis eye off his new friend. After all,\nhe had all his money. He thought about asking\r\n\r\n642\r\n00:54:41,077 --> 00:54:45,122\r\nhim to give it back, but decided\nthat would be unfriendly. He knew nothing\r\n\r\n643\r\n00:54:46,022 --> 00:54:48,080\r\nabout the customs of the strange\nland he was in.\r\n\r\n644\r\n00:54:48,008 --> 00:54:53,015\r\n\"I'll just watch him,\" he said to himself.\nHe knew he was stronger than his\r\n\r\n645\r\n00:54:54,005 --> 00:54:58,068\r\nfriend.\nSuddenly, there in the midst of all that confusion,\r\n\r\n646\r\n00:54:59,013 --> 00:55:03,982\r\nhe saw the most beautiful\nsword he had ever seen. The scabbard was embossed\r\n\r\n647\r\n00:55:04,099 --> 00:55:10,980\r\nin silver, and the handle\nwas black and encrusted with precious stones.\r\n\r\n648\r\n00:55:10,098 --> 00:55:13,197\r\nThe boy promised himself that,\nwhen he returned from Egypt, he would buy\r\n\r\n649\r\n00:55:14,097 --> 00:55:17,165\r\nthat sword.\n\"Ask the owner of that stall how much the\r\n\r\n650\r\n00:55:18,065 --> 00:55:22,081\r\nsword costs,\" he said to his friend.\nThen he realized that he had been distracted\r\n\r\n651\r\n00:55:22,081 --> 00:55:26,085\r\nfor a few moments, looking at the\nsword. His heart squeezed, as if his chest\r\n\r\n652\r\n00:55:27,021 --> 00:55:30,075\r\nhad suddenly compressed it. He was\nafraid to look around, because he knew what\r\n\r\n653\r\n00:55:30,075 --> 00:55:34,163\r\nhe would find. He continued to\nlook at the beautiful sword for a bit longer,\r\n\r\n654\r\n00:55:35,063 --> 00:55:38,129\r\nuntil he summoned the courage to\nturn around.\r\n\r\n655\r\n00:55:39,029 --> 00:55:42,578\r\nAll around him was the market, with people\ncoming and going, shouting and\r\n\r\n656\r\n00:55:42,839 --> 00:55:47,920\r\nbuying, and the aroma of strange foods...\nbut nowhere could he find his new\r\n\r\n657\r\n00:55:47,092 --> 00:55:51,031\r\ncompanion.\nThe boy wanted to believe that his friend\r\n\r\n658\r\n00:55:51,859 --> 00:55:56,270\r\nhad simply become separated from\nhim by accident. He decided to stay right\r\n\r\n659\r\n00:55:56,027 --> 00:56:01,029\r\nthere and await his return. As he\nwaited, a priest climbed to the top of a nearby\r\n\r\n660\r\n00:56:01,047 --> 00:56:05,054\r\ntower and began his chant;\neveryone in the market fell to their knees,\r\n\r\n661\r\n00:56:05,054 --> 00:56:10,383\r\ntouched their foreheads to the\nground, and took up the chant. Then, like\r\n\r\n662\r\n00:56:10,869 --> 00:56:15,965\r\na colony of worker ants, they\ndismantled their stalls and left.\r\n\r\n663\r\n00:56:16,829 --> 00:56:21,857\r\nThe sun began its departure, as well. The\nboy watched it through its trajectory\r\n\r\n664\r\n00:56:22,109 --> 00:56:25,990\r\nfor some time, until it was hidden behind\nthe white houses surrounding the\r\n\r\n665\r\n00:56:25,099 --> 00:56:30,148\r\nplaza. He recalled that when the sun had risen\nthat morning, he was on another\r\n\r\n666\r\n00:56:31,048 --> 00:56:36,051\r\ncontinent, still a shepherd with sixty sheep,\nand looking forward to meeting with\r\n\r\n667\r\n00:56:36,051 --> 00:56:40,123\r\na girl. That morning he had known everything\nthat was going to happen to him\r\n\r\n668\r\n00:56:41,023 --> 00:56:47,041\r\nas he walked through the familiar fields.\nBut now, as the sun began to set, he\r\n\r\n669\r\n00:56:47,041 --> 00:56:52,070\r\nwas in a different country, a stranger in\na strange land, where he couldn't even\r\n\r\n670\r\n00:56:52,007 --> 00:56:58,082\r\nspeak the language. He was no longer a shepherd,\nand he had nothing, not\r\n\r\n671\r\n00:56:59,045 --> 00:57:04,046\r\neven the money to return and start everything\nover.\r\n\r\n672\r\n00:57:04,046 --> 00:57:09,142\r\nAll this happened between sunrise and sunset,\nthe boy thought. He was feeling\r\n\r\n673\r\n00:57:10,042 --> 00:57:14,118\r\nsorry for himself, and lamenting the fact\nthat his life could have changed so\r\n\r\n674\r\n00:57:15,018 --> 00:57:22,018\r\nsuddenly and so drastically.\nHe was so ashamed that he wanted to cry. He\r\n\r\n675\r\n00:57:23,109 --> 00:57:27,157\r\nhad never even wept in front of\nhis own sheep. But the marketplace was empty,\r\n\r\n676\r\n00:57:27,589 --> 00:57:34,589\r\nand he was far from home, so\nhe wept. He wept because God was unfair, and\r\n\r\n677\r\n00:57:34,829 --> 00:57:40,430\r\nbecause this was the way God\nrepaid those who believed in their dreams.\r\n\r\n678\r\n00:57:40,043 --> 00:57:45,222\r\nWhen I had my sheep, I was happy, and I made\nthose around me happy.\r\n\r\n679\r\n00:57:45,609 --> 00:57:49,480\r\nPeople saw me coming and welcomed me, he thought.\nBut now I'm sad and\r\n\r\n680\r\n00:57:49,048 --> 00:57:54,141\r\nalone. I'm going to become bitter and distrustful\nof people because one person\r\n\r\n681\r\n00:57:55,041 --> 00:57:59,096\r\nbetrayed me. I'm going to hate those who have\nfound their treasure because I\r\n\r\n682\r\n00:57:59,096 --> 00:58:04,181\r\nnever found mine. And I'm going to hold on\nto what little I have, because I'm\r\n\r\n683\r\n00:58:05,081 --> 00:58:11,123\r\ntoo insignificant to conquer the world.\nHe opened his pouch to see what was left of\r\n\r\n684\r\n00:58:12,023 --> 00:58:15,065\r\nhis possessions; maybe there was a\nbit left of the sandwich he had eaten on the\r\n\r\n685\r\n00:58:15,065 --> 00:58:22,065\r\nship. But all he found was the heavy\nbook, his jacket, and the two stones the old\r\n\r\n686\r\n00:58:23,053 --> 00:58:29,055\r\nman had given him.\nAs he looked at the stones, he felt relieved\r\n\r\n687\r\n00:58:29,073 --> 00:58:34,116\r\nfor some reason. He had exchanged\nsix sheep for two precious stones that had\r\n\r\n688\r\n00:58:35,016 --> 00:58:39,080\r\nbeen taken from a gold breastplate.\nHe could sell the stones and buy a return\r\n\r\n689\r\n00:58:39,008 --> 00:58:44,030\r\nticket. But this time I'll be smarter,\nthe boy thought, removing them from the pouch\r\n\r\n690\r\n00:58:45,002 --> 00:58:49,077\r\nso he could put them in his\npocket. This was a port town, and the only\r\n\r\n691\r\n00:58:49,077 --> 00:58:55,131\r\ntruthful thing his friend had told him\nwas that port towns are full of thieves.\r\n\r\n692\r\n00:58:56,031 --> 00:58:59,810\r\nNow he understood why the owner of the bar\nhad been so upset: he was trying\r\n\r\n693\r\n00:59:00,089 --> 00:59:04,810\r\nto tell him not to trust that man. \"I'm like\neveryone else--I see the world in\r\n\r\n694\r\n00:59:04,081 --> 00:59:09,150\r\nterms of what I would like to see happen,\nnot what actually does.\"\r\n\r\n695\r\n00:59:10,005 --> 00:59:14,093\r\nHe ran his fingers slowly over the stones,\nsensing their temperature and feeling\r\n\r\n696\r\n00:59:15,038 --> 00:59:20,117\r\ntheir surfaces. They were his treasure. Just\nhandling them made him feel better.\r\n\r\n697\r\n00:59:21,017 --> 00:59:27,104\r\nThey reminded him of the old man.\n\"When you want something, all the universe\r\n\r\n698\r\n00:59:28,004 --> 00:59:33,004\r\nconspires in helping you to achieve\nit,\" he had said.\r\n\r\n699\r\n00:59:33,004 --> 00:59:37,043\r\nThe boy was trying to understand the truth\nof what the old man had said. There\r\n\r\n700\r\n00:59:37,043 --> 00:59:41,088\r\nhe was in the empty marketplace, without a\ncent to his name, and with not a\r\n\r\n701\r\n00:59:41,088 --> 00:59:46,089\r\nsheep to guard through the night. But the\nstones were proof that he had met\r\n\r\n702\r\n00:59:46,098 --> 00:59:50,122\r\nwith a king--a king who knew of the boy's\npast.\r\n\r\n703\r\n00:59:51,022 --> 00:59:58,022\r\n\"They're called Urim and Thummim, and they\ncan help you to read the omens.\"\r\n\r\n704\r\n00:59:58,071 --> 01:00:03,126\r\nThe boy put the stones back in the pouch and\ndecided to do an experiment. The\r\n\r\n705\r\n01:00:04,026 --> 01:00:08,345\r\nold man had said to ask very clear questions,\nand to do that, the boy had to\r\n\r\n706\r\n01:00:08,579 --> 01:00:14,570\r\nknow what he wanted. So, he asked if the old\nman's blessing was still with him.\r\n\r\n707\r\n01:00:14,057 --> 01:00:21,057\r\nHe took out one of the stones. It was \"yes.\"\n\"Am I going to find my treasure?\" he asked.\r\n\r\n708\r\n01:00:22,045 --> 01:00:25,123\r\nHe stuck his hand into the pouch, and felt\naround for one of the stones. As he\r\n\r\n709\r\n01:00:26,023 --> 01:00:30,872\r\ndid so, both of them pushed through a hole\nin the pouch and fell to the ground.\r\n\r\n710\r\n01:00:31,079 --> 01:00:34,790\r\nThe boy had never even noticed that there\nwas a hole in his pouch. He knelt\r\n\r\n711\r\n01:00:34,079 --> 01:00:39,102\r\ndown to find Urim and Thummim and put them\nback in the pouch. But as he saw\r\n\r\n712\r\n01:00:40,002 --> 01:00:44,811\r\nthem lying there on the ground, another phrase\ncame to his mind.\r\n\r\n713\r\n01:00:44,829 --> 01:00:50,710\r\n\"Learn to recognize omens, and follow them,\"\nthe old king had said.\r\n\r\n714\r\n01:00:50,071 --> 01:00:56,140\r\nAn omen. The boy smiled to himself. He picked\nup the two stones and put them\r\n\r\n715\r\n01:00:57,004 --> 01:01:02,031\r\nback in his pouch. He didn't consider mending\nthe hole--the stones could fall\r\n\r\n716\r\n01:01:02,067 --> 01:01:06,068\r\nthrough any time they wanted. He had learned\nthat there were certain things\r\n\r\n717\r\n01:01:06,077 --> 01:01:12,636\r\none shouldn't ask about, so as not to flee\nfrom one's own Personal Legend. \"I promised\r\n\r\n718\r\n01:01:13,329 --> 01:01:17,710\r\nthat I would make my own decisions,\" he said\nto himself.\r\n\r\n719\r\n01:01:17,071 --> 01:01:21,105\r\nBut the stones had told him that the old man\nwas still with him, and that made\r\n\r\n720\r\n01:01:22,005 --> 01:01:26,040\r\nhim feel more confident. He looked around\nat the empty plaza again, feeling\r\n\r\n721\r\n01:01:26,004 --> 01:01:33,004\r\nless desperate than before. This wasn't a\nstrange place; it was a new one.\r\n\r\n722\r\n01:01:34,043 --> 01:01:39,482\r\nAfter all, what he had always wanted was just\nthat: to know new places. Even if\r\n\r\n723\r\n01:01:39,869 --> 01:01:43,000\r\nhe never got to the Pyramids, he had already\ntraveled farther than any\r\n\r\n724\r\n01:01:43,000 --> 01:01:49,000\r\nshepherd he knew. Oh, if they only knew how\ndifferent things are just two hours\r\n\r\n725\r\n01:01:49,000 --> 01:01:53,047\r\nby ship from where they are, he thought. Although\nhis new world at the moment\r\n\r\n726\r\n01:01:53,047 --> 01:01:56,105\r\nwas just an empty marketplace, he had already\nseen it when it was teeming\r\n\r\n727\r\n01:01:57,005 --> 01:02:01,099\r\nwith life, and he would never forget it. He\nremembered the sword. It hurt him a\r\n\r\n728\r\n01:02:01,099 --> 01:02:06,428\r\nbit to think about it, but he had never seen\none like it before. As he mused\r\n\r\n729\r\n01:02:07,319 --> 01:02:11,040\r\nabout these things, he realized that he had\nto choose between thinking of\r\n\r\n730\r\n01:02:11,004 --> 01:02:16,004\r\nhimself as the poor victim of a thief and\nas an adventurer in quest of his\r\n\r\n731\r\n01:02:16,004 --> 01:02:20,813\r\ntreasure.\n\"I'm an adventurer, looking for treasure,\"\r\n\r\n732\r\n01:02:20,849 --> 01:02:23,050\r\nhe said to himself.\n*\r\n\r\n733\r\n01:02:23,005 --> 01:02:27,029\r\nHe was shaken into wakefulness by someone.\nHe had fallen asleep in the\r\n\r\n734\r\n01:02:27,029 --> 01:02:32,568\r\nmiddle of the marketplace, and life in the\nplaza was about to resume.\r\n\r\n735\r\n01:02:32,829 --> 01:02:35,670\r\nLooking around, he sought his sheep, and then\nrealized that he was in a new\r\n\r\n736\r\n01:02:35,067 --> 01:02:40,113\r\nworld. But instead of being saddened, he was\nhappy. He no longer had to seek\r\n\r\n737\r\n01:02:41,013 --> 01:02:46,752\r\nout food and water for the sheep; he could\ngo in search of his treasure, instead.\r\n\r\n738\r\n01:02:46,869 --> 01:02:52,750\r\nHe had not a cent in his pocket, but he had\nfaith. He had decided, the night\r\n\r\n739\r\n01:02:52,075 --> 01:02:55,082\r\nbefore, that he would be as much an adventurer\nas the ones he had admired in\r\n\r\n740\r\n01:02:56,045 --> 01:03:01,091\r\nbooks.\nHe walked slowly through the market. The merchants\r\n\r\n741\r\n01:03:01,091 --> 01:03:04,250\r\nwere assembling their\nstalls, and the boy helped a candy seller\r\n\r\n742\r\n01:03:05,069 --> 01:03:10,690\r\nto do his. The candy seller had a smile\non his face: he was happy, aware of what his\r\n\r\n743\r\n01:03:10,069 --> 01:03:14,155\r\nlife was about, and ready to begin\na day's work. His smile reminded the boy of\r\n\r\n744\r\n01:03:15,055 --> 01:03:20,614\r\nthe old man--the mysterious old\nking he had met. \"This candy merchant isn't\r\n\r\n745\r\n01:03:21,109 --> 01:03:25,207\r\nmaking candy so that later he can\ntravel or marry a shopkeeper's daughter. He's\r\n\r\n746\r\n01:03:26,089 --> 01:03:31,140\r\ndoing it because it's what he\nwants to do,\" thought the boy. He realized\r\n\r\n747\r\n01:03:31,014 --> 01:03:35,045\r\nthat he could do the same thing the\nold man had done--sense whether a person was\r\n\r\n748\r\n01:03:35,045 --> 01:03:41,464\r\nnear to or far from his Personal Legend.\nJust by looking at them. It's easy, and yet\r\n\r\n749\r\n01:03:41,869 --> 01:03:46,893\r\nI've never done it before, he thought.\nWhen the stall was assembled, the candy seller\r\n\r\n750\r\n01:03:47,109 --> 01:03:51,680\r\noffered the boy the first sweet\nhe had made for the day. The boy thanked him,\r\n\r\n751\r\n01:03:51,068 --> 01:03:55,100\r\nate it, and went on his way.\nWhen he had gone only a short distance, he\r\n\r\n752\r\n01:03:56,000 --> 01:03:59,072\r\nrealized that, while they were\nerecting the stall, one of them had spoken\r\n\r\n753\r\n01:03:59,072 --> 01:04:04,191\r\nArabic and the other Spanish.\nAnd they had understood each other perfectly\r\n\r\n754\r\n01:04:04,839 --> 01:04:08,920\r\nwell.\nThere must be a language that doesn't depend\r\n\r\n755\r\n01:04:08,092 --> 01:04:12,511\r\non words, the boy thought. I've\nalready had that experience with my sheep,\r\n\r\n756\r\n01:04:13,339 --> 01:04:19,670\r\nand now it's happening with people.\nHe was learning a lot of new things. Some\r\n\r\n757\r\n01:04:19,067 --> 01:04:22,246\r\nof them were things that he had\nalready experienced, and weren't really new,\r\n\r\n758\r\n01:04:22,849 --> 01:04:27,880\r\nbut that he had never perceived\nbefore. And he hadn't perceived them because\r\n\r\n759\r\n01:04:27,088 --> 01:04:32,106\r\nhe had become accustomed to\nthem. He realized: If I can learn to understand\r\n\r\n760\r\n01:04:33,006 --> 01:04:39,010\r\nthis language without words, I\ncan learn to understand the world.\r\n\r\n761\r\n01:04:39,046 --> 01:04:42,079\r\nRelaxed and unhurried, he resolved that he\nwould walk through the narrow\r\n\r\n762\r\n01:04:42,079 --> 01:04:47,156\r\nstreets of Tangier. Only in that way would\nhe be able to read the omens. He\r\n\r\n763\r\n01:04:48,056 --> 01:04:53,355\r\nknew it would require a lot of patience, but\nshepherds know all about patience.\r\n\r\n764\r\n01:04:53,859 --> 01:04:58,650\r\nOnce again he saw that, in that strange land,\nhe was applying the same lessons\r\n\r\n765\r\n01:04:58,065 --> 01:05:05,065\r\nhe had learned with his sheep.\n\"All things are one,\" the old man had said.\r\n\r\n766\r\n01:05:06,038 --> 01:05:09,227\r\n*\nThe crystal merchant awoke with the day, and\r\n\r\n767\r\n01:05:09,569 --> 01:05:13,622\r\nfelt the same anxiety that he felt\nevery morning. He had been in the same place\r\n\r\n768\r\n01:05:14,099 --> 01:05:19,420\r\nfor thirty years: a shop at the\ntop of a hilly street where few customers\r\n\r\n769\r\n01:05:19,042 --> 01:05:24,113\r\npassed. Now it was too late to change\nanything--the only thing he had ever learned\r\n\r\n770\r\n01:05:25,013 --> 01:05:29,962\r\nto do was to buy and sell crystal\nglassware. There had been a time when many\r\n\r\n771\r\n01:05:30,079 --> 01:05:34,520\r\npeople knew of his shop: Arab\nmerchants, French and English geologists,\r\n\r\n772\r\n01:05:34,052 --> 01:05:39,069\r\nGerman soldiers who were always\nwell-heeled. In those days it had been wonderful\r\n\r\n773\r\n01:05:39,069 --> 01:05:42,115\r\nto be selling crystal, and he\nhad thought how he would become rich, and\r\n\r\n774\r\n01:05:43,015 --> 01:05:45,100\r\nhave beautiful women at his side\nas he grew older.\r\n\r\n775\r\n01:05:46,000 --> 01:05:53,000\r\nBut, as time passed, Tangier had changed.\nThe nearby city of Ceuta had grown\r\n\r\n776\r\n01:05:53,063 --> 01:05:58,068\r\nfaster than Tangier, and business had fallen\noff. Neighbors moved away, and\r\n\r\n777\r\n01:05:59,013 --> 01:06:03,024\r\nthere remained only a few small shops on the\nhill. And no one was going to\r\n\r\n778\r\n01:06:03,024 --> 01:06:07,080\r\nclimb the hill just to browse through a few\nsmall shops.\r\n\r\n779\r\n01:06:07,008 --> 01:06:11,051\r\nBut the crystal merchant had no choice. He\nhad lived thirty years of his life\r\n\r\n780\r\n01:06:12,023 --> 01:06:18,142\r\nbuying and selling crystal pieces, and now\nit was too late to do anything else.\r\n\r\n781\r\n01:06:18,349 --> 01:06:22,425\r\nHe spent the entire morning observing the\ninfrequent comings and goings in the\r\n\r\n782\r\n01:06:23,109 --> 01:06:27,131\r\nstreet. He had done this for years, and knew\nthe schedule of everyone who\r\n\r\n783\r\n01:06:27,329 --> 01:06:34,140\r\npassed. But, just before lunchtime, a boy\nstopped in front of the shop. He was\r\n\r\n784\r\n01:06:34,014 --> 01:06:37,113\r\ndressed normally, but the practiced eyes of\nthe crystal merchant could see that\r\n\r\n785\r\n01:06:38,013 --> 01:06:43,212\r\nthe boy had no money to spend. Nevertheless,\nthe merchant decided to delay\r\n\r\n786\r\n01:06:43,329 --> 01:06:46,396\r\nhis lunch for a few minutes until the boy\nmoved on.\r\n\r\n787\r\n01:06:46,999 --> 01:06:50,140\r\n*\nA card hanging in the doorway announced that\r\n\r\n788\r\n01:06:50,014 --> 01:06:55,053\r\nseveral languages were spoken\nin the shop. The boy saw a man appear behind\r\n\r\n789\r\n01:06:55,053 --> 01:06:58,106\r\nthe counter.\n\"I can clean up those glasses in the window,\r\n\r\n790\r\n01:06:59,006 --> 01:07:03,045\r\nif you want,\" said the boy. \"The\nway they look now, nobody is going to want\r\n\r\n791\r\n01:07:03,099 --> 01:07:07,148\r\nto buy them.\"\nThe man looked at him without responding.\r\n\r\n792\r\n01:07:07,589 --> 01:07:11,680\r\n\"In exchange, you could give me something\nto eat.\"\r\n\r\n793\r\n01:07:11,068 --> 01:07:15,487\r\nThe man still said nothing, and the boy sensed\nthat he was going to have to\r\n\r\n794\r\n01:07:16,099 --> 01:07:21,660\r\nmake a decision. In his pouch, he had his\njacket--he certainly wasn't going to\r\n\r\n795\r\n01:07:21,066 --> 01:07:27,119\r\nneed it in the desert. Taking the jacket out,\nhe began to clean the glasses. In\r\n\r\n796\r\n01:07:28,019 --> 01:07:32,020\r\nhalf an hour, he had cleaned all the glasses\nin the window, and, as he was doing\r\n\r\n797\r\n01:07:32,002 --> 01:07:36,060\r\nso, two customers had entered the shop and\nbought some crystal.\r\n\r\n798\r\n01:07:36,078 --> 01:07:40,117\r\nWhen he had completed the cleaning, he asked\nthe man for something to eat.\r\n\r\n799\r\n01:07:40,819 --> 01:07:45,844\r\n\"Let's go and have some lunch,\" said the crystal\nmerchant.\r\n\r\n800\r\n01:07:46,069 --> 01:07:51,097\r\nHe put a sign on the door, and they went to\na small café nearby. As they sat\r\n\r\n801\r\n01:07:51,349 --> 01:07:55,540\r\ndown at the only table in the place, the crystal\nmerchant laughed.\r\n\r\n802\r\n01:07:55,054 --> 01:08:00,069\r\n\"You didn't have to do any cleaning,\" he said.\n\"The Koran requires me to feed a\r\n\r\n803\r\n01:08:00,069 --> 01:08:03,081\r\nhungry person.\"\n\"Well then, why did you let me do it?\" the\r\n\r\n804\r\n01:08:03,081 --> 01:08:06,170\r\nboy asked.\n\"Because the crystal was dirty. And both you\r\n\r\n805\r\n01:08:07,007 --> 01:08:12,100\r\nand I needed to cleanse our minds\nof negative thoughts.\"\r\n\r\n806\r\n01:08:13,063 --> 01:08:16,542\r\nWhen they had eaten, the merchant turned to\nthe boy and said, \"I'd like you to\r\n\r\n807\r\n01:08:17,109 --> 01:08:22,190\r\nwork in my shop. Two customers came in today\nwhile you were working, and\r\n\r\n808\r\n01:08:22,019 --> 01:08:26,038\r\nthat's a good omen.\"\nPeople talk a lot about omens, thought the\r\n\r\n809\r\n01:08:26,038 --> 01:08:32,047\r\nshepherd. But they really don't know\nwhat they're saying. Just as I hadn't realized\r\n\r\n810\r\n01:08:32,389 --> 01:08:36,400\r\nthat for so many years I had been\nspeaking a language without words to my sheep.\r\n\r\n811\r\n01:08:36,499 --> 01:08:39,532\r\n\"Do you want to go to work for me?\" the merchant\nasked.\r\n\r\n812\r\n01:08:39,829 --> 01:08:44,842\r\n\"I can work for the rest of today,\" the boy\nanswered. \"I'll work all night, until\r\n\r\n813\r\n01:08:44,959 --> 01:08:49,987\r\ndawn, and I'll clean every piece of crystal\nin your shop. In return, I need money\r\n\r\n814\r\n01:08:50,239 --> 01:08:54,316\r\nto get to Egypt tomorrow.\"\nThe merchant laughed. \"Even if you cleaned\r\n\r\n815\r\n01:08:55,009 --> 01:08:59,017\r\nmy crystal for an entire year...\neven if you earned a good commission selling\r\n\r\n816\r\n01:08:59,089 --> 01:09:04,089\r\nevery piece, you would still have\nto borrow money to get to Egypt. There are\r\n\r\n817\r\n01:09:04,089 --> 01:09:09,098\r\nthousands of kilometers of desert\nbetween here and there.\"\r\n\r\n818\r\n01:09:09,179 --> 01:09:15,179\r\nThere was a moment of silence so profound\nthat it seemed the city was asleep.\r\n\r\n819\r\n01:09:15,179 --> 01:09:19,243\r\nNo sound from the bazaars, no arguments among\nthe merchants, no men\r\n\r\n820\r\n01:09:19,819 --> 01:09:25,914\r\nclimbing to the towers to chant. No hope,\nno adventure, no old kings or\r\n\r\n821\r\n01:09:26,769 --> 01:09:33,769\r\ndestinies, no treasure, and no Pyramids. It\nwas as if the world had fallen silent\r\n\r\n822\r\n01:09:34,929 --> 01:09:40,932\r\nbecause the boy's soul had. He sat there,\nstaring blankly through the door of the\r\n\r\n823\r\n01:09:40,959 --> 01:09:45,977\r\ncafé, wishing that he had died, and that\neverything would end forever at that\r\n\r\n824\r\n01:09:46,139 --> 01:09:50,230\r\nmoment.\nThe merchant looked anxiously at the boy.\r\n\r\n825\r\n01:09:51,049 --> 01:09:53,144\r\nAll the joy he had seen that morning\nhad suddenly disappeared.\r\n\r\n826\r\n01:09:53,999 --> 01:09:58,420\r\n\"I can give you the money you need to get\nback to your country, my son,\" said\r\n\r\n827\r\n01:09:58,042 --> 01:10:03,084\r\nthe crystal merchant.\nThe boy said nothing. He got up, adjusted\r\n\r\n828\r\n01:10:03,084 --> 01:10:08,136\r\nhis clothing, and picked up his pouch.\n\"I'll work for you,\" he said.\r\n\r\n829\r\n01:10:09,036 --> 01:10:15,038\r\nAnd after another long silence, he added,\n\"I need money to buy some sheep.\"\r\n\r\n830\r\n01:10:15,038 --> 01:10:18,080\r\nPART 2\nThe boy had been working for the crystal merchant\r\n\r\n831\r\n01:10:18,008 --> 01:10:21,062\r\nfor almost a month, and he\ncould see that it wasn't exactly the kind\r\n\r\n832\r\n01:10:22,034 --> 01:10:26,633\r\nof job that would make him happy. The\nmerchant spent the entire day mumbling behind\r\n\r\n833\r\n01:10:26,939 --> 01:10:29,990\r\nthe counter, telling the boy to\nbe careful with the pieces and not to break\r\n\r\n834\r\n01:10:30,449 --> 01:10:33,481\r\nanything.\nBut he stayed with the job because the merchant,\r\n\r\n835\r\n01:10:33,769 --> 01:10:36,840\r\nalthough he was an old\ngrouch, treated him fairly; the boy received\r\n\r\n836\r\n01:10:37,479 --> 01:10:41,480\r\na good commission for each piece\nhe sold, and had already been able to put\r\n\r\n837\r\n01:10:41,489 --> 01:10:46,564\r\nsome money aside. That morning he\nhad done some calculating: if he continued\r\n\r\n838\r\n01:10:47,239 --> 01:10:52,010\r\nto work every day as he had been,\nhe would need a whole year to be able to buy\r\n\r\n839\r\n01:10:52,001 --> 01:10:56,630\r\nsome sheep.\n\"I'd like to build a display case for the\r\n\r\n840\r\n01:10:56,639 --> 01:11:01,150\r\ncrystal,\" the boy said to the merchant.\n\"We could place it outside, and attract those\r\n\r\n841\r\n01:11:01,015 --> 01:11:02,214\r\npeople who pass at the bottom of\nthe hill.\"\r\n\r\n842\r\n01:11:02,349 --> 01:11:07,670\r\n\"I've never had one before,\" the merchant\nanswered. \"People will pass by and\r\n\r\n843\r\n01:11:07,067 --> 01:11:12,616\r\nbump into it, and pieces will be broken.\"\n\"Well, when I took my sheep through the fields\r\n\r\n844\r\n01:11:13,219 --> 01:11:17,170\r\nsome of them might have died if\nwe had come upon a snake. But that's the way\r\n\r\n845\r\n01:11:17,017 --> 01:11:20,086\r\nlife is with sheep and with\nshepherds.\"\r\n\r\n846\r\n01:11:20,086 --> 01:11:23,575\r\nThe merchant turned to a customer who wanted\nthree crystal glasses. He was\r\n\r\n847\r\n01:11:24,349 --> 01:11:28,395\r\nselling better than ever... as if time had\nturned back to the old days when the\r\n\r\n848\r\n01:11:28,809 --> 01:11:34,380\r\nstreet had been one of Tangier's major attractions.\n\"Business has really improved,\" he said to\r\n\r\n849\r\n01:11:34,038 --> 01:11:39,027\r\nthe boy, after the customer had left.\n\"I'm doing much better, and soon you'll be\r\n\r\n850\r\n01:11:39,369 --> 01:11:43,900\r\nable to return to your sheep. Why\nask more out of life?\"\r\n\r\n851\r\n01:11:43,009 --> 01:11:46,568\r\n\"Because we have to respond to omens,\" the\nboy said, almost without meaning\r\n\r\n852\r\n01:11:47,459 --> 01:11:50,515\r\nto; then he regretted what he had said, because\nthe merchant had never met\r\n\r\n853\r\n01:11:51,019 --> 01:11:55,077\r\nthe king.\n\"It's called the principle of favorability,\r\n\r\n854\r\n01:11:55,599 --> 01:12:01,130\r\nbeginner's luck. Because life wants you\nto achieve your Personal Legend,\" the old\r\n\r\n855\r\n01:12:01,013 --> 01:12:05,017\r\nking had said.\nBut the merchant understood what the boy had\r\n\r\n856\r\n01:12:05,053 --> 01:12:10,053\r\nsaid. The boy's very presence in\nthe shop was an omen, and, as time passed\r\n\r\n857\r\n01:12:10,053 --> 01:12:13,142\r\nand money was pouring into the\ncash drawer, he had no regrets about having\r\n\r\n858\r\n01:12:14,042 --> 01:12:18,341\r\nhired the boy. The boy was being\npaid more money than he deserved, because\r\n\r\n859\r\n01:12:18,719 --> 01:12:21,670\r\nthe merchant, thinking that sales\nwouldn't amount to much, had offered the boy\r\n\r\n860\r\n01:12:21,067 --> 01:12:25,636\r\na high commission rate. He had\nassumed he would soon return to his sheep.\r\n\r\n861\r\n01:12:26,239 --> 01:12:30,030\r\n\"Why did you want to get to the Pyramids?\"\nhe asked, to get away from the\r\n\r\n862\r\n01:12:30,003 --> 01:12:33,882\r\nbusiness of the display.\n\"Because I've always heard about them,\" the\r\n\r\n863\r\n01:12:33,909 --> 01:12:37,953\r\nboy answered, saying nothing\nabout his dream. The treasure was now nothing\r\n\r\n864\r\n01:12:38,349 --> 01:12:41,320\r\nbut a painful memory, and he\ntried to avoid thinking about it.\r\n\r\n865\r\n01:12:41,032 --> 01:12:44,109\r\n\"I don't know anyone around here who would\nwant to cross the desert just to\r\n\r\n866\r\n01:12:45,009 --> 01:12:48,107\r\nsee the Pyramids,\" said the merchant. \"They're\njust a pile of stones. You could\r\n\r\n867\r\n01:12:49,007 --> 01:12:53,726\r\nbuild one in your backyard.\"\n\"You've never had dreams of travel,\" said\r\n\r\n868\r\n01:12:53,789 --> 01:12:58,830\r\nthe boy, turning to wait on a\ncustomer who had entered the shop.\r\n\r\n869\r\n01:12:59,199 --> 01:13:03,201\r\nTwo days later, the merchant spoke to the\nboy about the display.\r\n\r\n870\r\n01:13:03,219 --> 01:13:09,170\r\n\"I don't much like change,\" he said. \"You\nand I aren't like Hassan, that rich\r\n\r\n871\r\n01:13:09,017 --> 01:13:14,026\r\nmerchant. If he makes a buying mistake, it\ndoesn't affect him much. But we two\r\n\r\n872\r\n01:13:14,026 --> 01:13:19,255\r\nhave to live with our mistakes.\"\nThat's true enough, the boy thought, ruefully.\r\n\r\n873\r\n01:13:19,489 --> 01:13:25,510\r\n\"Why did you think we should have the display?\"\n\"I want to get back to my sheep faster. We\r\n\r\n874\r\n01:13:25,051 --> 01:13:29,052\r\nhave to take advantage when luck is\non our side, and do as much to help it as\r\n\r\n875\r\n01:13:29,061 --> 01:13:33,280\r\nit's doing to help us. It's called the\nprinciple of favorability. Or beginner's luck.\"\r\n\r\n876\r\n01:13:33,829 --> 01:13:38,870\r\nThe merchant was silent for a few moments.\nThen he said, \"The Prophet gave us\r\n\r\n877\r\n01:13:39,239 --> 01:13:44,317\r\nthe Koran, and left us just five obligations\nto satisfy during our lives. The most\r\n\r\n878\r\n01:13:45,019 --> 01:13:49,100\r\nimportant is to believe only in the one true\nGod. The others are to pray five\r\n\r\n879\r\n01:13:49,829 --> 01:13:54,921\r\ntimes a day, fast during Ramadan, and be charitable\nto the poor.\"\r\n\r\n880\r\n01:13:55,749 --> 01:14:00,822\r\nHe stopped there. His eyes filled with tears\nas he spoke of the Prophet. He was\r\n\r\n881\r\n01:14:01,479 --> 01:14:07,550\r\na devout man, and, even with all his impatience,\nhe wanted to live his life in\r\n\r\n882\r\n01:14:07,055 --> 01:14:11,130\r\naccordance with Muslim law.\n\"What's the fifth obligation?\" the boy asked.\r\n\r\n883\r\n01:14:12,003 --> 01:14:16,882\r\n\"Two days ago, you said that I had never dreamed\nof travel,\" the merchant\r\n\r\n884\r\n01:14:17,179 --> 01:14:24,179\r\nanswered. \"The fifth obligation of every Muslim\nis a pilgrimage. We are obliged,\r\n\r\n885\r\n01:14:24,199 --> 01:14:28,208\r\nat least once in our lives, to visit the holy\ncity of Mecca.\r\n\r\n886\r\n01:14:28,289 --> 01:14:34,340\r\n\"Mecca is a lot farther away than the Pyramids.\nWhen I was young, all I wanted\r\n\r\n887\r\n01:14:34,034 --> 01:14:38,413\r\nto do was put together enough money to start\nthis shop. I thought that someday\r\n\r\n888\r\n01:14:38,719 --> 01:14:43,811\r\nI'd be rich, and could go to Mecca. I began\nto make some money, but I could\r\n\r\n889\r\n01:14:44,639 --> 01:14:47,697\r\nnever bring myself to leave someone in charge\nof the shop; the crystals are\r\n\r\n890\r\n01:14:48,219 --> 01:14:52,305\r\ndelicate things. At the same time, people\nwere passing my shop all the time,\r\n\r\n891\r\n01:14:53,079 --> 01:14:57,380\r\nheading for Mecca. Some of them were rich\npilgrims, traveling in caravans with\r\n\r\n892\r\n01:14:57,038 --> 01:15:01,061\r\nservants and camels, but most of the people\nmaking the pilgrimage were poorer\r\n\r\n893\r\n01:15:01,061 --> 01:15:04,153\r\nthan I.\n\"All who went there were happy at having done\r\n\r\n894\r\n01:15:05,053 --> 01:15:10,057\r\nso. They placed the symbols of\nthe pilgrimage on the doors of their houses.\r\n\r\n895\r\n01:15:10,057 --> 01:15:14,101\r\nOne of them, a cobbler who made\nhis living mending boots, said that he had\r\n\r\n896\r\n01:15:15,001 --> 01:15:19,030\r\ntraveled for almost a year through\nthe desert, but that he got more tired when\r\n\r\n897\r\n01:15:19,039 --> 01:15:21,120\r\nhe had to walk through the streets\nof Tangier buying his leather.\"\r\n\r\n898\r\n01:15:21,849 --> 01:15:25,530\r\n\"Well, why don't you go to Mecca now?\" asked\nthe boy.\r\n\r\n899\r\n01:15:25,053 --> 01:15:30,142\r\n\"Because it's the thought of Mecca that keeps\nme alive. That's what helps me\r\n\r\n900\r\n01:15:31,042 --> 01:15:36,221\r\nface these days that are all the same, these\nmute crystals on the shelves, and\r\n\r\n901\r\n01:15:36,599 --> 01:15:41,760\r\nlunch and dinner at that same horrible café.\nI'm afraid that if my dream is\r\n\r\n902\r\n01:15:41,076 --> 01:15:46,685\r\nrealized, I'll have no reason to go on living.\n\"You dream about your sheep and the Pyramids,\r\n\r\n903\r\n01:15:47,369 --> 01:15:51,436\r\nbut you're different from me,\nbecause you want to realize your dreams. I\r\n\r\n904\r\n01:15:52,039 --> 01:15:57,074\r\njust want to dream about Mecca.\nI've already imagined a thousand times crossing\r\n\r\n905\r\n01:15:57,389 --> 01:16:01,450\r\nthe desert, arriving at the\nPlaza of the Sacred Stone, the seven times\r\n\r\n906\r\n01:16:01,999 --> 01:16:06,097\r\nI walk around it before allowing\nmyself to touch it. I've already imagined\r\n\r\n907\r\n01:16:06,979 --> 01:16:11,066\r\nthe people who would be at my side,\nand those in front of me, and the conversations\r\n\r\n908\r\n01:16:11,849 --> 01:16:17,880\r\nand prayers we would share.\nBut I'm afraid that it would all be a disappointment,\r\n\r\n909\r\n01:16:17,088 --> 01:16:20,747\r\nso I prefer just to dream\nabout it.\"\r\n\r\n910\r\n01:16:21,539 --> 01:16:26,530\r\nThat day, the merchant gave the boy permission\nto build the display. Not\r\n\r\n911\r\n01:16:26,053 --> 01:16:29,912\r\neveryone can see his dreams come true in the\nsame way.\r\n\r\n912\r\n01:16:30,389 --> 01:16:33,900\r\n*\nTwo more months passed, and the shelf brought\r\n\r\n913\r\n01:16:33,009 --> 01:16:37,538\r\nmany customers into the\ncrystal shop. The boy estimated that, if he\r\n\r\n914\r\n01:16:38,429 --> 01:16:42,433\r\nworked for six more months, he\ncould return to Spain and buy sixty sheep,\r\n\r\n915\r\n01:16:42,829 --> 01:16:48,650\r\nand yet another sixty. In less than a\nyear, he would have doubled his flock, and\r\n\r\n916\r\n01:16:48,065 --> 01:16:51,954\r\nhe would be able to do business with\nthe Arabs, because he was now able to speak\r\n\r\n917\r\n01:16:52,539 --> 01:16:56,634\r\ntheir strange language. Since that\nmorning in the marketplace, he had never again\r\n\r\n918\r\n01:16:57,489 --> 01:17:02,498\r\nmade use of Urim and\nThummim, because Egypt was now just as distant\r\n\r\n919\r\n01:17:02,579 --> 01:17:06,617\r\na dream for him as was Mecca\nfor the merchant. Anyway, the boy had become\r\n\r\n920\r\n01:17:06,959 --> 01:17:10,986\r\nhappy in his work, and thought\nall the time about the day when he would disembark\r\n\r\n921\r\n01:17:11,229 --> 01:17:17,312\r\nat Tarifa as a winner.\n\"You must always know what it is that you\r\n\r\n922\r\n01:17:18,059 --> 01:17:24,126\r\nwant,\" the old king had said. The boy\nknew, and was now working toward it. Maybe\r\n\r\n923\r\n01:17:24,729 --> 01:17:28,753\r\nit was his treasure to have wound\nup in that strange land, met up with a thief,\r\n\r\n924\r\n01:17:28,969 --> 01:17:32,971\r\nand doubled the size of his flock\nwithout spending a cent.\r\n\r\n925\r\n01:17:32,989 --> 01:17:37,033\r\nHe was proud of himself. He had learned some\nimportant things, like how to\r\n\r\n926\r\n01:17:37,429 --> 01:17:43,760\r\ndeal in crystal, and about the language without\nwords... and about omens. One\r\n\r\n927\r\n01:17:43,076 --> 01:17:46,132\r\nafternoon he had seen a man at the top of\nthe hill, complaining that it was\r\n\r\n928\r\n01:17:47,032 --> 01:17:51,561\r\nimpossible to find a decent place to get something\nto drink after such a climb.\r\n\r\n929\r\n01:17:51,849 --> 01:17:55,943\r\nThe boy, accustomed to recognizing omens,\nspoke to the merchant.\r\n\r\n930\r\n01:17:56,789 --> 01:18:00,280\r\n\"Let's sell tea to the people who climb the\nhill.\"\r\n\r\n931\r\n01:18:00,028 --> 01:18:03,737\r\n\"Lots of places sell tea around here,\" the\nmerchant said.\r\n\r\n932\r\n01:18:03,989 --> 01:18:09,070\r\n\"But we could sell tea in crystal glasses.\nThe people will enjoy the tea and want\r\n\r\n933\r\n01:18:09,007 --> 01:18:14,086\r\nto buy the glasses. I have been told that\nbeauty is the great seducer of men.\"\r\n\r\n934\r\n01:18:14,086 --> 01:18:18,705\r\nThe merchant didn't respond, but that afternoon,\nafter saying his prayers and\r\n\r\n935\r\n01:18:19,479 --> 01:18:23,551\r\nclosing the shop, he invited the boy to sit\nwith him and share his hookah, that\r\n\r\n936\r\n01:18:24,199 --> 01:18:30,130\r\nstrange pipe used by the Arabs.\n\"What is it you're looking for?\" asked the\r\n\r\n937\r\n01:18:30,013 --> 01:18:34,062\r\nold merchant.\n\"I've already told you. I need to buy my sheep\r\n\r\n938\r\n01:18:34,179 --> 01:18:37,192\r\nback, so I have to earn the\nmoney to do so.\"\r\n\r\n939\r\n01:18:37,309 --> 01:18:41,324\r\nThe merchant put some new coals in the hookah,\nand inhaled deeply.\r\n\r\n940\r\n01:18:41,459 --> 01:18:46,537\r\n\"I've had this shop for thirty years. I know\ngood crystal from bad, and\r\n\r\n941\r\n01:18:47,239 --> 01:18:52,239\r\neverything else there is to know about crystal.\nI know its dimensions and how it\r\n\r\n942\r\n01:18:52,239 --> 01:18:57,312\r\nbehaves. If we serve tea in crystal, the shop\nis going to expand. And then I'll\r\n\r\n943\r\n01:18:57,969 --> 01:19:02,036\r\nhave to change my way of life.\"\n\"Well, isn't that good?\"\r\n\r\n944\r\n01:19:02,639 --> 01:19:07,880\r\n\"I'm already used to the way things are. Before\nyou came, I was thinking about\r\n\r\n945\r\n01:19:07,088 --> 01:19:10,134\r\nhow much time I had wasted in the same place,\nwhile my friends had moved\r\n\r\n946\r\n01:19:11,034 --> 01:19:15,173\r\non, and either went bankrupt or did better\nthan they had before. It made me\r\n\r\n947\r\n01:19:15,479 --> 01:19:22,479\r\nvery depressed. Now, I can see that it hasn't\nbeen too bad. The shop is exactly\r\n\r\n948\r\n01:19:22,959 --> 01:19:26,017\r\nthe size I always wanted it to be. I don't\nwant to change anything, because I\r\n\r\n949\r\n01:19:26,539 --> 01:19:31,622\r\ndon't know how to deal with change. I'm used\nto the way I am.\"\r\n\r\n950\r\n01:19:32,369 --> 01:19:36,880\r\nThe boy didn't know what to say. The old man\ncontinued, \"You have been a real\r\n\r\n951\r\n01:19:36,088 --> 01:19:41,617\r\nblessing to me. Today, I understand something\nI didn't see before: every\r\n\r\n952\r\n01:19:42,409 --> 01:19:48,434\r\nblessing ignored becomes a curse. I don't\nwant anything else in life. But you are\r\n\r\n953\r\n01:19:48,659 --> 01:19:53,684\r\nforcing me to look at wealth and at horizons\nI have never known. Now that I\r\n\r\n954\r\n01:19:53,909 --> 01:19:57,932\r\nhave seen them, and now that I see how immense\nmy possibilities are, I'm\r\n\r\n955\r\n01:19:58,139 --> 01:20:03,187\r\ngoing to feel worse than I did before you\narrived. Because I know the things I\r\n\r\n956\r\n01:20:03,619 --> 01:20:08,670\r\nshould be able to accomplish, and I don't\nwant to do so.\"\r\n\r\n957\r\n01:20:08,067 --> 01:20:11,896\r\nIt's good I refrained from saying anything\nto the baker in Tarifa, thought the\r\n\r\n958\r\n01:20:12,499 --> 01:20:16,860\r\nboy to himself.\nThey went on smoking the pipe for a while\r\n\r\n959\r\n01:20:16,086 --> 01:20:21,090\r\nas the sun began to set. They were\nconversing in Arabic, and the boy was proud\r\n\r\n960\r\n01:20:21,009 --> 01:20:25,608\r\nof himself for being able to do so.\nThere had been a time when he thought that\r\n\r\n961\r\n01:20:26,499 --> 01:20:29,530\r\nhis sheep could teach him\neverything he needed to know about the world.\r\n\r\n962\r\n01:20:29,809 --> 01:20:32,905\r\nBut they could never have\ntaught him Arabic.\r\n\r\n963\r\n01:20:33,769 --> 01:20:35,775\r\nThere are probably other things in the world\nthat the sheep can't teach me,\r\n\r\n964\r\n01:20:36,369 --> 01:20:40,431\r\nthought the boy as he regarded the old merchant.\nAll they ever do, really, is\r\n\r\n965\r\n01:20:40,989 --> 01:20:45,034\r\nlook for food and water. And maybe it wasn't\nthat they were teaching me, but\r\n\r\n966\r\n01:20:45,439 --> 01:20:51,440\r\nthat I was learning from them.\n\"Maktub,\" the merchant said, finally.\r\n\r\n967\r\n01:20:51,449 --> 01:20:55,590\r\n\"What does that mean?\"\n\"You would have to have been born an Arab\r\n\r\n968\r\n01:20:55,059 --> 01:21:00,508\r\nto understand,\" he answered. \"But\nin your language it would be something like\r\n\r\n969\r\n01:21:01,039 --> 01:21:06,046\r\n'It is written.' \"\nAnd, as he smothered the coals in the hookah,\r\n\r\n970\r\n01:21:06,739 --> 01:21:11,510\r\nhe told the boy that he could\nbegin to sell tea in the crystal glasses.\r\n\r\n971\r\n01:21:11,051 --> 01:21:17,059\r\nSometimes, there's just no way to hold\nback the river.\r\n\r\n972\r\n01:21:17,059 --> 01:21:19,398\r\n*\nThe men climbed the hill, and they were tired\r\n\r\n973\r\n01:21:19,929 --> 01:21:24,280\r\nwhen they reached the top. But\nthere they saw a crystal shop that offered\r\n\r\n974\r\n01:21:24,028 --> 01:21:29,447\r\nrefreshing mint tea. They went in to\ndrink the tea, which was served in beautiful\r\n\r\n975\r\n01:21:29,699 --> 01:21:33,530\r\ncrystal glasses.\n\"My wife never thought of this,\" said one,\r\n\r\n976\r\n01:21:33,053 --> 01:21:38,062\r\nand he bought some crystal--he was\nentertaining guests that night, and the guests\r\n\r\n977\r\n01:21:38,539 --> 01:21:42,577\r\nwould be impressed by the beauty\nof the glassware. The other man remarked that\r\n\r\n978\r\n01:21:42,919 --> 01:21:46,090\r\ntea was always more delicious\nwhen it was served in crystal, because the\r\n\r\n979\r\n01:21:46,009 --> 01:21:50,086\r\naroma was retained. The third said\nthat it was a tradition in the Orient to use\r\n\r\n980\r\n01:21:50,086 --> 01:21:55,101\r\ncrystal glasses for tea because it had\nmagical powers.\r\n\r\n981\r\n01:21:56,001 --> 01:21:59,710\r\nBefore long, the news spread, and a great\nmany people began to climb the hill\r\n\r\n982\r\n01:21:59,719 --> 01:22:04,630\r\nto see the shop that was doing something new\nin a trade that was so old. Other\r\n\r\n983\r\n01:22:04,063 --> 01:22:07,157\r\nshops were opened that served tea in crystal,\nbut they weren't at the top of a\r\n\r\n984\r\n01:22:08,057 --> 01:22:14,088\r\nhill, and they had little business.\nEventually, the merchant had to hire two more\r\n\r\n985\r\n01:22:14,088 --> 01:22:19,427\r\nemployees. He began to import\nenormous quantities of tea, along with his\r\n\r\n986\r\n01:22:20,219 --> 01:22:23,317\r\ncrystal, and his shop was sought out\nby men and women with a thirst for things\r\n\r\n987\r\n01:22:24,199 --> 01:22:29,291\r\nnew.\nAnd, in that way, the months passed.\r\n\r\n988\r\n01:22:30,119 --> 01:22:33,211\r\n*\nThe boy awoke before dawn. It had been eleven\r\n\r\n989\r\n01:22:34,039 --> 01:22:39,130\r\nmonths and nine days since he\nhad first set foot on the African continent.\r\n\r\n990\r\n01:22:39,949 --> 01:22:45,968\r\nHe dressed in his Arabian clothing of white\nlinen, bought especially for this day.\r\n\r\n991\r\n01:22:46,139 --> 01:22:51,090\r\nHe put his headcloth in place and secured\nit with a ring made of camel skin.\r\n\r\n992\r\n01:22:51,009 --> 01:22:55,057\r\nWearing his new sandals, he descended the\nstairs silently.\r\n\r\n993\r\n01:22:55,057 --> 01:23:00,926\r\nThe city was still sleeping. He prepared himself\na sandwich and drank some hot\r\n\r\n994\r\n01:23:01,439 --> 01:23:06,494\r\ntea from a crystal glass. Then he sat in the\nsun-filled doorway, smoking the\r\n\r\n995\r\n01:23:06,989 --> 01:23:12,073\r\nhookah.\nHe smoked in silence, thinking of nothing,\r\n\r\n996\r\n01:23:12,829 --> 01:23:16,910\r\nand listening to the sound of the wind\nthat brought the scent of the desert. When\r\n\r\n997\r\n01:23:17,639 --> 01:23:21,704\r\nhe had finished his smoke, he\nreached into one of his pockets, and sat there\r\n\r\n998\r\n01:23:22,289 --> 01:23:27,307\r\nfor a few moments, regarding\nwhat he had withdrawn.\r\n\r\n999\r\n01:23:27,469 --> 01:23:33,510\r\nIt was a bundle of money. Enough to buy himself\na hundred and twenty sheep,\r\n\r\n1000\r\n01:23:33,051 --> 01:23:38,970\r\na return ticket, and a license to import products\nfrom Africa into his own\r\n\r\n1001\r\n01:23:39,429 --> 01:23:42,453\r\ncountry.\nHe waited patiently for the merchant to awaken\r\n\r\n1002\r\n01:23:42,669 --> 01:23:46,741\r\nand open the shop. Then the\ntwo went off to have some more tea.\r\n\r\n1003\r\n01:23:47,389 --> 01:23:52,474\r\n\"I'm leaving today,\" said the boy. \"I have\nthe money I need to buy my sheep.\r\n\r\n1004\r\n01:23:53,239 --> 01:23:57,321\r\nAnd you have the money you need to go to Mecca.\"\nThe old man said nothing.\r\n\r\n1005\r\n01:23:58,059 --> 01:24:04,132\r\n\"Will you give me your blessing?\" asked the\nboy. \"You have helped me.\" The\r\n\r\n1006\r\n01:24:04,789 --> 01:24:09,070\r\nman continued to prepare his tea, saying nothing.\nThen he turned to the boy.\r\n\r\n1007\r\n01:24:09,007 --> 01:24:15,616\r\n\"I am proud of you,\" he said. \"You brought\na new feeling into my crystal shop.\r\n\r\n1008\r\n01:24:15,679 --> 01:24:19,710\r\nBut you know that I'm not going to go to Mecca.\nJust as you know that you're\r\n\r\n1009\r\n01:24:19,989 --> 01:24:26,050\r\nnot going to buy your sheep.\"\n\"Who told you that?\" asked the boy, startled.\r\n\r\n1010\r\n01:24:26,005 --> 01:24:33,005\r\n\"Maktub\" said the old crystal merchant.\nAnd he gave the boy his blessing.\r\n\r\n1011\r\n01:24:33,086 --> 01:24:36,435\r\n*\nThe boy went to his room and packed his belongings.\r\n\r\n1012\r\n01:24:37,209 --> 01:24:42,300\r\nThey filled three sacks. As\nhe was leaving, he saw, in the corner of the\r\n\r\n1013\r\n01:24:42,003 --> 01:24:46,622\r\nroom, his old shepherd's pouch. It\nwas bunched up, and he had hardly thought\r\n\r\n1014\r\n01:24:46,919 --> 01:24:50,994\r\nof it for a long time. As he took his\njacket out of the pouch, thinking to give\r\n\r\n1015\r\n01:24:51,669 --> 01:24:58,669\r\nit to someone in the street, the two\nstones fell to the floor. Urim and Thummim.\r\n\r\n1016\r\n01:24:59,959 --> 01:25:05,015\r\nIt made the boy think of the old king, and\nit startled him to realize how long it\r\n\r\n1017\r\n01:25:05,519 --> 01:25:10,600\r\nhad been since he had thought of him. For\nnearly a year, he had been working\r\n\r\n1018\r\n01:25:11,329 --> 01:25:15,341\r\nincessantly, thinking only of putting aside\nenough money so that he could return\r\n\r\n1019\r\n01:25:15,449 --> 01:25:22,449\r\nto Spain with pride.\n\"Never stop dreaming,\" the old king had said.\r\n\r\n1020\r\n01:25:22,489 --> 01:25:29,489\r\n\"Follow the omens.\"\nThe boy picked up Urim and Thummim, and, once\r\n\r\n1021\r\n01:25:30,209 --> 01:25:35,237\r\nagain, had the strange\nsensation that the old king was nearby. He\r\n\r\n1022\r\n01:25:35,489 --> 01:25:41,557\r\nhad worked hard for a year, and the\nomens were that it was time to go.\r\n\r\n1023\r\n01:25:42,169 --> 01:25:47,280\r\nI'm going to go back to doing just what I\ndid before, the boy thought. Even\r\n\r\n1024\r\n01:25:47,028 --> 01:25:50,417\r\nthough the sheep didn't teach me to speak\nArabic.\r\n\r\n1025\r\n01:25:50,669 --> 01:25:55,260\r\nBut the sheep had taught him something even\nmore important: that there was a\r\n\r\n1026\r\n01:25:55,026 --> 01:25:58,425\r\nlanguage in the world that everyone understood,\na language the boy had used\r\n\r\n1027\r\n01:25:58,659 --> 01:26:01,820\r\nthroughout the time that he was trying to\nimprove things at the shop. It was the\r\n\r\n1028\r\n01:26:01,082 --> 01:26:07,165\r\nlanguage of enthusiasm, of things accomplished\nwith love and purpose, and as\r\n\r\n1029\r\n01:26:08,065 --> 01:26:14,084\r\npart of a search for something believed in\nand desired. Tangier was no longer a\r\n\r\n1030\r\n01:26:14,669 --> 01:26:18,726\r\nstrange city, and he felt that, just as he\nhad conquered this place, he could\r\n\r\n1031\r\n01:26:19,239 --> 01:26:25,317\r\nconquer the world.\n\"When you want something, all the universe\r\n\r\n1032\r\n01:26:26,019 --> 01:26:30,037\r\nconspires to help you achieve it,\"\nthe old king had said.\r\n\r\n1033\r\n01:26:30,199 --> 01:26:35,610\r\nBut the old king hadn't said anything about\nbeing robbed, or about endless\r\n\r\n1034\r\n01:26:35,061 --> 01:26:38,076\r\ndeserts, or about people who know what their\ndreams are but don't want to\r\n\r\n1035\r\n01:26:38,076 --> 01:26:42,495\r\nrealize them. The old king hadn't told him\nthat the Pyramids were just a pile of\r\n\r\n1036\r\n01:26:43,179 --> 01:26:47,188\r\nstones, or that anyone could build one in\nhis backyard. And he had forgotten to\r\n\r\n1037\r\n01:26:48,079 --> 01:26:51,280\r\nmention that, when you have enough money to\nbuy a flock larger than the one\r\n\r\n1038\r\n01:26:51,028 --> 01:26:55,657\r\nyou had before, you should buy it.\nThe boy picked up his pouch and put it with\r\n\r\n1039\r\n01:26:55,909 --> 01:27:00,940\r\nhis other things. He went down the\nstairs and found the merchant waiting on a\r\n\r\n1040\r\n01:27:01,219 --> 01:27:03,276\r\nforeign couple, while two other\ncustomers walked about the shop, drinking\r\n\r\n1041\r\n01:27:03,789 --> 01:27:08,010\r\ntea from crystal glasses. It was\nmore activity than usual for this time of\r\n\r\n1042\r\n01:27:08,001 --> 01:27:13,032\r\nthe morning. From where he stood, he\nsaw for the first time that the old merchant's\r\n\r\n1043\r\n01:27:13,032 --> 01:27:18,501\r\nhair was very much like the hair of\nthe old king. He remembered the smile of the\r\n\r\n1044\r\n01:27:18,789 --> 01:27:22,789\r\ncandy seller, on his first day in\nTangier, when he had nothing to eat and nowhere\r\n\r\n1045\r\n01:27:22,789 --> 01:27:27,828\r\nto go--that smile had also\nbeen like the old king's smile.\r\n\r\n1046\r\n01:27:28,179 --> 01:27:33,203\r\nIt's almost as if he had been here and left\nhis mark, he thought. And yet, none\r\n\r\n1047\r\n01:27:33,419 --> 01:27:37,475\r\nof these people has ever met the old king.\nOn the other hand, he said that he\r\n\r\n1048\r\n01:27:37,979 --> 01:27:43,001\r\nalways appeared to help those who are trying\nto realize their Personal Legend.\r\n\r\n1049\r\n01:27:43,199 --> 01:27:46,278\r\nHe left without saying good-bye to the crystal\nmerchant. He didn't want to cry\r\n\r\n1050\r\n01:27:46,989 --> 01:27:50,996\r\nwith the other people there. He was going\nto miss the place and all the good\r\n\r\n1051\r\n01:27:51,689 --> 01:27:55,743\r\nthings he had learned. He was more confident\nin himself, though, and felt as\r\n\r\n1052\r\n01:27:56,229 --> 01:28:01,590\r\nthough he could conquer the world.\n\"But I'm going back to the fields that I know,\r\n\r\n1053\r\n01:28:01,059 --> 01:28:06,278\r\nto take care of my flock again.\"\nHe said that to himself with certainty, but\r\n\r\n1054\r\n01:28:06,809 --> 01:28:11,827\r\nhe was no longer happy with his\ndecision. He had worked for an entire year\r\n\r\n1055\r\n01:28:11,989 --> 01:28:17,004\r\nto make a dream come true, and\nthat dream, minute by minute, was becoming\r\n\r\n1056\r\n01:28:17,139 --> 01:28:23,192\r\nless important. Maybe because\nthat wasn't really his dream.\r\n\r\n1057\r\n01:28:23,669 --> 01:28:27,704\r\nWho knows... maybe it's better to be like\nthe crystal merchant: never go to\r\n\r\n1058\r\n01:28:28,019 --> 01:28:32,052\r\nMecca, and just go through life wanting to\ndo so, he thought, again trying to\r\n\r\n1059\r\n01:28:32,349 --> 01:28:37,441\r\nconvince himself. But as he held Urim and\nThummim in his hand, they had\r\n\r\n1060\r\n01:28:38,269 --> 01:28:43,360\r\ntransmitted to him the strength and will of\nthe old king. By coincidence--or\r\n\r\n1061\r\n01:28:44,179 --> 01:28:48,227\r\nmaybe it was an omen, the boy thought--he\ncame to the bar he had entered on\r\n\r\n1062\r\n01:28:48,659 --> 01:28:53,880\r\nhis first day there. The thief wasn't there,\nand the owner brought him a cup of\r\n\r\n1063\r\n01:28:53,088 --> 01:28:57,107\r\ntea.\nI can always go back to being a shepherd,\r\n\r\n1064\r\n01:28:58,007 --> 01:29:02,011\r\nthe boy thought. I learned how to\ncare for sheep, and I haven't forgotten how\r\n\r\n1065\r\n01:29:02,011 --> 01:29:06,400\r\nthat's done. But maybe I'll never\nhave another chance to get to the Pyramids\r\n\r\n1066\r\n01:29:06,499 --> 01:29:11,506\r\nin Egypt. The old man wore a\nbreastplate of gold, and he knew about my\r\n\r\n1067\r\n01:29:12,199 --> 01:29:17,287\r\npast. He really was a king, a wise\nking.\r\n\r\n1068\r\n01:29:18,079 --> 01:29:23,167\r\nThe hills of Andalusia were only two hours\naway, but there was an entire desert\r\n\r\n1069\r\n01:29:23,959 --> 01:29:28,030\r\nbetween him and the Pyramids. Yet the boy\nfelt that there was another way to\r\n\r\n1070\r\n01:29:28,669 --> 01:29:33,677\r\nregard his situation: he was actually two\nhours closer to his treasure... the fact\r\n\r\n1071\r\n01:29:34,469 --> 01:29:39,505\r\nthat the two hours had stretched into an entire\nyear didn't matter.\r\n\r\n1072\r\n01:29:39,829 --> 01:29:43,858\r\nI know why I want to get back to my flock,\nhe thought. I understand sheep;\r\n\r\n1073\r\n01:29:44,119 --> 01:29:48,320\r\nthey're no longer a problem, and they can\nbe good friends. On the other hand, I\r\n\r\n1074\r\n01:29:48,032 --> 01:29:51,331\r\ndon't know if the desert can be a friend,\nand it's in the desert that I have to\r\n\r\n1075\r\n01:29:51,619 --> 01:29:56,698\r\nsearch for my treasure. If I don't find it,\nI can always go home. I finally have\r\n\r\n1076\r\n01:29:57,409 --> 01:30:01,417\r\nenough money, and all the time I need. Why\nnot?\r\n\r\n1077\r\n01:30:02,209 --> 01:30:06,800\r\nHe suddenly felt tremendously happy. He could\nalways go back to being a\r\n\r\n1078\r\n01:30:06,008 --> 01:30:10,517\r\nshepherd. He could always become a crystal\nsalesman again. Maybe the world\r\n\r\n1079\r\n01:30:11,309 --> 01:30:15,530\r\nhad other hidden treasures, but he had a dream,\nand he had met with a king.\r\n\r\n1080\r\n01:30:15,053 --> 01:30:21,662\r\nThat doesn't happen to just anyone!\nHe was planning as he left the bar. He had\r\n\r\n1081\r\n01:30:22,139 --> 01:30:25,224\r\nremembered that one of the crystal\nmerchant's suppliers transported his crystal\r\n\r\n1082\r\n01:30:25,989 --> 01:30:31,013\r\nby means of caravans that crossed\nthe desert. He held Urim and Thummim in his\r\n\r\n1083\r\n01:30:31,229 --> 01:30:36,570\r\nhand; because of those two\nstones, he was once again on the way to his\r\n\r\n1084\r\n01:30:36,057 --> 01:30:41,376\r\ntreasure.\n\"I am always nearby, when someone wants to\r\n\r\n1085\r\n01:30:41,889 --> 01:30:46,970\r\nrealize their Personal Legend,\" the old\nking had told him.\r\n\r\n1086\r\n01:30:47,699 --> 01:30:51,756\r\nWhat could it cost to go over to the supplier's\nwarehouse and find out if the\r\n\r\n1087\r\n01:30:52,269 --> 01:30:55,331\r\nPyramids were really that far away?\n*\r\n\r\n1088\r\n01:30:55,889 --> 01:30:59,921\r\nThe Englishman was sitting on a bench in a\nstructure that smelled of animals,\r\n\r\n1089\r\n01:31:00,209 --> 01:31:06,210\r\nsweat, and dust; it was part warehouse, part\ncorral. I never thought I'd end up\r\n\r\n1090\r\n01:31:06,309 --> 01:31:10,311\r\nin a place like this, he thought, as he leafed\nthrough the pages of a chemical\r\n\r\n1091\r\n01:31:10,329 --> 01:31:14,402\r\njournal. Ten years at the university, and\nhere I am in a corral.\r\n\r\n1092\r\n01:31:15,059 --> 01:31:20,102\r\nBut he had to move on. He believed in omens.\nAll his life and all his studies\r\n\r\n1093\r\n01:31:20,489 --> 01:31:25,510\r\nwere aimed at finding the one true language\nof the universe. First he had\r\n\r\n1094\r\n01:31:25,699 --> 01:31:31,760\r\nstudied Esperanto, then the world's religions,\nand now it was alchemy. He knew\r\n\r\n1095\r\n01:31:31,076 --> 01:31:35,775\r\nhow to speak Esperanto, he understood all\nthe major religions well, but he\r\n\r\n1096\r\n01:31:36,459 --> 01:31:41,531\r\nwasn't yet an alchemist. He had unraveled\nthe truths behind important\r\n\r\n1097\r\n01:31:42,179 --> 01:31:45,187\r\nquestions, but his studies had taken him to\na point beyond which he could not\r\n\r\n1098\r\n01:31:45,979 --> 01:31:50,980\r\nseem to go. He had tried in vain to establish\na relationship with an alchemist.\r\n\r\n1099\r\n01:31:51,079 --> 01:31:54,820\r\nBut the alchemists were strange people, who\nthought only about themselves,\r\n\r\n1100\r\n01:31:54,082 --> 01:31:59,421\r\nand almost always refused to help him. Who\nknows, maybe they had failed to\r\n\r\n1101\r\n01:32:00,159 --> 01:32:03,205\r\ndiscover the secret of the Master Work--the\nPhilosopher's Stone--and for this\r\n\r\n1102\r\n01:32:03,619 --> 01:32:08,692\r\nreason kept their knowledge to themselves.\nHe had already spent much of the fortune left\r\n\r\n1103\r\n01:32:09,349 --> 01:32:14,010\r\nto him by his father, fruitlessly\nseeking the Philosopher's Stone. He had spent\r\n\r\n1104\r\n01:32:14,001 --> 01:32:17,550\r\nenormous amounts of time at the\ngreat libraries of the world, and had purchased\r\n\r\n1105\r\n01:32:17,559 --> 01:32:21,565\r\nall the rarest and most\nimportant volumes on alchemy. In one he had\r\n\r\n1106\r\n01:32:22,159 --> 01:32:26,218\r\nread that, many years ago, a\nfamous Arabian alchemist had visited Europe.\r\n\r\n1107\r\n01:32:26,749 --> 01:32:32,749\r\nIt was said that he was more than\ntwo hundred years old, and that he had discovered\r\n\r\n1108\r\n01:32:32,749 --> 01:32:37,826\r\nthe Philosopher's Stone and\nthe Elixir of Life. The Englishman had been\r\n\r\n1109\r\n01:32:38,519 --> 01:32:42,541\r\nprofoundly impressed by the story.\nBut he would never have thought it more than\r\n\r\n1110\r\n01:32:42,739 --> 01:32:46,833\r\njust a myth, had not a friend of\nhis--returning from an archaeological expedition\r\n\r\n1111\r\n01:32:47,679 --> 01:32:53,320\r\nin the desert--told him about an\nArab that was possessed of exceptional powers.\r\n\r\n1112\r\n01:32:53,032 --> 01:32:58,751\r\n\"He lives at the Al-Fayoum oasis,\" his friend\nhad said. \"And people say that he is\r\n\r\n1113\r\n01:32:59,039 --> 01:33:04,087\r\ntwo hundred years old, and is able to transform\nany metal into gold.\"\r\n\r\n1114\r\n01:33:04,519 --> 01:33:08,523\r\nThe Englishman could not contain his excitement.\nHe canceled all his\r\n\r\n1115\r\n01:33:08,559 --> 01:33:11,565\r\ncommitments and pulled together the most important\nof his books, and now\r\n\r\n1116\r\n01:33:11,619 --> 01:33:18,619\r\nhere he was, sitting inside a dusty, smelly\nwarehouse. Outside, a huge caravan\r\n\r\n1117\r\n01:33:19,749 --> 01:33:23,791\r\nwas being prepared for a crossing of the Sahara,\nand was scheduled to pass\r\n\r\n1118\r\n01:33:24,169 --> 01:33:28,214\r\nthrough Al-Fayoum.\nI'm going to find that damned alchemist, the\r\n\r\n1119\r\n01:33:28,619 --> 01:33:32,702\r\nEnglishman thought. And the odor\nof the animals became a bit more tolerable.\r\n\r\n1120\r\n01:33:33,449 --> 01:33:38,464\r\nA young Arab, also loaded down with baggage,\nentered, and greeted the\r\n\r\n1121\r\n01:33:38,599 --> 01:33:41,658\r\nEnglishman.\n\"Where are you bound?\" asked the young Arab.\r\n\r\n1122\r\n01:33:42,189 --> 01:33:46,760\r\n\"I'm going into the desert,\" the man answered,\nturning back to his reading. He\r\n\r\n1123\r\n01:33:46,076 --> 01:33:50,005\r\ndidn't want any conversation at this point.\nWhat he needed to do was review all\r\n\r\n1124\r\n01:33:50,689 --> 01:33:53,724\r\nhe had learned over the years, because the\nalchemist would certainly put him to\r\n\r\n1125\r\n01:33:54,039 --> 01:33:58,068\r\nthe test.\nThe young Arab took out a book and began to\r\n\r\n1126\r\n01:33:58,329 --> 01:34:03,404\r\nread. The book was written in\nSpanish. That's good, thought the Englishman.\r\n\r\n1127\r\n01:34:04,079 --> 01:34:08,380\r\nHe spoke Spanish better than\nArabic, and, if this boy was going to Al-Fayoum,\r\n\r\n1128\r\n01:34:08,038 --> 01:34:11,217\r\nthere would be someone to talk\nto when there were no other important things\r\n\r\n1129\r\n01:34:11,559 --> 01:34:12,563\r\nto do.\n*\r\n\r\n1130\r\n01:34:12,599 --> 01:34:18,610\r\n\"That's strange,\" said the boy, as he tried\nonce again to read the burial scene\r\n\r\n1131\r\n01:34:18,709 --> 01:34:23,730\r\nthat began the book. \"I've been trying for\ntwo years to read this book, and I\r\n\r\n1132\r\n01:34:23,919 --> 01:34:28,922\r\nnever get past these first few pages.\" Even\nwithout a king to provide an\r\n\r\n1133\r\n01:34:28,949 --> 01:34:33,953\r\ninterruption, he was unable to concentrate.\nHe still had some doubts about the decision\r\n\r\n1134\r\n01:34:33,989 --> 01:34:39,063\r\nhe had made. But he was able to\nunderstand one thing: making a decision was\r\n\r\n1135\r\n01:34:39,729 --> 01:34:44,590\r\nonly the beginning of things. When\nsomeone makes a decision, he is really diving\r\n\r\n1136\r\n01:34:44,059 --> 01:34:48,438\r\ninto a strong current that will\ncarry him to places he had never dreamed of\r\n\r\n1137\r\n01:34:48,969 --> 01:34:54,041\r\nwhen he first made the decision.\nWhen I decided to seek out my treasure, I\r\n\r\n1138\r\n01:34:54,689 --> 01:34:58,695\r\nnever imagined that I'd wind up\nworking in a crystal shop, he thought. And\r\n\r\n1139\r\n01:34:59,289 --> 01:35:03,050\r\njoining this caravan may have been\nmy decision, but where it goes is going to\r\n\r\n1140\r\n01:35:03,005 --> 01:35:08,063\r\nbe a mystery to me.\nNearby was the Englishman, reading a book.\r\n\r\n1141\r\n01:35:08,063 --> 01:35:13,151\r\nHe seemed unfriendly, and had\nlooked irritated when the boy had entered.\r\n\r\n1142\r\n01:35:14,051 --> 01:35:18,056\r\nThey might even have become\nfriends, but the Englishman closed off the\r\n\r\n1143\r\n01:35:19,001 --> 01:35:21,780\r\nconversation.\nThe boy closed his book. He felt that he didn't\r\n\r\n1144\r\n01:35:21,789 --> 01:35:24,877\r\nwant to do anything that might\nmake him look like the Englishman. He took\r\n\r\n1145\r\n01:35:25,669 --> 01:35:27,745\r\nUrim and Thummim from his\npocket, and began playing with them.\r\n\r\n1146\r\n01:35:28,429 --> 01:35:35,429\r\nThe stranger shouted, \"Urim and Thummim!\"\nIn a flash the boy put them back in his pocket.\r\n\r\n1147\r\n01:35:35,909 --> 01:35:41,010\r\n\"They're not for sale,\" he said.\n\"They're not worth much,\" the Englishman answered.\r\n\r\n1148\r\n01:35:41,001 --> 01:35:43,063\r\n\"They're only made of\nrock crystal, and there are millions of rock\r\n\r\n1149\r\n01:35:43,063 --> 01:35:47,512\r\ncrystals in the earth. But those who\nknow about such things would know that those\r\n\r\n1150\r\n01:35:48,079 --> 01:35:51,135\r\nare Urim and Thummim. I didn't\nknow that they had them in this part of the\r\n\r\n1151\r\n01:35:51,639 --> 01:35:54,662\r\nworld.\"\n\"They were given to me as a present by a king,\"\r\n\r\n1152\r\n01:35:54,869 --> 01:35:58,877\r\nthe boy said.\nThe stranger didn't answer; instead, he put\r\n\r\n1153\r\n01:35:59,669 --> 01:36:03,702\r\nhis hand in his pocket, and took out\ntwo stones that were the same as the boy's.\r\n\r\n1154\r\n01:36:03,999 --> 01:36:08,044\r\n\"Did you say a king?\" he asked.\n\"I guess you don't believe that a king would\r\n\r\n1155\r\n01:36:08,449 --> 01:36:12,010\r\ntalk to someone like me, a\nshepherd,\" he said, wanting to end the conversation.\r\n\r\n1156\r\n01:36:12,001 --> 01:36:16,080\r\n\"Not at all. It was shepherds who were the\nfirst to recognize a king that the rest\r\n\r\n1157\r\n01:36:16,008 --> 01:36:20,347\r\nof the world refused to acknowledge. So, it's\nnot surprising that kings would talk\r\n\r\n1158\r\n01:36:21,139 --> 01:36:25,192\r\nto shepherds.\"\nAnd he went on, fearing that the boy wouldn't\r\n\r\n1159\r\n01:36:25,669 --> 01:36:28,677\r\nunderstand what he was talking\nabout, \"It's in the Bible. The same book that\r\n\r\n1160\r\n01:36:29,469 --> 01:36:33,530\r\ntaught me about Urim and\nThummim. These stones were the only form of\r\n\r\n1161\r\n01:36:33,053 --> 01:36:38,134\r\ndivination permitted by God. The\npriests carried them in a golden breastplate.\"\r\n\r\n1162\r\n01:36:39,034 --> 01:36:42,913\r\nThe boy was suddenly happy to be there at\nthe warehouse.\r\n\r\n1163\r\n01:36:43,219 --> 01:36:47,224\r\n\"Maybe this is an omen,\" said the Englishman,\nhalf aloud.\r\n\r\n1164\r\n01:36:47,269 --> 01:36:51,356\r\n\"Who told you about omens?\" The boy's interest\nwas increasing by the moment.\r\n\r\n1165\r\n01:36:52,139 --> 01:36:55,197\r\n\"Everything in life is an omen,\" said the\nEnglishman, now closing the journal he\r\n\r\n1166\r\n01:36:55,719 --> 01:36:59,860\r\nwas reading. \"There is a universal language,\nunderstood by everybody, but\r\n\r\n1167\r\n01:36:59,086 --> 01:37:03,665\r\nalready forgotten. I am in search of that\nuniversal language, among other\r\n\r\n1168\r\n01:37:04,439 --> 01:37:08,380\r\nthings. That's why I'm here. I have to find\na man who knows that universal\r\n\r\n1169\r\n01:37:08,038 --> 01:37:12,507\r\nlanguage. An alchemist.\"\nThe conversation was interrupted by the warehouse\r\n\r\n1170\r\n01:37:12,849 --> 01:37:16,610\r\nboss.\n\"You're in luck, you two,\" the fat Arab said.\r\n\r\n1171\r\n01:37:16,061 --> 01:37:18,840\r\n\"There's a caravan leaving today for\nAl-Fayoum.\"\r\n\r\n1172\r\n01:37:19,389 --> 01:37:26,110\r\n\"But I'm going to Egypt,\" the boy said.\n\"Al-Fayoum is in Egypt,\" said the Arab. \"What\r\n\r\n1173\r\n01:37:26,011 --> 01:37:29,059\r\nkind of Arab are you?\"\n\"That's a good luck omen,\" the Englishman\r\n\r\n1174\r\n01:37:29,059 --> 01:37:33,968\r\nsaid, after the fat Arab had gone\nout. \"If I could, I'd write a huge encyclopedia\r\n\r\n1175\r\n01:37:34,499 --> 01:37:38,780\r\njust about the words luck and\ncoincidence. It's with those words that the\r\n\r\n1176\r\n01:37:38,078 --> 01:37:43,017\r\nuniversal language is written.''\nHe told the boy it was no coincidence that\r\n\r\n1177\r\n01:37:43,719 --> 01:37:46,815\r\nhe had met him with Urim and\nThummim in his hand. And he asked the boy\r\n\r\n1178\r\n01:37:47,679 --> 01:37:50,679\r\nif he, too, were in search of the\nalchemist.\r\n\r\n1179\r\n01:37:50,679 --> 01:37:54,757\r\n\"I'm looking for a treasure,\" said the boy,\nand he immediately regretted having\r\n\r\n1180\r\n01:37:55,459 --> 01:37:58,477\r\nsaid it. But the Englishman appeared not to\nattach any importance to it.\r\n\r\n1181\r\n01:37:58,639 --> 01:38:04,380\r\n\"In a way, so am I,\" he said.\n\"I don't even know what alchemy is,\" the boy\r\n\r\n1182\r\n01:38:04,038 --> 01:38:08,197\r\nwas saying, when the warehouse\nboss called to them to come outside.\r\n\r\n1183\r\n01:38:08,539 --> 01:38:13,630\r\n*\n\"I'm the leader of the caravan,\" said a dark-eyed,\r\n\r\n1184\r\n01:38:13,063 --> 01:38:18,322\r\nbearded man. \"I hold the\npower of life and death for every person I\r\n\r\n1185\r\n01:38:18,889 --> 01:38:24,917\r\ntake with me. The desert is a\ncapricious lady, and sometimes she drives\r\n\r\n1186\r\n01:38:25,169 --> 01:38:29,820\r\nmen crazy.\"\nThere were almost two hundred people gathered\r\n\r\n1187\r\n01:38:29,082 --> 01:38:34,159\r\nthere, and four hundred\nanimals--camels, horses, mules, and fowl.\r\n\r\n1188\r\n01:38:35,059 --> 01:38:38,130\r\nIn the crowd were women, children,\nand a number of men with swords at their belts\r\n\r\n1189\r\n01:38:39,003 --> 01:38:44,192\r\nand rifles slung on their\nshoulders. The Englishman had several suitcases\r\n\r\n1190\r\n01:38:44,489 --> 01:38:48,497\r\nfilled with books. There was a\nbabble of noise, and the leader had to repeat\r\n\r\n1191\r\n01:38:49,289 --> 01:38:52,353\r\nhimself several times for\neveryone to understand what he was saying.\r\n\r\n1192\r\n01:38:52,929 --> 01:38:58,955\r\n\"There are a lot of different people here,\nand each has his own God. But the\r\n\r\n1193\r\n01:38:59,189 --> 01:39:04,130\r\nonly God I serve is Allah, and in his name\nI swear that I will do everything\r\n\r\n1194\r\n01:39:04,013 --> 01:39:09,622\r\npossible once again to win out over the desert.\nBut I want each and every one\r\n\r\n1195\r\n01:39:09,739 --> 01:39:13,796\r\nof you to swear by the God you believe in\nthat you will follow my orders no\r\n\r\n1196\r\n01:39:14,309 --> 01:39:19,403\r\nmatter what. In the desert, disobedience means\ndeath.\"\r\n\r\n1197\r\n01:39:20,249 --> 01:39:24,280\r\nThere was a murmur from the crowd. Each was\nswearing quietly to his or her\r\n\r\n1198\r\n01:39:24,028 --> 01:39:31,028\r\nown God. The boy swore to Jesus Christ. The\nEnglishman said nothing. And the\r\n\r\n1199\r\n01:39:31,061 --> 01:39:35,450\r\nmurmur lasted longer than a simple vow would\nhave. The people were also\r\n\r\n1200\r\n01:39:35,999 --> 01:39:41,015\r\npraying to heaven for protection.\nA long note was sounded on a bugle, and everyone\r\n\r\n1201\r\n01:39:41,159 --> 01:39:45,234\r\nmounted up. The boy and\nthe Englishman had bought camels, and climbed\r\n\r\n1202\r\n01:39:45,909 --> 01:39:50,860\r\nuncertainly onto their backs.\nThe boy felt sorry for the Englishman's camel,\r\n\r\n1203\r\n01:39:50,086 --> 01:39:53,185\r\nloaded down as he was with the\ncases of books.\r\n\r\n1204\r\n01:39:53,959 --> 01:39:57,027\r\n\"There's no such thing as coincidence,\" said\nthe Englishman, picking up the\r\n\r\n1205\r\n01:39:57,639 --> 01:40:01,721\r\nconversation where it had been interrupted\nin the warehouse. \"I'm here because\r\n\r\n1206\r\n01:40:02,459 --> 01:40:07,475\r\na friend of mine heard of an Arab who...\"\nBut the caravan began to move, and it was\r\n\r\n1207\r\n01:40:07,619 --> 01:40:11,638\r\nimpossible to hear what the\nEnglishman was saying. The boy knew what he\r\n\r\n1208\r\n01:40:11,809 --> 01:40:15,850\r\nwas about to describe, though:\nthe mysterious chain that links one thing\r\n\r\n1209\r\n01:40:16,219 --> 01:40:21,090\r\nto another, the same chain that had\ncaused him to become a shepherd, that had\r\n\r\n1210\r\n01:40:21,009 --> 01:40:25,268\r\ncaused his recurring dream, that\nhad brought him to a city near Africa, to\r\n\r\n1211\r\n01:40:25,349 --> 01:40:29,358\r\nfind a king, and to be robbed in order\nto meet a crystal merchant, and...\r\n\r\n1212\r\n01:40:29,439 --> 01:40:35,440\r\nThe closer one gets to realizing his Personal\nLegend, the more that Personal Legend becomes\r\n\r\n1213\r\n01:40:35,539 --> 01:40:39,545\r\nhis\ntrue reason for being, thought the boy.\r\n\r\n1214\r\n01:40:39,599 --> 01:40:43,658\r\nThe caravan moved toward the east. It traveled\nduring the morning, halted\r\n\r\n1215\r\n01:40:44,189 --> 01:40:49,189\r\nwhen the sun was at its strongest, and resumed\nlate in the afternoon. The boy\r\n\r\n1216\r\n01:40:49,189 --> 01:40:52,226\r\nspoke very little with the Englishman, who\nspent most of his time with his\r\n\r\n1217\r\n01:40:52,559 --> 01:40:55,630\r\nbooks.\nThe boy observed in silence the progress of\r\n\r\n1218\r\n01:40:56,269 --> 01:41:00,860\r\nthe animals and people across the\ndesert. Now everything was quite different\r\n\r\n1219\r\n01:41:00,086 --> 01:41:05,015\r\nfrom how it was that day they had\nset out: then, there had been confusion and\r\n\r\n1220\r\n01:41:05,789 --> 01:41:08,825\r\nshouting, the cries of children and\nthe whinnying of animals, all mixed with the\r\n\r\n1221\r\n01:41:09,149 --> 01:41:11,215\r\nnervous orders of the guides and\nthe merchants.\r\n\r\n1222\r\n01:41:11,809 --> 01:41:16,880\r\nBut, in the desert, there was only the sound\nof the eternal wind, and of the\r\n\r\n1223\r\n01:41:16,088 --> 01:41:21,577\r\nhoofbeats of the animals. Even the guides\nspoke very little to one another.\r\n\r\n1224\r\n01:41:22,369 --> 01:41:27,530\r\n\"I've crossed these sands many times,\" said\none of the camel drivers one night.\r\n\r\n1225\r\n01:41:27,053 --> 01:41:32,812\r\n\"But the desert is so huge, and the horizons\nso distant, that they make a person\r\n\r\n1226\r\n01:41:33,289 --> 01:41:40,289\r\nfeel small, and as if he should remain silent.\"\nThe boy understood intuitively what he meant,\r\n\r\n1227\r\n01:41:41,809 --> 01:41:46,838\r\neven without ever having set\nfoot in the desert before. Whenever he saw\r\n\r\n1228\r\n01:41:47,099 --> 01:41:53,280\r\nthe sea, or a fire, he fell silent,\nimpressed by their elemental force.\r\n\r\n1229\r\n01:41:53,028 --> 01:41:57,727\r\nI've learned things from the sheep, and I've\nlearned things from crystal, he\r\n\r\n1230\r\n01:41:57,979 --> 01:42:04,041\r\nthought. I can learn something from the desert,\ntoo. It seems old and wise.\r\n\r\n1231\r\n01:42:04,599 --> 01:42:09,660\r\nThe wind never stopped, and the boy remembered\nthe day he had sat at the\r\n\r\n1232\r\n01:42:10,209 --> 01:42:15,210\r\nfort in Tarifa with this same wind blowing\nin his face. It reminded him of the\r\n\r\n1233\r\n01:42:15,219 --> 01:42:18,294\r\nwool from his sheep... his sheep who were\nnow seeking food and water in the\r\n\r\n1234\r\n01:42:18,969 --> 01:42:24,043\r\nfields of Andalusia, as they always had.\n\"They're not my sheep anymore,\" he said to\r\n\r\n1235\r\n01:42:24,709 --> 01:42:28,756\r\nhimself, without nostalgia. \"They\nmust be used to their new shepherd, and have\r\n\r\n1236\r\n01:42:29,179 --> 01:42:35,207\r\nprobably already forgotten me.\nThat's good. Creatures like the sheep, that\r\n\r\n1237\r\n01:42:35,459 --> 01:42:39,760\r\nare used to traveling, know about\nmoving on.\"\r\n\r\n1238\r\n01:42:39,076 --> 01:42:42,755\r\nHe thought of the merchant's daughter, and\nwas sure that she had probably\r\n\r\n1239\r\n01:42:43,439 --> 01:42:46,514\r\nmarried. Perhaps to a baker, or to another\nshepherd who could read and could\r\n\r\n1240\r\n01:42:47,189 --> 01:42:53,192\r\ntell her exciting stories--after all, he probably\nwasn't the only one. But he was\r\n\r\n1241\r\n01:42:53,489 --> 01:42:58,489\r\nexcited at his intuitive understanding of\nthe camel driver's comment: maybe he\r\n\r\n1242\r\n01:42:58,489 --> 01:43:01,536\r\nwas also learning the universal language that\ndeals with the past and the\r\n\r\n1243\r\n01:43:01,959 --> 01:43:07,280\r\npresent of all people. \"Hunches,\" his mother\nused to call them. The boy was\r\n\r\n1244\r\n01:43:07,028 --> 01:43:11,033\r\nbeginning to understand that intuition is\nreally a sudden immersion of the soul\r\n\r\n1245\r\n01:43:11,078 --> 01:43:17,086\r\ninto the universal current of life, where\nthe histories of all people are connected,\r\n\r\n1246\r\n01:43:17,086 --> 01:43:21,425\r\nand we are able to know everything, because\nit's all written there.\r\n\r\n1247\r\n01:43:22,199 --> 01:43:28,380\r\n\"Maktub,\" the boy said, remembering the crystal\nmerchant.\r\n\r\n1248\r\n01:43:28,038 --> 01:43:33,043\r\nThe desert was all sand in some stretches,\nand rocky in others. When the\r\n\r\n1249\r\n01:43:33,088 --> 01:43:37,105\r\ncaravan was blocked by a boulder, it had to\ngo around it; if there was a large\r\n\r\n1250\r\n01:43:38,005 --> 01:43:43,264\r\nrocky area, they had to make a major detour.\nIf the sand was too fine for the\r\n\r\n1251\r\n01:43:43,309 --> 01:43:47,390\r\nanimals' hooves, they sought a way where the\nsand was more substantial. In\r\n\r\n1252\r\n01:43:48,119 --> 01:43:52,206\r\nsome places, the ground was covered with the\nsalt of dried-up lakes. The\r\n\r\n1253\r\n01:43:52,989 --> 01:43:56,046\r\nanimals balked at such places, and the camel\ndrivers were forced to dismount\r\n\r\n1254\r\n01:43:56,559 --> 01:44:00,655\r\nand unburden their charges. The drivers carried\nthe freight themselves over\r\n\r\n1255\r\n01:44:01,519 --> 01:44:06,528\r\nsuch treacherous footing, and then reloaded\nthe camels. If a guide were to fall\r\n\r\n1256\r\n01:44:07,419 --> 01:44:11,444\r\nill or die, the camel drivers would draw lots\nand appoint a new one.\r\n\r\n1257\r\n01:44:11,669 --> 01:44:16,733\r\nBut all this happened for one basic reason:\nno matter how many detours and\r\n\r\n1258\r\n01:44:17,309 --> 01:44:23,070\r\nadjustments it made, the caravan moved toward\nthe same compass point. Once\r\n\r\n1259\r\n01:44:23,007 --> 01:44:28,034\r\nobstacles were overcome, it returned to its\ncourse, sighting on a star that\r\n\r\n1260\r\n01:44:28,034 --> 01:44:33,183\r\nindicated the location of the oasis. When\nthe people saw that star shining in the\r\n\r\n1261\r\n01:44:33,489 --> 01:44:38,260\r\nmorning sky, they knew they were on the right\ncourse toward water, palm\r\n\r\n1262\r\n01:44:38,026 --> 01:44:42,111\r\ntrees, shelter, and other people. It was only\nthe Englishman who was unaware\r\n\r\n1263\r\n01:44:43,011 --> 01:44:48,107\r\nof all this; he was, for the most part, immersed\nin reading his books.\r\n\r\n1264\r\n01:44:49,007 --> 01:44:53,176\r\nThe boy, too, had his book, and he had tried\nto read it during the first few days\r\n\r\n1265\r\n01:44:53,239 --> 01:44:56,284\r\nof the journey. But he found it much more\ninteresting to observe the caravan\r\n\r\n1266\r\n01:44:56,689 --> 01:45:00,787\r\nand listen to the wind. As soon as he had\nlearned to know his camel better, and\r\n\r\n1267\r\n01:45:01,669 --> 01:45:06,722\r\nto establish a relationship with him, he threw\nthe book away. Although the boy\r\n\r\n1268\r\n01:45:07,199 --> 01:45:10,233\r\nhad developed a superstition that each time\nhe opened the book he would learn\r\n\r\n1269\r\n01:45:10,539 --> 01:45:15,624\r\nsomething important, he decided it was an\nunnecessary burden.\r\n\r\n1270\r\n01:45:16,389 --> 01:45:20,477\r\nHe became friendly with the camel driver who\ntraveled alongside him. At night,\r\n\r\n1271\r\n01:45:21,269 --> 01:45:25,283\r\nas they sat around the fire, the boy related\nto the driver his adventures as a\r\n\r\n1272\r\n01:45:25,409 --> 01:45:29,413\r\nshepherd.\nDuring one of these conversations, the driver\r\n\r\n1273\r\n01:45:29,449 --> 01:45:34,508\r\ntold of his own life.\n\"I used to live near El Cairum,\" he said.\r\n\r\n1274\r\n01:45:35,039 --> 01:45:42,039\r\n\"I had my orchard, my children, and a\nlife that would change not at all until I\r\n\r\n1275\r\n01:45:42,057 --> 01:45:47,136\r\ndied. One year, when the crop was the\nbest ever, we all went to Mecca, and I satisfied\r\n\r\n1276\r\n01:45:47,649 --> 01:45:52,682\r\nthe only unmet obligation in my\nlife. I could die happily, and that made me\r\n\r\n1277\r\n01:45:52,979 --> 01:45:57,820\r\nfeel good.\n\"One day, the earth began to tremble, and\r\n\r\n1278\r\n01:45:57,082 --> 01:46:01,911\r\nthe Nile overflowed its banks. It was\nsomething that I thought could happen only\r\n\r\n1279\r\n01:46:02,649 --> 01:46:06,654\r\nto others, never to me. My\nneighbors feared they would lose all their\r\n\r\n1280\r\n01:46:06,699 --> 01:46:09,797\r\nolive trees in the flood, and my wife\nwas afraid that we would lose our children.\r\n\r\n1281\r\n01:46:10,679 --> 01:46:13,742\r\nI thought that everything I owned\nwould be destroyed.\r\n\r\n1282\r\n01:46:14,309 --> 01:46:18,309\r\n\"The land was ruined, and I had to find some\nother way to earn a living. So now\r\n\r\n1283\r\n01:46:18,309 --> 01:46:24,401\r\nI'm a camel driver. But that disaster taught\nme to understand the word of Allah:\r\n\r\n1284\r\n01:46:25,229 --> 01:46:28,297\r\npeople need not fear the unknown if they are\ncapable of achieving what they\r\n\r\n1285\r\n01:46:28,909 --> 01:46:32,964\r\nneed and want.\n\"We are afraid of losing what we have, whether\r\n\r\n1286\r\n01:46:33,459 --> 01:46:40,459\r\nit's our life or \r\n\r\n1287\r\n01:46:50,289 --> 01:46:54,320\r\nour possessions\nand property. But this fear evaporates when\r\n\r\n1288\r\n01:46:54,599 --> 01:46:58,610\r\nwe understand that our life stories\nand the history of the world were written\r\n\r\n1289\r\n01:46:58,061 --> 01:47:04,190\r\nby the same hand.\"\nSometimes, their caravan met with another.\r\n\r\n1290\r\n01:47:04,739 --> 01:47:07,808\r\nOne always had something that the\nother needed--as if everything were indeed\r\n\r\n1291\r\n01:47:08,429 --> 01:47:13,465\r\nwritten by one hand. As they sat\naround the fire, the camel drivers exchanged\r\n\r\n1292\r\n01:47:13,789 --> 01:47:18,090\r\ninformation about windstorms,\nand told stories about the desert.\r\n\r\n1293\r\n01:47:18,009 --> 01:47:24,558\r\nAt other times, mysterious, hooded men would\nappear; they were Bedouins who\r\n\r\n1294\r\n01:47:24,639 --> 01:47:28,723\r\ndid surveillance along the caravan route.\nThey provided warnings about thieves\r\n\r\n1295\r\n01:47:29,479 --> 01:47:35,360\r\nand barbarian tribes. They came in silence\nand departed the same way, dressed\r\n\r\n1296\r\n01:47:35,036 --> 01:47:40,125\r\nin black garments that showed only their eyes.\nOne night, a camel driver came\r\n\r\n1297\r\n01:47:40,449 --> 01:47:43,526\r\nto the fire where the Englishman and the boy\nwere sitting. \"There are rumors of\r\n\r\n1298\r\n01:47:44,219 --> 01:47:50,610\r\ntribal wars,\" he told them.\nThe three fell silent. The boy noted that\r\n\r\n1299\r\n01:47:50,061 --> 01:47:56,128\r\nthere was a sense of fear in the air,\neven though no one said anything. Once again\r\n\r\n1300\r\n01:47:57,028 --> 01:48:04,028\r\nhe was experiencing the\nlanguage without words... the universal language.\r\n\r\n1301\r\n01:48:05,036 --> 01:48:10,505\r\nThe Englishman asked if they were in danger.\n\"Once you get into the desert, there's no\r\n\r\n1302\r\n01:48:10,829 --> 01:48:16,130\r\ngoing back,\" said the camel driver.\n\"And, when you can't go back, you have to\r\n\r\n1303\r\n01:48:16,013 --> 01:48:22,282\r\nworry only about the best way of\nmoving forward. The rest is up to Allah, including\r\n\r\n1304\r\n01:48:22,399 --> 01:48:26,424\r\nthe danger.\"\nAnd he concluded by saying the mysterious\r\n\r\n1305\r\n01:48:26,649 --> 01:48:31,657\r\nword: \"Maktub.\"\n\"You should pay more attention to the caravan,\"\r\n\r\n1306\r\n01:48:32,449 --> 01:48:36,450\r\nthe boy said to the Englishman,\nafter the camel driver had left. \"We make\r\n\r\n1307\r\n01:48:36,459 --> 01:48:38,554\r\na lot of detours, but we're always\nheading for the same destination.\"\r\n\r\n1308\r\n01:48:39,409 --> 01:48:43,880\r\n\"And you ought to read more about the world,\"\nanswered the Englishman.\r\n\r\n1309\r\n01:48:43,088 --> 01:48:49,077\r\n\"Books are like caravans in that respect.\"\nThe immense collection of people and animals\r\n\r\n1310\r\n01:48:49,869 --> 01:48:54,894\r\nbegan to travel faster. The days\nhad always been silent, but now, even the\r\n\r\n1311\r\n01:48:55,119 --> 01:48:58,180\r\nnights--when the travelers were\naccustomed to talking around the fires--had\r\n\r\n1312\r\n01:48:58,729 --> 01:49:02,823\r\nalso become quiet. And, one day,\nthe leader of the caravan made the decision\r\n\r\n1313\r\n01:49:03,669 --> 01:49:07,733\r\nthat the fires should no longer be\nlighted, so as not to attract attention to\r\n\r\n1314\r\n01:49:08,309 --> 01:49:11,315\r\nthe caravan.\nThe travelers adopted the practice of arranging\r\n\r\n1315\r\n01:49:11,909 --> 01:49:15,920\r\nthe animals in a circle at night,\nsleeping together in the center as protection\r\n\r\n1316\r\n01:49:16,019 --> 01:49:21,027\r\nagainst the nocturnal cold. And the\nleader posted armed sentinels at the fringes\r\n\r\n1317\r\n01:49:21,099 --> 01:49:26,090\r\nof the group.\nThe Englishman was unable to sleep one night.\r\n\r\n1318\r\n01:49:26,009 --> 01:49:29,082\r\nHe called to the boy, and they\ntook a walk along the dunes surrounding the\r\n\r\n1319\r\n01:49:29,082 --> 01:49:33,741\r\nencampment. There was a full\nmoon, and the boy told the Englishman the\r\n\r\n1320\r\n01:49:34,479 --> 01:49:38,522\r\nstory of his life.\nThe Englishman was fascinated with the part\r\n\r\n1321\r\n01:49:38,909 --> 01:49:42,912\r\nabout the progress achieved at the\ncrystal shop after the boy began working there.\r\n\r\n1322\r\n01:49:43,209 --> 01:49:47,760\r\n\"That's the principle that governs all things,\"\nhe said. \"In alchemy, it's called the\r\n\r\n1323\r\n01:49:47,076 --> 01:49:51,625\r\nSoul of the World. When you want something\nwith all your heart, that's when\r\n\r\n1324\r\n01:49:52,309 --> 01:49:55,372\r\nyou are closest to the Soul of the World.\nIt's always a positive force.\"\r\n\r\n1325\r\n01:49:55,939 --> 01:49:59,957\r\nHe also said that this was not just a human\ngift, that everything on the face of\r\n\r\n1326\r\n01:50:00,119 --> 01:50:03,184\r\nthe earth had a soul, whether mineral, vegetable,\nor animal--or even just a\r\n\r\n1327\r\n01:50:03,769 --> 01:50:07,831\r\nsimple thought.\n\"Everything on earth is being continuously\r\n\r\n1328\r\n01:50:08,389 --> 01:50:14,390\r\ntransformed, because the earth is\nalive... and it has a soul. We are part of\r\n\r\n1329\r\n01:50:14,489 --> 01:50:18,546\r\nthat soul, so we rarely recognize that it\nis working for us. But in the crystal shop\r\n\r\n1330\r\n01:50:19,059 --> 01:50:23,136\r\nyou probably realized that even the\nglasses were collaborating in your success.\"\r\n\r\n1331\r\n01:50:23,829 --> 01:50:25,912\r\nThe boy thought about that for a while as\nhe looked at the moon and the\r\n\r\n1332\r\n01:50:26,659 --> 01:50:31,718\r\nbleached sands. \"I have watched the caravan\nas it crossed the desert,\" he said.\r\n\r\n1333\r\n01:50:32,249 --> 01:50:36,290\r\n\"The caravan and the desert speak the same\nlanguage, and it's for that reason\r\n\r\n1334\r\n01:50:36,659 --> 01:50:40,745\r\nthat the desert allows the crossing. It's\ngoing to test the caravan's every step to\r\n\r\n1335\r\n01:50:41,519 --> 01:50:45,556\r\nsee if it's in time, and, if it is, we will\nmake it to the oasis.\"\r\n\r\n1336\r\n01:50:45,889 --> 01:50:49,971\r\n\"If either of us had joined this caravan based\nonly on personal courage, but\r\n\r\n1337\r\n01:50:50,709 --> 01:50:52,782\r\nwithout understanding that language, this\njourney would have been much more\r\n\r\n1338\r\n01:50:53,439 --> 01:50:56,503\r\ndifficult.\"\nThey stood there looking at the moon.\r\n\r\n1339\r\n01:50:57,079 --> 01:51:02,590\r\n\"That's the magic of omens,\" said the boy.\n\"I've seen how the guides read the\r\n\r\n1340\r\n01:51:02,059 --> 01:51:07,868\r\nsigns of the desert, and how the soul of the\ncaravan speaks to the soul of the\r\n\r\n1341\r\n01:51:08,399 --> 01:51:11,422\r\ndesert.\"\nThe Englishman said, \"I'd better pay more\r\n\r\n1342\r\n01:51:11,629 --> 01:51:15,678\r\nattention to the caravan.\"\n\"And I'd better read your books,\" said the\r\n\r\n1343\r\n01:51:16,119 --> 01:51:17,050\r\nboy.\n*\r\n\r\n1344\r\n01:51:17,005 --> 01:51:24,005\r\nThey were strange books. They spoke about\nmercury, salt, dragons, and kings,\r\n\r\n1345\r\n01:51:25,499 --> 01:51:29,570\r\nand he didn't understand any of it. But there\nwas one idea that seemed to\r\n\r\n1346\r\n01:51:30,209 --> 01:51:35,212\r\nrepeat itself throughout all the books: all\nthings are the manifestation of one\r\n\r\n1347\r\n01:51:35,239 --> 01:51:39,307\r\nthing only.\nIn one of the books he learned that the most\r\n\r\n1348\r\n01:51:39,919 --> 01:51:45,280\r\nimportant text in the literature of\nalchemy contained only a few lines, and had\r\n\r\n1349\r\n01:51:45,028 --> 01:51:47,647\r\nbeen inscribed on the surface of an\nemerald.\r\n\r\n1350\r\n01:51:47,899 --> 01:51:51,908\r\n\"It's the Emerald Tablet,\" said the Englishman,\nproud that he might teach\r\n\r\n1351\r\n01:51:51,989 --> 01:51:56,004\r\nsomething to the boy.\n\"Well, then, why do we need all these books?\"\r\n\r\n1352\r\n01:51:56,139 --> 01:52:00,233\r\nthe boy asked.\n\"So that we can understand those few lines,\"\r\n\r\n1353\r\n01:52:01,079 --> 01:52:05,123\r\nthe Englishman answered, without\nappearing really to believe what he had said.\r\n\r\n1354\r\n01:52:05,519 --> 01:52:10,530\r\nThe book that most interested the boy told\nthe stories of the famous alchemists.\r\n\r\n1355\r\n01:52:10,053 --> 01:52:14,061\r\nThey were men who had dedicated their entire\nlives to the purification of metals\r\n\r\n1356\r\n01:52:14,061 --> 01:52:19,134\r\nin their laboratories; they believed that,\nif a metal were heated for many years,\r\n\r\n1357\r\n01:52:20,034 --> 01:52:24,051\r\nit would free itself of all its individual\nproperties, and what was left would be\r\n\r\n1358\r\n01:52:24,051 --> 01:52:30,180\r\nthe Soul of the World. This Soul of the World\nallowed them to understand\r\n\r\n1359\r\n01:52:30,639 --> 01:52:34,070\r\nanything on the face of the earth, because\nit was the language with which all\r\n\r\n1360\r\n01:52:34,007 --> 01:52:40,426\r\nthings communicated. They called that discovery\nthe Master Work--it was part\r\n\r\n1361\r\n01:52:40,489 --> 01:52:45,550\r\nliquid and part solid.\n\"Can't you just observe men and omens in order\r\n\r\n1362\r\n01:52:46,099 --> 01:52:48,134\r\nto understand the language?\"\nthe boy asked.\r\n\r\n1363\r\n01:52:48,449 --> 01:52:53,260\r\n\"You have a mania for simplifying everything,\"\nanswered the Englishman,\r\n\r\n1364\r\n01:52:53,026 --> 01:52:57,105\r\nirritated. \"Alchemy is a serious discipline.\nEvery step has to be followed exactly\r\n\r\n1365\r\n01:52:58,005 --> 01:53:03,034\r\nas it was followed by the masters.\"\nThe boy learned that the liquid part of the\r\n\r\n1366\r\n01:53:03,079 --> 01:53:09,082\r\nMaster Work was called the Elixir of\nLife, and that it cured all illnesses; it\r\n\r\n1367\r\n01:53:09,379 --> 01:53:15,407\r\nalso kept the alchemist from growing old.\nAnd the solid part was called the Philosopher's\r\n\r\n1368\r\n01:53:15,659 --> 01:53:18,753\r\nStone.\n\"It's not easy to find the Philosopher's Stone,\"\r\n\r\n1369\r\n01:53:19,599 --> 01:53:23,760\r\nsaid the Englishman. \"The\nalchemists spent years in their laboratories,\r\n\r\n1370\r\n01:53:23,076 --> 01:53:27,130\r\nobserving the fire that purified the\nmetals. They spent so much time close to the\r\n\r\n1371\r\n01:53:28,003 --> 01:53:32,882\r\nfire that gradually they gave up\nthe vanities of the world. They discovered\r\n\r\n1372\r\n01:53:33,179 --> 01:53:38,230\r\nthat the purification of the metals had\nled to a purification of themselves.\"\r\n\r\n1373\r\n01:53:38,689 --> 01:53:41,755\r\nThe boy thought about the crystal merchant.\nHe had said that it was a good\r\n\r\n1374\r\n01:53:42,349 --> 01:53:46,363\r\nthing for the boy to clean the crystal pieces,\nso that he could free himself from\r\n\r\n1375\r\n01:53:46,489 --> 01:53:51,030\r\nnegative thoughts. The boy was becoming more\nand more convinced that\r\n\r\n1376\r\n01:53:51,003 --> 01:53:57,552\r\nalchemy could be learned in one's daily life.\n\"Also,\" said the Englishman, \"the Philosopher's\r\n\r\n1377\r\n01:53:57,579 --> 01:54:02,584\r\nStone has a fascinating property.\nA small sliver of the stone can transform\r\n\r\n1378\r\n01:54:02,629 --> 01:54:08,641\r\nlarge quantities of metal into gold.\"\nHaving heard that, the boy became even more\r\n\r\n1379\r\n01:54:08,749 --> 01:54:12,801\r\ninterested in alchemy. He\nthought that, with some patience, he'd be\r\n\r\n1380\r\n01:54:13,269 --> 01:54:18,010\r\nable to transform everything into\ngold. He read the lives of the various people\r\n\r\n1381\r\n01:54:18,001 --> 01:54:25,001\r\nwho had succeeded in doing so:\nHelvétius, Elias, Fulcanelli, and Geber.\r\n\r\n1382\r\n01:54:25,469 --> 01:54:30,492\r\nThey were fascinating stories: each of\nthem lived out his Personal Legend to the\r\n\r\n1383\r\n01:54:30,699 --> 01:54:37,590\r\nend. They traveled, spoke with wise men,\nperformed miracles for the incredulous, and\r\n\r\n1384\r\n01:54:37,059 --> 01:54:40,155\r\nowned the Philosopher's Stone and\nthe Elixir of Life.\r\n\r\n1385\r\n01:54:41,055 --> 01:54:44,954\r\nBut when the boy wanted to learn how to achieve\nthe Master Work, he became\r\n\r\n1386\r\n01:54:45,449 --> 01:54:52,380\r\ncompletely lost. There were just drawings,\ncoded instructions, and obscure texts.\r\n\r\n1387\r\n01:54:52,038 --> 01:54:56,027\r\n*\n\"Why do they make things so complicated?\"\r\n\r\n1388\r\n01:54:56,369 --> 01:55:00,404\r\nhe asked the Englishman one night.\nThe boy had noticed that the Englishman was\r\n\r\n1389\r\n01:55:00,719 --> 01:55:04,770\r\nirritable, and missed his books.\n\"So that those who have the responsibility\r\n\r\n1390\r\n01:55:05,229 --> 01:55:09,840\r\nfor understanding can understand,\"\nhe said. \"Imagine if everyone went around\r\n\r\n1391\r\n01:55:09,084 --> 01:55:12,343\r\ntransforming lead into gold. Gold\nwould lose its value.\r\n\r\n1392\r\n01:55:13,099 --> 01:55:17,124\r\n\"It's only those who are persistent, and willing\nto study things deeply, who\r\n\r\n1393\r\n01:55:17,349 --> 01:55:21,530\r\nachieve the Master Work. That's why I'm here\nin the middle of the desert. I'm\r\n\r\n1394\r\n01:55:21,053 --> 01:55:24,472\r\nseeking a true alchemist who will help me\nto decipher the codes.\"\r\n\r\n1395\r\n01:55:24,949 --> 01:55:28,995\r\n\"When were these books written?\" the boy asked.\n\"Many centuries ago.\"\r\n\r\n1396\r\n01:55:29,409 --> 01:55:33,435\r\n\"They didn't have the printing press in those\ndays,\" the boy argued. \"There was\r\n\r\n1397\r\n01:55:33,669 --> 01:55:38,030\r\nno way for everybody to know about alchemy.\nWhy did they use such strange\r\n\r\n1398\r\n01:55:38,003 --> 01:55:44,262\r\nlanguage, with so many drawings?\"\nThe Englishman didn't answer him directly.\r\n\r\n1399\r\n01:55:44,289 --> 01:55:47,324\r\nHe said that for the past few days he\nhad been paying attention to how the caravan\r\n\r\n1400\r\n01:55:47,639 --> 01:55:50,735\r\noperated, but that he hadn't\nlearned anything new. The only thing he had\r\n\r\n1401\r\n01:55:51,599 --> 01:55:55,687\r\nnoticed was that talk of war was\nbecoming more and more frequent.\r\n\r\n1402\r\n01:55:56,479 --> 01:55:58,780\r\n*\nThen one day the boy returned the books to\r\n\r\n1403\r\n01:55:58,078 --> 01:56:02,147\r\nthe Englishman. \"Did you learn\nanything?\" the Englishman asked, eager to\r\n\r\n1404\r\n01:56:02,849 --> 01:56:06,933\r\nhear what it might be. He needed\nsomeone to talk to so as to avoid thinking\r\n\r\n1405\r\n01:56:07,689 --> 01:56:12,783\r\nabout the possibility of war.\n\"I learned that the world has a soul, and\r\n\r\n1406\r\n01:56:13,629 --> 01:56:20,030\r\nthat whoever understands that soul can\nalso understand the language of things. I\r\n\r\n1407\r\n01:56:20,003 --> 01:56:24,742\r\nlearned that many alchemists realized\ntheir destinies, and wound up discovering\r\n\r\n1408\r\n01:56:24,769 --> 01:56:29,340\r\nthe Soul of the World, the\nPhilosopher's Stone, and the Elixir of Life.\r\n\r\n1409\r\n01:56:29,034 --> 01:56:33,126\r\n\"But, above all, I learned that these things\nare all so simple that they could be\r\n\r\n1410\r\n01:56:34,026 --> 01:56:40,965\r\nwritten on the surface of an emerald.\"\nThe Englishman was disappointed. The years\r\n\r\n1411\r\n01:56:41,199 --> 01:56:46,225\r\nof research, the magic symbols,\nthe strange words and the laboratory equipment...\r\n\r\n1412\r\n01:56:46,459 --> 01:56:50,528\r\nnone of this had made an\nimpression on the boy. His soul must be too\r\n\r\n1413\r\n01:56:51,149 --> 01:56:53,570\r\nprimitive to understand those\nthings, he thought.\r\n\r\n1414\r\n01:56:53,057 --> 01:56:56,976\r\nHe took back his books and packed them away\nagain in their bags.\r\n\r\n1415\r\n01:56:57,489 --> 01:57:03,090\r\n\"Go back to watching the caravan,\" he said.\n\"That didn't teach me anything,\r\n\r\n1416\r\n01:57:03,009 --> 01:57:06,518\r\neither.\"\nThe boy went back to contemplating the silence\r\n\r\n1417\r\n01:57:06,599 --> 01:57:12,626\r\nof the desert, and the sand\nraised by the animals. \"Everyone has his or\r\n\r\n1418\r\n01:57:12,869 --> 01:57:16,946\r\nher own way of learning things,\" he\nsaid to himself. \"His way isn't the same as\r\n\r\n1419\r\n01:57:17,639 --> 01:57:23,688\r\nmine, nor mine as his. But we're both\nin search of our destinies, and I respect\r\n\r\n1420\r\n01:57:24,129 --> 01:57:26,135\r\nhim for that.\"\n*\r\n\r\n1421\r\n01:57:26,189 --> 01:57:31,212\r\nThe caravan began to travel day and night.\nThe hooded Bedouins reappeared\r\n\r\n1422\r\n01:57:31,419 --> 01:57:34,504\r\nmore and more frequently, and the camel driver--who\nhad become a good friend\r\n\r\n1423\r\n01:57:35,269 --> 01:57:40,780\r\nof the boy's--explained that the war between\nthe tribes had already begun. The\r\n\r\n1424\r\n01:57:40,078 --> 01:57:46,457\r\ncaravan would be very lucky to reach the oasis.\nThe animals were exhausted, and the men talked\r\n\r\n1425\r\n01:57:47,159 --> 01:57:51,228\r\namong themselves less and\nless. The silence was the worst aspect of\r\n\r\n1426\r\n01:57:51,849 --> 01:57:55,550\r\nthe night, when the mere groan of a\ncamel--which before had been nothing but the\r\n\r\n1427\r\n01:57:55,055 --> 01:58:01,484\r\ngroan of a camel--now frightened\neveryone, because it might signal a raid.\r\n\r\n1428\r\n01:58:01,979 --> 01:58:08,010\r\nThe camel driver, though, seemed not to be\nvery concerned with the threat of\r\n\r\n1429\r\n01:58:08,001 --> 01:58:09,280\r\nwar.\n\"I'm alive,\" he said to the boy, as they ate\r\n\r\n1430\r\n01:58:09,289 --> 01:58:13,381\r\na bunch of dates one night, with no\nfires and no moon. \"When I'm eating, that's\r\n\r\n1431\r\n01:58:14,209 --> 01:58:19,300\r\nall I think about. If I'm on the\nmarch, I just concentrate on marching. If\r\n\r\n1432\r\n01:58:20,119 --> 01:58:24,171\r\nI have to fight, it will be just as good\na day to die as any other.\r\n\r\n1433\r\n01:58:24,639 --> 01:58:29,050\r\n\"Because I don't live in either my past or\nmy future. I'm interested only in the\r\n\r\n1434\r\n01:58:29,005 --> 01:58:34,364\r\npresent. If you can concentrate always on\nthe present, you'll be a happy man.\r\n\r\n1435\r\n01:58:34,409 --> 01:58:38,443\r\nYou'll see that there is life in the desert,\nthat there are stars in the heavens, and\r\n\r\n1436\r\n01:58:38,749 --> 01:58:43,757\r\nthat tribesmen fight because they are part\nof the human race. Life will be a\r\n\r\n1437\r\n01:58:43,829 --> 01:58:47,856\r\nparty for you, a grand festival, because life\nis the moment we're living right\r\n\r\n1438\r\n01:58:48,099 --> 01:58:52,195\r\nnow.\"\nTwo nights later, as he was getting ready\r\n\r\n1439\r\n01:58:53,059 --> 01:58:58,092\r\nto bed down, the boy looked for the\nstar they followed every night. He thought\r\n\r\n1440\r\n01:58:58,389 --> 01:59:02,448\r\nthat the horizon was a bit lower than\nit had been, because he seemed to see stars\r\n\r\n1441\r\n01:59:02,979 --> 01:59:08,981\r\non the desert itself.\n\"It's the oasis,\" said the camel driver.\r\n\r\n1442\r\n01:59:08,999 --> 01:59:12,260\r\n\"Well, why don't we go there right now?\" the\nboy asked.\r\n\r\n1443\r\n01:59:12,026 --> 01:59:15,051\r\n\"Because we have to sleep.\"\n*\r\n\r\n1444\r\n01:59:15,051 --> 01:59:19,920\r\nThe boy awoke as the sun rose. There, in front\nof him, where the small stars\r\n\r\n1445\r\n01:59:20,379 --> 01:59:24,418\r\nhad been the night before, was an endless\nrow of date palms, stretching across\r\n\r\n1446\r\n01:59:24,769 --> 01:59:29,300\r\nthe entire desert.\n\"We've done it!\" said the Englishman, who\r\n\r\n1447\r\n01:59:29,003 --> 01:59:34,702\r\nhad also awakened early.\nBut the boy was quiet. He was at home with\r\n\r\n1448\r\n01:59:34,999 --> 01:59:40,005\r\nthe silence of the desert, and he\nwas content just to look at the trees. He\r\n\r\n1449\r\n01:59:40,599 --> 01:59:45,610\r\nstill had a long way to go to reach the\npyramids, and someday this morning would just\r\n\r\n1450\r\n01:59:45,709 --> 01:59:50,778\r\nbe a memory. But this was the\npresent moment--the party the camel driver\r\n\r\n1451\r\n01:59:51,399 --> 01:59:55,436\r\nhad mentioned--and he wanted to\nlive it as he did the lessons of his past\r\n\r\n1452\r\n01:59:55,769 --> 02:00:00,590\r\nand his dreams of the future. Although\nthe vision of the date palms would someday\r\n\r\n1453\r\n02:00:00,059 --> 02:00:06,368\r\nbe just a memory, right now it\nsignified shade, water, and a refuge from\r\n\r\n1454\r\n02:00:06,899 --> 02:00:12,997\r\nthe war. Yesterday, the camel's groan\nsignaled danger, and now a row of date palms\r\n\r\n1455\r\n02:00:13,879 --> 02:00:20,879\r\ncould herald a miracle.\nThe world speaks many languages, the boy thought.\r\n\r\n1456\r\n02:00:21,749 --> 02:00:24,776\r\n*\nThe times rush past, and so do the caravans,\r\n\r\n1457\r\n02:00:25,019 --> 02:00:29,057\r\nthought the alchemist, as he\nwatched the hundreds of people and animals\r\n\r\n1458\r\n02:00:29,399 --> 02:00:35,010\r\narriving at the oasis. People were\nshouting at the new arrivals, dust obscured\r\n\r\n1459\r\n02:00:35,001 --> 02:00:39,090\r\nthe desert sun, and the children of\nthe oasis were bursting with excitement at\r\n\r\n1460\r\n02:00:39,099 --> 02:00:44,128\r\nthe arrival of the strangers. The\nalchemist saw the tribal chiefs greet the\r\n\r\n1461\r\n02:00:44,389 --> 02:00:48,820\r\nleader of the caravan, and converse\nwith him at length.\r\n\r\n1462\r\n02:00:48,082 --> 02:00:52,091\r\nBut none of that mattered to the alchemist.\nHe had already seen many people\r\n\r\n1463\r\n02:00:52,829 --> 02:00:57,831\r\ncome and go, and the desert remained as it\nwas. He had seen kings and\r\n\r\n1464\r\n02:00:57,849 --> 02:01:04,050\r\nbeggars walking the desert sands. The dunes\nwere changed constantly by the\r\n\r\n1465\r\n02:01:04,005 --> 02:01:09,036\r\nwind, yet these were the same sands he had\nknown since he was a child. He\r\n\r\n1466\r\n02:01:09,036 --> 02:01:12,925\r\nalways enjoyed seeing the happiness that the\ntravelers experienced when, after\r\n\r\n1467\r\n02:01:13,249 --> 02:01:19,253\r\nweeks of yellow sand and blue sky, they first\nsaw the green of the date palms.\r\n\r\n1468\r\n02:01:19,289 --> 02:01:24,366\r\nMaybe God created the desert so that man could\nappreciate the date trees, he\r\n\r\n1469\r\n02:01:25,059 --> 02:01:28,078\r\nthought.\nHe decided to concentrate on more practical\r\n\r\n1470\r\n02:01:28,249 --> 02:01:32,342\r\nmatters. He knew that in the\ncaravan there was a man to whom he was to\r\n\r\n1471\r\n02:01:33,179 --> 02:01:39,590\r\nteach some of his secrets. The\nomens had told him so. He didn't know the\r\n\r\n1472\r\n02:01:39,059 --> 02:01:44,738\r\nman yet, but his practiced eye would\nrecognize him when he appeared. He hoped that\r\n\r\n1473\r\n02:01:45,269 --> 02:01:49,300\r\nit would be someone as\ncapable as his previous apprentice.\r\n\r\n1474\r\n02:01:49,579 --> 02:01:53,110\r\nI don't know why these things have to be transmitted\nby word of mouth, he\r\n\r\n1475\r\n02:01:53,011 --> 02:01:58,370\r\nthought. It wasn't exactly that they were\nsecrets; God revealed his secrets easily\r\n\r\n1476\r\n02:01:58,469 --> 02:02:04,780\r\nto all his creatures.\nHe had only one explanation for this fact:\r\n\r\n1477\r\n02:02:04,078 --> 02:02:08,157\r\nthings have to be transmitted this way\nbecause they were made up from the pure life,\r\n\r\n1478\r\n02:02:09,057 --> 02:02:13,896\r\nand this kind of life cannot be\ncaptured in pictures or words.\r\n\r\n1479\r\n02:02:14,409 --> 02:02:16,505\r\nBecause people become fascinated with pictures\nand words, and wind up\r\n\r\n1480\r\n02:02:17,369 --> 02:02:20,610\r\nforgetting the Language of the World.\n*\r\n\r\n1481\r\n02:02:20,061 --> 02:02:25,010\r\nThe boy couldn't believe what he was seeing:\nthe oasis, rather than being just a\r\n\r\n1482\r\n02:02:25,559 --> 02:02:28,650\r\nwell surrounded by a few palm trees--as he\nhad seen once in a geography\r\n\r\n1483\r\n02:02:29,469 --> 02:02:33,478\r\nbook--was much larger than many towns back\nin Spain. There were three\r\n\r\n1484\r\n02:02:34,369 --> 02:02:39,280\r\nhundred wells, fifty thousand date trees,\nand innumerable colored tents spread\r\n\r\n1485\r\n02:02:39,028 --> 02:02:42,517\r\namong them.\n\"It looks like The Thousand and One Nights,\"\r\n\r\n1486\r\n02:02:42,769 --> 02:02:45,862\r\nsaid the Englishman, impatient to\nmeet with the alchemist.\r\n\r\n1487\r\n02:02:46,699 --> 02:02:49,743\r\nThey were surrounded by children, curious\nto look at the animals and people\r\n\r\n1488\r\n02:02:50,139 --> 02:02:54,197\r\nthat were arriving. The men of the oasis wanted\nto know if they had seen any\r\n\r\n1489\r\n02:02:54,719 --> 02:02:58,722\r\nfighting, and the women competed with one\nanother for access to the cloth and\r\n\r\n1490\r\n02:02:59,019 --> 02:03:03,105\r\nprecious stones brought by the merchants.\nThe silence of the desert was a\r\n\r\n1491\r\n02:03:03,879 --> 02:03:07,916\r\ndistant dream; the travelers in the caravan\nwere talking incessantly, laughing\r\n\r\n1492\r\n02:03:08,249 --> 02:03:11,273\r\nand shouting, as if they had emerged from\nthe spiritual world and found\r\n\r\n1493\r\n02:03:11,489 --> 02:03:17,523\r\nthemselves once again in the world of people.\nThey were relieved and happy.\r\n\r\n1494\r\n02:03:17,829 --> 02:03:20,875\r\nThey had been taking careful precautions in\nthe desert, but the camel driver\r\n\r\n1495\r\n02:03:21,289 --> 02:03:26,050\r\nexplained to the boy that oases were always\nconsidered to be neutral territories,\r\n\r\n1496\r\n02:03:26,005 --> 02:03:30,034\r\nbecause the majority of the inhabitants were\nwomen and children. There were\r\n\r\n1497\r\n02:03:30,079 --> 02:03:35,117\r\noases throughout the desert, but the tribesmen\nfought in the desert, leaving the\r\n\r\n1498\r\n02:03:35,459 --> 02:03:41,840\r\noases as places of refuge.\nWith some difficulty, the leader of the caravan\r\n\r\n1499\r\n02:03:41,084 --> 02:03:45,413\r\nbrought all his people together\nand gave them his instructions. The group\r\n\r\n1500\r\n02:03:46,169 --> 02:03:51,267\r\nwas to remain there at the oasis until\nthe conflict between the tribes was over.\r\n\r\n1501\r\n02:03:52,149 --> 02:03:55,260\r\nSince they were visitors, they would\nhave to share living space with those who\r\n\r\n1502\r\n02:03:55,026 --> 02:03:59,905\r\nlived there, and would be given the\nbest accommodations. That was the law of hospitality.\r\n\r\n1503\r\n02:04:00,139 --> 02:04:04,181\r\nThen he asked that\neveryone, including his own sentinels, hand\r\n\r\n1504\r\n02:04:04,559 --> 02:04:07,588\r\nover their arms to the men\nappointed by the tribal chieftains.\r\n\r\n1505\r\n02:04:07,849 --> 02:04:13,780\r\n\"Those are the rules of war,\" the leader explained.\n\"The oases may not shelter\r\n\r\n1506\r\n02:04:13,078 --> 02:04:18,130\r\narmies or troops.\"\nTo the boy's surprise, the Englishman took\r\n\r\n1507\r\n02:04:19,003 --> 02:04:23,192\r\na chrome-plated revolver out of his\nbag and gave it to the men who were collecting\r\n\r\n1508\r\n02:04:23,489 --> 02:04:26,560\r\nthe arms.\n\"Why a revolver?\" he asked.\r\n\r\n1509\r\n02:04:27,199 --> 02:04:32,202\r\n\"It helped me to trust in people,\" the Englishman\nanswered.\r\n\r\n1510\r\n02:04:32,229 --> 02:04:37,300\r\nMeanwhile, the boy thought about his treasure.\nThe closer he got to the\r\n\r\n1511\r\n02:04:37,939 --> 02:04:42,005\r\nrealization of his dream, the more difficult\nthings became. It seemed as if what\r\n\r\n1512\r\n02:04:42,599 --> 02:04:47,010\r\nthe old king had called \"beginner's luck\"\nwere no longer functioning. In his\r\n\r\n1513\r\n02:04:47,001 --> 02:04:51,210\r\npursuit of the dream, he was being constantly\nsubjected to tests of his\r\n\r\n1514\r\n02:04:51,219 --> 02:04:56,308\r\npersistence and courage. So he could not be\nhasty, nor impatient. If he pushed\r\n\r\n1515\r\n02:04:57,109 --> 02:05:01,550\r\nforward impulsively, he would fail to see\nthe signs and omens left by God along\r\n\r\n1516\r\n02:05:01,055 --> 02:05:06,107\r\nhis path.\nGod placed them along my path. He had surprised\r\n\r\n1517\r\n02:05:07,007 --> 02:05:11,416\r\nhimself with the thought.\nUntil then, he had considered the omens to\r\n\r\n1518\r\n02:05:11,479 --> 02:05:15,481\r\nbe things of this world. Like eating\nor sleeping, or like seeking love or finding\r\n\r\n1519\r\n02:05:15,499 --> 02:05:20,800\r\na job. He had never thought of them\nin terms of a language used by God to indicate\r\n\r\n1520\r\n02:05:20,008 --> 02:05:25,447\r\nwhat he should do.\n\"Don't be impatient,\" he repeated to himself.\r\n\r\n1521\r\n02:05:26,239 --> 02:05:30,296\r\n\"It's like the camel driver said:\n'Eat when it's time to eat. And move along\r\n\r\n1522\r\n02:05:30,809 --> 02:05:37,809\r\nwhen it's time to move along.' \"\nThat first day, everyone slept from exhaustion,\r\n\r\n1523\r\n02:05:38,007 --> 02:05:42,826\r\nincluding the Englishman. The\nboy was assigned a place far from his friend,\r\n\r\n1524\r\n02:05:42,889 --> 02:05:47,510\r\nin a tent with five other young\nmen of about his age. They were people of\r\n\r\n1525\r\n02:05:47,051 --> 02:05:52,057\r\nthe desert, and clamored to hear his\nstories about the great cities.\r\n\r\n1526\r\n02:05:52,057 --> 02:05:55,666\r\nThe boy told them about his life as a shepherd,\nand was about to tell them of\r\n\r\n1527\r\n02:05:56,179 --> 02:06:00,183\r\nhis experiences at the crystal shop when the\nEnglishman came into the tent.\r\n\r\n1528\r\n02:06:00,219 --> 02:06:05,267\r\n\"I've been looking for you all morning,\" he\nsaid, as he led the boy outside. \"I\r\n\r\n1529\r\n02:06:05,699 --> 02:06:08,722\r\nneed you to help me find out where the alchemist\nlives.\"\r\n\r\n1530\r\n02:06:08,929 --> 02:06:14,938\r\nFirst, they tried to find him on their own.\nAn alchemist would probably live in a\r\n\r\n1531\r\n02:06:15,019 --> 02:06:19,027\r\nmanner that was different from that of the\nrest of the people at the oasis, and it\r\n\r\n1532\r\n02:06:19,099 --> 02:06:24,172\r\nwas likely that in his tent an oven was continuously\nburning. They searched\r\n\r\n1533\r\n02:06:24,829 --> 02:06:27,863\r\neverywhere, and found that the oasis was much\nlarger than they could have\r\n\r\n1534\r\n02:06:28,169 --> 02:06:34,268\r\nimagined; there were hundreds of tents.\n\"We've wasted almost the entire day,\" said\r\n\r\n1535\r\n02:06:35,159 --> 02:06:38,190\r\nthe Englishman, sitting down with\nthe boy near one of the wells.\r\n\r\n1536\r\n02:06:38,469 --> 02:06:44,513\r\n\"Maybe we'd better ask someone,\" the boy suggested.\nThe Englishman didn't want to tell others\r\n\r\n1537\r\n02:06:44,909 --> 02:06:48,955\r\nabout his reasons for being at the\noasis, and couldn't make up his mind. But,\r\n\r\n1538\r\n02:06:49,369 --> 02:06:54,372\r\nfinally, he agreed that the boy, who\nspoke better Arabic than he, should do so.\r\n\r\n1539\r\n02:06:54,399 --> 02:06:57,458\r\nThe boy approached a woman who\nhad come to the well to fill a goatskin with\r\n\r\n1540\r\n02:06:57,989 --> 02:07:02,050\r\nwater.\n\"Good afternoon, ma'am. I'm trying to find\r\n\r\n1541\r\n02:07:02,005 --> 02:07:05,007\r\nout where the alchemist lives here at\nthe oasis.\"\r\n\r\n1542\r\n02:07:05,007 --> 02:07:10,136\r\nThe woman said she had never heard of such\na person, and hurried away. But\r\n\r\n1543\r\n02:07:10,199 --> 02:07:14,226\r\nbefore she fled, she advised the boy that\nhe had better not try to converse with\r\n\r\n1544\r\n02:07:14,469 --> 02:07:18,030\r\nwomen who were dressed in black, because they\nwere married women. He\r\n\r\n1545\r\n02:07:18,003 --> 02:07:23,082\r\nshould respect tradition.\nThe Englishman was disappointed. It seemed\r\n\r\n1546\r\n02:07:23,082 --> 02:07:28,781\r\nhe had made the long journey for\nnothing. The boy was also saddened; his friend\r\n\r\n1547\r\n02:07:29,519 --> 02:07:33,566\r\nwas in pursuit of his Personal Legend.\nAnd, when someone was in such pursuit, the\r\n\r\n1548\r\n02:07:33,989 --> 02:07:37,054\r\nentire universe made an effort to\nhelp him succeed--that's what the old king\r\n\r\n1549\r\n02:07:37,639 --> 02:07:41,070\r\nhad said. He couldn't have been\nwrong.\r\n\r\n1550\r\n02:07:41,007 --> 02:07:46,746\r\n\"I had never heard of alchemists before,\"\nthe boy said. \"Maybe no one here has,\r\n\r\n1551\r\n02:07:46,809 --> 02:07:50,822\r\neither.\"\nThe Englishman's eyes lit up. \"That's it!\r\n\r\n1552\r\n02:07:50,939 --> 02:07:56,010\r\nMaybe no one here knows what an\nalchemist is! Find out who it is who cures\r\n\r\n1553\r\n02:07:56,001 --> 02:08:01,001\r\nthe people's illnesses!\"\nSeveral women dressed in black came to the\r\n\r\n1554\r\n02:08:01,001 --> 02:08:05,600\r\nwell for water, but the boy would\nspeak to none of them, despite the Englishman's\r\n\r\n1555\r\n02:08:05,609 --> 02:08:07,706\r\ninsistence. Then a man\napproached.\r\n\r\n1556\r\n02:08:08,579 --> 02:08:12,820\r\n\"Do you know someone here who cures people's\nillnesses?\" the boy asked.\r\n\r\n1557\r\n02:08:12,082 --> 02:08:17,411\r\n\"Allah cures our illnesses,\" said the man,\nclearly frightened of the strangers.\r\n\r\n1558\r\n02:08:18,149 --> 02:08:22,215\r\n\"You're looking for witch doctors.\" He spoke\nsome verses from the Koran, and\r\n\r\n1559\r\n02:08:22,809 --> 02:08:25,280\r\nmoved on.\nAnother man appeared. He was older, and was\r\n\r\n1560\r\n02:08:25,028 --> 02:08:28,427\r\ncarrying a small bucket. The boy\nrepeated his question.\r\n\r\n1561\r\n02:08:28,679 --> 02:08:32,727\r\n\"Why do you want to find that sort of person?\"\nthe Arab asked.\r\n\r\n1562\r\n02:08:33,159 --> 02:08:36,760\r\n\"Because my friend here has traveled for many\nmonths in order to meet with\r\n\r\n1563\r\n02:08:36,076 --> 02:08:40,495\r\nhim,\" the boy said.\n\"If such a man is here at the oasis, he must\r\n\r\n1564\r\n02:08:41,179 --> 02:08:45,840\r\nbe the very powerful one,\" said the\nold man after thinking for a few moments.\r\n\r\n1565\r\n02:08:45,084 --> 02:08:49,180\r\n\"Not even the tribal chieftains are\nable to see him when they want to. Only when\r\n\r\n1566\r\n02:08:50,008 --> 02:08:55,807\r\nhe consents.\n\"Wait for the end of the war. Then leave with\r\n\r\n1567\r\n02:08:56,599 --> 02:09:01,614\r\nthe caravan. Don't try to enter\ninto the life of the oasis,\" he said, and\r\n\r\n1568\r\n02:09:01,749 --> 02:09:05,782\r\nwalked away.\nBut the Englishman was exultant. They were\r\n\r\n1569\r\n02:09:06,079 --> 02:09:11,115\r\non the right track.\nFinally, a young woman approached who was\r\n\r\n1570\r\n02:09:11,439 --> 02:09:16,260\r\nnot dressed in black. She had a\nvessel on her shoulder, and her head was covered\r\n\r\n1571\r\n02:09:16,026 --> 02:09:20,965\r\nby a veil, but her face was\nuncovered. The boy approached her to ask about\r\n\r\n1572\r\n02:09:21,199 --> 02:09:26,207\r\nthe alchemist.\nAt that moment, it seemed to him that time\r\n\r\n1573\r\n02:09:26,999 --> 02:09:33,999\r\nstood still, and the Soul of the\nWorld surged within him. When he looked into\r\n\r\n1574\r\n02:09:34,289 --> 02:09:41,289\r\nher dark eyes, and saw that her\nlips were poised between a laugh and silence,\r\n\r\n1575\r\n02:09:41,034 --> 02:09:46,293\r\nhe learned the most important\npart of the language that all the world spoke--the\r\n\r\n1576\r\n02:09:46,599 --> 02:09:50,530\r\nlanguage that everyone on\nearth was capable of understanding in their\r\n\r\n1577\r\n02:09:50,053 --> 02:09:57,053\r\nheart. It was love. Something older\nthan humanity, more ancient than the desert.\r\n\r\n1578\r\n02:09:59,001 --> 02:10:03,055\r\nSomething that exerted the same\nforce whenever two pairs of eyes met, as had\r\n\r\n1579\r\n02:10:03,055 --> 02:10:10,055\r\ntheirs here at the well. She\nsmiled, and that was certainly an omen--the\r\n\r\n1580\r\n02:10:11,309 --> 02:10:16,373\r\nomen he had been awaiting,\nwithout even knowing he was, for all his life.\r\n\r\n1581\r\n02:10:16,949 --> 02:10:22,996\r\nThe omen he had sought to find\nwith his sheep and in his books, in the crystals\r\n\r\n1582\r\n02:10:23,419 --> 02:10:29,433\r\nand in the silence of the desert.\nIt was the pure Language of the World. It\r\n\r\n1583\r\n02:10:29,559 --> 02:10:33,640\r\nrequired no explanation, just as the\nuniverse needs none as it travels through\r\n\r\n1584\r\n02:10:34,369 --> 02:10:39,550\r\nendless time. What the boy felt at\nthat moment was that he was in the presence\r\n\r\n1585\r\n02:10:39,055 --> 02:10:45,274\r\nof the only woman in his life, and\nthat, with no need for words, she recognized\r\n\r\n1586\r\n02:10:45,769 --> 02:10:52,320\r\nthe same thing. He was more\ncertain of it than of anything in the world.\r\n\r\n1587\r\n02:10:52,032 --> 02:10:56,171\r\nHe had been told by his parents and\ngrandparents that he must fall in love and\r\n\r\n1588\r\n02:10:56,459 --> 02:11:01,465\r\nreally know a person before\nbecoming committed. But maybe people who felt\r\n\r\n1589\r\n02:11:01,519 --> 02:11:05,542\r\nthat way had never learned\nthe universal language. Because, when you\r\n\r\n1590\r\n02:11:05,749 --> 02:11:08,834\r\nknow that language, it's easy to\nunderstand that someone in the world awaits\r\n\r\n1591\r\n02:11:09,599 --> 02:11:13,656\r\nyou, whether it's in the middle of\nthe desert or in some great city. And when\r\n\r\n1592\r\n02:11:14,169 --> 02:11:18,222\r\ntwo such people encounter each\nother, and their eyes meet, the past and the\r\n\r\n1593\r\n02:11:18,699 --> 02:11:24,720\r\nfuture become unimportant. There\nis only that moment, and the incredible certainty\r\n\r\n1594\r\n02:11:24,909 --> 02:11:29,940\r\nthat everything under the sun\nhas been written by one hand only. It is the\r\n\r\n1595\r\n02:11:30,219 --> 02:11:36,274\r\nhand that evokes love, and creates\na twin soul for every person in the world.\r\n\r\n1596\r\n02:11:36,769 --> 02:11:41,842\r\nWithout such love, one's dreams\nwould have no meaning.\r\n\r\n1597\r\n02:11:42,499 --> 02:11:49,499\r\nMaktub, thought the boy.\nThe Englishman shook the boy: \"Come on, ask\r\n\r\n1598\r\n02:11:51,149 --> 02:11:54,172\r\nher!\"\nThe boy stepped closer to the girl, and when\r\n\r\n1599\r\n02:11:54,379 --> 02:12:01,379\r\nshe smiled, he did the same.\n\"What's your name?\" he asked.\r\n\r\n1600\r\n02:12:02,009 --> 02:12:07,338\r\n\"Fatima,\" the girl said, averting her eyes.\n\"That's what some women in my country are\r\n\r\n1601\r\n02:12:07,419 --> 02:12:09,496\r\ncalled.\"\n\"It's the name of the Prophet's daughter,\"\r\n\r\n1602\r\n02:12:10,189 --> 02:12:15,242\r\nFatima said. \"The invaders carried the\nname everywhere.\" The beautiful girl spoke\r\n\r\n1603\r\n02:12:15,719 --> 02:12:19,787\r\nof the invaders with pride.\nThe Englishman prodded him, and the boy asked\r\n\r\n1604\r\n02:12:20,399 --> 02:12:22,483\r\nher about the man who cured\npeople's illnesses.\r\n\r\n1605\r\n02:12:23,239 --> 02:12:28,244\r\n\"That's the man who knows all the secrets\nof the world,\" she said. \"He\r\n\r\n1606\r\n02:12:28,739 --> 02:12:34,765\r\ncommunicates with the genies of the desert.\"\nThe genies were the spirits of good and evil.\r\n\r\n1607\r\n02:12:34,999 --> 02:12:39,088\r\nAnd the girl pointed to the south,\nindicating that it was there the strange man\r\n\r\n1608\r\n02:12:39,889 --> 02:12:45,952\r\nlived. Then she filled her vessel\nwith water and left.\r\n\r\n1609\r\n02:12:46,519 --> 02:12:51,594\r\nThe Englishman vanished, too, gone to find\nthe alchemist. And the boy sat there\r\n\r\n1610\r\n02:12:52,269 --> 02:12:57,311\r\nby the well for a long time, remembering that\none day in Tarifa the levanter\r\n\r\n1611\r\n02:12:57,689 --> 02:13:01,756\r\nhad brought to him the perfume of that woman,\nand realizing that he had loved\r\n\r\n1612\r\n02:13:02,359 --> 02:13:07,388\r\nher before he even knew she existed. He knew\nthat his love for her would\r\n\r\n1613\r\n02:13:07,649 --> 02:13:11,800\r\nenable him to discover every treasure in the\nworld.\r\n\r\n1614\r\n02:13:11,008 --> 02:13:16,847\r\nThe next day, the boy returned to the well,\nhoping to see the girl. To his\r\n\r\n1615\r\n02:13:17,639 --> 02:13:20,708\r\nsurprise, the Englishman was there, looking\nout at the desert,\r\n\r\n1616\r\n02:13:21,329 --> 02:13:26,780\r\n\"I waited all afternoon and evening,\" he said.\n\"He appeared with the first stars\r\n\r\n1617\r\n02:13:26,078 --> 02:13:29,917\r\nof evening. I told him what I was seeking,\nand he asked me if I had ever\r\n\r\n1618\r\n02:13:30,619 --> 02:13:35,642\r\ntransformed lead into gold. I told him that\nwas what I had come here to learn.\r\n\r\n1619\r\n02:13:35,849 --> 02:13:41,884\r\n\"He told me I should try to do so. That's\nall he said: 'Go and try.' \"\r\n\r\n1620\r\n02:13:42,199 --> 02:13:47,050\r\nThe boy didn't say anything. The poor Englishman\nhad traveled all this way,\r\n\r\n1621\r\n02:13:47,005 --> 02:13:50,654\r\nonly to be told that he should repeat what\nhe had already done so many times.\r\n\r\n1622\r\n02:13:50,699 --> 02:13:56,712\r\n\"So, then try,\" he said to the Englishman.\n\"That's what I'm going to do. I'm going to\r\n\r\n1623\r\n02:13:56,829 --> 02:14:01,913\r\nstart now.\"\nAs the Englishman left, Fatima arrived and\r\n\r\n1624\r\n02:14:02,669 --> 02:14:06,747\r\nfilled her vessel with water.\n\"I came to tell you just one thing,\" the boy\r\n\r\n1625\r\n02:14:07,449 --> 02:14:12,487\r\nsaid. \"I want you to be my wife. I\nlove you.\"\r\n\r\n1626\r\n02:14:12,829 --> 02:14:14,881\r\nThe girl dropped the container, and the water\nspilled.\r\n\r\n1627\r\n02:14:15,349 --> 02:14:20,386\r\n\"I'm going to wait here for you every day.\nI have crossed the desert in search of\r\n\r\n1628\r\n02:14:20,719 --> 02:14:24,728\r\na treasure that is somewhere near the Pyramids,\nand for me, the war seemed a\r\n\r\n1629\r\n02:14:25,619 --> 02:14:30,622\r\ncurse. But now it's a blessing, because it\nbrought me to you.\"\r\n\r\n1630\r\n02:14:30,919 --> 02:14:35,927\r\n\"The war is going to end someday,\" the girl\nsaid.\r\n\r\n1631\r\n02:14:35,999 --> 02:14:41,010\r\nThe boy looked around him at the date palms.\nHe reminded himself that he had\r\n\r\n1632\r\n02:14:41,109 --> 02:14:48,109\r\nbeen a shepherd, and that he could be a shepherd\nagain. Fatima was more\r\n\r\n1633\r\n02:14:49,349 --> 02:14:53,435\r\nimportant than his treasure.\n\"The tribesmen are always in search of treasure,\"\r\n\r\n1634\r\n02:14:54,209 --> 02:14:57,308\r\nthe girl said, as if she had\nguessed what he was thinking. \"And the women\r\n\r\n1635\r\n02:14:58,199 --> 02:15:01,225\r\nof the desert are proud of their\ntribesmen.\"\r\n\r\n1636\r\n02:15:01,459 --> 02:15:06,521\r\nShe refilled her vessel and left.\nThe boy went to the well every day to meet\r\n\r\n1637\r\n02:15:07,079 --> 02:15:11,162\r\nwith Fatima. He told her about his\nlife as a shepherd, about the king, and about\r\n\r\n1638\r\n02:15:11,909 --> 02:15:16,933\r\nthe crystal shop. They became\nfriends, and except for the fifteen minutes\r\n\r\n1639\r\n02:15:17,149 --> 02:15:23,204\r\nhe spent with her, each day seemed\nthat it would never pass. When he had been\r\n\r\n1640\r\n02:15:23,699 --> 02:15:27,721\r\nat the oasis for almost a month, the\nleader of the caravan called a meeting of\r\n\r\n1641\r\n02:15:27,919 --> 02:15:31,963\r\nall of the people traveling with him.\n\"We don't know when the war will end, so we\r\n\r\n1642\r\n02:15:32,359 --> 02:15:37,406\r\ncan't continue our journey,\" he\nsaid. \"The battles may last for a long time,\r\n\r\n1643\r\n02:15:37,829 --> 02:15:42,904\r\nperhaps even years. There are\npowerful forces on both sides, and the war\r\n\r\n1644\r\n02:15:43,579 --> 02:15:46,677\r\nis important to both armies. It's not\na battle of good against evil. It's a war\r\n\r\n1645\r\n02:15:47,559 --> 02:15:51,647\r\nbetween forces that are fighting for the\nbalance of power, and, when that type of battle\r\n\r\n1646\r\n02:15:52,439 --> 02:15:57,480\r\nbegins, it lasts longer than\nothers--because Allah is on both sides.\"\r\n\r\n1647\r\n02:15:57,849 --> 02:16:01,340\r\nThe people went back to where they were living,\nand the boy went to meet with\r\n\r\n1648\r\n02:16:01,034 --> 02:16:06,833\r\nFatima that afternoon. He told her about the\nmorning's meeting. \"The day after\r\n\r\n1649\r\n02:16:07,139 --> 02:16:13,260\r\nwe met,\" Fatima said, \"you told me that you\nloved me. Then, you taught me\r\n\r\n1650\r\n02:16:13,026 --> 02:16:19,028\r\nsomething of the universal language and the\nSoul of the World. Because of that,\r\n\r\n1651\r\n02:16:19,028 --> 02:16:24,877\r\nI have become a part of you.\"\nThe boy listened to the sound of her voice,\r\n\r\n1652\r\n02:16:25,129 --> 02:16:29,340\r\nand thought it to be more beautiful\nthan the sound of the wind in the date palms.\r\n\r\n1653\r\n02:16:29,034 --> 02:16:35,123\r\n\"I have been waiting for you here at this\noasis for a long time. I have forgotten\r\n\r\n1654\r\n02:16:35,429 --> 02:16:40,500\r\nabout my past, about my traditions, and the\nway in which men of the desert\r\n\r\n1655\r\n02:16:40,005 --> 02:16:46,005\r\nexpect women to behave. Ever since I was a\nchild, I have dreamed that the\r\n\r\n1656\r\n02:16:46,005 --> 02:16:49,974\r\ndesert would bring me a wonderful present.\nNow, my present has arrived, and\r\n\r\n1657\r\n02:16:50,469 --> 02:16:56,561\r\nit's you.\"\nThe boy wanted to take her hand. But Fatima's\r\n\r\n1658\r\n02:16:57,389 --> 02:17:00,320\r\nhands held to the handles of her\njug.\r\n\r\n1659\r\n02:17:00,032 --> 02:17:05,111\r\n\"You have told me about your dreams, about\nthe old king and your treasure.\r\n\r\n1660\r\n02:17:06,011 --> 02:17:11,040\r\nAnd you've told me about omens. So now, I\nfear nothing, because it was those\r\n\r\n1661\r\n02:17:11,004 --> 02:17:16,013\r\nomens that brought you to me. And I am a part\nof your dream, a part of your\r\n\r\n1662\r\n02:17:17,003 --> 02:17:21,098\r\nPersonal Legend, as you call it.\n\"That's why I want you to continue toward\r\n\r\n1663\r\n02:17:22,025 --> 02:17:26,994\r\nyour goal. If you have to wait until\nthe war is over, then wait. But if you have\r\n\r\n1664\r\n02:17:27,219 --> 02:17:34,210\r\nto go before then, go on in pursuit of\nyour dream. The dunes are changed by the wind,\r\n\r\n1665\r\n02:17:34,021 --> 02:17:38,050\r\nbut the desert never changes.\nThat's the way it will be with our love for\r\n\r\n1666\r\n02:17:38,005 --> 02:17:44,854\r\neach other.\n\"Maktub,\" she said. \"If I am really a part\r\n\r\n1667\r\n02:17:45,349 --> 02:17:50,560\r\nof your dream, you'll come back one\nday.\"\r\n\r\n1668\r\n02:17:50,056 --> 02:17:54,095\r\nThe boy was sad as he left her that day. He\nthought of all the married\r\n\r\n1669\r\n02:17:54,095 --> 02:17:58,159\r\nshepherds he had known. They had a difficult\ntime convincing their wives that\r\n\r\n1670\r\n02:17:59,059 --> 02:18:03,144\r\nthey had to go off into distant fields. Love\nrequired them to stay with the people\r\n\r\n1671\r\n02:18:04,044 --> 02:18:08,137\r\nthey loved.\nHe told Fatima that, at their next meeting.\r\n\r\n1672\r\n02:18:09,037 --> 02:18:14,045\r\n\"The desert takes our men from us, and they\ndon't always return,\" she said. \"We\r\n\r\n1673\r\n02:18:15,017 --> 02:18:20,096\r\nknow that, and we are used to it. Those who\ndon't return become a part of the\r\n\r\n1674\r\n02:18:20,096 --> 02:18:24,105\r\nclouds, a part of the animals that hide in\nthe ravines and of the water that\r\n\r\n1675\r\n02:18:25,005 --> 02:18:30,094\r\ncomes from the earth. They become a part of\neverything... they become the\r\n\r\n1676\r\n02:18:30,139 --> 02:18:35,270\r\nSoul of the World.\n\"Some do come back. And then the other women\r\n\r\n1677\r\n02:18:35,027 --> 02:18:37,103\r\nare happy because they\nbelieve that their men may one day return,\r\n\r\n1678\r\n02:18:38,003 --> 02:18:43,034\r\nas well. I used to look at those\nwomen and envy them their happiness. Now,\r\n\r\n1679\r\n02:18:43,034 --> 02:18:46,086\r\nI too will be one of the women\nwho wait.\r\n\r\n1680\r\n02:18:46,086 --> 02:18:52,167\r\n\"I'm a desert woman, and I'm proud of that.\nI want my husband to wander as\r\n\r\n1681\r\n02:18:53,067 --> 02:18:59,076\r\nfree as the wind that shapes the dunes. And,\nif I have to, I will accept the fact\r\n\r\n1682\r\n02:18:59,076 --> 02:19:03,105\r\nthat he has become a part of the clouds, and\nthe animals and the water of the\r\n\r\n1683\r\n02:19:04,005 --> 02:19:08,024\r\ndesert.\"\nThe boy went to look for the Englishman. He\r\n\r\n1684\r\n02:19:08,024 --> 02:19:12,078\r\nwanted to tell him about Fatima.\nHe was surprised when he saw that the Englishman\r\n\r\n1685\r\n02:19:12,078 --> 02:19:16,085\r\nhad built himself a furnace\noutside his tent. It was a strange furnace,\r\n\r\n1686\r\n02:19:17,048 --> 02:19:22,787\r\nfueled by firewood, with a transparent\nflask heating on top. As the Englishman stared\r\n\r\n1687\r\n02:19:23,219 --> 02:19:26,990\r\nout at the desert, his eyes\nseemed brighter than they had when he was\r\n\r\n1688\r\n02:19:26,099 --> 02:19:30,120\r\nreading his books.\n\"This is the first phase of the job,\" he said.\r\n\r\n1689\r\n02:19:31,002 --> 02:19:34,099\r\n\"I have to separate out the sulfur. To\ndo that successfully, I must have no fear\r\n\r\n1690\r\n02:19:35,017 --> 02:19:39,113\r\nof failure. It was my fear of failure\nthat first kept me from attempting the Master\r\n\r\n1691\r\n02:19:40,013 --> 02:19:44,772\r\nWork. Now, I'm beginning what I\ncould have started ten years ago. But I'm\r\n\r\n1692\r\n02:19:44,889 --> 02:19:48,340\r\nhappy at least that I didn't wait\ntwenty years.\"\r\n\r\n1693\r\n02:19:48,034 --> 02:19:52,100\r\nHe continued to feed the fire, and the boy\nstayed on until the desert turned pink\r\n\r\n1694\r\n02:19:53,000 --> 02:19:58,073\r\nin the setting sun. He felt the urge to go\nout into the desert, to see if its silence\r\n\r\n1695\r\n02:19:58,073 --> 02:20:03,162\r\nheld the answers to his questions.\nHe wandered for a while, keeping the date\r\n\r\n1696\r\n02:20:04,062 --> 02:20:09,124\r\npalms of the oasis within sight. He\nlistened to the wind, and felt the stones\r\n\r\n1697\r\n02:20:10,024 --> 02:20:15,062\r\nbeneath his feet. Here and there, he\nfound a shell, and realized that the desert,\r\n\r\n1698\r\n02:20:15,062 --> 02:20:20,105\r\nin remote times, had been a sea. He\nsat on a stone, and allowed himself to become\r\n\r\n1699\r\n02:20:21,005 --> 02:20:26,011\r\nhypnotized by the horizon. He\ntried to deal with the concept of love as\r\n\r\n1700\r\n02:20:26,065 --> 02:20:31,149\r\ndistinct from possession, and couldn't\nseparate them. But Fatima was a woman of the\r\n\r\n1701\r\n02:20:32,049 --> 02:20:37,130\r\ndesert, and, if anything could\nhelp him to understand, it was the desert.\r\n\r\n1702\r\n02:20:38,003 --> 02:20:43,065\r\nAs he sat there thinking, he sensed movement\nabove him. Looking up, he saw a\r\n\r\n1703\r\n02:20:43,092 --> 02:20:49,094\r\npair of hawks flying high in the sky.\nHe watched the hawks as they drifted on the\r\n\r\n1704\r\n02:20:50,012 --> 02:20:54,075\r\nwind. Although their flight\nappeared to have no pattern, it made a certain\r\n\r\n1705\r\n02:20:54,075 --> 02:21:00,117\r\nkind of sense to the boy. It was\njust that he couldn't grasp what it meant.\r\n\r\n1706\r\n02:21:01,017 --> 02:21:06,082\r\nHe followed the movement of the\nbirds, trying to read something into it. Maybe\r\n\r\n1707\r\n02:21:06,082 --> 02:21:11,089\r\nthese desert birds could explain to\nhim the meaning of love without ownership.\r\n\r\n1708\r\n02:21:11,089 --> 02:21:16,171\r\nHe felt sleepy. In his heart, he wanted to\nremain awake, but he also wanted to\r\n\r\n1709\r\n02:21:17,071 --> 02:21:22,079\r\nsleep. \"I am learning the Language of the\nWorld, and everything in the world is\r\n\r\n1710\r\n02:21:22,079 --> 02:21:26,137\r\nbeginning to make sense to me... even the\nflight of the hawks,\" he said to\r\n\r\n1711\r\n02:21:27,037 --> 02:21:33,064\r\nhimself. And, in that mood, he was grateful\nto be in love. When you are in love,\r\n\r\n1712\r\n02:21:33,064 --> 02:21:37,145\r\nthings make even more sense, he thought.\nSuddenly, one of the hawks made a flashing\r\n\r\n1713\r\n02:21:38,045 --> 02:21:43,047\r\ndive through the sky, attacking the\nother. As it did so, a sudden, fleeting image\r\n\r\n1714\r\n02:21:43,047 --> 02:21:48,108\r\ncame to the boy: an army, with its\nswords at the ready, riding into the oasis.\r\n\r\n1715\r\n02:21:49,008 --> 02:21:53,070\r\nThe vision vanished immediately, but\nit had shaken him. He had heard people speak\r\n\r\n1716\r\n02:21:53,007 --> 02:21:58,078\r\nof mirages, and had already\nseen some himself: they were desires that,\r\n\r\n1717\r\n02:21:59,041 --> 02:22:02,114\r\nbecause of their intensity,\nmaterialized over the sands of the desert.\r\n\r\n1718\r\n02:22:03,014 --> 02:22:08,073\r\nBut he certainly didn't desire that an\narmy invade the oasis.\r\n\r\n1719\r\n02:22:08,073 --> 02:22:12,080\r\nHe wanted to forget about the vision, and\nreturn to his meditation. He tried\r\n\r\n1720\r\n02:22:12,008 --> 02:22:16,050\r\nagain to concentrate on the pink shades of\nthe desert, and its stones. But there\r\n\r\n1721\r\n02:22:17,022 --> 02:22:21,028\r\nwas something there in his heart that wouldn't\nallow him to do so.\r\n\r\n1722\r\n02:22:21,028 --> 02:22:27,037\r\n\"Always heed the omens,\" the old king had\nsaid. The boy recalled what he had\r\n\r\n1723\r\n02:22:27,037 --> 02:22:31,126\r\nseen in the vision, and sensed that it was\nactually going to occur.\r\n\r\n1724\r\n02:22:32,026 --> 02:22:37,070\r\nHe rose, and made his way back toward the\npalm trees. Once again, he\r\n\r\n1725\r\n02:22:37,007 --> 02:22:41,029\r\nperceived the many languages in the things\nabout him: this time, the desert\r\n\r\n1726\r\n02:22:41,092 --> 02:22:45,100\r\nwas safe, and it was the oasis that had become\ndangerous.\r\n\r\n1727\r\n02:22:46,072 --> 02:22:50,109\r\nThe camel driver was seated at the base of\na palm tree, observing the sunset.\r\n\r\n1728\r\n02:22:51,009 --> 02:22:54,010\r\nHe saw the boy appear from the other side\nof the dunes.\r\n\r\n1729\r\n02:22:54,001 --> 02:22:57,003\r\n\"An army is coming,\" the boy said. \"I had\na vision.\"\r\n\r\n1730\r\n02:22:57,003 --> 02:23:03,067\r\n\"The desert fills men's hearts with visions,\"\nthe camel driver answered.\r\n\r\n1731\r\n02:23:03,094 --> 02:23:07,158\r\nBut the boy told him about the hawks: that\nhe had been watching their flight\r\n\r\n1732\r\n02:23:08,058 --> 02:23:13,100\r\nand had suddenly felt himself to have plunged\nto the Soul of the World.\r\n\r\n1733\r\n02:23:14,000 --> 02:23:18,092\r\nThe camel driver understood what the boy was\nsaying. He knew that any given\r\n\r\n1734\r\n02:23:18,092 --> 02:23:22,150\r\nthing on the face of the earth could reveal\nthe history of all things. One could\r\n\r\n1735\r\n02:23:23,005 --> 02:23:29,005\r\nopen a book to any page, or look at a person's\nhand; one could turn a card, or\r\n\r\n1736\r\n02:23:29,005 --> 02:23:33,014\r\nwatch the flight of the birds... whatever\nthe thing observed, one could find a\r\n\r\n1737\r\n02:23:33,059 --> 02:23:37,142\r\nconnection with his experience of the moment.\nActually, it wasn't that those\r\n\r\n1738\r\n02:23:38,042 --> 02:23:42,046\r\nthings, in themselves, revealed anything at\nall; it was just that people, looking\r\n\r\n1739\r\n02:23:42,046 --> 02:23:46,080\r\nat what was occurring around them, could find\na means of penetration to the\r\n\r\n1740\r\n02:23:46,008 --> 02:23:50,009\r\nSoul of the World.\nThe desert was full of men who earned their\r\n\r\n1741\r\n02:23:50,009 --> 02:23:54,083\r\nliving based on the ease with which\nthey could penetrate to the Soul of the World.\r\n\r\n1742\r\n02:23:55,064 --> 02:24:01,080\r\nThey were known as seers, and\nthey were held in fear by women and the elderly.\r\n\r\n1743\r\n02:24:01,008 --> 02:24:04,014\r\nTribesmen were also wary of\nconsulting them, because it would be impossible\r\n\r\n1744\r\n02:24:04,086 --> 02:24:09,091\r\nto be effective in battle if one\nknew that he was fated to die. The tribesmen\r\n\r\n1745\r\n02:24:10,036 --> 02:24:13,062\r\npreferred the taste of battle, and\nthe thrill of not knowing what the outcome\r\n\r\n1746\r\n02:24:13,062 --> 02:24:17,073\r\nwould be; the future was already\nwritten by Allah, and what he had written\r\n\r\n1747\r\n02:24:17,073 --> 02:24:21,146\r\nwas always for the good of man. So\nthe tribesmen lived only for the present,\r\n\r\n1748\r\n02:24:22,046 --> 02:24:25,124\r\nbecause the present was full of\nsurprises, and they had to be aware of many\r\n\r\n1749\r\n02:24:26,024 --> 02:24:31,030\r\nthings: Where was the enemy's\nsword? Where was his horse? What kind of blow\r\n\r\n1750\r\n02:24:31,084 --> 02:24:35,108\r\nshould one deliver next in\norder to remain alive? The camel driver was\r\n\r\n1751\r\n02:24:36,008 --> 02:24:41,030\r\nnot a fighter, and he had consulted\nwith seers. Many of them had been right about\r\n\r\n1752\r\n02:24:41,003 --> 02:24:46,069\r\nwhat they said, while some had\nbeen wrong. Then, one day, the oldest seer\r\n\r\n1753\r\n02:24:46,096 --> 02:24:51,100\r\nhe had ever sought out (and the\none most to be feared) had asked why the camel\r\n\r\n1754\r\n02:24:52,036 --> 02:24:54,135\r\ndriver was so interested in the\nfuture.\r\n\r\n1755\r\n02:24:55,035 --> 02:25:01,206\r\n\"Well... so I can do things,\" he had responded.\n\"And so I can change those things\r\n\r\n1756\r\n02:25:01,521 --> 02:25:05,360\r\nthat I don't want to happen.\"\n\"But then they wouldn't be a part of your\r\n\r\n1757\r\n02:25:05,036 --> 02:25:08,125\r\nfuture,\" the seer had said.\n\"Well, maybe I just want to know the future\r\n\r\n1758\r\n02:25:09,025 --> 02:25:11,066\r\nso I can prepare myself for what's\ncoming.\"\r\n\r\n1759\r\n02:25:11,066 --> 02:25:16,072\r\n\"If good things are coming, they will be a\npleasant surprise,\" said the seer. \"If\r\n\r\n1760\r\n02:25:17,026 --> 02:25:20,093\r\nbad things are, and you know in advance, you\nwill suffer greatly before they\r\n\r\n1761\r\n02:25:20,093 --> 02:25:23,166\r\neven occur.\"\n\"I want to know about the future because I'm\r\n\r\n1762\r\n02:25:24,066 --> 02:25:28,142\r\na man,\" the camel driver had said\nto the seer. \"And men always live their lives\r\n\r\n1763\r\n02:25:29,042 --> 02:25:35,050\r\nbased on the future.\"\nThe seer was a specialist in the casting of\r\n\r\n1764\r\n02:25:35,005 --> 02:25:39,030\r\ntwigs; he threw them on the ground,\nand made interpretations based on how they\r\n\r\n1765\r\n02:25:39,075 --> 02:25:46,075\r\nfell. That day, he didn't make a\ncast. He wrapped the twigs in a piece of cloth\r\n\r\n1766\r\n02:25:46,099 --> 02:25:51,126\r\nand put them back in his bag.\n\"I make my living forecasting the future for\r\n\r\n1767\r\n02:25:52,026 --> 02:25:56,035\r\npeople,\" he said. \"I know the\nscience of the twigs, and I know how to use\r\n\r\n1768\r\n02:25:57,016 --> 02:26:01,108\r\nthem to penetrate to the place\nwhere all is written. There, I can read the\r\n\r\n1769\r\n02:26:02,008 --> 02:26:06,015\r\npast, discover what has already been\nforgotten, and understand the omens that are\r\n\r\n1770\r\n02:26:06,078 --> 02:26:10,175\r\nhere in the present.\n\"When people consult me, it's not that I'm\r\n\r\n1771\r\n02:26:11,075 --> 02:26:18,075\r\nreading the future; I am guessing at\nthe future. The future belongs to God, and\r\n\r\n1772\r\n02:26:19,096 --> 02:26:24,185\r\nit is only he who reveals it, under\nextraordinary circumstances. How do I guess\r\n\r\n1773\r\n02:26:25,085 --> 02:26:31,160\r\nat the future? Based on the omens\nof the present. The secret is here in the\r\n\r\n1774\r\n02:26:32,006 --> 02:26:36,092\r\npresent. If you pay attention to the\npresent, you can improve upon it. And, if\r\n\r\n1775\r\n02:26:37,046 --> 02:26:42,105\r\nyou improve on the present, what\ncomes later will also be better. Forget about\r\n\r\n1776\r\n02:26:43,005 --> 02:26:48,073\r\nthe future, and live each day\naccording to the teachings, confident that\r\n\r\n1777\r\n02:26:48,073 --> 02:26:55,073\r\nGod loves his children. Each day, in\nitself, brings with it an eternity.\"\r\n\r\n1778\r\n02:26:56,072 --> 02:26:59,084\r\nThe camel driver had asked what the circumstances\nwere under which God\r\n\r\n1779\r\n02:26:59,084 --> 02:27:05,147\r\nwould allow him to see the future.\n\"Only when he, himself, reveals it. And God\r\n\r\n1780\r\n02:27:06,047 --> 02:27:12,051\r\nonly rarely reveals the future.\nWhen he does so, it is for only one reason:\r\n\r\n1781\r\n02:27:12,051 --> 02:27:17,074\r\nit's a future that was written so as to\nbe altered.\"\r\n\r\n1782\r\n02:27:17,074 --> 02:27:21,163\r\nGod had shown the boy a part of the future,\nthe camel driver thought. Why was\r\n\r\n1783\r\n02:27:22,063 --> 02:27:24,101\r\nit that he wanted the boy to serve as his\ninstrument?\r\n\r\n1784\r\n02:27:25,001 --> 02:27:30,043\r\n\"Go and speak to the tribal chieftains,\" said\nthe camel driver. \"Tell them about\r\n\r\n1785\r\n02:27:30,043 --> 02:27:33,084\r\nthe armies that are approaching.\"\n\"They'll laugh at me.\"\r\n\r\n1786\r\n02:27:33,084 --> 02:27:38,128\r\n\"They are men of the desert, and the men of\nthe desert are used to dealing with\r\n\r\n1787\r\n02:27:39,028 --> 02:27:42,073\r\nomens.\"\n\"Well, then, they probably already know.\"\r\n\r\n1788\r\n02:27:42,073 --> 02:27:47,090\r\n\"They're not concerned with that right now.\nThey believe that if they have to\r\n\r\n1789\r\n02:27:47,009 --> 02:27:51,011\r\nknow about something Allah wants them to know,\nsomeone will tell them about\r\n\r\n1790\r\n02:27:51,092 --> 02:27:57,170\r\nit. It has happened many times before. But,\nthis time, the person is you.\"\r\n\r\n1791\r\n02:27:58,007 --> 02:28:03,007\r\nThe boy thought of Fatima. And he decided\nhe would go to see the chiefs of the\r\n\r\n1792\r\n02:28:03,007 --> 02:28:04,050\r\ntribes.\n*\r\n\r\n1793\r\n02:28:05,013 --> 02:28:08,050\r\nThe boy approached the guard at the front\nof the huge white tent at the center\r\n\r\n1794\r\n02:28:08,005 --> 02:28:11,078\r\nof the oasis.\n\"I want to see the chieftains. I've brought\r\n\r\n1795\r\n02:28:12,023 --> 02:28:16,111\r\nomens from the desert.\"\nWithout responding, the guard entered the\r\n\r\n1796\r\n02:28:17,011 --> 02:28:21,100\r\ntent, where he remained for some\ntime. When he emerged, it was with a young\r\n\r\n1797\r\n02:28:22,000 --> 02:28:27,012\r\nArab, dressed in white and gold.\nThe boy told the younger man what he had seen,\r\n\r\n1798\r\n02:28:27,012 --> 02:28:32,109\r\nand the man asked him to\nwait there. He disappeared into the tent.\r\n\r\n1799\r\n02:28:33,009 --> 02:28:37,021\r\nNight fell, and an assortment of fighting\nmen and merchants entered and exited\r\n\r\n1800\r\n02:28:37,021 --> 02:28:41,100\r\nthe tent. One by one, the campfires were extinguished,\nand the oasis fell as\r\n\r\n1801\r\n02:28:42,000 --> 02:28:48,009\r\nquiet as the desert. Only the lights in the\ngreat tent remained. During all this\r\n\r\n1802\r\n02:28:48,009 --> 02:28:52,098\r\ntime, the boy thought about Fatima, and he\nwas still unable to understand his\r\n\r\n1803\r\n02:28:52,098 --> 02:28:57,184\r\nlast conversation with her.\nFinally, after hours of waiting, the guard\r\n\r\n1804\r\n02:28:58,084 --> 02:29:04,126\r\nbade the boy enter. The boy was\nastonished by what he saw inside. Never could\r\n\r\n1805\r\n02:29:05,026 --> 02:29:08,053\r\nhe have imagined that, there in\nthe middle of the desert, there existed a\r\n\r\n1806\r\n02:29:08,053 --> 02:29:13,067\r\ntent like this one. The ground was\ncovered with the most beautiful carpets he\r\n\r\n1807\r\n02:29:13,067 --> 02:29:17,084\r\nhad ever walked upon, and from the\ntop of the structure hung lamps of hand-wrought\r\n\r\n1808\r\n02:29:17,084 --> 02:29:22,113\r\ngold, each with a lighted\ncandle. The tribal chieftains were seated\r\n\r\n1809\r\n02:29:23,013 --> 02:29:28,091\r\nat the back of the tent in a semicircle,\nresting upon richly embroidered silk cushions.\r\n\r\n1810\r\n02:29:28,091 --> 02:29:34,183\r\nServants came and went with\nsilver trays laden with spices and tea. Other\r\n\r\n1811\r\n02:29:35,083 --> 02:29:39,098\r\nservants maintained the fires in the\nhookahs. The atmosphere was suffused with\r\n\r\n1812\r\n02:29:39,098 --> 02:29:44,175\r\nthe sweet scent of smoke.\nThere were eight chieftains, but the boy could\r\n\r\n1813\r\n02:29:45,075 --> 02:29:48,159\r\nsee immediately which of them\nwas the most important: an Arab dressed in\r\n\r\n1814\r\n02:29:49,059 --> 02:29:54,060\r\nwhite and gold, seated at the center\nof the semicircle. At his side was the young\r\n\r\n1815\r\n02:29:54,069 --> 02:29:55,161\r\nArab the boy had spoken with\nearlier.\r\n\r\n1816\r\n02:29:56,061 --> 02:30:00,089\r\n\"Who is this stranger who speaks of omens?\"\nasked one of the chieftains, eyeing\r\n\r\n1817\r\n02:30:00,089 --> 02:30:05,118\r\nthe boy.\n\"It is I,\" the boy answered. And he told what\r\n\r\n1818\r\n02:30:06,018 --> 02:30:09,107\r\nhe had seen.\n\"Why would the desert reveal such things to\r\n\r\n1819\r\n02:30:10,007 --> 02:30:14,013\r\na stranger, when it knows that we\nhave been here for generations?\" said another\r\n\r\n1820\r\n02:30:14,013 --> 02:30:17,096\r\nof the chieftains.\n\"Because my eyes are not yet accustomed to\r\n\r\n1821\r\n02:30:17,096 --> 02:30:21,155\r\nthe desert,\" the boy said. \"I can\nsee things that eyes habituated to the desert\r\n\r\n1822\r\n02:30:22,055 --> 02:30:26,091\r\nmight not see.\"\nAnd also because I know about the Soul of\r\n\r\n1823\r\n02:30:26,091 --> 02:30:30,183\r\nthe World, he thought to himself.\n\"The oasis is neutral ground. No one attacks\r\n\r\n1824\r\n02:30:31,083 --> 02:30:36,101\r\nan oasis,\" said a third chieftain.\n\"I can only tell you what I saw. If you don't\r\n\r\n1825\r\n02:30:37,001 --> 02:30:41,008\r\nwant to believe me, you don't have\nto do anything about it.\"\r\n\r\n1826\r\n02:30:41,008 --> 02:30:45,055\r\nThe men fell into an animated discussion.\nThey spoke in an Arabic dialect that\r\n\r\n1827\r\n02:30:45,055 --> 02:30:48,112\r\nthe boy didn't understand, but, when he made\nto leave, the guard told him to\r\n\r\n1828\r\n02:30:49,012 --> 02:30:55,018\r\nstay. The boy became fearful; the omens told\nhim that something was wrong.\r\n\r\n1829\r\n02:30:55,018 --> 02:30:58,043\r\nHe regretted having spoken to the camel driver\nabout what he had seen in the\r\n\r\n1830\r\n02:30:58,043 --> 02:31:02,050\r\ndesert.\nSuddenly, the elder at the center smiled almost\r\n\r\n1831\r\n02:31:02,005 --> 02:31:07,019\r\nimperceptibly, and the boy felt\nbetter. The man hadn't participated in the\r\n\r\n1832\r\n02:31:07,064 --> 02:31:12,068\r\ndiscussion, and, in fact, hadn't said a\nword up to that point. But the boy was already\r\n\r\n1833\r\n02:31:12,068 --> 02:31:15,077\r\nused to the Language of the\nWorld, and he could feel the vibrations of\r\n\r\n1834\r\n02:31:16,058 --> 02:31:22,123\r\npeace throughout the tent. Now his\nintuition was that he had been right in coming.\r\n\r\n1835\r\n02:31:23,023 --> 02:31:27,814\r\nThe discussion ended. The chieftains were\nsilent for a few moments as they\r\n\r\n1836\r\n02:31:28,021 --> 02:31:32,990\r\nlistened to what the old man was saying. Then\nhe turned to the boy: this time\r\n\r\n1837\r\n02:31:32,099 --> 02:31:39,099\r\nhis expression was cold and distant.\n\"Two thousand years ago, in a distant land,\r\n\r\n1838\r\n02:31:40,046 --> 02:31:46,046\r\na man who believed in dreams was\nthrown into a dungeon and then sold as a slave,\"\r\n\r\n1839\r\n02:31:46,046 --> 02:31:51,075\r\nthe old man said, now in the\ndialect the boy understood. \"Our merchants\r\n\r\n1840\r\n02:31:51,075 --> 02:31:56,138\r\nbought that man, and brought him\nto Egypt. All of us know that whoever believes\r\n\r\n1841\r\n02:31:57,038 --> 02:32:01,111\r\nin dreams also knows how to\ninterpret them.\"\r\n\r\n1842\r\n02:32:02,011 --> 02:32:06,042\r\nThe elder continued, \"When the pharaoh dreamed\nof cows that were thin and\r\n\r\n1843\r\n02:32:06,042 --> 02:32:13,042\r\ncows that were fat, this man I'm speaking\nof rescued Egypt from famine. His\r\n\r\n1844\r\n02:32:13,058 --> 02:32:18,142\r\nname was Joseph. He, too, was a stranger in\na strange land, like you, and he\r\n\r\n1845\r\n02:32:19,042 --> 02:32:25,101\r\nwas probably about your age.\"\nHe paused, and his eyes were still unfriendly.\r\n\r\n1846\r\n02:32:26,001 --> 02:32:32,074\r\n\"We always observe the Tradition. The Tradition\nsaved Egypt from famine in\r\n\r\n1847\r\n02:32:32,074 --> 02:32:38,100\r\nthose days, and made the Egyptians the wealthiest\nof peoples. The Tradition\r\n\r\n1848\r\n02:32:39,000 --> 02:32:43,067\r\nteaches men how to cross the desert, and how\ntheir children should marry. The\r\n\r\n1849\r\n02:32:43,067 --> 02:32:49,092\r\nTradition says that an oasis is neutral territory,\nbecause both sides have oases,\r\n\r\n1850\r\n02:32:49,092 --> 02:32:54,117\r\nand so both are vulnerable.\"\nNo one said a word as the old man continued.\r\n\r\n1851\r\n02:32:55,017 --> 02:33:02,017\r\n\"But the Tradition also says that we should\nbelieve the messages of the desert.\r\n\r\n1852\r\n02:33:02,271 --> 02:33:07,260\r\nEverything we know was taught to us by the\ndesert.\"\r\n\r\n1853\r\n02:33:07,026 --> 02:33:11,038\r\nThe old man gave a signal, and everyone stood.\nThe meeting was over. The\r\n\r\n1854\r\n02:33:11,038 --> 02:33:15,040\r\nhookahs were extinguished, and the guards\nstood at attention. The boy made\r\n\r\n1855\r\n02:33:15,058 --> 02:33:20,101\r\nready to leave, but the old man spoke again:\n\"Tomorrow, we are going to break the agreement\r\n\r\n1856\r\n02:33:21,001 --> 02:33:26,053\r\nthat says that no one at the\noasis may carry arms. Throughout the entire\r\n\r\n1857\r\n02:33:26,053 --> 02:33:31,544\r\nday we will be on the lookout for\nour enemies. When the sun sets, the men will\r\n\r\n1858\r\n02:33:32,021 --> 02:33:38,710\r\nonce again surrender their arms\nto me. For every ten dead men among our enemies,\r\n\r\n1859\r\n02:33:38,071 --> 02:33:41,083\r\nyou will receive a piece of\ngold.\r\n\r\n1860\r\n02:33:41,083 --> 02:33:46,180\r\n\"But arms cannot be drawn unless they also\ngo into battle. Arms are as\r\n\r\n1861\r\n02:33:47,008 --> 02:33:51,071\r\ncapricious as the desert, and, if they are\nnot used, the next time they might not\r\n\r\n1862\r\n02:33:52,043 --> 02:33:57,065\r\nfunction. If at least one of them hasn't been\nused by the end of the day\r\n\r\n1863\r\n02:33:57,065 --> 02:34:04,065\r\ntomorrow, one will be used on you.\"\nWhen the boy left the tent, the oasis was\r\n\r\n1864\r\n02:34:05,071 --> 02:34:11,113\r\nilluminated only by the light of the full\nmoon. He was twenty minutes from his tent,\r\n\r\n1865\r\n02:34:12,013 --> 02:34:17,107\r\nand began to make his way there.\nHe was alarmed by what had happened. He had\r\n\r\n1866\r\n02:34:18,007 --> 02:34:21,066\r\nsucceeded in reaching through\nto the Soul of the World, and now the price\r\n\r\n1867\r\n02:34:21,066 --> 02:34:26,113\r\nfor having done so might be his life.\nIt was a frightening bet. But he had been\r\n\r\n1868\r\n02:34:27,013 --> 02:34:31,045\r\nmaking risky bets ever since the day\nhe had sold his sheep to pursue his Personal\r\n\r\n1869\r\n02:34:31,045 --> 02:34:35,094\r\nLegend. And, as the camel driver had said,\nto die tomorrow was no worse than dying on\r\n\r\n1870\r\n02:34:35,094 --> 02:34:39,675\r\nany other day. Every day was\nthere to be lived or to mark one's departure\r\n\r\n1871\r\n02:34:40,521 --> 02:34:47,521\r\nfrom this world. Everything\ndepended on one word: \"Maktub.\"\r\n\r\n1872\r\n02:34:47,065 --> 02:34:51,147\r\nWalking along in the silence, he had no regrets.\nIf he died tomorrow, it would\r\n\r\n1873\r\n02:34:52,047 --> 02:34:56,088\r\nbe because God was not willing to change the\nfuture. He would at least have\r\n\r\n1874\r\n02:34:56,088 --> 02:34:59,729\r\ndied after having crossed the strait, after\nhaving worked in a crystal shop, and\r\n\r\n1875\r\n02:35:00,521 --> 02:35:06,380\r\nafter having known the silence of the desert\nand Fatima's eyes. He had lived\r\n\r\n1876\r\n02:35:06,038 --> 02:35:11,097\r\nevery one of his days intensely since he had\nleft home so long ago. If he died\r\n\r\n1877\r\n02:35:11,097 --> 02:35:14,184\r\ntomorrow, he would already have seen more\nthan other shepherds, and he was\r\n\r\n1878\r\n02:35:15,084 --> 02:35:18,155\r\nproud of that.\nSuddenly he heard a thundering sound, and\r\n\r\n1879\r\n02:35:19,055 --> 02:35:23,776\r\nhe was thrown to the ground by a\nwind such as he had never known. The area\r\n\r\n1880\r\n02:35:24,271 --> 02:35:29,650\r\nwas swirling in dust so intense that\nit hid the moon from view. Before him was\r\n\r\n1881\r\n02:35:29,065 --> 02:35:35,098\r\nan enormous white horse, rearing\nover him with a frightening scream.\r\n\r\n1882\r\n02:35:35,098 --> 02:35:40,100\r\nWhen the blinding dust had settled a bit,\nthe boy trembled at what he saw.\r\n\r\n1883\r\n02:35:41,018 --> 02:35:46,085\r\nAstride the animal was a horseman dressed\ncompletely in black, with a falcon\r\n\r\n1884\r\n02:35:46,085 --> 02:35:51,160\r\nperched on his left shoulder. He wore a turban\nand his entire face, except for\r\n\r\n1885\r\n02:35:52,006 --> 02:35:57,022\r\nhis eyes, was covered with a black kerchief.\nHe appeared to be a messenger\r\n\r\n1886\r\n02:35:57,076 --> 02:36:02,099\r\nfrom the desert, but his presence was much\nmore powerful than that of a mere\r\n\r\n1887\r\n02:36:02,099 --> 02:36:06,101\r\nmessenger.\nThe strange horseman drew an enormous, curved\r\n\r\n1888\r\n02:36:07,001 --> 02:36:12,009\r\nsword from a scabbard\nmounted on his saddle. The steel of its blade\r\n\r\n1889\r\n02:36:12,009 --> 02:36:16,061\r\nglittered in the light of the moon.\n\"Who dares to read the meaning of the flight\r\n\r\n1890\r\n02:36:16,061 --> 02:36:20,062\r\nof the hawks?\" he demanded, so\nloudly that his words seemed to echo through\r\n\r\n1891\r\n02:36:20,071 --> 02:36:22,082\r\nthe fifty thousand palm trees of\nAl-Fayoum.\r\n\r\n1892\r\n02:36:22,082 --> 02:36:27,167\r\n\"It is I who dared to do so,\" said the boy.\nHe was reminded of the image of\r\n\r\n1893\r\n02:36:28,067 --> 02:36:32,125\r\nSantiago Matamoros, mounted on his white horse,\nwith the infidels beneath his\r\n\r\n1894\r\n02:36:33,025 --> 02:36:39,025\r\nhooves. This man looked exactly the same,\nexcept that now the roles were\r\n\r\n1895\r\n02:36:39,025 --> 02:36:44,088\r\nreversed.\n\"It is I who dared to do so,\" he repeated,\r\n\r\n1896\r\n02:36:44,088 --> 02:36:49,155\r\nand he lowered his head to receive a\nblow from the sword. \"Many lives will be saved,\r\n\r\n1897\r\n02:36:50,055 --> 02:36:53,061\r\nbecause I was able to see\nthrough to the Soul of the World.\"\r\n\r\n1898\r\n02:36:54,015 --> 02:37:01,015\r\nThe sword didn't fall. Instead, the stranger\nlowered it slowly, until the point\r\n\r\n1899\r\n02:37:01,095 --> 02:37:06,456\r\ntouched the boy's forehead. It drew a droplet\nof blood.\r\n\r\n1900\r\n02:37:07,311 --> 02:37:14,311\r\nThe horseman was completely immobile, as was\nthe boy. It didn't even occur to\r\n\r\n1901\r\n02:37:14,073 --> 02:37:20,117\r\nthe boy to flee. In his heart, he felt a strange\nsense of joy: he was about to die\r\n\r\n1902\r\n02:37:21,017 --> 02:37:28,017\r\nin pursuit of his Personal Legend. And for\nFatima. The omens had been true, after all.\r\n\r\n1903\r\n02:37:28,048 --> 02:37:32,079\r\nHere he was, face-to-face with his enemy,\nbut there was no need to be\r\n\r\n1904\r\n02:37:32,079 --> 02:37:37,085\r\nconcerned about dying--the Soul of the World\nawaited him, and he would soon\r\n\r\n1905\r\n02:37:37,085 --> 02:37:44,085\r\nbe a part of it. And, tomorrow, his enemy\nwould also be apart of that Soul.\r\n\r\n1906\r\n02:37:45,046 --> 02:37:50,065\r\nThe stranger continued to hold the sword at\nthe boy's forehead. \"Why did you\r\n\r\n1907\r\n02:37:50,065 --> 02:37:54,146\r\nread the flight of the birds?\"\n\"I read only what the birds wanted to tell\r\n\r\n1908\r\n02:37:55,046 --> 02:38:01,049\r\nme. They wanted to save the oasis.\nTomorrow all of you will die, because there\r\n\r\n1909\r\n02:38:01,076 --> 02:38:03,167\r\nare more men at the oasis than you\nhave.\"\r\n\r\n1910\r\n02:38:04,067 --> 02:38:09,109\r\nThe sword remained where it was. \"Who are\nyou to change what Allah has\r\n\r\n1911\r\n02:38:10,009 --> 02:38:14,016\r\nwilled?\"\n\"Allah created the armies, and he also created\r\n\r\n1912\r\n02:38:14,016 --> 02:38:19,067\r\nthe hawks. Allah taught me the\nlanguage of the birds. Everything has been\r\n\r\n1913\r\n02:38:19,067 --> 02:38:24,418\r\nwritten by the same hand,\" the boy\nsaid, remembering the camel driver's words.\r\n\r\n1914\r\n02:38:25,021 --> 02:38:29,170\r\nThe stranger withdrew the sword from the boy's\nforehead, and the boy felt\r\n\r\n1915\r\n02:38:29,017 --> 02:38:32,026\r\nimmensely relieved. But he still couldn't\nflee.\r\n\r\n1916\r\n02:38:32,026 --> 02:38:39,026\r\n\"Be careful with your prognostications,\" said\nthe stranger. \"When something is\r\n\r\n1917\r\n02:38:39,038 --> 02:38:46,038\r\nwritten, there is no way to change it.\"\n\"All I saw was an army,\" said the boy. \"I\r\n\r\n1918\r\n02:38:46,038 --> 02:38:51,105\r\ndidn't see the outcome of the battle.\"\nThe stranger seemed satisfied with the answer.\r\n\r\n1919\r\n02:38:52,005 --> 02:38:57,007\r\nBut he kept the sword in his\nhand. \"What is a stranger doing in a strange\r\n\r\n1920\r\n02:38:57,007 --> 02:39:01,053\r\nland?\"\n\"I am following my Personal Legend. It's not\r\n\r\n1921\r\n02:39:01,053 --> 02:39:06,105\r\nsomething you would understand.\"\nThe stranger placed his sword in its scabbard,\r\n\r\n1922\r\n02:39:07,005 --> 02:39:12,032\r\nand the boy relaxed.\n\"I had to test your courage,\" the stranger\r\n\r\n1923\r\n02:39:12,032 --> 02:39:17,046\r\nsaid. \"Courage is the quality most\nessential to understanding the Language of\r\n\r\n1924\r\n02:39:17,046 --> 02:39:21,124\r\nthe World.\"\nThe boy was surprised. The stranger was speaking\r\n\r\n1925\r\n02:39:22,024 --> 02:39:24,113\r\nof things that very few\npeople knew about.\r\n\r\n1926\r\n02:39:25,013 --> 02:39:32,013\r\n\"You must not let up, even after having come\nso far,\" he continued. \"You must\r\n\r\n1927\r\n02:39:32,073 --> 02:39:39,073\r\nlove the desert, but never trust it completely.\nBecause the desert tests all men:\r\n\r\n1928\r\n02:39:39,075 --> 02:39:44,096\r\nit challenges every step, and kills those\nwho become distracted.\"\r\n\r\n1929\r\n02:39:44,096 --> 02:39:49,907\r\nWhat he said reminded the boy of the old king.\n\"If the warriors come here, and your head\r\n\r\n1930\r\n02:39:50,771 --> 02:39:57,050\r\nis still on your shoulders at sunset,\ncome and find me,\" said the stranger.\r\n\r\n1931\r\n02:39:57,005 --> 02:40:01,087\r\nThe same hand that had brandished the sword\nnow held a whip. The horse\r\n\r\n1932\r\n02:40:01,087 --> 02:40:06,738\r\nreared again, raising a cloud of dust.\n\"Where do you live?\" shouted the boy, as the\r\n\r\n1933\r\n02:40:07,521 --> 02:40:13,040\r\nhorseman rode away.\nThe hand with the whip pointed to the south.\r\n\r\n1934\r\n02:40:13,004 --> 02:40:17,091\r\nThe boy had met the alchemist.\n*\r\n\r\n1935\r\n02:40:17,091 --> 02:40:20,157\r\nNext morning, there were two thousand armed\nmen scattered throughout the\r\n\r\n1936\r\n02:40:21,057 --> 02:40:26,108\r\npalm trees at Al-Fayoum. Before the sun had\nreached its high point, five\r\n\r\n1937\r\n02:40:27,008 --> 02:40:31,105\r\nhundred tribesmen appeared on the horizon.\nThe mounted troops entered the\r\n\r\n1938\r\n02:40:32,005 --> 02:40:37,038\r\noasis from the north; it appeared to be a\npeaceful expedition, but they all\r\n\r\n1939\r\n02:40:37,038 --> 02:40:42,126\r\ncarried arms hidden in their robes. When they\nreached the white tent at the\r\n\r\n1940\r\n02:40:43,026 --> 02:40:48,062\r\ncenter of Al-Fayoum, they withdrew their scimitars\nand rifles. And they attacked\r\n\r\n1941\r\n02:40:48,062 --> 02:40:53,081\r\nan empty tent.\nThe men of the oasis surrounded the horsemen\r\n\r\n1942\r\n02:40:53,081 --> 02:40:58,104\r\nfrom the desert and within half\nan hour all but one of the intruders were\r\n\r\n1943\r\n02:40:59,004 --> 02:41:03,063\r\ndead. The children had been kept at\nthe other side of a grove of palm trees, and\r\n\r\n1944\r\n02:41:03,063 --> 02:41:08,071\r\nsaw nothing of what had happened.\nThe women had remained in their tents, praying\r\n\r\n1945\r\n02:41:08,071 --> 02:41:11,149\r\nfor the safekeeping of their\nhusbands, and saw nothing of the battle, either.\r\n\r\n1946\r\n02:41:12,049 --> 02:41:16,092\r\nWere it not for the bodies there\non the ground, it would have appeared to be\r\n\r\n1947\r\n02:41:16,092 --> 02:41:21,160\r\na normal day at the oasis.\nThe only tribesman spared was the commander\r\n\r\n1948\r\n02:41:22,006 --> 02:41:27,020\r\nof the battalion. That afternoon,\nhe was brought before the tribal chieftains,\r\n\r\n1949\r\n02:41:27,074 --> 02:41:31,130\r\nwho asked him why he had violated\nthe Tradition. The commander said that his\r\n\r\n1950\r\n02:41:32,003 --> 02:41:36,010\r\nmen had been starving and thirsty,\nexhausted from many days of battle, and had\r\n\r\n1951\r\n02:41:37,000 --> 02:41:42,057\r\ndecided to take the oasis so as to\nbe able to return to the war.\r\n\r\n1952\r\n02:41:42,057 --> 02:41:45,139\r\nThe tribal chieftain said that he felt sorry\nfor the tribesmen, but that the\r\n\r\n1953\r\n02:41:46,039 --> 02:41:50,136\r\nTradition was sacred. He condemned the commander\nto death without honor.\r\n\r\n1954\r\n02:41:51,036 --> 02:41:56,049\r\nRather than being killed by a blade or a bullet,\nhe was hanged from a dead\r\n\r\n1955\r\n02:41:56,049 --> 02:42:01,054\r\npalm tree, where his body twisted in the desert\nwind.\r\n\r\n1956\r\n02:42:01,054 --> 02:42:05,119\r\nThe tribal chieftain called for the boy, and\npresented him with fifty pieces of\r\n\r\n1957\r\n02:42:06,019 --> 02:42:11,050\r\ngold. He repeated his story about Joseph of\nEgypt, and asked the boy to\r\n\r\n1958\r\n02:42:11,005 --> 02:42:15,009\r\nbecome the counselor of the oasis.\n*\r\n\r\n1959\r\n02:42:15,009 --> 02:42:19,012\r\nWhen the sun had set, and the first stars\nmade their appearance, the boy\r\n\r\n1960\r\n02:42:19,093 --> 02:42:24,095\r\nstarted to walk to the south. He eventually\nsighted a single tent, and a group of\r\n\r\n1961\r\n02:42:25,013 --> 02:42:30,056\r\nArabs passing by told the boy that it was\na place inhabited by genies. But the\r\n\r\n1962\r\n02:42:30,056 --> 02:42:35,061\r\nboy sat down and waited.\nNot until the moon was high did the alchemist\r\n\r\n1963\r\n02:42:36,006 --> 02:42:41,008\r\nride into view. He carried two\ndead hawks over his shoulder.\r\n\r\n1964\r\n02:42:41,026 --> 02:42:46,124\r\n\"I am here,\" the boy said.\n\"You shouldn't be here,\" the alchemist answered.\r\n\r\n1965\r\n02:42:47,024 --> 02:42:51,051\r\n\"Or is it your Personal Legend that\nbrings you here?\"\r\n\r\n1966\r\n02:42:51,051 --> 02:42:55,060\r\n\"With the wars between the tribes, it's impossible\nto cross the desert. So I have\r\n\r\n1967\r\n02:42:56,041 --> 02:43:01,124\r\ncome here.\"\nThe alchemist dismounted from his horse, and\r\n\r\n1968\r\n02:43:02,024 --> 02:43:05,080\r\nsignaled that the boy should\nenter the tent with him. It was a tent like\r\n\r\n1969\r\n02:43:05,008 --> 02:43:10,062\r\nmany at the oasis. The boy looked\naround for the ovens and other apparatus used\r\n\r\n1970\r\n02:43:11,034 --> 02:43:16,086\r\nin alchemy, but saw none. There\nwere only some books in a pile, a small cooking\r\n\r\n1971\r\n02:43:16,086 --> 02:43:19,093\r\nstove, and the carpets, covered\nwith mysterious designs.\r\n\r\n1972\r\n02:43:20,056 --> 02:43:25,134\r\n\"Sit down. We'll have something to drink and\neat these hawks,\" said the\r\n\r\n1973\r\n02:43:26,034 --> 02:43:29,072\r\nalchemist.\nThe boy suspected that they were the same\r\n\r\n1974\r\n02:43:29,072 --> 02:43:32,141\r\nhawks he had seen on the day\nbefore, but he said nothing. The alchemist\r\n\r\n1975\r\n02:43:33,041 --> 02:43:38,055\r\nlighted the fire, and soon a delicious\naroma filled the tent. It was better than\r\n\r\n1976\r\n02:43:38,055 --> 02:43:42,100\r\nthe scent of the hookahs.\n\"Why did you want to see me?\" the boy asked.\r\n\r\n1977\r\n02:43:43,000 --> 02:43:48,026\r\n\"Because of the omens,\" the alchemist answered.\n\"The wind told me you would\r\n\r\n1978\r\n02:43:48,026 --> 02:43:53,053\r\nbe coming, and that you would need help.\"\n\"It's not I the wind spoke about. It's the\r\n\r\n1979\r\n02:43:53,053 --> 02:43:56,090\r\nother foreigner, the Englishman. He's\nthe one that's looking for you.\"\r\n\r\n1980\r\n02:43:56,009 --> 02:44:01,018\r\n\"He has other things to do first. But he's\non the right track. He has begun to try\r\n\r\n1981\r\n02:44:02,008 --> 02:44:06,019\r\nto understand the desert.\"\n\"And what about me?\"\r\n\r\n1982\r\n02:44:06,091 --> 02:44:10,162\r\n\"When a person really desires something, all\nthe universe conspires to help that\r\n\r\n1983\r\n02:44:11,062 --> 02:44:15,134\r\nperson to realize his dream,\" said the alchemist,\nechoing the words of the old\r\n\r\n1984\r\n02:44:16,034 --> 02:44:21,060\r\nking. The boy understood. Another person was\nthere to help him toward his\r\n\r\n1985\r\n02:44:21,006 --> 02:44:25,097\r\nPersonal Legend.\n\"So you are going to instruct me?\"\r\n\r\n1986\r\n02:44:26,051 --> 02:44:31,113\r\n\"No. You already know all you need to know.\nI am only going to point you in\r\n\r\n1987\r\n02:44:32,013 --> 02:44:36,100\r\nthe direction of your treasure.\"\n\"But there's a tribal war,\" the boy reiterated.\r\n\r\n1988\r\n02:44:37,000 --> 02:44:42,008\r\n\"I know what's happening in the desert.\"\n\"I have already found my treasure. I have\r\n\r\n1989\r\n02:44:42,008 --> 02:44:47,023\r\na camel, I have my money from the\ncrystal shop, and I have fifty gold pieces.\r\n\r\n1990\r\n02:44:47,095 --> 02:44:49,098\r\nIn my own country, I would be a rich\nman.\"\r\n\r\n1991\r\n02:44:50,025 --> 02:44:54,082\r\n\"But none of that is from the Pyramids,\" said\nthe alchemist.\r\n\r\n1992\r\n02:44:54,082 --> 02:44:59,093\r\n\"I also have Fatima. She is a treasure greater\nthan anything else I have won.\"\r\n\r\n1993\r\n02:44:59,093 --> 02:45:05,187\r\n\"She wasn't found at the Pyramids, either.\"\nThey ate in silence. The alchemist opened\r\n\r\n1994\r\n02:45:06,087 --> 02:45:11,130\r\na bottle and poured a red liquid into\nthe boy's cup. It was the most delicious wine\r\n\r\n1995\r\n02:45:12,003 --> 02:45:16,090\r\nhe had ever tasted.\n\"Isn't wine prohibited here?\" the boy asked\r\n\r\n1996\r\n02:45:17,017 --> 02:45:22,020\r\n\"It's not what enters men's mouths that's\nevil,\" said the alchemist. \"It's what\r\n\r\n1997\r\n02:45:22,047 --> 02:45:28,120\r\ncomes out of their mouths that is.\"\nThe alchemist was a bit daunting, but, as\r\n\r\n1998\r\n02:45:29,002 --> 02:45:34,005\r\nthe boy drank the wine, he relaxed.\nAfter they finished eating they sat outside\r\n\r\n1999\r\n02:45:34,005 --> 02:45:38,047\r\nthe tent, under a moon so brilliant\nthat it made the stars pale.\r\n\r\n2000\r\n02:45:38,092 --> 02:45:43,145\r\n\"Drink and enjoy yourself,\" said the alchemist,\nnoticing that the boy was feeling\r\n\r\n2001\r\n02:45:44,045 --> 02:45:49,123\r\nhappier. \"Rest well tonight, as if you were\na warrior preparing for combat.\r\n\r\n2002\r\n02:45:50,023 --> 02:45:56,060\r\nRemember that wherever your heart is, there\nyou will find your treasure. You've\r\n\r\n2003\r\n02:45:56,006 --> 02:46:00,013\r\ngot to find the treasure, so that everything\nyou have learned along the way can\r\n\r\n2004\r\n02:46:01,003 --> 02:46:08,003\r\nmake sense.\n\"Tomorrow, sell your camel and buy a horse.\r\n\r\n2005\r\n02:46:08,057 --> 02:46:12,119\r\nCamels are traitorous: they walk\nthousands of paces and never seem to tire.\r\n\r\n2006\r\n02:46:13,019 --> 02:46:19,055\r\nThen suddenly, they kneel and die.\nBut horses tire bit by bit. You always know\r\n\r\n2007\r\n02:46:19,055 --> 02:46:24,108\r\nhow much you can ask of them, and\nwhen it is that they are about to die.\"\r\n\r\n2008\r\n02:46:25,008 --> 02:46:27,049\r\n*\nThe following night, the boy appeared at the\r\n\r\n2009\r\n02:46:27,049 --> 02:46:31,055\r\nalchemist's tent with a horse. The\nalchemist was ready, and he mounted his own\r\n\r\n2010\r\n02:46:31,055 --> 02:46:35,121\r\nsteed and placed the falcon on\nhis left shoulder. He said to the boy, \"Show\r\n\r\n2011\r\n02:46:36,021 --> 02:46:40,057\r\nme where there is life out in the\ndesert. Only those who can see such signs\r\n\r\n2012\r\n02:46:40,057 --> 02:46:46,059\r\nof life are able to find treasure.\"\nThey began to ride out over the sands, with\r\n\r\n2013\r\n02:46:46,059 --> 02:46:50,071\r\nthe moon lighting their way. I don't\nknow if I'll be able to find life in the desert,\r\n\r\n2014\r\n02:46:50,071 --> 02:46:54,078\r\nthe boy thought. I don't know the\ndesert that well yet.\r\n\r\n2015\r\n02:46:55,041 --> 02:46:59,095\r\nHe wanted to say so to the alchemist, but\nhe was afraid of the man. They\r\n\r\n2016\r\n02:46:59,095 --> 02:47:02,148\r\nreached the rocky place where the boy had\nseen the hawks in the sky, but now\r\n\r\n2017\r\n02:47:03,048 --> 02:47:07,129\r\nthere was only silence and the wind.\n\"I don't know how to find life in the desert,\"\r\n\r\n2018\r\n02:47:08,029 --> 02:47:12,114\r\nthe boy said. \"I know that there is\nlife here, but I don't know where to look.\"\r\n\r\n2019\r\n02:47:13,014 --> 02:47:20,014\r\n\"Life attracts life,\" the alchemist answered.\nAnd then the boy understood. He loosened the\r\n\r\n2020\r\n02:47:22,032 --> 02:47:26,131\r\nreins on his horse, who galloped\nforward over the rocks and sand. The alchemist\r\n\r\n2021\r\n02:47:27,031 --> 02:47:31,032\r\nfollowed as the boy's horse ran\nfor almost half an hour. They could no longer\r\n\r\n2022\r\n02:47:31,041 --> 02:47:35,092\r\nsee the palms of the oasis--only\nthe gigantic moon above them, and its silver\r\n\r\n2023\r\n02:47:35,092 --> 02:47:39,171\r\nreflections from the stones of the\ndesert. Suddenly, for no apparent reason,\r\n\r\n2024\r\n02:47:40,071 --> 02:47:45,086\r\nthe boy's horse began to slow.\n\"There's life here,\" the boy said to the alchemist.\r\n\r\n2025\r\n02:47:45,086 --> 02:47:48,153\r\n\"I don't know the language of\nthe desert, but my horse knows the language\r\n\r\n2026\r\n02:47:49,053 --> 02:47:53,142\r\nof life.\"\nThey dismounted, and the alchemist said nothing.\r\n\r\n2027\r\n02:47:54,042 --> 02:47:59,048\r\nAdvancing slowly, they\nsearched among the stones. The alchemist stopped\r\n\r\n2028\r\n02:47:59,048 --> 02:48:03,141\r\nabruptly, and bent to the\nground. There was a hole there among the stones.\r\n\r\n2029\r\n02:48:04,041 --> 02:48:08,062\r\nThe alchemist put his hand\ninto the hole, and then his entire arm, up\r\n\r\n2030\r\n02:48:08,062 --> 02:48:13,121\r\nto his shoulder. Something was\nmoving there, and the alchemist's eyes--the\r\n\r\n2031\r\n02:48:14,021 --> 02:48:19,042\r\nboy could see only his\neyes-squinted with his effort. His arm seemed\r\n\r\n2032\r\n02:48:19,042 --> 02:48:23,056\r\nto be battling with whatever was\nin the hole. Then, with a motion that startled\r\n\r\n2033\r\n02:48:23,056 --> 02:48:27,059\r\nthe boy, he withdrew his arm and\nleaped to his feet. In his hand, he grasped\r\n\r\n2034\r\n02:48:27,059 --> 02:48:32,120\r\na snake by the tail.\nThe boy leapt as well, but away from the alchemist.\r\n\r\n2035\r\n02:48:33,002 --> 02:48:36,073\r\nThe snake fought\nfrantically, making hissing sounds that shattered\r\n\r\n2036\r\n02:48:36,271 --> 02:48:40,710\r\nthe silence of the desert. It was\na cobra, whose venom could kill a person in\r\n\r\n2037\r\n02:48:40,071 --> 02:48:43,074\r\nminutes.\n\"Watch out for his venom,\" the boy said. But\r\n\r\n2038\r\n02:48:44,001 --> 02:48:47,043\r\neven though the alchemist had put\nhis hand in the hole, and had surely already\r\n\r\n2039\r\n02:48:47,043 --> 02:48:51,118\r\nbeen bitten, his expression was\ncalm. \"The alchemist is two hundred years\r\n\r\n2040\r\n02:48:52,018 --> 02:48:58,057\r\nold,\" the Englishman had told him.\nHe must know how to deal with the snakes of\r\n\r\n2041\r\n02:48:58,057 --> 02:49:00,058\r\nthe desert.\nThe boy watched as his companion went to his\r\n\r\n2042\r\n02:49:00,058 --> 02:49:04,132\r\nhorse and withdrew a scimitar.\nWith its blade, he drew a circle in the sand,\r\n\r\n2043\r\n02:49:05,032 --> 02:49:09,086\r\nand then he placed the snake within\nit. The serpent relaxed immediately.\r\n\r\n2044\r\n02:49:09,086 --> 02:49:15,140\r\n\"Not to worry,\" said the alchemist. \"He won't\nleave the circle. You found life in\r\n\r\n2045\r\n02:49:16,004 --> 02:49:21,090\r\nthe desert, the omen that I needed.\"\n\"Why was that so important?\"\r\n\r\n2046\r\n02:49:22,026 --> 02:49:26,114\r\n\"Because the Pyramids are surrounded by the\ndesert.\"\r\n\r\n2047\r\n02:49:27,014 --> 02:49:32,036\r\nThe boy didn't want to talk about the Pyramids.\nHis heart was heavy, and he\r\n\r\n2048\r\n02:49:32,036 --> 02:49:35,131\r\nhad been melancholy since the previous night.\nTo continue his search for the\r\n\r\n2049\r\n02:49:36,031 --> 02:49:41,059\r\ntreasure meant that he had to abandon Fatima.\n\"I'm going to guide you across the desert,\"\r\n\r\n2050\r\n02:49:41,059 --> 02:49:45,090\r\nthe alchemist said.\n\"I want to stay at the oasis,\" the boy answered.\r\n\r\n2051\r\n02:49:45,009 --> 02:49:50,052\r\n\"I've found Fatima, and, as far\nas I'm concerned, she's worth more than treasure.\"\r\n\r\n2052\r\n02:49:51,033 --> 02:49:55,101\r\n\"Fatima is a woman of the desert,\" said the\nalchemist. \"She knows that men\r\n\r\n2053\r\n02:49:56,001 --> 02:50:00,087\r\nhave to go away in order to return. And she\nalready has her treasure: it's you.\r\n\r\n2054\r\n02:50:00,087 --> 02:50:04,175\r\nNow she expects that you will find what it\nis you're looking for.\"\r\n\r\n2055\r\n02:50:05,075 --> 02:50:10,137\r\n\"Well, what if I decide to stay?\"\n\"Let me tell you what will happen. You'll\r\n\r\n2056\r\n02:50:11,037 --> 02:50:18,037\r\nbe the counselor of the oasis. You have\nenough gold to buy many sheep and many camels.\r\n\r\n2057\r\n02:50:18,058 --> 02:50:24,105\r\nYou'll marry Fatima, and\nyou'll both be happy for a year. You'll learn\r\n\r\n2058\r\n02:50:25,005 --> 02:50:31,030\r\nto love the desert, and you'll get to\nknow every one of the fifty thousand palms.\r\n\r\n2059\r\n02:50:31,003 --> 02:50:35,099\r\nYou'll watch them as they grow,\ndemonstrating how the world is always changing.\r\n\r\n2060\r\n02:50:36,026 --> 02:50:40,038\r\nAnd you'll get better and\nbetter at understanding omens, because the\r\n\r\n2061\r\n02:50:40,038 --> 02:50:47,038\r\ndesert is the best teacher there is.\n\"Sometime during the second year, you'll remember\r\n\r\n2062\r\n02:50:47,058 --> 02:50:52,087\r\nabout the treasure. The\nomens will begin insistently to speak of it,\r\n\r\n2063\r\n02:50:52,087 --> 02:50:56,170\r\nand you'll try to ignore them. You'll\nuse your knowledge for the welfare of the\r\n\r\n2064\r\n02:50:57,007 --> 02:51:02,035\r\noasis and its inhabitants. The tribal\nchieftains will appreciate what you do. And\r\n\r\n2065\r\n02:51:02,098 --> 02:51:05,116\r\nyour camels will bring you wealth\nand power.\r\n\r\n2066\r\n02:51:06,016 --> 02:51:12,033\r\n\"During the third year, the omens will continue\nto speak of your treasure and\r\n\r\n2067\r\n02:51:12,033 --> 02:51:19,033\r\nyour Personal Legend. You'll walk around,\nnight after night, at the oasis, and Fatima\r\n\r\n2068\r\n02:51:19,092 --> 02:51:21,693\r\nwill\nbe unhappy because she'll feel it was she\r\n\r\n2069\r\n02:51:22,521 --> 02:51:27,340\r\nwho interrupted your quest. But you\nwill love her, and she'll return your love.\r\n\r\n2070\r\n02:51:27,034 --> 02:51:32,034\r\nYou'll remember that she never asked\nyou to stay, because a woman of the desert\r\n\r\n2071\r\n02:51:32,034 --> 02:51:38,046\r\nknows that she must await her\nman. So you won't blame her. But many times\r\n\r\n2072\r\n02:51:38,046 --> 02:51:43,051\r\nyou'll walk the sands of the\ndesert, thinking that maybe you could have\r\n\r\n2073\r\n02:51:43,051 --> 02:51:48,123\r\nleft... that you could have trusted\nmore in your love for Fatima. Because what\r\n\r\n2074\r\n02:51:49,023 --> 02:51:55,091\r\nkept you at the oasis was your own\nfear that you might never come back. At that\r\n\r\n2075\r\n02:51:55,091 --> 02:52:01,112\r\npoint, the omens will tell you that\nyour treasure is buried forever.\r\n\r\n2076\r\n02:52:02,012 --> 02:52:09,012\r\n\"Then, sometime during the fourth year, the\nomens will abandon you, because\r\n\r\n2077\r\n02:52:09,038 --> 02:52:14,094\r\nyou've stopped listening to them. The tribal\nchieftains will see that, and you'll\r\n\r\n2078\r\n02:52:14,094 --> 02:52:19,117\r\nbe dismissed from your position as counselor.\nBut, by then, you'll be a rich\r\n\r\n2079\r\n02:52:20,017 --> 02:52:25,062\r\nmerchant, with many camels and a great deal\nof merchandise. You'll spend the\r\n\r\n2080\r\n02:52:25,062 --> 02:52:32,062\r\nrest of your days knowing that you didn't\npursue your Personal Legend, and that now\r\n\r\n2081\r\n02:52:33,012 --> 02:52:34,014\r\nit's\ntoo late.\r\n\r\n2082\r\n02:52:34,032 --> 02:52:41,032\r\n\"You must understand that love never keeps\na man from pursuing his Personal Legend. If\r\n\r\n2083\r\n02:52:41,076 --> 02:52:46,084\r\nhe abandons that pursuit, it's because it\nwasn't true love... the love that speaks\r\n\r\n2084\r\n02:52:47,056 --> 02:52:53,085\r\nthe Language of the World.\"\nThe alchemist erased the circle in the sand,\r\n\r\n2085\r\n02:52:53,085 --> 02:52:58,159\r\nand the snake slithered away\namong the rocks. The boy remembered the crystal\r\n\r\n2086\r\n02:52:59,059 --> 02:53:02,067\r\nmerchant who had always\nwanted to go to Mecca, and the Englishman\r\n\r\n2087\r\n02:53:02,067 --> 02:53:06,145\r\nin search of the alchemist. He\nthought of the woman who had trusted in the\r\n\r\n2088\r\n02:53:07,045 --> 02:53:12,045\r\ndesert. And he looked out over the\ndesert that had brought him to the woman he\r\n\r\n2089\r\n02:53:12,045 --> 02:53:15,131\r\nloved.\nThey mounted their horses, and this time it\r\n\r\n2090\r\n02:53:16,031 --> 02:53:20,084\r\nwas the boy who followed the\nalchemist back to the oasis. The wind brought\r\n\r\n2091\r\n02:53:20,084 --> 02:53:26,130\r\nthe sounds of the oasis to them,\nand the boy tried to hear Fatima's voice.\r\n\r\n2092\r\n02:53:27,003 --> 02:53:32,034\r\nBut that night, as he had watched the cobra\nwithin the circle, the strange\r\n\r\n2093\r\n02:53:32,061 --> 02:53:37,063\r\nhorseman with the falcon on his shoulder had\nspoken of love and treasure, of\r\n\r\n2094\r\n02:53:37,081 --> 02:53:40,179\r\nthe women of the desert and of his Personal\nLegend.\r\n\r\n2095\r\n02:53:41,079 --> 02:53:47,145\r\n\"I'm going with you,\" the boy said. And he\nimmediately felt peace in his heart.\r\n\r\n2096\r\n02:53:48,045 --> 02:53:54,374\r\n\"We'll leave tomorrow before sunrise,\" was\nthe alchemist's only response.\r\n\r\n2097\r\n02:53:54,779 --> 02:53:58,170\r\n*\nThe boy spent a sleepless night. Two hours\r\n\r\n2098\r\n02:53:58,017 --> 02:54:01,061\r\nbefore dawn, he awoke one of the\nboys who slept in his tent, and asked him\r\n\r\n2099\r\n02:54:01,061 --> 02:54:05,138\r\nto show him where Fatima lived. They\nwent to her tent, and the boy gave his friend\r\n\r\n2100\r\n02:54:06,038 --> 02:54:10,084\r\nenough gold to buy a sheep.\nThen he asked his friend to go to into the\r\n\r\n2101\r\n02:54:10,084 --> 02:54:14,132\r\ntent where Fatima was sleeping, and\nto awaken her and tell her that he was waiting\r\n\r\n2102\r\n02:54:15,032 --> 02:54:19,483\r\noutside. The young Arab did as\nhe was asked, and was given enough gold to\r\n\r\n2103\r\n02:54:19,771 --> 02:54:23,920\r\nbuy yet another sheep.\n\"Now leave us alone,\" said the boy to the\r\n\r\n2104\r\n02:54:23,092 --> 02:54:27,174\r\nyoung Arab. The Arab returned to his\ntent to sleep, proud to have helped the counselor\r\n\r\n2105\r\n02:54:28,074 --> 02:54:33,090\r\nof the oasis, and happy at\nhaving enough money to buy himself some sheep.\r\n\r\n2106\r\n02:54:33,009 --> 02:54:37,061\r\nFatima appeared at the entrance to the tent.\nThe two walked out among the\r\n\r\n2107\r\n02:54:38,042 --> 02:54:43,051\r\npalms. The boy knew that it was a violation\nof the Tradition, but that didn't\r\n\r\n2108\r\n02:54:43,051 --> 02:54:47,812\r\nmatter to him now.\n\"I'm going away,\" he said. \"And I want you\r\n\r\n2109\r\n02:54:48,271 --> 02:54:52,240\r\nto know that I'm coming back. I love\nyou because...\"\r\n\r\n2110\r\n02:54:52,024 --> 02:54:59,024\r\n\"Don't say anything,\" Fatima interrupted.\n\"One is loved because one is loved. No\r\n\r\n2111\r\n02:54:59,078 --> 02:55:04,086\r\nreason is needed for loving.\"\nBut the boy continued, \"I had a dream, and\r\n\r\n2112\r\n02:55:05,058 --> 02:55:10,143\r\nI met with a king. I sold crystal and\ncrossed the desert. And, because the tribes\r\n\r\n2113\r\n02:55:11,043 --> 02:55:17,089\r\ndeclared war, I went to the well,\nseeking the alchemist. So, I love you because\r\n\r\n2114\r\n02:55:17,089 --> 02:55:21,090\r\nthe entire universe conspired to\nhelp me find you.\"\r\n\r\n2115\r\n02:55:21,009 --> 02:55:26,053\r\nThe two embraced. It was the first time either\nhad touched the other.\r\n\r\n2116\r\n02:55:27,034 --> 02:55:33,130\r\n\"I'll be back,\" the boy said.\n\"Before this, I always looked to the desert\r\n\r\n2117\r\n02:55:34,003 --> 02:55:40,007\r\nwith longing,\" said Fatima. \"Now it\nwill be with hope. My father went away one\r\n\r\n2118\r\n02:55:40,034 --> 02:55:46,088\r\nday, but he returned to my mother,\nand he has always come back since then.\"\r\n\r\n2119\r\n02:55:46,088 --> 02:55:50,185\r\nThey said nothing else. They walked a bit\nfarther among the palms, and then\r\n\r\n2120\r\n02:55:51,085 --> 02:55:56,129\r\nthe boy left her at the entrance to her tent.\n\"I'll return, just as your father came back\r\n\r\n2121\r\n02:55:57,029 --> 02:56:01,041\r\nto your mother,\" he said.\nHe saw that Fatima's eyes were filled with\r\n\r\n2122\r\n02:56:01,041 --> 02:56:03,105\r\ntears.\n\"You're crying?\"\r\n\r\n2123\r\n02:56:04,005 --> 02:56:08,103\r\n\"I'm a woman of the desert,\" she said, averting\nher face. \"But above all, I'm a\r\n\r\n2124\r\n02:56:09,003 --> 02:56:16,003\r\nwoman.\"\nFatima went back to her tent, and, when daylight\r\n\r\n2125\r\n02:56:16,044 --> 02:56:20,120\r\ncame, she went out to do the\nchores she had done for years. But everything\r\n\r\n2126\r\n02:56:21,002 --> 02:56:27,038\r\nhad changed. The boy was no\nlonger at the oasis, and the oasis would never\r\n\r\n2127\r\n02:56:27,056 --> 02:56:31,120\r\nagain have the same meaning it\nhad had only yesterday. It would no longer\r\n\r\n2128\r\n02:56:32,002 --> 02:56:36,050\r\nbe a place with fifty thousand palm\ntrees and three hundred wells, where the pilgrims\r\n\r\n2129\r\n02:56:36,068 --> 02:56:40,167\r\narrived, relieved at the end\nof their long journeys. From that day on,\r\n\r\n2130\r\n02:56:41,067 --> 02:56:45,115\r\nthe oasis would be an empty place for\nher.\r\n\r\n2131\r\n02:56:46,015 --> 02:56:50,110\r\nFrom that day on, it was the desert that would\nbe important. She would look to\r\n\r\n2132\r\n02:56:51,001 --> 02:56:54,088\r\nit every day, and would try to guess which\nstar the boy was following in search\r\n\r\n2133\r\n02:56:54,097 --> 02:56:58,148\r\nof his treasure. She would have to send her\nkisses on the wind, hoping that the\r\n\r\n2134\r\n02:56:59,021 --> 02:57:03,890\r\nwind would touch the boy's face, and would\ntell him that she was alive. That she\r\n\r\n2135\r\n02:57:03,089 --> 02:57:07,115\r\nwas waiting for him, a woman awaiting a courageous\nman in search of his\r\n\r\n2136\r\n02:57:08,015 --> 02:57:13,089\r\ntreasure. From that day on, the desert would\nrepresent only one thing to her:\r\n\r\n2137\r\n02:57:13,089 --> 02:57:15,167\r\nthe hope for his return.\n*\r\n\r\n2138\r\n02:57:16,067 --> 02:57:20,160\r\n\"Don't think about what you've left behind,\"\nthe alchemist said to the boy as\r\n\r\n2139\r\n02:57:21,006 --> 02:57:25,069\r\nthey began to ride across the sands of the\ndesert. \"Everything is written in the\r\n\r\n2140\r\n02:57:26,023 --> 02:57:29,060\r\nSoul of the World, and there it will stay\nforever.\"\r\n\r\n2141\r\n02:57:29,006 --> 02:57:34,061\r\n\"Men dream more about coming home than about\nleaving,\" the boy said. He\r\n\r\n2142\r\n02:57:35,015 --> 02:57:42,015\r\nwas already reaccustomed to desert's silence.\n\"If what one finds is made of pure matter,\r\n\r\n2143\r\n02:57:42,033 --> 02:57:47,107\r\nit will never spoil. And one can\nalways come back. If what you had found was\r\n\r\n2144\r\n02:57:48,007 --> 02:57:52,064\r\nonly a moment of light, like the\nexplosion of a star, you would find nothing\r\n\r\n2145\r\n02:57:52,064 --> 02:57:57,067\r\non your return.\"\nThe man was speaking the language of alchemy.\r\n\r\n2146\r\n02:57:57,094 --> 02:58:00,169\r\nBut the boy knew that he was\nreferring to Fatima.\r\n\r\n2147\r\n02:58:01,069 --> 02:58:04,160\r\nIt was difficult not to think about what he\nhad left behind. The desert, with its\r\n\r\n2148\r\n02:58:05,006 --> 02:58:09,085\r\nendless monotony, put him to dreaming. The\nboy could still see the palm trees,\r\n\r\n2149\r\n02:58:10,039 --> 02:58:14,090\r\nthe wells, and the face of the woman he loved.\nHe could see the Englishman at\r\n\r\n2150\r\n02:58:14,009 --> 02:58:20,018\r\nhis experiments, and the camel driver who\nwas a teacher without realizing it.\r\n\r\n2151\r\n02:58:20,099 --> 02:58:24,151\r\nMaybe the alchemist has never been in love,\nthe boy thought.\r\n\r\n2152\r\n02:58:25,051 --> 02:58:29,312\r\nThe alchemist rode in front, with the falcon\non his shoulder. The bird knew the\r\n\r\n2153\r\n02:58:29,771 --> 02:58:33,580\r\nlanguage of the desert well, and whenever\nthey stopped, he flew off in search\r\n\r\n2154\r\n02:58:33,058 --> 02:58:39,059\r\nof game. On the first day he returned with\na rabbit, and on the second with two\r\n\r\n2155\r\n02:58:39,068 --> 02:58:43,069\r\nbirds.\nAt night, they spread their sleeping gear\r\n\r\n2156\r\n02:58:43,069 --> 02:58:48,069\r\nand kept their fires hidden. The desert\nnights were cold, and were becoming darker\r\n\r\n2157\r\n02:58:48,069 --> 02:58:53,082\r\nand darker as the phases of the\nmoon passed. They went on for a week, speaking\r\n\r\n2158\r\n02:58:53,082 --> 02:58:57,106\r\nonly of the precautions they\nneeded to follow in order to avoid the battles\r\n\r\n2159\r\n02:58:58,006 --> 02:59:03,085\r\nbetween the tribes. The war\ncontinued, and at times the wind carried the\r\n\r\n2160\r\n02:59:03,085 --> 02:59:09,085\r\nsweet, sickly smell of blood. Battles\nhad been fought nearby, and the wind reminded\r\n\r\n2161\r\n02:59:09,085 --> 02:59:13,506\r\nthe boy that there was the\nlanguage of omens, always ready to show him\r\n\r\n2162\r\n02:59:14,271 --> 02:59:18,610\r\nwhat his eyes had failed to\nobserve.\r\n\r\n2163\r\n02:59:18,061 --> 02:59:22,090\r\nOn the seventh day, the alchemist decided\nto make camp earlier than usual.\r\n\r\n2164\r\n02:59:22,009 --> 02:59:27,012\r\nThe falcon flew off to find game, and the\nalchemist offered his water container\r\n\r\n2165\r\n02:59:28,002 --> 02:59:31,097\r\nto the boy.\n\"You are almost at the end of your journey,\"\r\n\r\n2166\r\n02:59:32,015 --> 02:59:38,067\r\nsaid the alchemist. \"I congratulate\nyou for having pursued your Personal Legend.\"\r\n\r\n2167\r\n02:59:38,067 --> 02:59:42,082\r\n\"And you've told me nothing along the way,\"\nsaid the boy. \"I thought you were\r\n\r\n2168\r\n02:59:42,082 --> 02:59:46,128\r\ngoing to teach me some of the things you know.\nA while ago, I rode through the\r\n\r\n2169\r\n02:59:47,028 --> 02:59:50,073\r\ndesert with a man who had books on alchemy.\nBut I wasn't able to learn\r\n\r\n2170\r\n02:59:50,073 --> 02:59:54,085\r\nanything from them.\"\n\"There is only one way to learn,\" the alchemist\r\n\r\n2171\r\n02:59:54,085 --> 02:59:59,149\r\nanswered. \"It's through action.\nEverything you need to know you have learned\r\n\r\n2172\r\n03:00:00,049 --> 03:00:05,084\r\nthrough your journey. You need\nto learn only one thing more.\"\r\n\r\n2173\r\n03:00:05,084 --> 03:00:09,125\r\nThe boy wanted to know what that was, but\nthe alchemist was searching the\r\n\r\n2174\r\n03:00:10,025 --> 03:00:15,094\r\nhorizon, looking for the falcon.\n\"Why are you called the alchemist?\"\r\n\r\n2175\r\n03:00:15,094 --> 03:00:19,190\r\n\"Because that's what I am.\"\n\"And what went wrong when other alchemists\r\n\r\n2176\r\n03:00:20,009 --> 03:00:23,010\r\ntried to make gold and were\nunable to do so?\"\r\n\r\n2177\r\n03:00:24,000 --> 03:00:30,024\r\n\"They were looking only for gold,\" his companion\nanswered. \"They were seeking\r\n\r\n2178\r\n03:00:30,024 --> 03:00:35,103\r\nthe treasure of their Personal Legend, without\nwanting actually to live out the Personal\r\n\r\n2179\r\n03:00:36,003 --> 03:00:40,016\r\nLegend.\"\n\"What is it that I still need to know?\" the\r\n\r\n2180\r\n03:00:40,016 --> 03:00:44,094\r\nboy asked.\nBut the alchemist continued to look to the\r\n\r\n2181\r\n03:00:44,094 --> 03:00:49,128\r\nhorizon. And finally the falcon\nreturned with their meal. They dug a hole\r\n\r\n2182\r\n03:00:50,028 --> 03:00:53,109\r\nand lit their fire in it, so that the light\nof the flames would not be seen.\r\n\r\n2183\r\n03:00:54,009 --> 03:01:00,090\r\n\"I'm an alchemist simply because I'm an alchemist,\"\nhe said, as he prepared the\r\n\r\n2184\r\n03:01:00,009 --> 03:01:04,036\r\nmeal. \"I learned the science from my grandfather,\nwho learned from his father,\r\n\r\n2185\r\n03:01:05,017 --> 03:01:11,072\r\nand so on, back to the creation of the world.\nIn those times, the Master Work\r\n\r\n2186\r\n03:01:11,072 --> 03:01:17,103\r\ncould be written simply on an emerald. But\nmen began to reject simple things,\r\n\r\n2187\r\n03:01:18,003 --> 03:01:23,080\r\nand to write tracts, interpretations, and\nphilosophical studies. They also began\r\n\r\n2188\r\n03:01:23,008 --> 03:01:28,014\r\nto feel that they knew a better way than others\nhad. Yet the Emerald Tablet is\r\n\r\n2189\r\n03:01:29,004 --> 03:01:33,012\r\nstill alive today.\"\n\"What was written on the Emerald Tablet?\"\r\n\r\n2190\r\n03:01:34,002 --> 03:01:39,101\r\nthe boy wanted to know.\nThe alchemist began to draw in the sand, and\r\n\r\n2191\r\n03:01:40,019 --> 03:01:44,350\r\ncompleted his drawing in less\nthan five minutes. As he drew, the boy thought\r\n\r\n2192\r\n03:01:44,521 --> 03:01:49,190\r\nof the old king, and the plaza\nwhere they had met that day; it seemed as\r\n\r\n2193\r\n03:01:49,019 --> 03:01:52,024\r\nif it had taken place years and\nyears ago.\r\n\r\n2194\r\n03:01:52,069 --> 03:01:57,087\r\n\"This is what was written on the Emerald Tablet,\"\nsaid the alchemist, when he\r\n\r\n2195\r\n03:01:57,087 --> 03:02:00,150\r\nhad finished.\nThe boy tried to read what was written in\r\n\r\n2196\r\n03:02:01,005 --> 03:02:05,099\r\nthe sand.\n\"It's a code,\" said the boy, a bit disappointed.\r\n\r\n2197\r\n03:02:06,044 --> 03:02:09,068\r\n\"It looks like what I saw in the\nEnglishman's books.\"\r\n\r\n2198\r\n03:02:09,068 --> 03:02:14,144\r\n\"No,\" the alchemist answered. \"It's like the\nflight of those two hawks; it can't be\r\n\r\n2199\r\n03:02:15,044 --> 03:02:22,044\r\nunderstood by reason alone. The Emerald Tablet\nis a direct passage to the Soul\r\n\r\n2200\r\n03:02:22,049 --> 03:02:26,133\r\nof the World.\n\"The wise men understood that this natural\r\n\r\n2201\r\n03:02:27,033 --> 03:02:34,033\r\nworld is only an image and a copy\nof paradise. The existence of this world is\r\n\r\n2202\r\n03:02:35,024 --> 03:02:42,024\r\nsimply a guarantee that there exists a\nworld that is perfect. God created the world\r\n\r\n2203\r\n03:02:42,063 --> 03:02:47,117\r\nso that, through its visible objects,\nmen could understand his spiritual teachings\r\n\r\n2204\r\n03:02:48,017 --> 03:02:52,056\r\nand the marvels of his wisdom.\nThat's what I mean by action.\"\r\n\r\n2205\r\n03:02:52,056 --> 03:02:57,068\r\n\"Should I understand the Emerald Tablet?\"\nthe boy asked.\r\n\r\n2206\r\n03:02:57,068 --> 03:03:01,142\r\n\"Perhaps, if you were in a laboratory of alchemy,\nthis would be the right time to\r\n\r\n2207\r\n03:03:02,042 --> 03:03:06,893\r\nstudy the best way to understand the Emerald\nTablet. But you are in the desert.\r\n\r\n2208\r\n03:03:07,271 --> 03:03:12,440\r\nSo immerse yourself in it. The desert will\ngive you an understanding of the\r\n\r\n2209\r\n03:03:12,044 --> 03:03:17,140\r\nworld; in fact, anything on the face of the\nearth will do that. You don't even\r\n\r\n2210\r\n03:03:18,004 --> 03:03:23,048\r\nhave to understand the desert: all you have\nto do is contemplate a simple grain\r\n\r\n2211\r\n03:03:23,084 --> 03:03:28,122\r\nof sand, and you will see in it all the marvels\nof creation.\"\r\n\r\n2212\r\n03:03:29,022 --> 03:03:36,022\r\n\"How do I immerse myself in the desert?\"\n\"Listen to your heart. It knows all things,\r\n\r\n2213\r\n03:03:38,021 --> 03:03:45,021\r\nbecause it came from the Soul of the\nWorld, and it will one day return there.\"\r\n\r\n2214\r\n03:03:47,561 --> 03:03:50,000\r\n*\nThey crossed the desert for another two days\r\n\r\n2215\r\n03:03:50,000 --> 03:03:54,091\r\nin silence. The alchemist had\nbecome much more cautious, because they were\r\n\r\n2216\r\n03:03:54,091 --> 03:03:58,124\r\napproaching the area where\nthe most violent battles were being waged.\r\n\r\n2217\r\n03:03:59,024 --> 03:04:02,109\r\nAs they moved along, the boy tried\nto listen to his heart.\r\n\r\n2218\r\n03:04:03,009 --> 03:04:09,016\r\nIt was not easy to do; in earlier times, his\nheart had always been ready to tell\r\n\r\n2219\r\n03:04:09,016 --> 03:04:13,020\r\nits story, but lately that wasn't true. There\nhad been times when his heart spent\r\n\r\n2220\r\n03:04:13,056 --> 03:04:17,060\r\nhours telling of its sadness, and at other\ntimes it became so emotional over the\r\n\r\n2221\r\n03:04:17,096 --> 03:04:23,174\r\ndesert sunrise that the boy had to hide his\ntears. His heart beat fastest when it\r\n\r\n2222\r\n03:04:24,074 --> 03:04:28,173\r\nspoke to the boy of treasure, and more slowly\nwhen the boy stared entranced at\r\n\r\n2223\r\n03:04:29,073 --> 03:04:34,094\r\nthe endless horizons of the desert. But his\nheart was never quiet, even when the\r\n\r\n2224\r\n03:04:34,094 --> 03:04:39,098\r\nboy and the alchemist had fallen into silence.\n\"Why do we have to listen to our hearts?\"\r\n\r\n2225\r\n03:04:40,034 --> 03:04:42,965\r\nthe boy asked, when they had made\ncamp that day.\r\n\r\n2226\r\n03:04:43,271 --> 03:04:48,920\r\n\"Because, wherever your heart is, that is\nwhere you'll find your treasure.\"\r\n\r\n2227\r\n03:04:48,092 --> 03:04:54,119\r\n\"But my heart is agitated,\" the boy said.\n\"It has its dreams, it gets emotional,\r\n\r\n2228\r\n03:04:55,019 --> 03:04:59,023\r\nand it's become passionate over a woman of\nthe desert. It asks things of me,\r\n\r\n2229\r\n03:04:59,059 --> 03:05:02,087\r\nand it keeps me from sleeping many nights,\nwhen I'm thinking about her.\"\r\n\r\n2230\r\n03:05:02,087 --> 03:05:09,087\r\n\"Well, that's good. Your heart is alive. Keep\nlistening to what it has to say.\"\r\n\r\n2231\r\n03:05:11,087 --> 03:05:14,128\r\nDuring the next three days, the two travelers\npassed by a number of armed\r\n\r\n2232\r\n03:05:15,028 --> 03:05:20,073\r\ntribesmen, and saw others on the horizon.\nThe boy's heart began to speak of\r\n\r\n2233\r\n03:05:20,073 --> 03:05:25,130\r\nfear. It told him stories it had heard from\nthe Soul of the World, stories of men\r\n\r\n2234\r\n03:05:26,003 --> 03:05:31,007\r\nwho sought to find their treasure and never\nsucceeded. Sometimes it frightened\r\n\r\n2235\r\n03:05:31,034 --> 03:05:35,055\r\nthe boy with the idea that he might not find\nhis treasure, or that he might die\r\n\r\n2236\r\n03:05:35,055 --> 03:05:41,056\r\nthere in the desert. At other times, it told\nthe boy that it was satisfied: it had\r\n\r\n2237\r\n03:05:41,065 --> 03:05:46,069\r\nfound love and riches.\n\"My heart is a traitor,\" the boy said to the\r\n\r\n2238\r\n03:05:47,005 --> 03:05:50,091\r\nalchemist, when they had paused to\nrest the horses. \"It doesn't want me to go\r\n\r\n2239\r\n03:05:50,091 --> 03:05:54,096\r\non.\"\n\"That makes sense,\" the alchemist answered.\r\n\r\n2240\r\n03:05:54,096 --> 03:05:58,168\r\n\"Naturally it's afraid that, in\npursuing your dream, you might lose everything\r\n\r\n2241\r\n03:05:59,068 --> 03:06:03,110\r\nyou've won.\"\n\"Well, then, why should I listen to my heart?\"\r\n\r\n2242\r\n03:06:04,001 --> 03:06:10,025\r\n\"Because you will never again be able to keep\nit quiet. Even if you pretend not\r\n\r\n2243\r\n03:06:10,034 --> 03:06:15,046\r\nto have heard what it tells you, it will always\nbe there inside you, repeating to\r\n\r\n2244\r\n03:06:15,046 --> 03:06:18,087\r\nyou what you're thinking about life and about\nthe world.\"\r\n\r\n2245\r\n03:06:18,087 --> 03:06:25,087\r\n\"You mean I should listen, even if it's treasonous?\"\n\"Treason is a blow that comes unexpectedly.\r\n\r\n2246\r\n03:06:26,054 --> 03:06:30,140\r\nIf you know your heart well, it will\nnever be able to do that to you. Because you'll\r\n\r\n2247\r\n03:06:31,004 --> 03:06:35,070\r\nknow its dreams and wishes, and\nwill know how to deal with them.\r\n\r\n2248\r\n03:06:36,006 --> 03:06:40,095\r\n\"You will never be able to escape from your\nheart. So it's better to listen to\r\n\r\n2249\r\n03:06:40,095 --> 03:06:47,095\r\nwhat it has to say. That way, you'll never\nhave to fear an unanticipated blow.\"\r\n\r\n2250\r\n03:06:48,069 --> 03:06:52,074\r\nThe boy continued to listen to his heart as\nthey crossed the desert. He came to\r\n\r\n2251\r\n03:06:52,074 --> 03:06:58,153\r\nunderstand its dodges and tricks, and to accept\nit as it was. He lost his fear, and\r\n\r\n2252\r\n03:06:59,053 --> 03:07:03,058\r\nforgot about his need to go back to the oasis,\nbecause, one afternoon, his heart\r\n\r\n2253\r\n03:07:04,003 --> 03:07:09,025\r\ntold him that it was happy. \"Even though I\ncomplain sometimes,\" it said, \"it's\r\n\r\n2254\r\n03:07:09,025 --> 03:07:14,059\r\nbecause I'm the heart of a person, and people's\nhearts are that way. People are\r\n\r\n2255\r\n03:07:14,059 --> 03:07:17,065\r\nafraid to pursue their most important dreams,\nbecause they feel that they don't\r\n\r\n2256\r\n03:07:18,019 --> 03:07:23,042\r\ndeserve them, or that they'll be unable to\nachieve them. We, their hearts,\r\n\r\n2257\r\n03:07:23,042 --> 03:07:27,101\r\nbecome fearful just thinking of loved ones\nwho go away forever, or of moments\r\n\r\n2258\r\n03:07:28,001 --> 03:07:31,035\r\nthat could have been good but weren't, or\nof treasures that might have been\r\n\r\n2259\r\n03:07:31,035 --> 03:07:35,120\r\nfound but were forever hidden in the sands.\nBecause, when these things\r\n\r\n2260\r\n03:07:36,002 --> 03:07:40,083\r\nhappen, we suffer terribly.\"\n\"My heart is afraid that it will have to suffer,\"\r\n\r\n2261\r\n03:07:41,001 --> 03:07:44,087\r\nthe boy told the alchemist one\nnight as they looked up at the moonless sky.\r\n\r\n2262\r\n03:07:44,087 --> 03:07:50,146\r\n\"Tell your heart that the fear of suffering\nis worse than the suffering itself. And\r\n\r\n2263\r\n03:07:51,046 --> 03:07:55,122\r\nthat no heart has ever suffered when it goes\nin search of its dreams, because\r\n\r\n2264\r\n03:07:56,022 --> 03:08:01,073\r\nevery second of the search is a second's encounter\nwith God and with eternity.\"\r\n\r\n2265\r\n03:08:01,271 --> 03:08:07,460\r\n\"Every second of the search is an encounter\nwith God,\" the boy told his heart.\r\n\r\n2266\r\n03:08:07,046 --> 03:08:11,084\r\n\"When I have been truly searching for my treasure,\nevery day has been\r\n\r\n2267\r\n03:08:11,084 --> 03:08:14,167\r\nluminous, because I've known that every hour\nwas a part of the dream that I\r\n\r\n2268\r\n03:08:15,067 --> 03:08:19,151\r\nwould find it. When I have been truly searching\nfor my treasure, I've discovered\r\n\r\n2269\r\n03:08:20,051 --> 03:08:23,117\r\nthings along the way that I never would have\nseen had I not had the courage to\r\n\r\n2270\r\n03:08:24,017 --> 03:08:27,024\r\ntry things that seemed impossible for a shepherd\nto achieve.\"\r\n\r\n2271\r\n03:08:27,087 --> 03:08:34,087\r\nSo his heart was quiet for an entire afternoon.\nThat night, the boy slept deeply,\r\n\r\n2272\r\n03:08:35,081 --> 03:08:39,085\r\nand, when he awoke, his heart began to tell\nhim things that came from the Soul\r\n\r\n2273\r\n03:08:40,021 --> 03:08:47,021\r\nof the World. It said that all people who\nare happy have God within them. And\r\n\r\n2274\r\n03:08:47,024 --> 03:08:50,031\r\nthat happiness could be found in a grain of\nsand from the desert, as the\r\n\r\n2275\r\n03:08:50,094 --> 03:08:56,095\r\nalchemist had said. Because a grain of sand\nis a moment of creation, and the\r\n\r\n2276\r\n03:08:57,004 --> 03:09:01,028\r\nuniverse has taken millions of years to create\nit. \"Everyone on earth has a\r\n\r\n2277\r\n03:09:01,028 --> 03:09:06,079\r\ntreasure that awaits him,\" his heart said.\n\"We, people's hearts, seldom say\r\n\r\n2278\r\n03:09:06,079 --> 03:09:09,112\r\nmuch about those treasures, because people\nno longer want to go in search of\r\n\r\n2279\r\n03:09:10,012 --> 03:09:15,068\r\nthem. We speak of them only to children. Later,\nwe simply let life proceed, in\r\n\r\n2280\r\n03:09:15,068 --> 03:09:20,145\r\nits own direction, toward its own fate. But,\nunfortunately, very few follow the\r\n\r\n2281\r\n03:09:21,045 --> 03:09:26,137\r\npath laid out for them--the path to their\ndestinies, and to happiness. Most people\r\n\r\n2282\r\n03:09:27,037 --> 03:09:30,085\r\nsee the world as a threatening place, and,\nbecause they do, the world turns out,\r\n\r\n2283\r\n03:09:30,085 --> 03:09:34,163\r\nindeed, to be a threatening place.\n\"So, we, their hearts, speak more and more\r\n\r\n2284\r\n03:09:35,063 --> 03:09:39,139\r\nsoftly. We never stop speaking out,\nbut we begin to hope that our words won't\r\n\r\n2285\r\n03:09:40,039 --> 03:09:44,101\r\nbe heard: we don't want people to\nsuffer because they don't follow their hearts.\"\r\n\r\n2286\r\n03:09:45,001 --> 03:09:49,086\r\n\"Why don't people's hearts tell them to continue\nto follow their dreams?\" the\r\n\r\n2287\r\n03:09:49,086 --> 03:09:53,131\r\nboy asked the alchemist.\n\"Because that's what makes a heart suffer\r\n\r\n2288\r\n03:09:54,031 --> 03:10:01,031\r\nmost, and hearts don't like to suffer.\"\nFrom then on, the boy understood his heart.\r\n\r\n2289\r\n03:10:02,052 --> 03:10:07,094\r\nHe asked it, please, never to stop\nspeaking to him. He asked that, when he wandered\r\n\r\n2290\r\n03:10:07,094 --> 03:10:12,099\r\nfar from his dreams, his\nheart press him and sound the alarm. The boy\r\n\r\n2291\r\n03:10:13,044 --> 03:10:17,102\r\nswore that, every time he heard\nthe alarm, he would heed its message.\r\n\r\n2292\r\n03:10:18,002 --> 03:10:23,060\r\nThat night, he told all of this to the alchemist.\nAnd the alchemist understood that\r\n\r\n2293\r\n03:10:23,006 --> 03:10:26,014\r\nthe boy's heart had returned to the Soul of\nthe World.\r\n\r\n2294\r\n03:10:26,068 --> 03:10:32,097\r\n\"So what should I do now?\" the boy asked.\n\"Continue in the direction of the Pyramids,\"\r\n\r\n2295\r\n03:10:32,097 --> 03:10:37,156\r\nsaid the alchemist. \"And continue to\npay heed to the omens. Your heart is still\r\n\r\n2296\r\n03:10:38,056 --> 03:10:41,071\r\ncapable of showing you where the\ntreasure is.\"\r\n\r\n2297\r\n03:10:41,071 --> 03:10:48,071\r\n\"Is that the one thing I still needed to know?\"\n\"No,\" the alchemist answered. \"What you still\r\n\r\n2298\r\n03:10:48,074 --> 03:10:54,157\r\nneed to know is this: before a\ndream is realized, the Soul of the World tests\r\n\r\n2299\r\n03:10:55,057 --> 03:11:02,057\r\neverything that was learned along\nthe way. It does this not because it is evil,\r\n\r\n2300\r\n03:11:02,069 --> 03:11:08,152\r\nbut so that we can, in addition to\nrealizing our dreams, master the lessons we've\r\n\r\n2301\r\n03:11:09,052 --> 03:11:15,074\r\nlearned as we've moved toward\nthat dream. That's the point at which most\r\n\r\n2302\r\n03:11:15,074 --> 03:11:20,162\r\npeople give up. It's the point at\nwhich, as we say in the language of the desert,\r\n\r\n2303\r\n03:11:21,062 --> 03:11:25,130\r\none 'dies of thirst just when the\npalm trees have appeared on the horizon.'\r\n\r\n2304\r\n03:11:26,003 --> 03:11:33,003\r\n\"Every search begins with beginner's luck.\nAnd every search ends with the\r\n\r\n2305\r\n03:11:33,052 --> 03:11:39,119\r\nvictor's being severely tested.\"\nThe boy remembered an old proverb from his\r\n\r\n2306\r\n03:11:40,019 --> 03:11:46,112\r\ncountry. It said that the darkest\nhour of the night came just before the dawn.\r\n\r\n2307\r\n03:11:47,012 --> 03:11:49,047\r\n*\nOn the following day, the first clear sign\r\n\r\n2308\r\n03:11:49,047 --> 03:11:54,076\r\nof danger appeared. Three armed\ntribesmen approached, and asked what the boy\r\n\r\n2309\r\n03:11:54,076 --> 03:11:55,082\r\nand the alchemist were doing\nthere.\r\n\r\n2310\r\n03:11:56,036 --> 03:11:59,121\r\n\"I'm hunting with my falcon,\" the alchemist\nanswered.\r\n\r\n2311\r\n03:12:00,021 --> 03:12:04,023\r\n\"We're going to have to search you to see\nwhether you're armed,\" one of the\r\n\r\n2312\r\n03:12:04,041 --> 03:12:08,041\r\ntribesmen said.\nThe alchemist dismounted slowly, and the boy\r\n\r\n2313\r\n03:12:08,041 --> 03:12:12,073\r\ndid the same.\n\"Why are you carrying money?\" asked the tribesman,\r\n\r\n2314\r\n03:12:12,073 --> 03:12:13,148\r\nwhen he had searched the\nboy's bag.\r\n\r\n2315\r\n03:12:14,048 --> 03:12:20,069\r\n\"I need it to get to the Pyramids,\" he said.\nThe tribesman who was searching the alchemist's\r\n\r\n2316\r\n03:12:20,069 --> 03:12:24,152\r\nbelongings found a small\ncrystal flask filled with a liquid, and a\r\n\r\n2317\r\n03:12:25,052 --> 03:12:28,095\r\nyellow glass egg that was slightly larger\nthan a chicken's egg.\r\n\r\n2318\r\n03:12:28,095 --> 03:12:34,152\r\n\"What are these things?\" he asked.\n\"That's the Philosopher's Stone and the Elixir\r\n\r\n2319\r\n03:12:35,052 --> 03:12:41,124\r\nof Life. It's the Master Work of the\nalchemists. Whoever swallows that elixir will\r\n\r\n2320\r\n03:12:42,024 --> 03:12:47,057\r\nnever be sick again, and a\nfragment from that stone turns any metal into\r\n\r\n2321\r\n03:12:47,057 --> 03:12:51,104\r\ngold.\"\nThe Arabs laughed at him, and the alchemist\r\n\r\n2322\r\n03:12:52,004 --> 03:12:56,080\r\nlaughed along. They thought his\nanswer was amusing, and they allowed the boy\r\n\r\n2323\r\n03:12:56,008 --> 03:12:58,092\r\nand the alchemist to proceed\nwith all of their belongings.\r\n\r\n2324\r\n03:12:59,064 --> 03:13:02,157\r\n\"Are you crazy?\" the boy asked the alchemist,\nwhen they had moved on. \"What\r\n\r\n2325\r\n03:13:03,057 --> 03:13:07,131\r\ndid you do that for?\"\n\"To show you one of life's simple lessons,\"\r\n\r\n2326\r\n03:13:08,031 --> 03:13:13,052\r\nthe alchemist answered. \"When you\npossess great treasures within you, and try\r\n\r\n2327\r\n03:13:13,052 --> 03:13:18,113\r\nto tell others of them, seldom are\nyou believed.\"\r\n\r\n2328\r\n03:13:19,013 --> 03:13:23,078\r\nThey continued across the desert. With every\nday that passed, the boy's heart\r\n\r\n2329\r\n03:13:23,078 --> 03:13:27,137\r\nbecame more and more silent. It no longer\nwanted to know about things of the\r\n\r\n2330\r\n03:13:28,037 --> 03:13:33,046\r\npast or future; it was content simply to contemplate\nthe desert, and to drink\r\n\r\n2331\r\n03:13:33,046 --> 03:13:39,064\r\nwith the boy from the Soul of the World. The\nboy and his heart had become\r\n\r\n2332\r\n03:13:39,064 --> 03:13:45,156\r\nfriends, and neither was capable now of betraying\nthe other.\r\n\r\n2333\r\n03:13:46,056 --> 03:13:50,085\r\nWhen his heart spoke to him, it was to provide\na stimulus to the boy, and to\r\n\r\n2334\r\n03:13:50,085 --> 03:13:53,184\r\ngive him strength, because the days of silence\nthere in the desert were\r\n\r\n2335\r\n03:13:54,084 --> 03:13:59,106\r\nwearisome. His heart told the boy what his\nstrongest qualities were: his courage\r\n\r\n2336\r\n03:14:00,006 --> 03:14:04,071\r\nin having given up his sheep and in trying\nto live out his Personal Legend, and his\r\n\r\n2337\r\n03:14:04,071 --> 03:14:08,084\r\nenthusiasm during the time he had worked at\nthe crystal shop.\r\n\r\n2338\r\n03:14:08,084 --> 03:14:12,168\r\nAnd his heart told him something else that\nthe boy had never noticed: it told the\r\n\r\n2339\r\n03:14:13,068 --> 03:14:18,126\r\nboy of dangers that had threatened him, but\nthat he had never perceived. His\r\n\r\n2340\r\n03:14:19,026 --> 03:14:23,037\r\nheart said that one time it had hidden the\nrifle the boy had taken from his\r\n\r\n2341\r\n03:14:23,037 --> 03:14:28,044\r\nfather, because of the possibility that the\nboy might wound himself. And it\r\n\r\n2342\r\n03:14:28,044 --> 03:14:31,081\r\nreminded the boy of the day when he had been\nill and vomiting out in the\r\n\r\n2343\r\n03:14:31,081 --> 03:14:36,123\r\nfields, after which he had fallen into a deep\nsleep. There had been two thieves\r\n\r\n2344\r\n03:14:37,023 --> 03:14:41,081\r\nfarther ahead who were planning to steal the\nboy's sheep and murder him. But,\r\n\r\n2345\r\n03:14:41,081 --> 03:14:46,093\r\nsince the boy hadn't passed by, they had decided\nto move on, thinking that he\r\n\r\n2346\r\n03:14:46,093 --> 03:14:52,094\r\nhad changed his route.\n\"Does a man's heart always help him?\" the\r\n\r\n2347\r\n03:14:52,094 --> 03:14:56,130\r\nboy asked the alchemist.\n\"Mostly just the hearts of those who are trying\r\n\r\n2348\r\n03:14:57,003 --> 03:15:02,094\r\nto realize their destinies. But\nthey do help children, drunkards, and the\r\n\r\n2349\r\n03:15:03,021 --> 03:15:07,035\r\nelderly, too.\"\n\"Does that mean that I'll never run into danger?\"\r\n\r\n2350\r\n03:15:07,035 --> 03:15:13,124\r\n\"It means only that the heart does what it\ncan,\" the alchemist said.\r\n\r\n2351\r\n03:15:14,024 --> 03:15:18,075\r\nOne afternoon, they passed by the encampment\nof one of the tribes. At each\r\n\r\n2352\r\n03:15:18,075 --> 03:15:22,103\r\ncorner of the camp were Arabs garbed in beautiful\nwhite robes, with arms at the\r\n\r\n2353\r\n03:15:23,003 --> 03:15:27,067\r\nready. The men were smoking their hookahs\nand trading stories from the\r\n\r\n2354\r\n03:15:27,067 --> 03:15:30,119\r\nbattlefield. No one paid any attention to\nthe two travelers.\r\n\r\n2355\r\n03:15:31,019 --> 03:15:36,036\r\n\"There's no danger,\" the boy said, when they\nhad moved on past the\r\n\r\n2356\r\n03:15:36,036 --> 03:15:39,072\r\nencampment.\nThe alchemist sounded angry: \"Trust in your\r\n\r\n2357\r\n03:15:39,072 --> 03:15:43,137\r\nheart, but never forget that you're\nin the desert. When men are at war with one\r\n\r\n2358\r\n03:15:44,037 --> 03:15:48,121\r\nanother, the Soul of the World can\nhear the screams of battle. No one fails to\r\n\r\n2359\r\n03:15:49,021 --> 03:15:53,095\r\nsuffer the consequences of\neverything under the sun.\"\r\n\r\n2360\r\n03:15:53,095 --> 03:15:57,151\r\nAll things are one, the boy thought. And then,\nas if the desert wanted to\r\n\r\n2361\r\n03:15:58,051 --> 03:16:02,059\r\ndemonstrate that the alchemist was right,\ntwo horsemen appeared from behind\r\n\r\n2362\r\n03:16:02,059 --> 03:16:06,066\r\nthe travelers.\n\"You can't go any farther,\" one of them said.\r\n\r\n2363\r\n03:16:06,066 --> 03:16:09,081\r\n\"You're in the area where the\ntribes are at war.\"\r\n\r\n2364\r\n03:16:09,081 --> 03:16:13,089\r\n\"I'm not going very far,\" the alchemist answered,\nlooking straight into the eyes\r\n\r\n2365\r\n03:16:14,061 --> 03:16:18,159\r\nof the horsemen. They were silent for a moment,\nand then agreed that the boy\r\n\r\n2366\r\n03:16:19,059 --> 03:16:24,106\r\nand the alchemist could move along.\nThe boy watched the exchange with fascination.\r\n\r\n2367\r\n03:16:25,006 --> 03:16:28,039\r\n\"You dominated those\nhorsemen with the way you looked at them,\"\r\n\r\n2368\r\n03:16:28,039 --> 03:16:32,073\r\nhe said.\n\"Your eyes show the strength of your soul,\"\r\n\r\n2369\r\n03:16:32,073 --> 03:16:37,130\r\nanswered the alchemist.\nThat's true, the boy thought. He had noticed\r\n\r\n2370\r\n03:16:38,003 --> 03:16:41,087\r\nthat, in the midst of the multitude\nof armed men back at the encampment, there\r\n\r\n2371\r\n03:16:42,014 --> 03:16:46,083\r\nhad been one who stared fixedly\nat the two. He had been so far away that his\r\n\r\n2372\r\n03:16:46,083 --> 03:16:49,164\r\nface wasn't even visible. But the\nboy was certain that he had been looking at\r\n\r\n2373\r\n03:16:50,064 --> 03:16:53,158\r\nthem.\nFinally, when they had crossed the mountain\r\n\r\n2374\r\n03:16:54,058 --> 03:16:58,101\r\nrange that extended along the\nentire horizon, the alchemist said that they\r\n\r\n2375\r\n03:16:59,001 --> 03:17:01,074\r\nwere only two days from the\nPyramids.\r\n\r\n2376\r\n03:17:01,074 --> 03:17:04,171\r\n\"If we're going to go our separate ways soon,\"\nthe boy said, \"then teach me\r\n\r\n2377\r\n03:17:05,071 --> 03:17:09,153\r\nabout alchemy.\"\n\"You already know about alchemy. It is about\r\n\r\n2378\r\n03:17:10,053 --> 03:17:15,120\r\npenetrating to the Soul of the\nWorld, and discovering the treasure that has\r\n\r\n2379\r\n03:17:16,002 --> 03:17:20,085\r\nbeen reserved for you.\"\n\"No, that's not what I mean. I'm talking about\r\n\r\n2380\r\n03:17:21,003 --> 03:17:27,050\r\ntransforming lead into gold.\"\nThe alchemist fell as silent as the desert,\r\n\r\n2381\r\n03:17:27,005 --> 03:17:30,102\r\nand answered the boy only after they\nhad stopped to eat.\r\n\r\n2382\r\n03:17:31,047 --> 03:17:38,047\r\n\"Everything in the universe evolved,\" he said.\n\"And, for wise men, gold is the\r\n\r\n2383\r\n03:17:39,057 --> 03:17:44,091\r\nmetal that evolved the furthest. Don't ask\nme why; I don't know why. I just\r\n\r\n2384\r\n03:17:44,091 --> 03:17:50,120\r\nknow that the Tradition is always right.\n\"Men have never understood the words of the\r\n\r\n2385\r\n03:17:51,002 --> 03:17:57,071\r\nwise. So gold, instead of being\nseen as a symbol of evolution, became the\r\n\r\n2386\r\n03:17:57,089 --> 03:18:01,136\r\nbasis for conflict.\"\n\"There are many languages spoken by things,\"\r\n\r\n2387\r\n03:18:02,036 --> 03:18:06,054\r\nthe boy said. \"There was a time\nwhen, for me, a camel's whinnying was nothing\r\n\r\n2388\r\n03:18:06,054 --> 03:18:11,059\r\nmore than whinnying. Then it\nbecame a signal of danger. And, finally, it\r\n\r\n2389\r\n03:18:11,059 --> 03:18:16,123\r\nbecame just a whinny again.\"\nBut then he stopped. The alchemist probably\r\n\r\n2390\r\n03:18:17,023 --> 03:18:22,060\r\nalready knew all that.\n\"I have known true alchemists,\" the alchemist\r\n\r\n2391\r\n03:18:22,006 --> 03:18:25,082\r\ncontinued. \"They locked\nthemselves in their laboratories, and tried\r\n\r\n2392\r\n03:18:26,036 --> 03:18:31,119\r\nto evolve, as gold had. And they\nfound the Philosopher's Stone, because they\r\n\r\n2393\r\n03:18:32,019 --> 03:18:37,107\r\nunderstood that when something\nevolves, everything around that thing evolves\r\n\r\n2394\r\n03:18:38,007 --> 03:18:44,059\r\nas well.\n\"Others stumbled upon the stone by accident.\r\n\r\n2395\r\n03:18:44,059 --> 03:18:48,127\r\nThey already had the gift, and\ntheir souls were readier for such things than\r\n\r\n2396\r\n03:18:49,027 --> 03:18:54,038\r\nthe souls of others. But they don't\ncount. They're quite rare.\r\n\r\n2397\r\n03:18:54,038 --> 03:18:59,136\r\n\"And then there were the others, who were\ninterested only in gold. They never\r\n\r\n2398\r\n03:19:00,036 --> 03:19:06,045\r\nfound the secret. They forgot that lead, copper,\nand iron have their own\r\n\r\n2399\r\n03:19:06,045 --> 03:19:11,129\r\ndestinies to fulfill. And anyone who interferes\nwith the Personal Legend of another thing\r\n\r\n2400\r\n03:19:12,029 --> 03:19:19,029\r\nnever will discover his own.\"\nThe alchemist's words echoed out like a curse.\r\n\r\n2401\r\n03:19:20,006 --> 03:19:23,048\r\nHe reached over and picked up a\nshell from the ground.\r\n\r\n2402\r\n03:19:23,048 --> 03:19:30,048\r\n\"This desert was once a sea,\" he said.\n\"I noticed that,\" the boy answered.\r\n\r\n2403\r\n03:19:32,039 --> 03:19:36,048\r\nThe alchemist told the boy to place the shell\nover his ear. He had done that\r\n\r\n2404\r\n03:19:36,048 --> 03:19:40,100\r\nmany times when he was a child, and had heard\nthe sound of the sea.\r\n\r\n2405\r\n03:19:41,000 --> 03:19:48,000\r\n\"The sea has lived on in this shell, because\nthat's its Personal Legend. And it will never\r\n\r\n2406\r\n03:19:48,023 --> 03:19:54,112\r\ncease doing so until the desert is once again\ncovered by water.\"\r\n\r\n2407\r\n03:19:55,012 --> 03:20:00,096\r\nThey mounted their horses, and rode out in\nthe direction of the Pyramids of\r\n\r\n2408\r\n03:20:00,096 --> 03:20:00,179\r\nEgypt.\n*\r\n\r\n2409\r\n03:20:01,079 --> 03:20:05,085\r\nThe sun was setting when the boy's heart sounded\na danger signal. They were\r\n\r\n2410\r\n03:20:06,039 --> 03:20:10,060\r\nsurrounded by gigantic dunes, and the boy\nlooked at the alchemist to see\r\n\r\n2411\r\n03:20:10,006 --> 03:20:15,042\r\nwhether he had sensed anything. But he appeared\nto be unaware of any danger.\r\n\r\n2412\r\n03:20:15,096 --> 03:20:20,148\r\nFive minutes later, the boy saw two horsemen\nwaiting ahead of them. Before he\r\n\r\n2413\r\n03:20:21,048 --> 03:20:25,077\r\ncould say anything to the alchemist, the two\nhorsemen had become ten, and\r\n\r\n2414\r\n03:20:25,077 --> 03:20:30,132\r\nthen a hundred. And then they were everywhere\nin the dunes.\r\n\r\n2415\r\n03:20:31,032 --> 03:20:36,065\r\nThey were tribesmen dressed in blue, with\nblack rings surrounding their turbans.\r\n\r\n2416\r\n03:20:36,065 --> 03:20:41,074\r\nTheir faces were hidden behind blue veils,\nwith only their eyes showing.\r\n\r\n2417\r\n03:20:42,055 --> 03:20:46,121\r\nEven from a distance, their eyes conveyed\nthe strength of their souls. And their\r\n\r\n2418\r\n03:20:47,021 --> 03:20:50,098\r\neyes spoke of death.\n*\r\n\r\n2419\r\n03:20:50,098 --> 03:20:54,131\r\nThe two were taken to a nearby military camp.\nA soldier shoved the boy and\r\n\r\n2420\r\n03:20:55,031 --> 03:20:58,088\r\nthe alchemist into a tent where the chief\nwas holding a meeting with his staff.\r\n\r\n2421\r\n03:20:58,088 --> 03:21:04,169\r\n\"These are the spies,\" said one of the men.\n\"We're just travelers,\" the alchemist answered.\r\n\r\n2422\r\n03:21:05,069 --> 03:21:09,122\r\n\"You were seen at the enemy camp three days\nago. And you were talking with\r\n\r\n2423\r\n03:21:10,022 --> 03:21:14,056\r\none of the troops there.\"\n\"I'm just a man who wanders the desert and\r\n\r\n2424\r\n03:21:14,056 --> 03:21:19,085\r\nknows the stars,\" said the\nalchemist. \"I have no information about troops\r\n\r\n2425\r\n03:21:19,085 --> 03:21:24,177\r\nor about the movement of the\ntribes. I was simply acting as a guide for\r\n\r\n2426\r\n03:21:25,077 --> 03:21:30,126\r\nmy friend here.\"\n\"Who is your friend?\" the chief asked.\r\n\r\n2427\r\n03:21:31,026 --> 03:21:37,054\r\n\"An alchemist,\" said the alchemist. \"He understands\nthe forces of nature. And he\r\n\r\n2428\r\n03:21:37,054 --> 03:21:43,126\r\nwants to show you his extraordinary powers.\"\nThe boy listened quietly. And fearfully.\r\n\r\n2429\r\n03:21:44,026 --> 03:21:48,034\r\n\"What is a foreigner doing here?\" asked another\nof the men.\r\n\r\n2430\r\n03:21:48,034 --> 03:21:53,118\r\n\"He has brought money to give to your tribe,\"\nsaid the alchemist, before the boy\r\n\r\n2431\r\n03:21:54,018 --> 03:21:59,019\r\ncould say a word. And seizing the boy's bag,\nthe alchemist gave the gold coins\r\n\r\n2432\r\n03:21:59,019 --> 03:22:04,031\r\nto the chief.\nThe Arab accepted them without a word. There\r\n\r\n2433\r\n03:22:04,031 --> 03:22:07,032\r\nwas enough there to buy a lot of\nweapons.\r\n\r\n2434\r\n03:22:07,041 --> 03:22:14,041\r\n\"What is an alchemist?\" he asked, finally.\n\"It's a man who understands nature and the\r\n\r\n2435\r\n03:22:14,077 --> 03:22:19,081\r\nworld. If he wanted to, he could\ndestroy this camp just with the force of the\r\n\r\n2436\r\n03:22:19,081 --> 03:22:23,160\r\nwind.\"\nThe men laughed. They were used to the ravages\r\n\r\n2437\r\n03:22:24,006 --> 03:22:27,102\r\nof war, and knew that the\nwind could not deliver them a fatal blow.\r\n\r\n2438\r\n03:22:28,056 --> 03:22:33,127\r\nYet each felt his heart beat a bit\nfaster. They were men of the desert, and they\r\n\r\n2439\r\n03:22:34,027 --> 03:22:39,041\r\nwere fearful of sorcerers.\n\"I want to see him do it,\" said the chief.\r\n\r\n2440\r\n03:22:39,041 --> 03:22:44,123\r\n\"He needs three days,\" answered the alchemist.\n\"He is going to transform\r\n\r\n2441\r\n03:22:45,023 --> 03:22:51,040\r\nhimself into the wind, just to demonstrate\nhis powers. If he can't do so, we\r\n\r\n2442\r\n03:22:51,004 --> 03:22:55,025\r\nhumbly offer you our lives, for the honor\nof your tribe.\"\r\n\r\n2443\r\n03:22:55,061 --> 03:23:00,062\r\n\"You can't offer me something that is already\nmine,\" the chief said, arrogantly.\r\n\r\n2444\r\n03:23:00,071 --> 03:23:06,158\r\nBut he granted the travelers three days.\nThe boy was shaking with fear, but the alchemist\r\n\r\n2445\r\n03:23:07,058 --> 03:23:12,077\r\nhelped him out of the tent.\n\"Don't let them see that you're afraid,\" the\r\n\r\n2446\r\n03:23:12,077 --> 03:23:16,123\r\nalchemist said. \"They are brave\nmen, and they despise cowards.\"\r\n\r\n2447\r\n03:23:17,023 --> 03:23:23,029\r\nBut the boy couldn't even speak. He was able\nto do so only after they had\r\n\r\n2448\r\n03:23:23,029 --> 03:23:27,092\r\nwalked through the center of the camp. There\nwas no need to imprison them:\r\n\r\n2449\r\n03:23:27,092 --> 03:23:32,114\r\nthe Arabs simply confiscated their horses.\nSo, once again, the world had\r\n\r\n2450\r\n03:23:33,014 --> 03:23:37,095\r\ndemonstrated its many languages: the desert\nonly moments ago had been\r\n\r\n2451\r\n03:23:37,095 --> 03:23:42,122\r\nendless and free, and now it was an impenetrable\nwall.\r\n\r\n2452\r\n03:23:43,022 --> 03:23:47,085\r\n\"You gave them everything I had!\" the boy\nsaid. \"Everything I've saved in my\r\n\r\n2453\r\n03:23:47,085 --> 03:23:51,147\r\nentire life!\"\n\"Well, what good would it be to you if you\r\n\r\n2454\r\n03:23:52,047 --> 03:23:57,131\r\nhad t6 die?\" the alchemist answered.\n\"Your money saved us for three days. It's\r\n\r\n2455\r\n03:23:58,031 --> 03:24:00,099\r\nnot often that money saves a person's\nlife.\"\r\n\r\n2456\r\n03:24:00,099 --> 03:24:06,157\r\nBut the boy was too frightened to listen to\nwords of wisdom. He had no idea\r\n\r\n2457\r\n03:24:07,057 --> 03:24:13,110\r\nhow he was going to transform himself into\nthe wind. He wasn't an alchemist!\r\n\r\n2458\r\n03:24:14,001 --> 03:24:18,015\r\nThe alchemist asked one of the soldiers for\nsome tea, and poured some on the\r\n\r\n2459\r\n03:24:18,024 --> 03:24:23,035\r\nboy's wrists. A wave of relief washed over\nhim, and the alchemist muttered\r\n\r\n2460\r\n03:24:23,035 --> 03:24:30,035\r\nsome words that the boy didn't understand.\n\"Don't give in to your fears,\" said the alchemist,\r\n\r\n2461\r\n03:24:30,004 --> 03:24:36,008\r\nin a strangely gentle voice. \"If\nyou do, you won't be able to talk to your\r\n\r\n2462\r\n03:24:36,044 --> 03:24:39,115\r\nheart.\"\n\"But I have no idea how to turn myself into\r\n\r\n2463\r\n03:24:40,015 --> 03:24:45,084\r\nthe wind.\"\n\"If a person is living out his Personal Legend,\r\n\r\n2464\r\n03:24:45,084 --> 03:24:50,098\r\nhe knows everything he needs to know.\nThere is only one thing that makes a dream\r\n\r\n2465\r\n03:24:50,098 --> 03:24:53,104\r\nimpossible to achieve: the fear of\nfailure.\"\r\n\r\n2466\r\n03:24:54,058 --> 03:24:59,061\r\n\"I'm not afraid of failing. It's just that\nI don't know how to turn myself into the\r\n\r\n2467\r\n03:24:59,088 --> 03:25:03,152\r\nwind.\"\n\"Well, you'll have to learn; your life depends\r\n\r\n2468\r\n03:25:04,052 --> 03:25:07,054\r\non it.\"\n\"But what if I can't?\"\r\n\r\n2469\r\n03:25:07,072 --> 03:25:13,131\r\n\"Then you'll die in the midst of trying to\nrealize your Personal Legend. That's a lot\r\n\r\n2470\r\n03:25:14,031 --> 03:25:15,123\r\nbetter\nthan dying like millions of other people,\r\n\r\n2471\r\n03:25:16,023 --> 03:25:18,085\r\nwho never even knew what their\ndestinies were.\r\n\r\n2472\r\n03:25:18,085 --> 03:25:23,122\r\n\"But don't worry,\" the alchemist continued.\n\"Usually the threat of death makes\r\n\r\n2473\r\n03:25:24,022 --> 03:25:27,099\r\npeople a lot more aware of their lives.\"\n*\r\n\r\n2474\r\n03:25:27,099 --> 03:25:31,151\r\nThe first day passed. There was a major battle\nnearby, and a number of\r\n\r\n2475\r\n03:25:32,051 --> 03:25:36,052\r\nwounded were brought back to the camp. The\ndead soldiers were replaced by\r\n\r\n2476\r\n03:25:36,052 --> 03:25:41,089\r\nothers, and life went on. Death doesn't change\nanything, the boy thought.\r\n\r\n2477\r\n03:25:41,089 --> 03:25:45,160\r\n\"You could have died later on,\" a soldier\nsaid to the body of one of his\r\n\r\n2478\r\n03:25:46,006 --> 03:25:51,072\r\ncompanions. \"You could have died after peace\nhad been declared. But, in any\r\n\r\n2479\r\n03:25:52,026 --> 03:25:57,098\r\ncase, you were going to die.\"\nAt the end of the day, the boy went looking\r\n\r\n2480\r\n03:25:57,098 --> 03:26:00,133\r\nfor the alchemist, who had taken his\nfalcon out into the desert.\r\n\r\n2481\r\n03:26:01,033 --> 03:26:06,068\r\n\"I still have no idea how to turn myself into\nthe wind,\" the boy repeated.\r\n\r\n2482\r\n03:26:06,068 --> 03:26:13,068\r\n\"Remember what I told you: the world is only\nthe visible aspect of God. And\r\n\r\n2483\r\n03:26:14,014 --> 03:26:19,051\r\nthat what alchemy does is to bring spiritual\nperfection into contact with the\r\n\r\n2484\r\n03:26:19,051 --> 03:26:22,092\r\nmaterial plane.\"\n\"What are you doing?\"\r\n\r\n2485\r\n03:26:22,092 --> 03:26:27,190\r\n\"Feeding my falcon.\"\n\"If I'm not able to turn myself into the wind,\r\n\r\n2486\r\n03:26:28,009 --> 03:26:31,091\r\nwe're going to die,\" the boy said.\n\"Why feed your falcon?\"\r\n\r\n2487\r\n03:26:32,072 --> 03:26:38,084\r\n\"You're the one who may die,\" the alchemist\nsaid. \"I already know how to turn\r\n\r\n2488\r\n03:26:38,084 --> 03:26:40,148\r\nmyself into the wind.\"\n*\r\n\r\n2489\r\n03:26:41,048 --> 03:26:45,090\r\nOn the second day, the boy climbed to the\ntop of a cliff near the camp. The\r\n\r\n2490\r\n03:26:45,009 --> 03:26:49,022\r\nsentinels allowed him to go; they had already\nheard about the sorcerer who\r\n\r\n2491\r\n03:26:50,003 --> 03:26:54,094\r\ncould turn himself into the wind, and they\ndidn't want to go near him. In any\r\n\r\n2492\r\n03:26:54,094 --> 03:26:58,140\r\ncase, the desert was impassable.\nHe spent the entire afternoon of the second\r\n\r\n2493\r\n03:26:59,004 --> 03:27:04,033\r\nday looking out over the desert,\nand listening to his heart. The boy knew the\r\n\r\n2494\r\n03:27:04,069 --> 03:27:10,075\r\ndesert sensed his fear. They both\nspoke the same language.\r\n\r\n2495\r\n03:27:10,075 --> 03:27:13,170\r\n*\nOn the third day, the chief met with his officers.\r\n\r\n2496\r\n03:27:14,007 --> 03:27:17,023\r\nHe called the alchemist to the\nmeeting and said, \"Let's go see the boy who\r\n\r\n2497\r\n03:27:17,086 --> 03:27:23,090\r\nturns himself into the wind.\"\n\"Let's,\" the alchemist answered.\r\n\r\n2498\r\n03:27:23,009 --> 03:27:27,105\r\nThe boy took them to the cliff where he had\nbeen on the previous day. He told\r\n\r\n2499\r\n03:27:28,086 --> 03:27:33,147\r\nthem all to be seated.\n\"It's going to take a while,\" the boy said.\r\n\r\n2500\r\n03:27:34,047 --> 03:27:40,056\r\n\"We're in no hurry,\" the chief answered. \"We\nare men of the desert.\"\r\n\r\n2501\r\n03:27:40,056 --> 03:27:45,074\r\nThe boy looked out at the horizon. There were\nmountains in the distance. And\r\n\r\n2502\r\n03:27:45,074 --> 03:27:49,128\r\nthere were dunes, rocks, and plants that insisted\non living where survival\r\n\r\n2503\r\n03:27:50,028 --> 03:27:54,086\r\nseemed impossible. There was the desert that\nhe had wandered for so many\r\n\r\n2504\r\n03:27:54,086 --> 03:28:01,086\r\nmonths; despite all that time, he knew only\na small part of it. Within that small\r\n\r\n2505\r\n03:28:01,091 --> 03:28:07,162\r\npart, he had found an Englishman, caravans,\ntribal wars, and an oasis with fifty\r\n\r\n2506\r\n03:28:08,062 --> 03:28:13,066\r\nthousand palm trees and three hundred wells.\n\"What do you want here today?\" the desert\r\n\r\n2507\r\n03:28:14,002 --> 03:28:18,054\r\nasked him. \"Didn't you spend\nenough time looking at me yesterday?\"\r\n\r\n2508\r\n03:28:18,054 --> 03:28:23,089\r\n\"Somewhere you are holding the person I love,\"\nthe boy said. \"So, when I look\r\n\r\n2509\r\n03:28:23,089 --> 03:28:28,145\r\nout over your sands, I am also looking at\nher. I want to return to her, and I\r\n\r\n2510\r\n03:28:29,045 --> 03:28:31,111\r\nneed your help so that I can turn myself into\nthe wind.\"\r\n\r\n2511\r\n03:28:32,011 --> 03:28:39,011\r\n\"What is love?\" the desert asked.\n\"Love is the falcon's flight over your sands.\r\n\r\n2512\r\n03:28:39,095 --> 03:28:44,097\r\nBecause for him, you are a green\nfield, from which he always returns with game.\r\n\r\n2513\r\n03:28:44,097 --> 03:28:48,099\r\nHe knows your rocks, your\ndunes, and your mountains, and you are generous\r\n\r\n2514\r\n03:28:48,099 --> 03:28:52,113\r\nto him.\"\n\"The falcon's beak carries bits of me, myself,\"\r\n\r\n2515\r\n03:28:53,013 --> 03:28:57,067\r\nthe desert said. \"For years, I care\nfor his game, feeding it with the little water\r\n\r\n2516\r\n03:28:57,067 --> 03:29:01,110\r\nthat I have, and then I show him\nwhere the game is. And, one day, as I enjoy\r\n\r\n2517\r\n03:29:02,001 --> 03:29:06,024\r\nthe fact that his game thrives on\nmy surface, the falcon dives out of the sky,\r\n\r\n2518\r\n03:29:06,033 --> 03:29:09,128\r\nand takes away what I've created.\"\n\"But that's why you created the game in the\r\n\r\n2519\r\n03:29:10,028 --> 03:29:15,056\r\nfirst place,\" the boy answered. \"To\nnourish the falcon. And the falcon then nourishes\r\n\r\n2520\r\n03:29:15,056 --> 03:29:19,077\r\nman. And, eventually, man\nwill nourish your sands, where the game will\r\n\r\n2521\r\n03:29:19,077 --> 03:29:21,160\r\nonce again flourish. That's how the\nworld goes.\"\r\n\r\n2522\r\n03:29:22,006 --> 03:29:27,032\r\n\"So is that what love is?\"\n\"Yes, that's what love is. It's what makes\r\n\r\n2523\r\n03:29:27,086 --> 03:29:31,157\r\nthe game become the falcon, the\nfalcon become man, and man, in his turn, the\r\n\r\n2524\r\n03:29:32,057 --> 03:29:36,138\r\ndesert. It's what turns lead into\ngold, and makes the gold return to the earth.\"\r\n\r\n2525\r\n03:29:37,038 --> 03:29:40,107\r\n\"I don't understand what you're talking about,\"\nthe desert said.\r\n\r\n2526\r\n03:29:41,007 --> 03:29:44,082\r\n\"But you can at least understand that somewhere\nin your sands there is a\r\n\r\n2527\r\n03:29:44,082 --> 03:29:50,084\r\nwoman waiting for me. And that's why I have\nto turn myself into the wind.\"\r\n\r\n2528\r\n03:29:51,002 --> 03:29:56,085\r\nThe desert didn't answer him for a few moments.\nThen it told him, \"I'll give you my sands\r\n\r\n2529\r\n03:29:56,085 --> 03:30:00,151\r\nto help the wind to blow, but, alone, I\ncan't do anything. You have to ask for help\r\n\r\n2530\r\n03:30:01,051 --> 03:30:06,122\r\nfrom the wind.\"\nA breeze began to blow. The tribesmen watched\r\n\r\n2531\r\n03:30:07,022 --> 03:30:10,075\r\nthe boy from a distance,\ntalking among themselves in a language that\r\n\r\n2532\r\n03:30:10,075 --> 03:30:14,169\r\nthe boy couldn't understand.\nThe alchemist smiled.\r\n\r\n2533\r\n03:30:15,069 --> 03:30:19,148\r\nThe wind approached the boy and touched his\nface. It knew of the boy's talk\r\n\r\n2534\r\n03:30:20,048 --> 03:30:24,053\r\nwith the desert, because the winds know everything.\nThey blow across the world\r\n\r\n2535\r\n03:30:24,098 --> 03:30:27,133\r\nwithout a birthplace, and with no place to\ndie.\r\n\r\n2536\r\n03:30:28,033 --> 03:30:32,131\r\n\"Help me,\" the boy said. \"One day you carried\nthe voice of my loved one to\r\n\r\n2537\r\n03:30:33,031 --> 03:30:36,035\r\nme.\"\n\"Who taught you to speak the language of the\r\n\r\n2538\r\n03:30:36,035 --> 03:30:41,071\r\ndesert and the wind?\"\n\"My heart,\" the boy answered.\r\n\r\n2539\r\n03:30:41,071 --> 03:30:46,167\r\nThe wind has many names. In that part of the\nworld, it was called the sirocco,\r\n\r\n2540\r\n03:30:47,067 --> 03:30:51,103\r\nbecause it brought moisture from the oceans\nto the east. In the distant land the\r\n\r\n2541\r\n03:30:52,003 --> 03:30:56,024\r\nboy came from, they called it the levanter,\nbecause they believed that it\r\n\r\n2542\r\n03:30:56,024 --> 03:31:01,043\r\nbrought with it the sands of the desert, and\nthe screams of the Moorish wars.\r\n\r\n2543\r\n03:31:01,043 --> 03:31:05,052\r\nPerhaps, in the places beyond the pastures\nwhere his sheep lived, men thought\r\n\r\n2544\r\n03:31:05,052 --> 03:31:10,073\r\nthat the wind came from Andalusia. But, actually,\nthe wind came from no place\r\n\r\n2545\r\n03:31:10,073 --> 03:31:16,172\r\nat all, nor did it go to any place; that's\nwhy it was stronger than the desert.\r\n\r\n2546\r\n03:31:17,072 --> 03:31:20,140\r\nSomeone might one day plant trees in the desert,\nand even raise sheep there,\r\n\r\n2547\r\n03:31:21,004 --> 03:31:26,055\r\nbut never would they harness the wind.\n\"You can't be the wind,\" the wind said. \"We're\r\n\r\n2548\r\n03:31:26,091 --> 03:31:31,116\r\ntwo very different things.\"\n\"That's not true,\" the boy said. \"I learned\r\n\r\n2549\r\n03:31:32,016 --> 03:31:37,021\r\nthe alchemist's secrets in my travels. I\nhave inside me the winds, the deserts, the\r\n\r\n2550\r\n03:31:37,066 --> 03:31:41,088\r\noceans, the stars, and everything\ncreated in the universe. We were all made\r\n\r\n2551\r\n03:31:41,088 --> 03:31:47,105\r\nby the same hand, and we have the\nsame soul. I want to be like you, able to\r\n\r\n2552\r\n03:31:48,005 --> 03:31:52,018\r\nreach every corner of the world, cross\nthe seas, blow away the sands that cover my\r\n\r\n2553\r\n03:31:52,018 --> 03:31:54,087\r\ntreasure, and carry the voice of\nthe woman I love.\"\r\n\r\n2554\r\n03:31:54,087 --> 03:31:58,091\r\n\"I heard what you were talking about the other\nday with the alchemist,\" the\r\n\r\n2555\r\n03:31:58,091 --> 03:32:03,093\r\nwind said. \"He said that everything has its\nown Personal Legend. But people can't turn\r\n\r\n2556\r\n03:32:04,011 --> 03:32:08,088\r\nthemselves into the wind.\"\n\"Just teach me to be the wind for a few moments,\"\r\n\r\n2557\r\n03:32:08,088 --> 03:32:11,096\r\nthe boy said. \"So you and I\ncan talk about the limitless possibilities\r\n\r\n2558\r\n03:32:12,068 --> 03:32:18,085\r\nof people and the winds.\"\nThe wind's curiosity was aroused, something\r\n\r\n2559\r\n03:32:18,085 --> 03:32:21,173\r\nthat had never happened before. It\nwanted to talk about those things, but it\r\n\r\n2560\r\n03:32:22,073 --> 03:32:26,117\r\ndidn't know how to turn a man into the\nwind. And look how many things the wind already\r\n\r\n2561\r\n03:32:27,017 --> 03:32:32,049\r\nknew how to do! It created\ndeserts, sank ships, felled entire forests,\r\n\r\n2562\r\n03:32:32,049 --> 03:32:37,068\r\nand blew through cities filled with\nmusic and strange noises. It felt that it\r\n\r\n2563\r\n03:32:37,068 --> 03:32:41,099\r\nhad no limits, yet here was a boy saying\nthat there were other things the wind should\r\n\r\n2564\r\n03:32:41,099 --> 03:32:45,112\r\nbe able to do.\n\"This is what we call love,\" the boy said,\r\n\r\n2565\r\n03:32:46,012 --> 03:32:50,064\r\nseeing that the wind was close to\ngranting what he requested. \"When you are\r\n\r\n2566\r\n03:32:50,064 --> 03:32:54,151\r\nloved, you can do anything in\ncreation. When you are loved, there's no need\r\n\r\n2567\r\n03:32:55,051 --> 03:32:58,083\r\nat all to understand what's\nhappening, because everything happens within\r\n\r\n2568\r\n03:32:58,083 --> 03:33:01,175\r\nyou, and even men can turn\nthemselves into the wind. As long as the wind\r\n\r\n2569\r\n03:33:02,075 --> 03:33:06,126\r\nhelps, of course.\"\nThe wind was a proud being, and it was becoming\r\n\r\n2570\r\n03:33:07,026 --> 03:33:12,077\r\nirritated with what the boy\nwas saying. It commenced to blow harder, raising\r\n\r\n2571\r\n03:33:12,077 --> 03:33:17,079\r\nthe desert sands. But finally it\nhad to recognize that, even making its way\r\n\r\n2572\r\n03:33:17,079 --> 03:33:22,084\r\naround the world, it didn't know how\nto turn a man into the wind. And it knew nothing\r\n\r\n2573\r\n03:33:23,029 --> 03:33:27,105\r\nabout love.\n\"In my travels around the world, I've often\r\n\r\n2574\r\n03:33:28,005 --> 03:33:31,088\r\nseen people speaking of love and\nlooking toward the heavens,\" the wind said,\r\n\r\n2575\r\n03:33:31,088 --> 03:33:35,159\r\nfurious at having to acknowledge its\nown limitations. \"Maybe it's better to ask\r\n\r\n2576\r\n03:33:36,059 --> 03:33:39,130\r\nheaven.\"\n\"Well then, help me do that,\" the boy said.\r\n\r\n2577\r\n03:33:40,003 --> 03:33:44,081\r\n\"Fill this place with a sandstorm so\nstrong that it blots out the sun. Then I can\r\n\r\n2578\r\n03:33:45,008 --> 03:33:48,013\r\nlook to heaven without blinding\nmyself.\"\r\n\r\n2579\r\n03:33:48,013 --> 03:33:53,040\r\nSo the wind blew with all its strength, and\nthe sky was filled with sand. The sun\r\n\r\n2580\r\n03:33:53,004 --> 03:33:59,061\r\nwas turned into a golden disk.\nAt the camp, it was difficult to see anything.\r\n\r\n2581\r\n03:33:59,097 --> 03:34:02,156\r\nThe men of the desert were\nalready familiar with that wind. They called\r\n\r\n2582\r\n03:34:03,056 --> 03:34:09,085\r\nit the simum, and it was worse than\na storm at sea. Their horses cried out, and\r\n\r\n2583\r\n03:34:09,085 --> 03:34:12,088\r\nall their weapons were filled with\nsand.\r\n\r\n2584\r\n03:34:12,088 --> 03:34:15,164\r\nOn the heights, one of the commanders turned\nto the chief and said, \"Maybe we\r\n\r\n2585\r\n03:34:16,064 --> 03:34:20,142\r\nhad better end this!\"\nThey could barely see the boy. Their faces\r\n\r\n2586\r\n03:34:21,042 --> 03:34:25,042\r\nwere covered with the blue cloths,\nand their eyes showed fear.\r\n\r\n2587\r\n03:34:25,042 --> 03:34:31,095\r\n\"Let's stop this,\" another commander said.\n\"I want to see the greatness of Allah,\" the\r\n\r\n2588\r\n03:34:31,095 --> 03:34:37,193\r\nchief said, with respect. \"I want to\nsee how a man turns himself into the wind.\"\r\n\r\n2589\r\n03:34:38,093 --> 03:34:40,181\r\nBut he made a mental note of the names of\nthe two men who had expressed\r\n\r\n2590\r\n03:34:41,081 --> 03:34:44,157\r\ntheir fear. As soon as the wind stopped, he\nwas going to remove them from\r\n\r\n2591\r\n03:34:45,057 --> 03:34:48,149\r\ntheir commands, because true men of the desert\nare not afraid.\r\n\r\n2592\r\n03:34:49,049 --> 03:34:55,087\r\n\"The wind told me that you know about love\n\" the boy said to the sun. \"If you\r\n\r\n2593\r\n03:34:55,087 --> 03:34:59,122\r\nknow about love, you must also know about\nthe Soul of the World, because it's\r\n\r\n2594\r\n03:35:00,022 --> 03:35:05,080\r\nmade of love.\"\n\"From where I am,\" the sun said, \"I can see\r\n\r\n2595\r\n03:35:05,008 --> 03:35:10,059\r\nthe Soul of the World. It\ncommunicates with my soul, and together we\r\n\r\n2596\r\n03:35:11,031 --> 03:35:16,082\r\ncause the plants to grow and the\nsheep to seek out shade. From where I am--and\r\n\r\n2597\r\n03:35:16,082 --> 03:35:23,082\r\nI'm a long way from the earth--I\nlearned how to love. I know that if I came\r\n\r\n2598\r\n03:35:25,001 --> 03:35:30,047\r\neven a little bit closer to the earth,\neverything there would die, and the Soul of\r\n\r\n2599\r\n03:35:30,056 --> 03:35:37,056\r\nthe World would no longer exist. So\nwe contemplate each other, and we want each\r\n\r\n2600\r\n03:35:37,093 --> 03:35:43,108\r\nother, and I give it life and\nwarmth, and it gives me my reason for living.\"\r\n\r\n2601\r\n03:35:44,008 --> 03:35:50,026\r\n\"So you know about love,\" the boy said.\n\"And I know the Soul of the World, because\r\n\r\n2602\r\n03:35:50,026 --> 03:35:54,101\r\nwe have talked at great length to\neach other during this endless trip through\r\n\r\n2603\r\n03:35:55,001 --> 03:36:01,009\r\nthe universe. It tells me that its\ngreatest problem is that, up until now, only\r\n\r\n2604\r\n03:36:01,009 --> 03:36:05,100\r\nthe minerals and vegetables\nunderstand that all things are one. That there's\r\n\r\n2605\r\n03:36:06,000 --> 03:36:12,056\r\nno need for iron to be the same\nas copper, or copper the same as gold. Each\r\n\r\n2606\r\n03:36:12,056 --> 03:36:17,059\r\nperforms its own exact function as\na unique being, and everything would be a\r\n\r\n2607\r\n03:36:17,059 --> 03:36:21,127\r\nsymphony of peace if the hand that\nwrote all this had stopped on the fifth day\r\n\r\n2608\r\n03:36:22,027 --> 03:36:28,027\r\nof creation.\n\"But there was a sixth day,\" the sun went\r\n\r\n2609\r\n03:36:28,027 --> 03:36:31,081\r\non.\n\"You are wise, because you observe everything\r\n\r\n2610\r\n03:36:31,081 --> 03:36:37,118\r\nfrom a distance,\" the boy said.\n\"But you don't know about love. If there hadn't\r\n\r\n2611\r\n03:36:38,018 --> 03:36:43,030\r\nbeen a sixth day, man would not\nexist; copper would always be just copper,\r\n\r\n2612\r\n03:36:43,003 --> 03:36:48,011\r\nand lead just lead. It's true that\neverything has its Personal Legend, but one\r\n\r\n2613\r\n03:36:49,001 --> 03:36:52,006\r\nday that Personal Legend will be realized.\nSo each\r\n\r\n2614\r\n03:36:52,006 --> 03:36:56,045\r\nthing has to transform itself into something\nbetter, and to acquire a new\r\n\r\n2615\r\n03:36:56,099 --> 03:37:02,100\r\nPersonal Legend, until, someday, the Soul\nof the World becomes one thing only.\"\r\n\r\n2616\r\n03:37:03,009 --> 03:37:09,094\r\nThe sun thought about that, and decided to\nshine more brightly. The wind, which\r\n\r\n2617\r\n03:37:09,094 --> 03:37:13,155\r\nwas enjoying the conversation, started to\nblow with greater force, so that the\r\n\r\n2618\r\n03:37:14,055 --> 03:37:19,058\r\nsun would not blind the boy.\n\"This is why alchemy exists,\" the boy said.\r\n\r\n2619\r\n03:37:19,058 --> 03:37:23,134\r\n\"So that everyone will search for his\ntreasure, find it, and then want to be better\r\n\r\n2620\r\n03:37:24,034 --> 03:37:28,112\r\nthan he was in his former life. Lead\nwill play its role until the world has no\r\n\r\n2621\r\n03:37:29,012 --> 03:37:33,070\r\nfurther need for lead; and then lead will\nhave to turn itself into gold.\r\n\r\n2622\r\n03:37:33,007 --> 03:37:37,050\r\n\"That's what alchemists do. They show that,\nwhen we strive to become better\r\n\r\n2623\r\n03:37:38,013 --> 03:37:42,044\r\nthan we are, everything around us becomes\nbetter, too.\"\r\n\r\n2624\r\n03:37:42,044 --> 03:37:47,044\r\n\"Well, why did you say that I don't know about\nlove?\" the sun asked the boy.\r\n\r\n2625\r\n03:37:47,044 --> 03:37:52,080\r\n\"Because it's not love to be static like the\ndesert, nor is it love to roam the\r\n\r\n2626\r\n03:37:52,008 --> 03:37:57,090\r\nworld like the wind. And it's not love to\nsee everything from a distance, like you\r\n\r\n2627\r\n03:37:58,062 --> 03:38:05,062\r\ndo. Love is the force that transforms and\nimproves the Soul of the World. When\r\n\r\n2628\r\n03:38:06,067 --> 03:38:11,069\r\nI first reached through to it, I thought the\nSoul of the World was perfect. But\r\n\r\n2629\r\n03:38:11,087 --> 03:38:15,143\r\nlater, I could see that it was like other\naspects of creation, and had its own\r\n\r\n2630\r\n03:38:16,043 --> 03:38:22,048\r\npassions and wars. It is we who nourish the\nSoul of the World, and the world we\r\n\r\n2631\r\n03:38:22,048 --> 03:38:25,101\r\nlive in will be either better or worse, depending\non whether we become better\r\n\r\n2632\r\n03:38:26,001 --> 03:38:31,066\r\nor worse. And that's where the power of love\ncomes in. Because when we love,\r\n\r\n2633\r\n03:38:31,066 --> 03:38:33,105\r\nwe always strive to become better than we\nare.\"\r\n\r\n2634\r\n03:38:34,005 --> 03:38:41,005\r\n\"So what do you want of me?\" the sun asked.\n\"I want you to help me turn myself into the\r\n\r\n2635\r\n03:38:41,058 --> 03:38:47,141\r\nwind,\" the boy answered.\n\"Nature knows me as the wisest being in creation,\"\r\n\r\n2636\r\n03:38:48,041 --> 03:38:53,094\r\nthe sun said. \"But I don't\nknow how to turn you into the wind.\"\r\n\r\n2637\r\n03:38:53,094 --> 03:38:58,192\r\n\"Then, whom should I ask?\"\nThe sun thought for a minute. The wind was\r\n\r\n2638\r\n03:38:59,092 --> 03:39:03,147\r\nlistening closely, and wanted to tell\nevery corner of the world that the sun's wisdom\r\n\r\n2639\r\n03:39:04,047 --> 03:39:09,082\r\nhad its limitations. That it was\nunable to deal with this boy who spoke the\r\n\r\n2640\r\n03:39:09,082 --> 03:39:15,106\r\nLanguage of the World.\n\"Speak to the hand that wrote all,\" said the\r\n\r\n2641\r\n03:39:16,006 --> 03:39:19,175\r\nsun.\nThe wind screamed with delight, and blew harder\r\n\r\n2642\r\n03:39:19,229 --> 03:39:23,510\r\nthan ever. The tents were\nbeing blown from their ties to the earth,\r\n\r\n2643\r\n03:39:23,051 --> 03:39:27,086\r\nand the animals were being freed from\ntheir tethers. On the cliff, the men clutched\r\n\r\n2644\r\n03:39:27,086 --> 03:39:31,152\r\nat each other as they sought to keep\nfrom being blown away.\r\n\r\n2645\r\n03:39:32,052 --> 03:39:38,090\r\nThe boy turned to the hand that wrote all.\nAs he did so, he sensed that the\r\n\r\n2646\r\n03:39:38,009 --> 03:39:42,013\r\nuniverse had fallen silent, and he decided\nnot to speak.\r\n\r\n2647\r\n03:39:43,003 --> 03:39:50,003\r\nA current of love rushed from his heart, and\nthe boy began to pray. It was a\r\n\r\n2648\r\n03:39:50,009 --> 03:39:55,021\r\nprayer that he had never said before, because\nit was a prayer without words or\r\n\r\n2649\r\n03:39:56,002 --> 03:40:00,067\r\npleas. His prayer didn't give thanks for his\nsheep having found new pastures; it\r\n\r\n2650\r\n03:40:00,067 --> 03:40:04,101\r\ndidn't ask that the boy be able to sell more\ncrystal; and it didn't beseech that\r\n\r\n2651\r\n03:40:05,001 --> 03:40:10,090\r\nthe woman he had met continue to await his\nreturn. In the silence, the boy\r\n\r\n2652\r\n03:40:10,009 --> 03:40:15,081\r\nunderstood that the desert, the wind, and\nthe sun were also trying to understand\r\n\r\n2653\r\n03:40:16,062 --> 03:40:22,069\r\nthe signs written by the hand, and were seeking\nto follow their paths, and to\r\n\r\n2654\r\n03:40:22,069 --> 03:40:27,165\r\nunderstand what had been written on a single\nemerald. He saw that omens were\r\n\r\n2655\r\n03:40:28,065 --> 03:40:32,152\r\nscattered throughout the earth and in space,\nand that there was no reason or\r\n\r\n2656\r\n03:40:33,052 --> 03:40:38,761\r\nsignificance attached to their appearance;\nhe could see that not the deserts, nor\r\n\r\n2657\r\n03:40:39,229 --> 03:40:45,070\r\nthe winds, nor the sun, nor people knew why\nthey had been created. But that\r\n\r\n2658\r\n03:40:45,007 --> 03:40:50,102\r\nthe hand had a reason for all of this, and\nthat only the hand could perform\r\n\r\n2659\r\n03:40:51,002 --> 03:40:58,002\r\nmiracles, or transform the sea into a desert...\nor a man into the wind. Because\r\n\r\n2660\r\n03:41:00,013 --> 03:41:04,072\r\nonly the hand understood that it was a larger\ndesign that had moved the\r\n\r\n2661\r\n03:41:04,072 --> 03:41:09,119\r\nuniverse to the point at which six days of\ncreation had evolved into a Master\r\n\r\n2662\r\n03:41:10,019 --> 03:41:14,087\r\nWork.\nThe boy reached through to the Soul of the\r\n\r\n2663\r\n03:41:14,087 --> 03:41:20,155\r\nWorld, and saw that it was a part of\nthe Soul of God. And he saw that the Soul\r\n\r\n2664\r\n03:41:21,055 --> 03:41:28,055\r\nof God was his own soul. And that he,\na boy, could perform miracles.\r\n\r\n2665\r\n03:41:31,081 --> 03:41:34,162\r\n*\nThe simum blew that day as it had never blown\r\n\r\n2666\r\n03:41:35,062 --> 03:41:39,124\r\nbefore. For generations\nthereafter, the Arabs recounted the legend\r\n\r\n2667\r\n03:41:40,024 --> 03:41:45,013\r\nof a boy who had turned himself into\nthe wind, almost destroying a military camp,\r\n\r\n2668\r\n03:41:45,229 --> 03:41:49,760\r\nin defiance of the most powerful\nchief in the desert.\r\n\r\n2669\r\n03:41:49,076 --> 03:41:53,045\r\nWhen the simum ceased to blow, everyone looked\nto the place where the boy\r\n\r\n2670\r\n03:41:53,729 --> 03:41:59,910\r\nhad been. But he was no longer there; he was\nstanding next to a sand-covered\r\n\r\n2671\r\n03:41:59,091 --> 03:42:05,127\r\nsentinel, on the far side of the camp.\nThe men were terrified at his sorcery. But\r\n\r\n2672\r\n03:42:06,027 --> 03:42:10,065\r\nthere were two people who were\nsmiling: the alchemist, because he had found\r\n\r\n2673\r\n03:42:10,065 --> 03:42:16,118\r\nhis perfect disciple, and the chief,\nbecause that disciple had understood the glory\r\n\r\n2674\r\n03:42:17,018 --> 03:42:21,090\r\nof God.\nThe following day, the general bade the boy\r\n\r\n2675\r\n03:42:21,009 --> 03:42:25,010\r\nand the alchemist farewell, and\nprovided them with an escort party to accompany\r\n\r\n2676\r\n03:42:26,000 --> 03:42:28,077\r\nthem as far as they chose.\n*\r\n\r\n2677\r\n03:42:28,077 --> 03:42:32,176\r\nThey rode for the entire day. Toward the end\nof the afternoon, they came upon\r\n\r\n2678\r\n03:42:33,076 --> 03:42:37,127\r\na Coptic monastery. The alchemist dismounted,\nand told the escorts they could\r\n\r\n2679\r\n03:42:38,027 --> 03:42:42,105\r\nreturn to the camp.\n\"From here on, you will be alone,\" the alchemist\r\n\r\n2680\r\n03:42:43,005 --> 03:42:47,012\r\nsaid. \"You are only three hours\nfrom the Pyramids.\"\r\n\r\n2681\r\n03:42:47,012 --> 03:42:54,012\r\n\"Thank you,\" said the boy. \"You taught me\nthe Language of the World.\"\r\n\r\n2682\r\n03:42:56,011 --> 03:43:03,011\r\n\"I only invoked what you already knew.\"\nThe alchemist knocked on the gate of the monastery.\r\n\r\n2683\r\n03:43:05,015 --> 03:43:09,594\r\nA monk dressed in black\ncame to the gates. They spoke for a few minutes\r\n\r\n2684\r\n03:43:09,729 --> 03:43:13,260\r\nin the Coptic tongue, and the\nalchemist bade the boy enter.\r\n\r\n2685\r\n03:43:13,026 --> 03:43:20,026\r\n\"I asked him to let me use the kitchen for\na while,\" the alchemist smiled.\r\n\r\n2686\r\n03:43:21,033 --> 03:43:24,072\r\nThey went to the kitchen at the back of the\nmonastery. The alchemist lighted\r\n\r\n2687\r\n03:43:24,072 --> 03:43:29,090\r\nthe fire, and the monk brought him some lead,\nwhich the alchemist placed in an\r\n\r\n2688\r\n03:43:29,009 --> 03:43:33,096\r\niron pan. When the lead had become liquid,\nthe alchemist took from his pouch\r\n\r\n2689\r\n03:43:34,077 --> 03:43:40,106\r\nthe strange yellow egg. He scraped from it\na sliver as thin as a hair, wrapped it\r\n\r\n2690\r\n03:43:41,006 --> 03:43:45,064\r\nin wax, and added it to the pan in which the\nlead had melted.\r\n\r\n2691\r\n03:43:45,064 --> 03:43:51,072\r\nThe mixture took on a reddish color, almost\nthe color of blood. The alchemist\r\n\r\n2692\r\n03:43:51,072 --> 03:43:57,110\r\nremoved the pan from the fire, and set it\naside to cool. As he did so, he talked\r\n\r\n2693\r\n03:43:58,001 --> 03:44:03,056\r\nwith the monk about the tribal wars.\n\"I think they're going to last for a long\r\n\r\n2694\r\n03:44:03,065 --> 03:44:08,069\r\ntime,\" he said to the monk.\nThe monk was irritated. The caravans had been\r\n\r\n2695\r\n03:44:08,069 --> 03:44:12,074\r\nstopped at Giza for some time,\nwaiting for the wars to end. \"But God's will\r\n\r\n2696\r\n03:44:13,019 --> 03:44:18,074\r\nbe done,\" the monk said.\n\"Exactly,\" answered the alchemist.\r\n\r\n2697\r\n03:44:18,074 --> 03:44:24,092\r\nWhen the pan had cooled, the monk and the\nboy looked at it, dazzled. The lead\r\n\r\n2698\r\n03:44:24,092 --> 03:44:30,151\r\nhad dried into the shape of the pan, but it\nwas no longer lead. It was gold.\r\n\r\n2699\r\n03:44:30,979 --> 03:44:34,900\r\n\"Will I learn to do that someday?\" the boy\nasked.\r\n\r\n2700\r\n03:44:34,009 --> 03:44:40,025\r\n\"This was my Personal Legend, not yours,\"\nthe alchemist answered. \"But I wanted to\r\n\r\n2701\r\n03:44:41,006 --> 03:44:46,094\r\nshow you that it was possible.\"\nThey returned to the gates of the monastery.\r\n\r\n2702\r\n03:44:46,094 --> 03:44:49,153\r\nThere, the alchemist separated the\ndisk into four parts.\r\n\r\n2703\r\n03:44:50,053 --> 03:44:55,128\r\n\"This is for you,\" he said, holding one of\nthe parts out to the monk. \"It's for your\r\n\r\n2704\r\n03:44:56,028 --> 03:45:01,079\r\ngenerosity to the pilgrims.\"\n\"But this payment goes well beyond my generosity,\"\r\n\r\n2705\r\n03:45:01,079 --> 03:45:05,083\r\nthe monk responded.\n\"Don't say that again. Life might be listening,\r\n\r\n2706\r\n03:45:06,019 --> 03:45:12,074\r\nand give you less the next time.\"\nThe alchemist turned to the boy. \"This is\r\n\r\n2707\r\n03:45:12,074 --> 03:45:15,063\r\nfor you. To make up for what you gave\nto the general.\"\r\n\r\n2708\r\n03:45:15,729 --> 03:45:21,020\r\nThe boy was about to say that it was much\nmore than he had given the general.\r\n\r\n2709\r\n03:45:21,002 --> 03:45:24,051\r\nBut he kept quiet, because he had heard what\nthe alchemist said to the monk.\r\n\r\n2710\r\n03:45:24,051 --> 03:45:30,055\r\n\"And this is for me,\" said the alchemist,\nkeeping one of the parts. \"Because I\r\n\r\n2711\r\n03:45:30,091 --> 03:45:34,160\r\nhave to return to the desert, where there\nare tribal wars.\"\r\n\r\n2712\r\n03:45:34,979 --> 03:45:37,640\r\nHe took the fourth part and handed it to the\nmonk.\r\n\r\n2713\r\n03:45:37,064 --> 03:45:42,137\r\n\"This is for the boy. If he ever needs it.\"\n\"But I'm going in search of my treasure,\"\r\n\r\n2714\r\n03:45:43,037 --> 03:45:45,085\r\nthe boy said. \"I'm very close to it\nnow.\"\r\n\r\n2715\r\n03:45:45,085 --> 03:45:48,139\r\n\"And I'm certain you'll find it,\" the alchemist\nsaid.\r\n\r\n2716\r\n03:45:49,039 --> 03:45:54,051\r\n\"Then why this?\"\n\"Because you have already lost your savings\r\n\r\n2717\r\n03:45:54,051 --> 03:46:00,079\r\ntwice. Once to the thief, and once\nto the general. I'm an old, superstitious\r\n\r\n2718\r\n03:46:00,079 --> 03:46:06,102\r\nArab, and I believe in our proverbs.\nThere's one that says, 'Everything that happens\r\n\r\n2719\r\n03:46:07,002 --> 03:46:12,081\r\nonce can never happen again.\nBut everything that happens twice will surely\r\n\r\n2720\r\n03:46:12,081 --> 03:46:16,178\r\nhappen a third time.' \" They\nmounted their horses.\r\n\r\n2721\r\n03:46:17,078 --> 03:46:21,119\r\n*\n\"I want to tell you a story about dreams,\"\r\n\r\n2722\r\n03:46:22,019 --> 03:46:25,057\r\nsaid the alchemist.\nThe boy brought his horse closer.\r\n\r\n2723\r\n03:46:25,057 --> 03:46:31,060\r\n\"In ancient Rome, at the time of Emperor Tiberius,\nthere lived a good man who\r\n\r\n2724\r\n03:46:31,087 --> 03:46:36,112\r\nhad two sons. One was in the military, and\nhad been sent to the most distant\r\n\r\n2725\r\n03:46:37,012 --> 03:46:42,054\r\nregions of the empire. The other son was a\npoet, and delighted all of Rome with\r\n\r\n2726\r\n03:46:42,054 --> 03:46:48,081\r\nhis beautiful verses.\n\"One night, the father had a dream. An angel\r\n\r\n2727\r\n03:46:48,081 --> 03:46:52,152\r\nappeared to him, and told him\nthat the words of one of his sons would be\r\n\r\n2728\r\n03:46:53,052 --> 03:46:59,052\r\nlearned and repeated throughout the\nworld for all generations to come. The father\r\n\r\n2729\r\n03:46:59,052 --> 03:47:04,087\r\nwoke from his dream grateful and\ncrying, because life was generous, and had\r\n\r\n2730\r\n03:47:04,087 --> 03:47:08,089\r\nrevealed to him something any\nfather would be proud to know.\r\n\r\n2731\r\n03:47:09,007 --> 03:47:15,019\r\n\"Shortly thereafter, the father died as he\ntried to save a child who was about to\r\n\r\n2732\r\n03:47:15,019 --> 03:47:20,036\r\nbe crushed by the wheels of a chariot. Since\nhe had lived his entire life in a\r\n\r\n2733\r\n03:47:20,036 --> 03:47:24,905\r\nmanner that was correct and fair, he went\ndirectly to heaven, where he met the\r\n\r\n2734\r\n03:47:25,229 --> 03:47:31,260\r\nangel that had appeared in his dream.\n\" 'You were always a good man,' the angel\r\n\r\n2735\r\n03:47:31,026 --> 03:47:37,039\r\nsaid to him. 'You lived your life in a\nloving way, and died with dignity. I can now\r\n\r\n2736\r\n03:47:37,039 --> 03:47:44,039\r\ngrant you any wish you desire.'\n\" 'Life was good to me,' the man said. 'When\r\n\r\n2737\r\n03:47:44,089 --> 03:47:48,114\r\nyou appeared in my dream, I felt\nthat all my efforts had been rewarded, because\r\n\r\n2738\r\n03:47:49,014 --> 03:47:54,018\r\nmy son's poems will be read by\nmen for generations to come. I don't want\r\n\r\n2739\r\n03:47:54,054 --> 03:47:59,116\r\nanything for myself. But any father\nwould be proud of the fame achieved by one\r\n\r\n2740\r\n03:48:00,016 --> 03:48:06,047\r\nwhom he had cared for as a child,\nand educated as he grew up. Sometime in the\r\n\r\n2741\r\n03:48:06,047 --> 03:48:10,099\r\ndistant future, I would like to see\nmy son's words.'\r\n\r\n2742\r\n03:48:10,099 --> 03:48:15,160\r\n\"The angel touched the man's shoulder, and\nthey were both projected far into\r\n\r\n2743\r\n03:48:16,006 --> 03:48:21,098\r\nthe future. They were in an immense setting,\nsurrounded by thousands of\r\n\r\n2744\r\n03:48:22,052 --> 03:48:27,071\r\npeople speaking a strange language.\n\"The man wept with happiness.\r\n\r\n2745\r\n03:48:27,071 --> 03:48:32,094\r\n\" 'I knew that my son's poems were immortal,'\nhe said to the angel through his\r\n\r\n2746\r\n03:48:32,094 --> 03:48:36,152\r\ntears. 'Can you please tell me which of my\nson's poems these people are\r\n\r\n2747\r\n03:48:37,052 --> 03:48:41,097\r\nrepeating?'\n\"The angel came closer to the man, and, with\r\n\r\n2748\r\n03:48:41,097 --> 03:48:45,170\r\ntenderness, led him to a bench\nnearby, where they sat down.\r\n\r\n2749\r\n03:48:46,007 --> 03:48:51,007\r\n\"'The verses of your son who was the poet\nwere very popular in Rome,' the\r\n\r\n2750\r\n03:48:51,007 --> 03:48:55,018\r\nangel said. 'Everyone loved them and enjoyed\nthem. But when the reign of\r\n\r\n2751\r\n03:48:55,081 --> 03:49:01,099\r\nTiberius ended, his poems were forgotten.\nThe words you're hearing now are\r\n\r\n2752\r\n03:49:01,099 --> 03:49:08,099\r\nthose of your son in the military.'\n\"The man looked at the angel in surprise.\r\n\r\n2753\r\n03:49:09,399 --> 03:49:16,290\r\n\" 'Your son went to serve at a distant place,\nand became a centurion. He was\r\n\r\n2754\r\n03:49:16,029 --> 03:49:22,117\r\njust and good. One afternoon, one of his servants\nfell ill, and it appeared that\r\n\r\n2755\r\n03:49:23,017 --> 03:49:29,079\r\nhe would die. Your son had heard of a rabbi\nwho was able to cure illnesses, and\r\n\r\n2756\r\n03:49:29,079 --> 03:49:35,080\r\nhe rode out for days and days in search of\nthis man. Along the way, he learned\r\n\r\n2757\r\n03:49:35,008 --> 03:49:40,047\r\nthat the man he was seeking was the Son of\nGod. He met others who had been\r\n\r\n2758\r\n03:49:41,019 --> 03:49:47,074\r\ncured by him, and they instructed your son\nin the man's teachings. And so,\r\n\r\n2759\r\n03:49:47,074 --> 03:49:53,162\r\ndespite the fact that he was a Roman centurion,\nhe converted to their faith.\r\n\r\n2760\r\n03:49:54,062 --> 03:49:57,130\r\nShortly thereafter, he reached the place where\nthe man he was looking for was\r\n\r\n2761\r\n03:49:58,003 --> 03:50:02,009\r\nvisiting.'\n\" 'He told the man that one of his servants\r\n\r\n2762\r\n03:50:02,009 --> 03:50:08,016\r\nwas gravely ill, and the rabbi made\nready to go to his house with him. But the\r\n\r\n2763\r\n03:50:08,097 --> 03:50:13,158\r\ncenturion was a man of faith, and,\nlooking into the eyes of the rabbi, he knew\r\n\r\n2764\r\n03:50:14,058 --> 03:50:17,079\r\nthat he was surely in the presence\nof the Son of God.'\r\n\r\n2765\r\n03:50:17,079 --> 03:50:24,079\r\n\" 'And this is what your son said,' the angel\ntold the man. 'These are the words\r\n\r\n2766\r\n03:50:25,076 --> 03:50:31,081\r\nhe said to the rabbi at that point, and they\nhave never been forgotten: \"My\r\n\r\n2767\r\n03:50:31,081 --> 03:50:38,081\r\nLord, I am not worthy that you should come\nunder my roof. But only speak a\r\n\r\n2768\r\n03:50:39,028 --> 03:50:46,028\r\nword and my servant will be healed.\" \"'\nThe alchemist said, \"No matter what he does,\r\n\r\n2769\r\n03:50:48,084 --> 03:50:53,093\r\nevery person on earth plays a\ncentral role in the history of the world.\r\n\r\n2770\r\n03:50:54,074 --> 03:51:01,074\r\nAnd normally he doesn't know it.\"\nThe boy smiled. He had never imagined that\r\n\r\n2771\r\n03:51:02,018 --> 03:51:07,084\r\nquestions about life would be of\nsuch importance to a shepherd.\r\n\r\n2772\r\n03:51:07,084 --> 03:51:14,084\r\n\"Good-bye,\" the alchemist said.\n\"Good-bye,\" said the boy.\r\n\r\n2773\r\n03:51:14,093 --> 03:51:15,152\r\n*\nThe boy rode along through the desert for\r\n\r\n2774\r\n03:51:16,052 --> 03:51:21,144\r\nseveral hours, listening avidly to\nwhat his heart had to say. It was his heart\r\n\r\n2775\r\n03:51:22,044 --> 03:51:24,583\r\nthat would tell him where his\ntreasure was hidden.\r\n\r\n2776\r\n03:51:24,979 --> 03:51:30,460\r\n\"Where your treasure is, there also will be\nyour heart,\" the alchemist had told\r\n\r\n2777\r\n03:51:30,046 --> 03:51:34,114\r\nhim.\nBut his heart was speaking of other things.\r\n\r\n2778\r\n03:51:35,014 --> 03:51:39,031\r\nWith pride, it told the story of a\nshepherd who had left his flock to follow\r\n\r\n2779\r\n03:51:39,031 --> 03:51:44,120\r\na dream he had on two different\noccasions. It told of Personal Legend, and\r\n\r\n2780\r\n03:51:45,002 --> 03:51:49,781\r\nof the many men who had wandered in search\nof distant lands or beautiful women, confronting\r\n\r\n2781\r\n03:51:49,979 --> 03:51:55,580\r\nthe people of their times with\ntheir preconceived notions. It spoke of journeys,\r\n\r\n2782\r\n03:51:55,058 --> 03:51:58,084\r\ndiscoveries, books, and\nchange.\r\n\r\n2783\r\n03:51:58,084 --> 03:52:04,103\r\nAs he was about to climb yet another dune,\nhis heart whispered, \"Be aware of\r\n\r\n2784\r\n03:52:05,003 --> 03:52:11,007\r\nthe place where you are brought to tears.\nThat's where I am, and that's where\r\n\r\n2785\r\n03:52:11,007 --> 03:52:17,076\r\nyour treasure is.\"\nThe boy climbed the dune slowly. A full moon\r\n\r\n2786\r\n03:52:17,076 --> 03:52:21,120\r\nrose again in the starry sky: it\nhad been a month since he had set forth from\r\n\r\n2787\r\n03:52:22,002 --> 03:52:27,079\r\nthe oasis. The moonlight cast\nshadows through the dunes, creating the appearance\r\n\r\n2788\r\n03:52:27,097 --> 03:52:30,143\r\nof a rolling sea; it\nreminded the boy of the day when that horse\r\n\r\n2789\r\n03:52:31,043 --> 03:52:35,134\r\nhad reared in the desert, and he\nhad come to know the alchemist. And the moon\r\n\r\n2790\r\n03:52:36,034 --> 03:52:41,115\r\nfell on the desert's silence, and\non a man's journey in search of treasure.\r\n\r\n2791\r\n03:52:42,015 --> 03:52:46,089\r\nWhen he reached the top of the dune, his heart\nleapt. There, illuminated by the\r\n\r\n2792\r\n03:52:46,089 --> 03:52:49,155\r\nlight of the moon and the brightness of the\ndesert, stood the solemn and\r\n\r\n2793\r\n03:52:50,055 --> 03:52:57,055\r\nmajestic Pyramids of Egypt.\nThe boy fell to his knees and wept. He thanked\r\n\r\n2794\r\n03:53:00,031 --> 03:53:03,950\r\nGod for making him believe in\nhis Personal Legend, and for leading him to\r\n\r\n2795\r\n03:53:04,229 --> 03:53:11,229\r\nmeet a king, a merchant, an Englishman,\nand an alchemist. And above all for his having\r\n\r\n2796\r\n03:53:11,024 --> 03:53:15,030\r\nmet a woman of the desert who\nhad told him that love would never keep a\r\n\r\n2797\r\n03:53:15,003 --> 03:53:21,051\r\nman from his Personal Legend.\nIf he wanted to, he could now return to the\r\n\r\n2798\r\n03:53:21,078 --> 03:53:26,135\r\noasis, go back to Fatima, and live\nhis life as a simple shepherd. After all,\r\n\r\n2799\r\n03:53:27,035 --> 03:53:31,164\r\nthe alchemist continued to live in the\ndesert, even though he understood the Language\r\n\r\n2800\r\n03:53:31,479 --> 03:53:35,440\r\nof the World, and knew how to\ntransform lead into gold. He didn't need to\r\n\r\n2801\r\n03:53:35,044 --> 03:53:40,086\r\ndemonstrate his science and art to\nanyone. The boy told himself that, on the\r\n\r\n2802\r\n03:53:40,086 --> 03:53:45,091\r\nway toward realizing his own Personal Legend,\nhe had learned all he needed to know, and\r\n\r\n2803\r\n03:53:46,036 --> 03:53:49,090\r\nhad experienced everything he\nmight have dreamed of.\r\n\r\n2804\r\n03:53:49,009 --> 03:53:55,054\r\nBut here he was, at the point of finding his\ntreasure, and he reminded himself\r\n\r\n2805\r\n03:53:56,035 --> 03:54:01,081\r\nthat no project is completed until its objective\nhas been achieved. The boy\r\n\r\n2806\r\n03:54:01,081 --> 03:54:05,166\r\nlooked at the sands around him, and saw that,\nwhere his tears had fallen, a\r\n\r\n2807\r\n03:54:06,066 --> 03:54:11,145\r\nscarab beetle was scuttling through the sand.\nDuring his time in the desert, he\r\n\r\n2808\r\n03:54:12,045 --> 03:54:18,056\r\nhad learned that, in Egypt, the scarab beetles\nare a symbol of God.\r\n\r\n2809\r\n03:54:18,056 --> 03:54:23,475\r\nAnother omen! The boy began to dig into the\ndune. As he did so, he thought of\r\n\r\n2810\r\n03:54:23,979 --> 03:54:27,770\r\nwhat the crystal merchant had once said: that\nanyone could build a pyramid in\r\n\r\n2811\r\n03:54:27,077 --> 03:54:32,083\r\nhis backyard. The boy could see now that he\ncouldn't do so if he placed stone\r\n\r\n2812\r\n03:54:32,083 --> 03:54:38,111\r\nupon stone for the rest of his life.\nThroughout the night, the boy dug at the place\r\n\r\n2813\r\n03:54:39,011 --> 03:54:43,880\r\nhe had chosen, but found\nnothing. He felt weighted down by the centuries\r\n\r\n2814\r\n03:54:43,979 --> 03:54:48,500\r\nof time since the Pyramids had\nbeen built. But he didn't stop. He struggled\r\n\r\n2815\r\n03:54:48,005 --> 03:54:51,070\r\nto continue digging as he fought the\nwind, which often blew the sand back into\r\n\r\n2816\r\n03:54:52,015 --> 03:54:57,015\r\nthe excavation. His hands were\nabraded and exhausted, but he listened to\r\n\r\n2817\r\n03:54:57,015 --> 03:55:02,081\r\nhis heart. It had told him to dig\nwhere his tears fell.\r\n\r\n2818\r\n03:55:02,081 --> 03:55:06,119\r\nAs he was attempting to pull out the rocks\nhe encountered, he heard footsteps.\r\n\r\n2819\r\n03:55:07,019 --> 03:55:10,102\r\nSeveral figures approached him. Their backs\nwere to the moonlight, and the\r\n\r\n2820\r\n03:55:11,002 --> 03:55:13,047\r\nboy could see neither their eyes nor their\nfaces.\r\n\r\n2821\r\n03:55:13,047 --> 03:55:17,556\r\n\"What are you doing here?\" one of the figures\ndemanded.\r\n\r\n2822\r\n03:55:17,979 --> 03:55:21,880\r\nBecause he was terrified, the boy didn't answer.\nHe had found where his\r\n\r\n2823\r\n03:55:21,088 --> 03:55:24,136\r\ntreasure was, and was frightened at what might\nhappen.\r\n\r\n2824\r\n03:55:25,036 --> 03:55:29,043\r\n\"We're refugees from the tribal wars, and\nwe need money,\" the other figure\r\n\r\n2825\r\n03:55:29,043 --> 03:55:33,084\r\nsaid. \"What are you hiding there?\"\n\"I'm not hiding anything,\" the boy answered.\r\n\r\n2826\r\n03:55:33,084 --> 03:55:37,182\r\nBut one of them seized the boy and yanked\nhim back out of the hole. Another,\r\n\r\n2827\r\n03:55:38,082 --> 03:55:41,101\r\nwho was searching the boy's bags, found the\npiece of gold.\r\n\r\n2828\r\n03:55:42,001 --> 03:55:47,039\r\n\"There's gold here,\" he said.\nThe moon shone on the face of the Arab who\r\n\r\n2829\r\n03:55:47,039 --> 03:55:50,106\r\nhad seized him, and in the man's\neyes the boy saw death.\r\n\r\n2830\r\n03:55:51,006 --> 03:55:54,089\r\n\"He's probably got more gold hidden in the\nground.\"\r\n\r\n2831\r\n03:55:54,089 --> 03:56:00,145\r\nThey made the boy continue digging, but he\nfound nothing. As the sun rose, the\r\n\r\n2832\r\n03:56:01,045 --> 03:56:06,140\r\nmen began to beat the boy. He was bruised\nand bleeding, his clothing was torn\r\n\r\n2833\r\n03:56:07,004 --> 03:56:12,015\r\nto shreds, and he felt that death was near.\n\"What good is money to you if you're going\r\n\r\n2834\r\n03:56:12,051 --> 03:56:18,120\r\nto die? It's not often that money can\nsave someone's life,\" the alchemist had said.\r\n\r\n2835\r\n03:56:19,002 --> 03:56:23,781\r\nFinally, the boy screamed at the\nmen, \"I'm digging for treasure!\" And, although\r\n\r\n2836\r\n03:56:23,979 --> 03:56:27,520\r\nhis mouth was bleeding and\nswollen, he told his attackers that he had\r\n\r\n2837\r\n03:56:27,052 --> 03:56:29,058\r\ntwice dreamed of a treasure hidden\nnear the Pyramids of Egypt.\r\n\r\n2838\r\n03:56:30,012 --> 03:56:35,027\r\nThe man who appeared to be the leader of the\ngroup spoke to one of the\r\n\r\n2839\r\n03:56:35,027 --> 03:56:39,119\r\nothers: \"Leave him. He doesn't have anything\nelse. He must have stolen this\r\n\r\n2840\r\n03:56:40,019 --> 03:56:45,066\r\ngold.\"\nThe boy fell to the sand, nearly unconscious.\r\n\r\n2841\r\n03:56:45,066 --> 03:56:48,109\r\nThe leader shook him and said,\n\"We're leaving.\"\r\n\r\n2842\r\n03:56:49,009 --> 03:56:53,104\r\nBut before they left, he came back to the\nboy and said, \"You're not going to die.\r\n\r\n2843\r\n03:56:54,004 --> 03:57:00,015\r\nYou'll live, and you'll learn that a man shouldn't\nbe so stupid. Two years ago,\r\n\r\n2844\r\n03:57:00,015 --> 03:57:05,094\r\nright here on this spot, I had a recurrent\ndream, too. I dreamed that I should\r\n\r\n2845\r\n03:57:05,094 --> 03:57:09,152\r\ntravel to the fields of Spain and look for\na ruined church where shepherds and\r\n\r\n2846\r\n03:57:10,052 --> 03:57:14,136\r\ntheir sheep slept. In my dream, there was\na sycamore growing out of the ruins\r\n\r\n2847\r\n03:57:15,036 --> 03:57:19,109\r\nof the sacristy, and I was told that, if I\ndug at the roots of the sycamore, I\r\n\r\n2848\r\n03:57:20,009 --> 03:57:24,097\r\nwould find a hidden treasure. But I'm not\nso stupid as to cross an entire desert\r\n\r\n2849\r\n03:57:24,097 --> 03:57:29,129\r\njust because of a recurrent dream.\"\nAnd they disappeared.\r\n\r\n2850\r\n03:57:30,029 --> 03:57:36,062\r\nThe boy stood up shakily, and looked once\nmore at the Pyramids. They seemed\r\n\r\n2851\r\n03:57:36,062 --> 03:57:43,062\r\nto laugh at him, and he laughed back, his\nheart bursting with joy.\r\n\r\n2852\r\n03:57:44,092 --> 03:57:48,096\r\nBecause now he knew where his treasure was.\r\n\r\n2853\r\n03:57:48,096 --> 03:57:52,865\r\nThe boy reached the small, abandoned church\njust as night was falling. The\r\n\r\n2854\r\n03:57:53,729 --> 03:57:57,920\r\nsycamore was still there in the sacristy,\nand the stars could still be seen through\r\n\r\n2855\r\n03:57:57,092 --> 03:58:01,164\r\nthe half-destroyed roof. He remembered the\ntime he had been there with his\r\n\r\n2856\r\n03:58:02,064 --> 03:58:07,152\r\nsheep; it had been a peaceful night... except\nfor the dream.\r\n\r\n2857\r\n03:58:08,052 --> 03:58:13,084\r\nNow he was here not with his flock, but with\na shovel.\r\n\r\n2858\r\n03:58:13,084 --> 03:58:18,089\r\nHe sat looking at the sky for a long time.\nThen he took from his knapsack a\r\n\r\n2859\r\n03:58:18,089 --> 03:58:23,126\r\nbottle of wine, and drank some. He remembered\nthe night in the desert when\r\n\r\n2860\r\n03:58:24,026 --> 03:58:27,079\r\nhe had sat with the alchemist, as they looked\nat the stars and drank wine\r\n\r\n2861\r\n03:58:27,079 --> 03:58:32,118\r\ntogether. He thought of the many roads he\nhad traveled, and of the strange way\r\n\r\n2862\r\n03:58:33,018 --> 03:58:38,040\r\nGod had chosen to show him his treasure. If\nhe hadn't believed in the\r\n\r\n2863\r\n03:58:38,004 --> 03:58:43,007\r\nsignificance of recurrent dreams, he would\nnot have met the Gypsy woman, the\r\n\r\n2864\r\n03:58:43,007 --> 03:58:50,007\r\nking, the thief, or... \"Well, it's a long\nlist. But the path was written in the omens,\r\n\r\n2865\r\n03:58:51,001 --> 03:58:55,082\r\nand there was no way I could go wrong,\" he\nsaid to himself.\r\n\r\n2866\r\n03:58:55,091 --> 03:59:01,165\r\nHe fell asleep, and when he awoke the sun\nwas already high. He began to dig at\r\n\r\n2867\r\n03:59:02,065 --> 03:59:07,069\r\nthe base of the sycamore.\n\"You old sorcerer,\" the boy shouted up to\r\n\r\n2868\r\n03:59:08,005 --> 03:59:13,434\r\nthe sky. \"You knew the whole story.\nYou even left a bit of gold at the monastery\r\n\r\n2869\r\n03:59:13,479 --> 03:59:18,380\r\nso I could get back to this church.\nThe monk laughed when he saw me come back\r\n\r\n2870\r\n03:59:18,038 --> 03:59:21,137\r\nin tatters. Couldn't you have\nsaved me from that?\"\r\n\r\n2871\r\n03:59:22,037 --> 03:59:29,037\r\n\"No,\" he heard a voice on the wind say. \"If\nI had told you, you wouldn't have\r\n\r\n2872\r\n03:59:29,047 --> 03:59:33,143\r\nseen the Pyramids. They're beautiful, aren't\nthey?\"\r\n\r\n2873\r\n03:59:34,043 --> 03:59:40,050\r\nThe boy smiled, and continued digging. Half\nan hour later, his shovel hit\r\n\r\n2874\r\n03:59:40,005 --> 03:59:47,005\r\nsomething solid. An hour later, he had before\nhim a chest of Spanish gold coins.\r\n\r\n2875\r\n03:59:47,091 --> 03:59:51,117\r\nThere were also precious stones, gold masks\nadorned with red and white\r\n\r\n2876\r\n03:59:52,017 --> 03:59:58,021\r\nfeathers, and stone statues embedded with\njewels. The spoils of a conquest that\r\n\r\n2877\r\n03:59:58,057 --> 04:00:02,466\r\nthe country had long ago forgotten, and that\nsome conquistador had failed to\r\n\r\n2878\r\n04:00:02,979 --> 04:00:08,660\r\ntell his children about.\nThe boy took out Urim and Thummim from his\r\n\r\n2879\r\n04:00:08,066 --> 04:00:15,066\r\nbag. He had used the two stones\nonly once, one morning when he was at a marketplace.\r\n\r\n2880\r\n04:00:16,076 --> 04:00:21,082\r\nHis life and his path had\nalways provided him with enough omens.\r\n\r\n2881\r\n04:00:22,036 --> 04:00:27,077\r\nHe placed Urim and Thummim in the chest. They\nwere also a part of his new\r\n\r\n2882\r\n04:00:27,077 --> 04:00:31,160\r\ntreasure, because they were a reminder of\nthe old king, whom he would never\r\n\r\n2883\r\n04:00:32,006 --> 04:00:38,635\r\nsee again.\nIt's true; life really is generous to those\r\n\r\n2884\r\n04:00:39,229 --> 04:00:44,990\r\nwho pursue their Personal Legend, the boy\nthought. Then he remembered that he had to\r\n\r\n2885\r\n04:00:44,099 --> 04:00:48,153\r\nget to Tarifa so he could give\none-tenth of his treasure to the Gypsy woman,\r\n\r\n2886\r\n04:00:49,053 --> 04:00:54,054\r\nas he had promised. Those\nGypsies are really smart, he thought. Maybe\r\n\r\n2887\r\n04:00:54,063 --> 04:00:57,125\r\nit was because they moved around\nso much.\r\n\r\n2888\r\n04:00:58,025 --> 04:01:03,026\r\nThe wind began to blow again. It was the levanter,\nthe wind that came from\r\n\r\n2889\r\n04:01:03,026 --> 04:01:09,069\r\nAfrica. It didn't bring with it the smell\nof the desert, nor the threat of Moorish\r\n\r\n2890\r\n04:01:09,069 --> 04:01:16,069\r\ninvasion. Instead, it brought the scent of\na perfume he knew well, and the touch\r\n\r\n2891\r\n04:01:17,019 --> 04:01:24,019\r\nof a kiss--a kiss that came from far away,\nslowly, slowly, until it rested on his\r\n\r\n2892\r\n04:01:27,022 --> 04:01:33,065\r\nlips.\nThe boy smiled. It was the first time she\r\n\r\n2893\r\n04:01:33,065 --> 04:01:37,756\r\nhad done that.\n\"I'm coming, Fatima,\" he said.\r\n\r\n","markerStore":{"nextMarkerId":113,"markersById":{"0":{"range":{"start":{"row":0,"column":0},"end":{"row":0,"column":0}},"properties":{"type":"selection","editorId":546,"preserveFolds":true,"goalScreenRange":null},"reversed":false,"tailed":false,"valid":true,"invalidate":"never","maintainHistory":true}},"version":2},"history":{"version":3,"nextCheckpointId":0,"undoStack":[],"redoStack":[]},"encoding":"utf8","filePath":"/Users/joegesualdo/Downloads/The Alchemist By Paulo Coelho - Audiobook [original] [English].srt","digestWhenLastPersisted":"da39a3ee5e6b4b0d3255bfef95601890afd80709","preferredLineEnding":null,"deserializer":"TextBuffer","version":2},{"load":false,"text":"Name,Email,Financial Status,Paid at,Fulfillment Status,Fulfilled at,Accepts Marketing,Currency,Subtotal,Shipping,Taxes,Total,Discount Code,Discount Amount,Shipping Method,Created at,Lineitem quantity,Lineitem name,Lineitem price,Lineitem compare at price,Lineitem sku,Lineitem requires shipping,Lineitem taxable,Lineitem fulfillment status,Billing Name,Billing Street,Billing Address1,Billing Address2,Billing Company,Billing City,Billing Zip,Billing Province,Billing Country,Billing Phone,Shipping Name,Shipping Street,Shipping Address1,Shipping Address2,Shipping Company,Shipping City,Shipping Zip,Shipping Province,Shipping Country,Shipping Phone,Notes,Note Attributes,Cancelled at,Payment Method,Payment Reference,Refunded Amount,Vendor,Id,Tags,Risk Level,Source,Lineitem discount,Tax 1 Name,Tax 1 Value,Tax 2 Name,Tax 2 Value,Tax 3 Name,Tax 3 Value,Tax 4 Name,Tax 4 Value,Tax 5 Name,Tax 5 Value\n#1001,testing@test.com,paid,2015-09-04 12:54:26 -0400,fulfilled,2015-09-10 15:27:23 -0400,yes,USD,6.25,7.00,1.18,14.43,FREEBOWLS,8.00,Tier 1,2015-09-04 12:54:26 -0400,3,Peanut Butter Cacao - Regular,3.50,,4,true,true,fulfilled,TEst Test,\"300, Madison Ave\",300,Madison Ave,\"\",New York,'10017,NY,US,\"\",TEst Test,\"300, Madison Ave\",300,Madison Ave,\"\"